A9490 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-HITS-BOS &LR;      10-17 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-HITS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRESS DOESN'T LEAD TO PRODUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's obvious the New York Yankees are getting to Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic strides they've made since last facing the Red Sox
righthander a month ago were graphically emphasized by the
statistics Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   They had twice as many hits against Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   They struck out five fewer times.
</P>
<P>
   They worked him for a couple of walks.
</P>
<P>
   They got rid of him two innings sooner.
</P>
<P>
   All right, so they scored one fewer run, but let's not nitpick.
</P>
<P>
   What more encouragement could they possibly want _ other than a
hint of victory or a whiff of sustained success?
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that this 13-1 humbling at Fenway Park in Game 3 of
the American League Championship Series _ in which Martinez yielded
two hits and no runs while striking out a Boston postseason-record
12 batters in seven innings _ was a step forward in a most relative
sense. On Sept. 10 at Yankee Stadium, Martinez allowed only a home
run by Chili Davis, walked nobody, and struck out 17 in a 3-1
complete-game victory.
</P>
<P>
   All the victims could do in Saturday's aftermath was compare
degrees of excellence, and that was almost as much an exercise in
futility as trying to hit Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a difference, it was in dominance, the Yankees
seemed to agree. In September, a healthy Martinez had been
overpowering. Saturday, a gimpy Martinez obliged his ailing back by
relying on his curveball, his changeup, and his uncanny cunning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazing,'' said New York left fielder Ricky Ledee, who struck
out twice against Martinez. ``What he did against us in New York
was amazing. It looked today like he was hurting. So to do what he
did against us today was amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ledee seemed stuck for variety in his superlatives, Martinez
encountered no such problem with his repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   ``His velocity wasn't there, but he had command,'' said center
fielder Bernie Williams, a one-strikeout casualty. ``Even when we
went deep in the count and had him 3 and 1 or 3 and 2, he could
still strike us out with the changeup. He did absolutely the best
he could with the stuff he had today.''
</P>
<P>
   Because even though he was missing a key weapon, there was still
plenty in the arsenal. It's just that Saturday the Yankees were
left blinking in bewilderment. In September, they didn't have the
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched us completely different than the time before,''
said shortstop Derek Jeter, who went down once looking, once
swinging after creating false hope with a first-inning single.
``Early on, you could tell he didn't have his fastball. That's what
I got my hit on. But he was hitting his spots. He's the type of
pitcher who doesn't need his fastball because he has three
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps right fielder Paul O'Neill, another member of the 2-K
club, offered the most logical explanation: Don't try to explain
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best pitcher in baseball,'' said O'Neill. ``What he
has or doesn't have doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to the Yankees, anyway, because they sure don't have it
against Martinez.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
