A9492 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SOXPLAYOFFS-FANS-     10-17 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SOXPLAYOFFS-FANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FENWAY FAITHFUL GIVE HERO'S WELCOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cacophony coming from the area between Yawkey Way and
Lansdowne Street was a mix of cheers and jeers. Boos reserved for
New York's Roger Clemens, with shouts of support for Boston ace
Pedro Martinez. When Martinez capped his first inning of work with
a strikeout of Bernie Williams, the crowd gave Martinez a standing
ovation that begged Clemens to top the opening act of the home
team's ace. The Red Sox fans would not make it easy for their
former hero.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the first, Fenway Park throbbed with chants of
``Raaah-ger, Raaah-ger.'' Fans targeted Clemens with their
sing-song cry until he produced three outs, and by then the Sox
already had a 2-0 lead on John Valentin's home run. And beneath the
disapproving clamor, individuals with strong rooting interests _
and lungs _ spit out a few choice words.
</P>
<P>
   If you wanted to experience baseball partisanship at its most
extreme, there was no better place to be than Fenway for Saturday's
Game 3 of the American League Championship Series. The pitching
matchup between Clemens and Martinez brought fans to new heights of
name-calling. And the mound showdown took the intense rivalry
between Boston and New York to new levels.
</P>
<P>
   Standing beside the visiting bullpen, David Clifford held a
homemade T-shirt over the right-field wall for Clemens to read. The
shirt read, ``Hey Roger, would you leave your wife if another woman
offered you more?'' The question referred to Clemens leaving the
Sox and signing with Toronto for more money. While Clifford held up
his shirt, others shouted, ``You sold your soul,'' ``Just have
another doughnut, Roger,'' and ``That's right, you fat Texan.''
</P>
<P>
   The few Clemens fans seated around the bullpen were vocal,
though they could not make as much noise as their Boston
counterparts. Anthony Manzo of Providence practically yelled
himself hoarse, trying to root for Roger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to make sure I yell a little louder to protect him a
little bit,'' Manzo said before shouting words of encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Manzo's support, Clemens would last only two innings
plus, yielding five runs, as he took the loss in a 13-1 Boston
rout.
</P>
<P>
   The hostilities started even before the game. Yankees outfielder
Darryl Strawberry was harassed during batting practice with
references to his troubled past. Those in the outfield cheered when
Clemens overthrew catcher Jorge Posada with a practice toss. Boston
fans would comment to people taking seats next to them, ``You
better be a Red Sox fan.'' When Yankees fans braved Red Sox
enclaves, hecklers were waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Schumacher of Garden City, N.Y., wore a hat made especially
for the occasion that read simply, ``1918.'' He expected a lot of
heckling, but said the only statement he needed to make was the one
written above the brim.
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher found a seat in front of die-hard Red Sox fan Pete
Wilson of Waltham. It was a seating arrangement that tempted both
sides to put their best barbs forward. Wilson and friend James Wood
of Scituate felt the Yankees fans in front of them were asking for
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   After New York shortstop Derek Jeter got a single in the first,
the teasing from the visiting fans started.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just wait till your fat boy Clemens gets out there,'' said
Wilson, whose words were prophetic. ``That's why we gave him to
you. Watch when he gets shelled today. After (Game 3), they'll hate
Clemens in Boston, they'll hate him in Toronto, and they'll hate
him in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Out in the bleachers, fans from both sides expressed their
opinions with signs and body paint. On a back wall, Pedro and
Rocket name tags were posted for each pitcher's strikeout count.
Red K's were designated for Martinez, with blue K's for Clemens.
Yankees fan Andre Larocque of Salisbury, Vt., brought 16 K's for
each player, but was hoping he would have plenty to borrow from the
Martinez stash to place under the Yankee starter's nickname. As it
turned out, he needed only two blue K's. Twelve red K's were
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Another sign in the bleachers read, ``Pedro's fallen Yankees.''
Underneath the title were action shots of each Yankee batter. Steve
Colby and Jordon Pranski planned to cut out the face of each batter
Martinez struck out. Other fans wore bumper stickers and pins
proclaiming, ``Reverse the Curse'' and ``Cy Young vs. Cy Old.''
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the seventh, as the Sox' run count rose into
double figures, the Fenway faithful had a burning question. ``Where
is Roger?'' they chanted, knowing full well Clemens's day long had
been over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
