<HEADER>
A9493 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SOXPLAYOFFS-DAUBA     10-17 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SOXPLAYOFFS-DAUBACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUBACH HANGING IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The answer to The Daubach Riddle, as with all good mysteries,
will not be known until the final page is turned.
</P>
<P>
   As the spotlight shining on these 1999 Red Sox grows brighter
and brighter on the team now playing for the American League
pennant, more and more baseball fans from around the country are
asking the question that has been asked in Boston every day Jimy
Williams posts his lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Why is Brian Daubach playing?
</P>
<P>
   Even Daubach acknowledges there have been times _ particularly
during his lost six weeks from mid-August until the end of the
regular season _ when he showed up at the ballpark and peeked at
the lineup with trepidation. More often than not, though, his name
would be on it.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other night, the rookie arrived at Jacobs Field in
Cleveland with serious doubts as to whether he'd be starting in the
fifth and deciding Division Series game against the Indians. ``The
night before, we scored 23 runs and I didn't get a hit,'' he said.
``And I'd had only one hit in the series. So I didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds and hundreds of managers through baseball's history
might have sat the slumping Daubach that night, but Jimy Williams
did not. And Daubach made his manager's faith pay off right away,
with two hits in the first three innings of that madcap game, which
the Red Sox eventually won, 12-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how much that meant to me, for Jimy to have
me in the lineup,'' said Daubach. ``I can't tell you how much I owe
to Jimy for sticking with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams moved the rookie down in the order (from third to
seventh) in Saturday's Game 3 against the Yankees, and the move
paid immediate dividends when Daubach hit a two-run homer off
Hideki Irabu in the third inning to up the Sox' lead to 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened those three or four weeks,'' he
said of his mid-August slump. ``I might have been slumping a little
bit at first, but after that it really got to me mentally. I tried
to change so many things, and when you try to change too many
things, it gets to you. Then it really got to be mental with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus was born The Daubach Riddle.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 16, the first baseman-designated hitter was the American
League's hottest hitter, and that night against Oakland at Fenway
Park, with the Red Sox trailing, 5-3, the 27-year-old had one of
the most courageous at-bats in recent Boston memory. On a 3-2 count
with the bases loaded and two out in the ninth, Daubach drove a
pitch over the right-field foul pole for what appeared to be the
winning grand slam. It was called foul. But on the next pitch, the
ninth of his at-bat, Daubach drove the ball off the The Wall,
clearing the bases to give the Red Sox a 6-5 win, their most
dramatic comeback of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But as if by magic, Daubach's swing suddenly disappeared. As if
he were being punished by the baseball gods for his dramatic
heroics, Daubach could hit nothing over the next week and the weeks
after that. ``It was just a little slump at first,'' said Daubach.
But it grew and grew until it seemed a foul ball into the stands
constituted a quality at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't as tough as it might have been, because we were
winning,'' said Daubach. ``If we weren't winning, it would have
been much, much tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, following the Aug. 16 dramatics, Daubach was hitting
.339 and the Red Sox were two games ahead of Oakland in a tight
race for the AL wild card. When the season ended Oct. 3, Daubach
was down to .294 _ but the Red Sox had run away with the wild card.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach believes that his swing started to return in the
Cleveland series. ``This series is the same way,'' he said. ``I
started off a little bit slow, but I feel the same way: that my
swing is back.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes there's a fine line between slumping and success. In
Thursday's Game 2 at Yankee Stadium, Daubach hit two balls to left
field that ``were hit good but just didn't fall in,'' he said. ``I
don't know, in Fenway one might have been off The Wall and one
might have been a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, The Daubach Riddle has yet to be solved. When the
final game has been played and the final page turns, it may be
clearer whether Williams's loyalty to Brian Daubach has been a
winning strategy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
