<HEADER>
A9494 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SOXPLAYOFFS-VALEN     10-17 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SOXPLAYOFFS-VALENTIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTSEASON SPLURGE CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He wasn't trying to take Rawjuh out of the yahd. ``With a man on
third, I was just trying to hit a fly ball,'' shrugged John
Valentin, after the Rocket's red glare had faded over the Fens
Saturday night. ``I took a good swing _ and I hit a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   So it goes, so it has gone for the Red Sox third baseman ever
since the leaves began to turn. He beats Cleveland in Game 3 of the
Division Series to stop the flow of carmine blood. He knocks in
seven runs in Game 4, helps hang up ridiculous numbers on the
scoreboard and leaves the Indians shellshocked.
</P>
<P>
   And Saturday night, with Boston down two games to the Yankees
and hoping just to survive the weekend, Valentin jump-started his
mates with a two-run blow into the left-center-field screen mere
minutes into the first inning that knocked Roger Clemens back on
his heels and began one of the worst autumn days in New York
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has some impressive numbers in eight games in these
playoffs,'' said manager Jimy Williams, after Valentin had gone 3
for 6 and knocked in five runs to bring his postseason tally to
four home runs and 17 RBIs. ``And certainly, when you're down two
games and you can get a couple of runs up, that helps us a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so much the two runs that helped as much as their
stunning immediacy. All summer long, the Fenway faithful had
fantasized about the Sox socking it to Rawjuh in the ALCS. By the
time Clemens took the hill, the ballpark was spilling over with
pent-up emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman's leadoff triple, which right fielder Paul O'Neill
lost in the sun, doubled the decibel level. Up stepped Valentin,
hoping just to loft something deep enough to allow Offerman to tag.
``Being down 0-2, we knew we needed to get some runs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens ran the count to 2-2, then dealt Valentin a cross-seam
fastball away. ``But it ran like a two-seamer and it was up, too,''
Clemens said. ``He put it in the net.''
</P>
<P>
   And just like that, it was Christmas in October from Hartford to
Presque Isle, Maine _ and Clemens soon went pffft. ``You definitely
don't want to have a start like that,'' he said. ``At two runs,
you're fighting and clawing right then. Because we knew Pedro would
be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin wasn't done. His grounder to short scored Trot Nixon
with a third Red Sox run in the second inning. His single in the
fifth sent Darren Lewis home with the eighth run. And his single
off the wall in the seventh scored Nixon with the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   All of those, though, were merely bonus skyrockets to punctuate
Valentin's extraordinary autumnal fireworks show. A month ago he
was on the disabled list with patella tendinitis, wondering if his
season was finished. It was, actually, an unintended blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got some rest and found out what was wrong with my knee,''
said Valentin, who'll have surgery whenever this extended
summer-stock drama ends. ``I got physical therapy and started to
feel better. When the DL was up, I told Jimy that I wanted to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   He ended the season with a five-game hitting streak, and a week
ago Saturday his bat turned to gold. John Valentin has become Yaz
in 1967, Fisk in 1975, Hendu in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Is it a dream? ``Not really,'' Valentin says.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
