<HEADLINE>
OFFERMAN EARNING STRIPES AS A YANKEE KILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He set the tone in the first inning Saturday by ripping a fly
ball to right field that Paul O'Neill lost in the sun for a leadoff
triple.
</P>
<P>
   With one swing of his bat, Jose Offerman had taken some of the
luster off Roger Clemens's postseason return to Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman kept it up in the second when he lined a single to left
that kept a rally alive. Not that anyone should be surprised by
what Offerman did in the Red Sox' 13-1 victory over the Yankees in
Game 3 of the American League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman banged out 12 hits in 37 at-bats (.324) against Yankee
pitching during the regular season. Although most of the Red Sox'
bats cooled during the first two games of the ALCS in New York,
Offerman banged out five hits in his first 10 at-bats. He went 3
for 6 Saturday to keep his average at .500 for the series.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's game, Offerman is a sizzling 15 for 34 (.441)
in eight postseason games.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Offerman came to the Red Sox, he did well against
Yankee pitching, posting a career .300 average since he came to
Kansas City in 1996 in a trade from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret,'' said Offerman when asked about his success
against the Yankees. ``I don't call it luck or whatever. You never
feel comfortable when you face the staff the Yankees have. Maybe
it's good luck for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Offerman said the games' importance hasn't changed his approach
at the plate. ``You try and give a good performance,'' he said.
``You don't try and do anything different.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, he was delighted to start the game with a bang.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great when you get to score in the beginning,'' said
Offerman, who ripped Clemens's second pitch of the game into the
right-field corner.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman has done his best to silence critics who questioned the
Red Sox' sanity when he signed a four-year, $26 million deal as a
free agent.
</P>
<P>
   But from the start, Offerman proved he was worth the money,
worth the confidence Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette showed
when he signed him. It showed in his first game in a Red Sox
uniform, when he went 4 for 5 in an 5-3 over Kansas City on Opening
Day.
</P>
<P>
   He has shown it with his hitting, which was never really in
question, with a solid .294 season.
</P>
<P>
   But he also has made the defensive plays at second base, turning
what was supposed to be a weakness into a strength. Saturday he
made a leaping backhanded stab of a Bernie Williams line drive in
the top of the seventh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
