<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9496 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     10-17 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS LEFT TO FACE CURSE OF OLD AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is finished and doesn't know it yet. If someone decided to
remake ``Ghost'' with a sports angle, he could be the star. His
problem is that he looks in the mirror and still sees ``Roger
Clemens, The Rocket.'' Clemens and his mirror do each other a
disservice because ``The Rocket'' is a pitching artifact. A more
accurate reflection would be of a 37-year-old Clemens, ``Decent
Pitcher Who Used To Be Great.''
</P>
<P>
   If you don't believe that, all you have to do is listen to the
prayers of the New York Yankees this morning. They are praying that
their American League Championship Series with the Red Sox doesn't
go seven games. If it does, Clemens will face Pedro Martinez again.
The only way that would be a fair matchup is if you took a
computer-generated Clemens from 1986 and matched him with Martinez,
today's best pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens-Martinez Saturday at Fenway Park was hyped as a
heavyweight fight. The boxing analogy was perfect because just like
in boxing, the expected gem never materialized. It was a rout.
Clemens was in a position to give the Yankees a 3-0 series lead.
Instead, he lasted two-plus innings and gave up five runs. Jose
Offerman opened the game with a triple to right field. The next
batter, former teammate John Valentin, homered to left.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Clemens was done and most of the 33,190 fans in
the park knew it. Clemens told Yankees manager Joe Torre that he
had no problem pitching at Fenway. It was not the truth. He said he
has pitched in hostile places, such as Texas, so pitching here
would not be any different. It was not the truth. He said the crowd
chanting his name and a derisive ``Where Is Roger?'' did not bother
him. It did.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees eventually lost, 13-1. Clemens was so bad that he
couldn't even complete his mess; he handed the ball to Torre after
throwing a strike to Brian Daubach. None of this means the Yankees
will lose the next three games to the Sox and go home for the
winter. What it does mean is that Clemens is New York's problem
now.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees pitcher David Cone said he talked with Clemens and that
he was upset, ``but it wasn't like he was on a suicide watch.''
Cone also said that he told Clemens not to be upset because ``he
still has a chance to get the last laugh. He seemed to like that
one.''
</P>
<P>
   I like Cone. He is a smart man. But he knows better. If the Sox
and Yankees take this series to seven games and Clemens pitches the
last game, the Sox are going to the World Series. Clemens has
always been a fine regular-season pitcher. He hasn't been a
postseason bust because, as Yankees catcher Joe Girardi said, ``His
ERA in the playoffs is in the 3's. That's excellent for the
American League.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is not at a Martinez level. That's another reason
watching Clemens was like being in the Fenway wing of the Museum of
Fine Arts. He represents the old Sox, the Sox who were stars in the
regular season and OK in the playoffs. These Sox may not be the
most gifted players in the game, but you know where to find their
best players when games need to be won. What makes Martinez great
is that he shows up when you expect him to. What makes Nomar
Garciaparra great is that he plays hurt and drives in runs when his
team needs him. Clemens has never done things like that. And he
never will.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Clemens, dressed in a blue shirt that read
``Disney, Wide World of Sports,'' gave an equally interesting and
bizarre recap of his short afternoon in the Fens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I was making some good pitches,'' he said. ``They got
some good hits off some good pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after saying that, he began to operate the language as
only he can. ``Those guys are tough,'' he said of the Sox. ``I
think I know a couple guys in the opposing dugout too well. I think
a couple of them are too comfortable, to be honest with you,
against me. I have to make some changes there.''
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to be saying he is going to start brushing some guys
back. He was asked to clarify.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think I need to expand,'' he said. ``I just think some
guys are too comfortable and it is not a great feeling to have. I
just think some guys get too comfortable up there and you like to
expand and it is something I need to do more of.''
</P>
<P>
   He is finished and he doesn't know it. The Sox are comfortable
because Clemens does not scare them. That won't change if he
screams, brushes them back, or expands. Even the most loyal Yankee
fan roots for the uniform rather than the man when Clemens pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Some people tried to float theories of Clemens experiencing back
tightness and grimacing in the dugout to explain his wildness.
Torre was asked about that. ``I think the score was making him
grimace,'' the manager said. He also said of Clemens, ``I just
didn't think the stuff was there. That's as simplistic as it can
be.''
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner, who was not feeling well, was seen and
heard in the Yankee clubhouse Saturday night. He said that games
like this cannot happen often. But if the Yankees go to seven games
in this series and lose, it will be The Boss's fault. He had a
big-game pitcher in David Wells and traded him away. He acquired a
great regular-season winner who has never dominated in big games.
For at least one season, that is the Yankees' own curse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
