<DOCNO> NYT19991017.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9499 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-ALPLAYOFFS-PITCHE     10-17 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALPLAYOFFS-PITCHERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABERHAGEN VIES WITH PETTITTE FOR CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT AND BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are both playoff veterans, only they earned their
reputations in different decades. Control is their calling card,
overcompetitiveness their downfall. But the difference between
Sunday night's Game 4 starters is that the Yankees' Andy Pettitte
has already recovered from his worst stretch of the season; Bret
Saberhagen is hoping to do the same for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   After further review, Saberhagen has had the destructive quirks
of his last two outings scrutinized, analyzed, and documented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at the tapes and tried to iron out a couple of
things,'' said the veteran righthander, who was knocked around
liberally in his two starts against the Indians in the Division
Series. ``First, you've got to identify them, and then it becomes a
matter of making adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   A perfect 3-0 in September, Saberhagen was seen as a critical
piece of the pitching rotation when the Sox opened the playoffs. By
the end of the Cleveland series, he appeared to be in critical
condition.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 2, Saberhagen gave up six runs in 2 2/3 innings,
allowing five hits and an uncharacteristic three walks. After
giving up a career-low 11 walks all season, the veteran suddenly
had trouble finding the plate, and at times looked uncomfortable on
the mound. Saberhagen walked the leadoff hitter in the third
inning, ending a streak of 111 innings in which he had not issued a
free pass to the leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 5, he exited in the second inning after Wil Cordero
opened with a single and Travis Fryman followed with a home run.
The inning before, Saberhagen had given up a 477-foot blast to Jim
Thome. A craftsman since he broke into the majors in 1984, suddenly
he was getting blasted, heaving one fat pitch after another up to
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was rushing too much, being a little too quick with
my delivery, and that hurt me,'' said Saberhagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shoulder felt the best it's felt all year, and maybe my
velocity was too good. I've got to try to slow it down a little out
there and hit spots. That's how I'll be effective out there.''
</P>
<P>
   You want effective? How about the progression of Pettitte, who
went from trade bait to top rate in the span of a month.
</P>
<P>
   He lugged a burdensome 5-7 record and 5.59 ERA into the All-Star
break, and there was widespread speculation that when the schedule
resumed for the Yankees, Pettitte wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Pettitte he had two rather influential lobbyists
_ manager Joe Torre and pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre. And
miraculously, Yankees owner George Steinbrenner elected to follow a
policy based on something other than personal whim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was just Mel Stottlemyre and myself basically could
not shake the memory of how well he has pitched in the postseason
and in very important games,'' said Torre. ``Every time I was asked
for my opinion, we were strong in favor of keeping Andy. That
didn't mean we were going to keep him, but it got to a point where
George Steinbrenner said, `Well, it is going to be your decision.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, there was another season's reprieve for Andy Pettitte, New
York Yankee. He showed his gratitude by ringing up a 9-4 record and
3.84 ERA after the break. To reinforce Torre's argument, the
lefthander shackled Texas in Game 2 of the Division Series,
allowing seven hits and one run in 7 1/3 innings of a 3-1 victory
at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made the decision,'' said Torre of his lefthander, ``and
I'm glad we did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-99 0035EDT &QL; 
