<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9500 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SOXPLAYOFFS-NOMAR     10-17 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SOXPLAYOFFS-NOMAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA STAYS UP TO SPEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He had four hits, scored twice, drove home three teammates, and
added a home run and double to his already impressive postseason
resume.
</P>
<P>
   He also found time to leap high and snag a Scott Brosius liner
in the fifth, carbon-copying his scintillating plays in Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   For 3 hours 14 minutes Saturday afternoon at Fenway Park, Red
Sox shortstop Nomar Garciaparra provided the heart that
complemented Pedro Martinez's soul in a dominating 13-1 victory
over the Yankees in Game 3 of the American League Championship
Series in which both players played in pain.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra's sore right wrist, courtesy of Oriole Alberto
Reyes's inside pitch as the regular season wound down, was painful
enough to keep him out of Game 3 of the Division Series a week ago
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in addition to his usual ritual of adjusting his wristbands
between pitches, Garciaparra, between half-innings, changes the
protective bandage on his wrist, one for batting, one for fielding.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why he's a little bit later than the rest of those guys
going out on the field because he has to have a different tape
job,'' explained manager Jimy Williams after Saturday's 13-1
blowout of the Yankees in which Garciaparra added postseason home
run No. 4, his second against the Yankees. ``He just loves to play.
I think you all know that. He's a fine, fine player.''
</P>
<P>
   One who has played through the pain to the tune of 12 hits in 25
postseason at-bats (.480) with 3 doubles, 4 homers, and 9 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody is 100 percent at this stage of the
game,'' Garciaparra said when asked about his ability to bounce
back. ``You still have to go out there and play. As long as I'm
healthy enough, I'm going to keep on going out there.''
</P>
<P>
   He reached base five times Saturday, with the first trip a gift
from Yankee second baseman Chuck Knoblauch, who threw wildly past
first on Garciaparra's grounder.
</P>
<P>
   But there was nothing tainted about his next four trips _ a line
drive RBI double, a clean single to left, a base hit to right, and
a lofty drive over the Green Monster for a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra said he didn't feel any particular joy in watching
Roger Clemens take Saturday's loss. He was more concerned about his
team taking the win and perhaps changing the momentum of the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a matter of who was out there on the mound,'' said
Garciaparra. ``It was a matter of what we had to go out there and
do. That was the key. We just came out, swung the bats, and did
it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was clear that Game 4 of the ALCS was on Garciaparra's mind
before he even hit the Game 3 postgame shower.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game's over with. The score was irrelevant,'' said
Garciaparra. ``We have another game tomorrow. It's all about
winning. We want to keep playing. We're still down.''
</P>
<P>
   But hardly out, thanks in large measure to the gutsy everyday
leader of the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
