<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9501 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     10-17 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKET FIZZLES IN PLAYOFFS AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pedro's native tongue is Spanish, but the Rocket was the one
pleading, ``No mas.'' Does this make up for eight decades of
heartache? No, but it feels pretty damn good.
</P>
<P>
   Next time those annoying Yankee fans hit you with Bucky
(Bleeping) Dent, Mike Torrez, Harry Frazee, Jacob Ruppert, or
George Herman Ruth, drop a Roger Clemens on 'em.
</P>
<P>
   Folks will try to put a Curse Reverse spin on what happened at
Fenway Saturday and maybe that's not a bad idea. After taking it on
the chin from the New Yorkers for three generations, the Red Sox
rode the strong arm of Pedro Martinez and routed turncoat Clemens
and the Yankees, 13-1, in one of the most raucous, robust days in
the 88-year history of Old Fenway. It was the worst loss in the
long, proud history of Yankees postseason baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It was Cy Young vs. Cy Old (bumper stickers said so). It was the
man we once thought was the greatest Red Sox pitcher of them all .
. . against the man we now think is the greatest Red Sox pitcher of
them all. Roger and Pedro were going to put dueling doughnuts on
the board for eight or nine innings and maybe settle it by standing
behind home plate and seeing which one could throw a ball over the
Green Monster.
</P>
<P>
   But no. The fight of the century turned into Sonny Liston-Floyd
Patterson, at Comiskey Park, 1962. It was over before the afternoon
sun dropped over Mission Hill. It turned out to be Cy Sterling vs.
Sy Sperling.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro (seven innings, two hits, 12 strikeouts) performed as
expected. Not blessed with his best stuff on this day, he was the
lionhearted godson of Luis Tiant, spinning a beauty as Sox Nation
chanted his name.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, on the other hand, titillated his legion of detractors
with a sorry, two-plus innings that would have embarrassed Reggie
Cleveland or John Wasdin. Living down to his suspect postseason
past, the Rocket gave up five runs, six hits, and two walks before
he was mercifully lifted with no outs in the third. He is a
first-ballot Hall of Famer, but badly needs another chance to
redeem his playoff reputation. It must scare Yankee fans to think
of a potential seventh game featuring Pedro-Rocket Redux.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the man who pitched well said he had nothing. And the man
who was routed gave a clinic in denial.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro: ``I'm hurting and I'm not lying. I don't feel like I have
my fastball like I should. I strained my back muscle. I haven't had
time to get rest. I'm hurting every pitch I throw. The first
inning, I had exactly what I had the whole game. Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger: ``I felt great. Everything went pretty well in the
bullpen and I took it to the mound with me, too. From the second
inning on, I felt good. They got some hits off some good pitches.
Give those guys credit. They fought.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Sox leading, 10-0, in the seventh, Sox fans chanted
``Where is Roger?''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out he must have been visiting a hypnotist _ the only
person who could convince him that nothing dreadful had happened.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was not alone in Yankee misery. Paul O'Neill lost a
flyball in the sun and Chuck Knoblauch committed one of three
Yankee errors when he made a patented Steve Sax toss toward first
on a Nomar Garciaparra grounder. Meanwhile, the Yanks had no answer
for John ``Mr. October'' Valentin (five more RBIs) or the former
shoe salesman from Belleville, Ill., Brian Daubach (home run and
double). Boston cracked 21 hits (``I think a couple of 'em are too
comfortable against me, to be honest,'' warned Clemens).
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have got to win two of the next three now. They
cannot possibly want the Rocket vs. the Pocket Rocket in a seventh
and deciding game. Clemens through the years has been cut some
slack regarding his postseason performance (two wins in 11 starts),
but his Saturday flop at Fenway raises serious doubt about chances
in any Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thrown the ball well in postseason play,'' he said. ``I
wouldn't consider tonight one of those. I knew what I was up
against. Obviously, I would love to make a better showing. I hope I
don't have to pitch again, but if I do, I'll be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, what is left to say about the Dominican King? Unlike
Clemens in '86 (24-4), Pedro in '99 seems to be getting better in
October. He was shutting out the Indians in the Division Series
when he hurt his back in Game 1, came back to win Game 5 with six
innings of hitless relief, and Saturday struck out more batters
than any Sox pitcher in postseason history (which includes Babe
Ruth).
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will never forget Pedro's 17-strikeout, one-hitter
in the Bronx last month, possibly the best game ever pitched
against the Pinstripes. New York has zero runs, three hits, and 29
strikeouts in its last 16 innings against Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   When it got to 13-0, the chant was, ``Just Like Cleveland.''
Then came ``Hey, hey, hey . . . goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They can associate with these players,'' Sox manager Jimy
Williams said of the Sox fans. ``That's what I think. The people in
the community, they're in these uniforms, so to speak, even though
they're not playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely incredible. The Red Sox humiliated and embarrassed
the world champion New York Yankees. But try to remember that this
was only one game in a seven-game series. The New Yorkers still
lead, two games to one. It's not a good idea to gloat too much over
one game. After all, Pedro can't pitch every day. And unfortunately
for Boston, neither can Roger.
</P>
<P>
   Did Boston fans unleash too much venom and ridicule on the heads
of the Yanks? Perhaps. But after eight decades of Yankee-inflicted
pain, and seeing New York win 24 world championships since Boston's
last title, citizens of Red Sox Nation could not contain
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to blame 'em.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
