<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9506 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN--Mets-Braves-HNS &LR;      10-17 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--Mets-Braves-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Braves get an Olerud awakening
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ The laws of probability were destined to put an end to
this at some point.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, one of the New York Mets' big guns would start
firing. Likewise, the Atlanta Braves couldn't keep winning with a
popgun offensive attack. And what were the odds of John Rocker
continuing to shoot holes through conventional wisdom, especially
in a hostile environment?
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly inevitable was prolonged for another day _ maybe
three or four _ as the Mets rallied for a 3-2 victory over the
Braves on Saturday night at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who had won six consecutive playoff games, hold a
3-1 lead in the best-of-seven series, which continues today.
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud's two-out chopper off Ozzie Guillen's glove in the
eighth inning drove home two runs and ended the Braves' hopes of a
sweep. A crowd of 55,872 screamed their approval and hurled debris
onto the field after Rocker failed to deliver for the first time
this postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``The baseball gods have been on our side for three games,''
Braves third baseman Chipper Jones said. ``Tonight, they were on
the Mets' side.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Mets have a glimmer of hope _ something that
flickered on and off in Saturday's cliff-hanging game. Neither team
scored _ and barely anyone even hit safely _ until the sixth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were two lead changes, the last coming when Olerud
singled in two runs in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that no one has ever come back from 3-0, but we're not
trying to win three games at one time,'' Mets catcher Mike Piazza
said. ``We still have to win three games, so it doesn't look good,
but we just have to take small steps. Hopefully, this will change
the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to get any easier, but we're not just going to
lay over and die for them. We're going to battle until the very
end.''
</P>
<P>
   They did just that Saturday, with hard-throwing closer Armando
Benitez gunning down the Braves in order in the ninth to seal the
victory. That was a stage Rocker has dominated in the playoffs;
this time he missed out on another chance at glory by a matter of
inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried a lot of different approaches against him and
haven't had a lot of success,'' said Olerud, who was 0-for-9 with
five strikeouts in his career against Rocker. ``I was just trying
to get a good pitch to hit. I was looking for a fastball and trying
to adjust to the breaking ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Olerud's two-run single was anything but a scorcher, and it
would have been the third out of the inning had Guillen been
playing more toward second base.
</P>
<P>
   But with the flame-throwing Rocker on the mound, Guillen was
toward the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just hit it in the right place,'' said Guillen, who entered
the game in an eighth-inning double switch.
</P>
<P>
   Said Jones: ``If Ozzie would have been playing a half-step up
the middle, we're out of the inning. It's a helpless feeling. Our
guy was throwing 97 mph; Ozzie was positioned the way he should
have been, it just didn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' Greg Maddux will face Masato Yoshii today in a
rematch of the Game 1 starters, but they'll have to be on top of
their games to match Saturday's performances.
</P>
<P>
   The best pitcher's duel this series has seen was being waged
over the first five innings as the Braves' John Smoltz and Mets
counterpart Rick Reed matched zeros. Smoltz retired 13 of the first
14 batters he faced and Reed sat down 14 of the first 15 Braves who
took hacks at his deceptive assortment of pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz blinked first, allowing a two-out solo homer to Olerud in
the sixth inning. Olerud, who had two hits and no RBIs in his
previous 13 NLCS at-bats, crushed a 1-1 pitch over the right-field
wall to give the Mets a lead for only the second time in the
series.
</P>
<P>
   The thought of actually being in control of a game must have
sent the Mets into shock because two innings later they found
themselves in a familiar position _ trailing and facing the
unenviable task of rallying against a Braves bullpen anchored by
Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan blasted Reed's first pitch of the eighth inning
over the center-field wall and Klesko followed by launching a shot
to right field.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 808 feet later, the Braves held a 2-1 lead and
thoughts of champagne on ice no doubt danced through their minds.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the sixth time a team has hit back-to-back homers in
the NLCS and the first time since the Mets' Darryl Strawberry and
Kevin McReynolds did it in 1988. The Braves' late-inning magic put
a damper on an otherwise brilliant night for Reed, who only allowed
three hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have a total of six hits in the last two games and
are hitting .198 in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Braves manager Bobby Cox has made all the right moves this
postseason, but perhaps he should have given Smoltz the rest of the
night off after the Braves took a 2-1 lead in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Cox left Smoltz in to face Roger Cedeno, who opened the
inning with a base hit _ his third of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to throw him a cutter inside, it came back across the
plate, and he smacked it,'' Smoltz said.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno stole second and reliever Mike Remlinger walked Melvin
Mora before Cox called on Rocker. Mora and Cedeno pulled off an
uncontested double steal, which turned out to be a pivotal play in
the inning because it put the go-ahead run in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't have looked too good if we had gotten thrown out
at third,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine said. ``I know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, you just knew that wasn't going to happen on the Mets'
night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
