r a BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      10-17 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-CON SETTING BAR TOO LOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - Maybe it was the 17 years he spent in prison, or maybe
it was the seven he's been out, but James Hamm finally has reached
the point where he has absolutely no self-respect.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Otherwise, he'd never be a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   It's sad, really, because Hamm once showed promise.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, he pleaded guilty to the mur der of Willard J. Morley
Jr. during a botched drug deal. Of those days Hamm has said, ``My
problems were mostly with drugs; that was the core of the diffi
culty.''
</P>
<P>
   For his crime he received a life sen tence and was shipped off
to a maximum security prison, where he could have picked up where
he'd left off, dealing in drugs and death.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Hamm transformed himself from a coldblooded killer into
a reformed, educated man.
</P>
<P>
   He earned a college degree while in prison and began serving as
an advocate for other inmates. He studied the Eastern religion of
Taoism.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, his sentence was commuted by then-Gov. Rose Mofford,
who tried to back out of the deal when she started tak ing
political heat.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm wasn't bitter.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke of understanding the public's concern about releasing
someone who had done what he'd done.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Mofford's decision to rescind Hamm's commutation was
overturned by the courts, and Hamm was freed. &QL; 
SCORES FOR THE LAW
</P>
<P>
   He scored well enough on examina tions to be admitted to Arizona
State Uni versity's law school, from which he graduated.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, when Hamm's self-as surance was at its highest,
he tried to en ter the ranks of society's most valuable profession
_ teaching.
</P>
<P>
   He was offered the chance to instruct criminal-justice classes
at ASU until, once again, weak-kneed politicians caved in to public
pressure and reneged.
</P>
<P>
   It was suggested at the time that Hamm set his sights on a
profession in which honor and integrity don't mean much, in which
prison skills are more valuable than intellect, in which morality
is never a question, because no one has any.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, he chose the law.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Arizona Supreme Court announced that Hamm's name
was among the 436 applicants who had passed the Arizona Bar
examination.
</P>
<P>
   In order to become a practicing attor ney, however, Hamm first
must be ap proved by the Supreme Court's Committee on (I'm not
making this up) Character and Fitness.
</P>
<P>
   According to some of the state Bar's most esteemed members,
there's a good chance Hamm will be rejected.
</P>
<P>
   We can only hope. &QL; 
TODAY'S NEWSMAKERS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who reads the paper or watches TV is aware of lawyers
who've made the news over the past couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   There was the defense attorney who got videotaped at the county
jail while letting a client look too closely at her le gal briefs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Attorney General's Of fice went after a law firm
for running a bait-and-switch operation.
</P>
<P>
   And just last week, a county prosecutor got arrested and charged
with sexually exploiting minors on the Internet and having sex with
two teenage boys.
</P>
<P>
   It goes on.
</P>
<P>
   The state Bar itself made an out-of-court settlement two years
ago with a for mer secretary who claimed an official there had
``pinned her against a wall'' and pressured her sexually.
</P>
<P>
   Members of this fraternity now get to judge the character of
James Hamm, who told me Friday he would very much ap preciate the
Bar committee's approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be proud to practice law,'' he said. ``I'd like to be able
to do some good for the community and prove that people can, in
fact, turn their lives around.''
</P>
<P>
   The man has no self-esteem left.
</P>
<P>
   He needs support.
</P>
<P>
   He needs guidance.
</P>
<P>
   He needs to see that he's not only do ing himself a disservice
by attempting to hang around with these people, he may be violating
his parole. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini &LR; pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-99 0055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991017.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9508 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      10-17 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-CON SETTING BAR TOO LOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - Maybe it was the 17 years he spent in prison, or maybe
it was the seven he's been out, but James Hamm finally has reached
the point where he has absolutely no self-respect.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Otherwise, he'd never be a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   It's sad, really, because Hamm once showed promise.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, he pleaded guilty to the mur der of Willard J. Morley
Jr. during a botched drug deal. Of those days Hamm has said, ``My
problems were mostly with drugs; that was the core of the diffi
culty.''
</P>
<P>
   For his crime he received a life sen tence and was shipped off
to a maximum security prison, where he could have picked up where
he'd left off, dealing in drugs and death.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Hamm transformed himself from a coldblooded killer into
a reformed, educated man.
</P>
<P>
   He earned a college degree while in prison and began serving as
an advocate for other inmates. He studied the Eastern religion of
Taoism.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, his sentence was commuted by then-Gov. Rose Mofford,
who tried to back out of the deal when she started tak ing
political heat.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm wasn't bitter.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke of understanding the public's concern about releasing
someone who had done what he'd done.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Mofford's decision to rescind Hamm's commutation was
overturned by the courts, and Hamm was freed. &QL; 
SCORES FOR THE LAW
</P>
<P>
   He scored well enough on examina tions to be admitted to Arizona
State Uni versity's law school, from which he graduated.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, when Hamm's self-as surance was at its highest,
he tried to en ter the ranks of society's most valuable profession
_ teaching.
</P>
<P>
   He was offered the chance to instruct criminal-justice classes
at ASU until, once again, weak-kneed politicians caved in to public
pressure and reneged.
</P>
<P>
   It was suggested at the time that Hamm set his sights on a
profession in which honor and integrity don't mean much, in which
prison skills are more valuable than intellect, in which morality
is never a question, because no one has any.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, he chose the law.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Arizona Supreme Court announced that Hamm's name
was among the 436 applicants who had passed the Arizona Bar
examination.
</P>
<P>
   In order to become a practicing attor ney, however, Hamm first
must be ap proved by the Supreme Court's Committee on (I'm not
making this up) Character and Fitness.
</P>
<P>
   According to some of the state Bar's most esteemed members,
there's a good chance Hamm will be rejected.
</P>
<P>
   We can only hope. &QL; 
TODAY'S NEWSMAKERS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who reads the paper or watches TV is aware of lawyers
who've made the news over the past couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   There was the defense attorney who got videotaped at the county
jail while letting a client look too closely at her le gal briefs.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Attorney General's Of fice went after a law firm
for running a bait-and-switch operation.
</P>
<P>
   And just last week, a county prosecutor got arrested and charged
with sexually exploiting minors on the Internet and having sex with
two teenage boys.
</P>
<P>
   It goes on.
</P>
<P>
   The state Bar itself made an out-of-court settlement two years
ago with a for mer secretary who claimed an official there had
``pinned her against a wall'' and pressured her sexually.
</P>
<P>
   Members of this fraternity now get to judge the character of
James Hamm, who told me Friday he would very much ap preciate the
Bar committee's approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be proud to practice law,'' he said. ``I'd like to be able
to do some good for the community and prove that people can, in
fact, turn their lives around.''
</P>
<P>
   The man has no self-esteem left.
</P>
<P>
   He needs support.
</P>
<P>
   He needs guidance.
</P>
<P>
   He needs to see that he's not only do ing himself a disservice
by attempting to hang around with these people, he may be violating
his parole. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini &LR; pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
