<HEADLINE>
LOSSES PILE UP FOR DALLAS STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Stars defenseman Derian Hatcher looked down,
struggling to find words to express his frustration. ``When it
rains, it pours,'' he finally settled on. He had bigger problems
than a 3-2 loss to the Nashville Predators on his mind. An already
struggling and battered Stars bunch lost more than a game last
night, they lost two more key players to injury. Stars winger Jere
Lehtinen fractured his right ankle in the second period and will
have surgery today. He will miss six to eight weeks. Stars
defenseman Richard Matvichuk will have arthroscopic surgery on his
left knee today and will miss at least 10 to 14 days. The Stars
were already missing defenseman Shawn Chambers (out three months)
and forwards Grant Marshall (eight weeks) and Brian Skrudland
(three to four weeks). ``It's frustrating to be this early and to
try to come out of the funk we're in and have bodies going down
left and right,'' Stars forward Mike Modano said. Yes, what started
out as a simple loss to Anaheim on Oct. 8 has developed into a
full-fledged funk. The Stars are 1-3-1 in their past five games,
scoring seven goals in those games. The games have begun to play
like skipping CDs, too. Start slow, fall behind, mount a furious
comeback late, hope it's enough. ``You can't keep mounting
comebacks,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``It takes a lot of
energy.'' Not even a two-goal performance from Modano could save
the Stars from their slow start last night. By the time Modano
scored his first goal, the Predators had a 3-0 lead. Nashville's
second goal typified what Hitchcock has been complaining about when
he says the defending Stanley Cup champions aren't playing their
game. Stars defenseman Sergei Zubov had pinched in too deep and
committed a turnover, giving Nashville a 2 on 1. Predators winger
Scott Walker faked a slap shot to pull Stars goalie Manny Fernandez
out of position and then passed across the crease to an open Greg
Johnson for an easy goal at 12:40 of the first period. The
Predators had scored just two goals in the first and second periods
combined in their first five games this season. They had three last
night. Nashville's first goal came on the power play. Cliff Ronning
deflected a shot by Craig Millar between Fernandez's pad and the
post at 5:48 of the first period. The Predators' third goal was by
winger Ville Peltonen with 14:39 remaining in the second period.
``So the game isn't even halfway over and we're in a hole,'' Stars
winger Mike Keane said. ``So, you see, it's not really hard to
figure out what our problem is.'' The problem definitely isn't
chances. The Stars had a number of good scoring chances,
outshooting the Predators 38-27. The problem was finishing. Only
Modano was able to do that. His first goal was a result of hustle.
Predators defenseman Drake Berehowsky was going down to touch up
the puck for an icing call and a pursuing Modano instead caused him
to collide with Nashville goalie Mike Dunham. Stars winger Warren
Luhning, playing on the line because of Lehtinen's injury, instead
got to the puck and passed back to Modano, who popped the puck in
from the crease before Dunham knew what hit him. Modano's second
goal was a result of skill. He got behind Nashville's defense, took
a pass from Hatcher and proceed to bury a goal high and glove-side
on Dunham. ``Beside the start,'' Modano said, the sentence cutting
off. The start when compared with the finish was what made the game
that much more frustrating, a popular word in the Stars locker
room. ``I think we're bringing most of the frustration on
ourselves,'' Hatcher said. ``We haven't played well. Tonight's
actually been the best we've played in a little while here.'' And
the obstacles just got a little bigger.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
