<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RALLY INSPIRES THOUGHTS OF ANOTHER METS MIRACLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I might be completely off my Rocker, but let me be
the first to float this off-the-wall theory at you: If the Mets can
get a little help from the Great Weatherman in the Sky sometime
today, they might yet pull off the biggest comeback in Major League
Baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, I know. You figure I've overloaded on pastrami at the
Carnegie Deli or that I've spent too much time in the backseat of
New York cabs, dazed by drivers with unpronounceable names who
obviously bought their driver's licenses at the nearest convenience
store.
</P>
<P>
   You might be right. But admit it, you were sitting there with
the remote control in your hand last night, debating about whether
to change the channel after the Braves took a 2-1 lead in the
eighth inning at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   You knew in your heart of hearts that the Mets were done, that
the Atlanta brooms were four John Rocker outs away from the sweep,
and the only reason you didn't push the button was because you
wanted to watch the Braves' closer defiantly stick it to the Mets
and their fans one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Rocker went brain dead _ by most accounts, not exactly
a huge leap _ and the Mets, teetering once again on the brink of
extinction, yanked a heart-stopping 3-2 victory out of thin air.
</P>
<P>
   It could be the start of something big. Something huge. No team
in baseball history has ever come back from an 0-3 deficit in
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Much depends, believe it or not, on today's weather. It's
supposed to rain, starting at about game time, and continue through
Monday. If, say, the game was to be rained out after a couple of
innings and the Braves lost Greg Maddux's start ...
</P>
<P>
   OK, it's a reach, but isn't that exactly what this entire
improbable Mets' season has been? You know how these New York
stories go; they're always bigger than life.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets season was two innings away from being over last night
after Rick Reed, who had pitched superbly, suddenly coughed up a
1-0 lead by serving up back-to-back home runs to Brian Jordan and
Ryan Klesko leading off the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   With the dominating Rocker loosening up in the bullpen, Shea
Stadium immediately went on life support.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of things got kicked \Rin the dugout\S,'' Mets
manager Bobby Valentine conceded.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets once again refused to die.
</P>
<P>
   Consider these improbable events:
</P>
<P>
   A decision by Braves manager Bobby Cox would backfire; a risky
double-steal put on by Valentine would catch the Braves completely
by surprise, setting up John Olerud's game-winning hit; Rocker, to
the delight of the fans, would finally fail.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Cedeno led off the bottom of the eighth with his third
single off Braves starter John Smoltz and Melvin Mora, a
strangely-timed defensive replacement for Rickey Henderson in the
top of the inning, worked a two-out walk off reliever Mike
Remlinger.
</P>
<P>
   Cox waved for Rocker, who had split his time equally between
tormenting the fans and dominating the Mets. Someone in the stands
fired a bottle of water that skipped past him as Rocker ran in from
the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typical,'' he said later.
</P>
<P>
   Cox wanted Rocker to face Olerud, who already had accounted for
the Mets' only run of the night with a long solo homer off Smoltz
in the sixth. With the pitcher's slot due to lead off the next
inning, Cox made the logical double-switch, sending Ozzie Guillen
to replace Walt Weiss at shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker came to the mound with his usual swagger, but he forgot
one thing: the runners.
</P>
<P>
   So Valentine daringly put on the double-steal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we caught 'em a little bit by surprise,'' Valentine
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno and Mora were safe without a throw, setting the stage for
the dramatic finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't thinking about the runners at all,'' Rocker admitted.
``I was concentrating solely on the hitter. Those guys, you make a
mistake to Olerud and he hits one in the gap with two out, they're
going to score anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the runners both in scoring position, it didn't take a
gapper. Olerud, who hadn't touched Rocker the entire series,
chopped a 2-2 fastball back up the middle. It skipped of a lunging
Guillen's glove and rolled into center field as both runners scored
and the stadium erupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the cheaper hits I've ever given up in my entire
life,'' Rocker said. ``If Ozzie's playing one step over to the
left, that ball's fielded cleanly and the play's made and we're
three outs \Rin the ninth\S away from going to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I've let the fans get in my head, and I've gone
out there and thrown balls to the backstop or gone 3-0 on every
hitter. They think they're in my head, but I'm in their head.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but finally getting to Rocker was a huge psychological
boost for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as firing the team up, when Johnny got that hit tonight
it was amazing how pumped up that dugout was,'' Mets outfielder
Darryl Hamilton said, ``not only because we got the lead, but
because we got him. That's a good thing. That gets us going for
\Rtoday\S.''
</P>
<P>
   At least it keeps them alive for one more day.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if they can just get a little help from the Weatherman. ...
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
