<HEADLINE>
A NET FOR U.S. RETIREES IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RUSS WILES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) -Charles and Etta Carlis readily admit that the azure
waters, white sandy beaches and one-hour drive to Arizona were the
main reasons they chose to retire in Rocky Point rather than
another Mexican town. But it helps that Rocky Point also has
connections to the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet access was a determining factor,'' said Charles
Carlis, who moved there with his wife from Green Valley two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Carlises monitor their investment portfolio through an
online brokerage account, send e-mail to friends in the United
States and Europe, and make travel arrangements for periodic trips
to America and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really provides a window to the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although parts of Mexico still lack modern plumbing, electricity
and telephone service, the Internet has arrived in many sizable
cities and towns, as well as beachfront retirement communities like
Rocky Point and, farther south, San Carlos.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just a Sonoran phenomenon, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the American communities in Vallarta and Cabo, everybody
uses the Internet,'' said Bruce Greenberg, a real estate appraiser
with offices in Tucson and San Jose del Cabo, at the tip of the
Baja Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet's availability means that American retirees and
other expatriates can take advantage of the slower-paced,
less-costly lifestyle of a Third World nation while tapping into
the commercial, entertainment and informational pulse of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The computer revolution is making it easier for adventuresome
types to settle in exotic foreign locales, especially the first of
the graying baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey by New York-based Scudder Kemper Investments that
was released in late September, only 27 percent of respondents from
the World War II generation (people born before 1933) said they are
connected to the Internet. By contrast, 67 percent of baby boomers
said they are, as did 53 percent of the ``swing'' generation, those
born from 1933 to 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Most expatriates in the Sonoran beachfront communities already
had been in touch with the United States via television _ satellite
dishes are widespread _ along with English-language magazines and
newspapers such as The Arizona Republic. The Internet is a more
recent phenomenon, but one with potentially more impact because of
interactivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to book hotel rooms and concert tickets (in Santa
Fe) right from my home in this sleepy fishing village,'' Charles
Carlis said.
</P>
<P>
   Another invaluable use, as Clyde Berry has discovered, is
researching medical questions. Berry lives with his wife, Kat, and
four children in a white stucco house up a hill from the beach in
San Carlos, a resort and retirement town nearly 400 miles south of
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   He has artificial joints, as well as diabetes and other ailments
resulting from injuries suffered in Vietnam. Mexico's medical
infrastructure clearly is inferior to that of the United States,
but the Internet helps narrow the gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go online a lot to look up health information,'' said Berry,
a former job recruiter from Texas who receives a military
disability pension from the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear exactly how many of the estimated 600,000 Americans
living in Mexico are in Sonora. But expatriates figure there are
perhaps 2,000 permanent residents in the Rocky Point area and at
least 500 in San Carlos. Both communities are growing.
</P>
<P>
   Even for those with Internet access, most Americans head up to
Tucson or Phoenix occasionally to register vehicles, see doctors,
make major shopping hauls and conduct any banking they can't do
electronically or through the mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone down here is technically an Arizonan,'' Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   And there are several thousand more Americans who own property
along the Sonoran beachfront but don't live permanently in Mexico.
Many of these people also like having Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Baldwin, a professor at Arizona State University West, and
his wife, Connie, have had a vacation home in Rocky Point since
1991. Their dwelling lacks electricity, so they have learned to
make do on solar power and propane.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Internet arrived in Rocky Point, they decided to
purchase a small apartment in town, a room in a converted hotel,
that includes an electrical connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought it expressly so that I could go into town and spend
an hour on the Internet to get e-mail, dial into ASU or whatever,''
said Bruce, who teaches accounting.
</P>
<P>
   But although the Internet is making it easier to live in Mexico,
it's certainly not the reason people have relocated there. Water
recreation, a slower pace of life and a lower rate of violent crime
are among the main lures of the Sonoran coast for Americans, along
with a reduced cost of living.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say it's about 30 percent cheaper to live the same
lifestyle,'' said Jeff Reeco, a Realtor with Rocky Point
Reservations.
</P>
<P>
   A live-in maid, for example, costs less than $100 a week, and a
cavity can be filled for about $20, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Berrys say their six-person, two-cat household lives
comfortably on about $3,000 a month, including a mortgage payment
of $1,000, monthly private-school expenses of $60 per child and
meals that average about $1 per person.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, you can buy as many stalks of celery as you need,''
Clyde Berry said. ``You don't have to buy the whole bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   However, computers, television sets and other electronic goods
generally are more costly in Mexico than in the United States, and
so are Internet services. The Carlises say they spend about $280 a
year for Internet access, which includes about 100 hours of usage
each month, generally a higher rate than what's available
stateside.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Internet is opening up new possibilities for people
interested in living in Mexico, its arrival has been something of a
mixed blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Many part- and full-time expatriates say that they bought homes
in Sonora for the peace and quiet and that they don't fully welcome
modern technological intrusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't equipped our (beachfront) home for television
because we like to get away,'' Connie Baldwin said. ``We spend most
of our time down here reading books. What a concept!'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Russ Wiles can be reached at (602) 444-8616 or at
russ.wiles(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
