<HEADLINE>
TOMLINSON TOPS 1,000 YARDS FOR SEASON IN TCU ROMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ There may be a long, hard road ahead, but in
their first adventure as the official pariah of the Western
Athletic Conference, the TCU Horned Frogs came through with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   LaDainian Tomlinson crested the 1,000-yard mark at an earlier
juncture than any back in TCU history, both quarterbacks threw
touchdown passes, the defense created a couple of scores, and Tulsa
was buried, 56-17, before a crowd of 27,957 at Amon Carter Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And so, after two consecutive blowout victories, the Frogs (3-3,
2-1 Western Athletic Conference) may have created the proper surge
for a trip to Houston next week and a showdown with league-leading
Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're getting close to being where we want to be,''
coach Dennis Franchione said. ``But when we're ready to start
talking about a championship race, I'll let you know.''
</P>
<P>
   It was another disaster for the Golden Hurricane, (1-5, 0-3)
which lost its fifth consecutive game, in addition to its best
players on offense and defense _ quarterback Michael Wall and
linebacker Ashon Farley _ both of whom departed with knee injuries.
</P>
<P>
   For TCU, it was a night on which almost everything worked, no
matter what.
</P>
<P>
   On an 80-yard run that gave TCU the lead for good in the second
quarter, Tomlinson _ who scored four times and had 178 yards on 16
carries _ was afraid he had stepped out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the pitch, and it seemed like the line had kind of
walled off the defense,'' he said, ``and I saw a little seam and
took the sideline. I didn't know if I had stepped out, but I didn't
hear a whistle so I just kept running.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomlinson eventually cut back inside cornerback Todd Franz for
the score that put TCU ahead, 14-10, with 3:04 left in the half. He
finished the evening with 1,060 yards in six games, surpassing
Kenneth Davis _ who was watching from the sidelines _ as the
quickest Frog to reach that plateau. Davis did it in seven games in
1984.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Shannon Brazzell intercepted a pass at the Tulsa
15, returned to the seven, and set up a 5-yard touchdown run by
Patrick Batteaux for a 21-10 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs, who had the ball for only 24:44 in the game, then
scored 35 points in the third quarter. Almost nothing could go
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   On a 50-yard scoring pass to Mike Scarborough, quarterback Casey
Printers thought he had created a collision.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I faked to LT, I saw the safeties coming up, so I threw
to Mike,'' he said. ``Then I saw Kevin Brown going over into the
same area, and I said, `No! No! get out of there.' ''
</P>
<P>
   No problem. Scarborough made the catch, shook off Franz, and
scored easily.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, LaTarence Dunbar was rushing the Tulsa punter and
fell down. But Chad Bayer managed to block the punt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I jumped up, and the ball hit me in the face mask,'' Dunbar
said, ``so I just ran it in for the score \R10 yards\S.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the game, Scarborough caught another touchdown pass
_ 15 yards from Batteaux _ and Tomlinson scored twice more. It was
56-10 going into the fourth quarter, and Franchione cleared the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had two unfortunate injuries, and I feel bad for them,''
Franchione said of Tulsa, which managed only 216. ``We really made
good use of our time with the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it looks a little strange. In weighing time of
possession against points, always take points.''
</P>
<P>
   With Batteaux rushing for 77 yards, Dunbar adding 45 on four
reverses and Printers throwing for 94, the Frogs managed 465 yards
in 56 plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing better offensively, Casey is getting more
comfortable, and LaTarence is becoming a weapon,'' Franchione said.
``We've played so well lately, I don't know how to act.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
