<SLUG> BC-FBC-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEREVER IT WAS, TCU IS BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ You're not going to believe this, but there
was a fleeting stretch in last night's TCU gigglefest where it
actually looked like the visitors could win.
</P>
<P>
   Saw it myself.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be an illusion, of course. Just more Stupid WAC
Tricks.
</P>
<P>
   LaDainian Tomlinson took a second-quarter pitchout, crossed
through several time zones, and that was that. The Horned Frogs
were on their way to harnessing the Tulsa Golden Hurricane, 56-17,
and launching an atmospheric mini-disturbance of their own.
</P>
<P>
   They're back. Back in the Western Athletic Conference hunt. But
don't expect them to say that _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a topic,'' head coach Dennis Franchione announced. ``I'll
let you know when we're ready to talk about that.''
</P>
<P>
   They're back, though nobody can really say where they're back
from, nor whether they were ever on the brink of that perch to
begin with.
</P>
<P>
   In two weeks of playing at Amon Carter Stadium, the Frogs have
outscored guests, 98-17, and leveled their season record at 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing about these two weeks is that we came home and
got back to playing TCU football,'' Franchione said. ``There has
been a confirmation of some things about ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Their faith had been shaken, in other words. The Frogs had
failed to finish the job in a season-opening loss to nationally
ranked Arizona. A punchless 10-point loss to a very beatable
Northwestern team came the next week.
</P>
<P>
   But in the WAC, it isn't over until it's over. And even then,
there are still two more time zones to go through.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, here we were in the first quarter last night, watching the
Golden Hurricane blow through like a bad cold front. For 15 curious
minutes, Tulsa's John Mosley, not Tomlinson, looked like the
nation's leading ground gainer, and Hurricane quarterbacks were 6
for 6 through the air.
</P>
<P>
   But something possessed Tulsa quarterback Michael Wall to call
his own number on a third-down play at the TCU 14. The Frogs'
Reggie Hunt met him head-on at the 6, and Wall didn't get up.
</P>
<P>
   Wall had injured a knee, putting the night in the hands of
heralded freshman Josh Blankenship. Whatever edge that the
Hurricane had was swiftly lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had two really unfortunate injuries,'' Franchione
graciously noted. ``We didn't expect to get 56. We expected it
would be a close game.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's the WAC for you. A little defense can get you a long
way. In two weeks, you can be exactly where Fresno was.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs are back. Wherever they were.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious of the differences are Tomlinson and freshman
quarterback Casey Printers. Except for the night when Fresno State
swaddled him in attention, Tomlinson has run with increasing
confidence each week. Printers, meanwhile, seems to have come miles
since his anxious debut at Northwestern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't reach into my pocket and hand him experience,''
Franchione said.
</P>
<P>
   And he's right. But Fran still was the one who was wary about
handing the keys to a freshman in the first place. Franchione
selected senior Patrick Batteaux to quarterback his team against
Arizona and Northwestern.
</P>
<P>
   A bad decision? Hindsight would look at TCU's 1-3 start and
conclude yes. But there are hundreds of college coaches who would
start a senior over a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Printers' best moment last night was a 50-yard scoring pass to
receiver Mike Scarborough. Batteaux remains the option specialist,
but when Printers sprints out, defenses seem to thin quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing a few things he didn't do in the first few weeks,''
Franchione assessed. ``And I think he's going to play better and
better.''
</P>
<P>
   And none too soon, because there are more Stupid WAC Tricks just
ahead. With Fresno State losing to SMU and, in effect, coming back
to the conference pack, the Frogs find themselves on a collision
path with ... well, Rice.
</P>
<P>
   The WAC's big game next week _ are you sitting down, Darrell
Royal? _ is going to be TCU at Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Based upon last night, the Frogs appear ready over the next two
weeks to tackle the WAC's rugged outback, which in this case is
downtown Houston and Honolulu. They have the nation's most
productive running back. They have the league's best scoring
defense. They have found their quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   They're back. Back from Northwestern. Back from Fresno.
</P>
<P>
   And where to now?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
