<HEADLINE>
NHL FANS SHOULDN'T NEED A LOAN FOR TICKETS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jennifer Floyd 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Welcome to Nassau Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Come on in. Sit down wherever. Plenty of seats to choose from,
well, at least there were last game.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, when the New York Islanders played a game against the
Atlanta Thrashers on Thursday night, 5,219 tickets were sold for
the game. However, a turnstile count showed only 3,062 were in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Nassau Coliseum holds 16,297 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Want to take a stab at why?
</P>
<P>
   Simple numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Not win, losses or goals scored, but P.P.T. That's price per
ticket, and the NHL leads the four major sports in the average
P.P.T. according to a survey published by Chicago-based Team
Marketing Report, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it costs more to go to an NHL game than an NFL, NBA or MLB
game.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL led the pack last year, but in a strong off-season move
the NHL passed them. Commissioner Gary Bettman has to be so proud.
</P>
<P>
   The average P.P.T. in the NHL is $45.70 this season compared
with $45.63 for the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two important factors continue to play into the continuing
increase in NHL ticket prices,'' said Matthew Freedman, editor of
Team Marketing report. ``First, teams obviously are trying to keep
pace with escalating player and operational costs. Second, a
significant amount of NHL teams consistently sell 80 percent or
more of their tickets, so they have yet to see any significant
price resistance from fans.''
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Maple Leafs lead the league in P.P.T., averaging a
cool $69.92 a ticket to see the Maple Leafs. That's U.S. dollars,
too. The Calgary Flames are the cheapest, averaging a $27.85 a
ticket. The Stars rank sixth with an average ticket price of
$50.87. If you want to bring your family of four with two small
beers, four small Cokes, four hot dogs, two caps, two programs and
parking, the price tag will be $272.99. The league average is
$254.58.
</P>
<P>
   Can you say loan?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and by the way, the Islanders rank 26th in the NHL in P.P.T.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets? $34.68.
</P>
<P>
   Beer? $5.50.
</P>
<P>
   Parking? $5.50.
</P>
<P>
   Cap? $15.00.
</P>
<P>
   Staying home and watching ``ER''? Priceless.
SPOTLIGHT
Jill Johnson Luc Robitaille, shown taking a shot against Ed
Belfour, has quietly moved to the early lead in the NHL scoring
race.
Robitaille makes noise as scorer, no kidding
Before this season started, everybody wanted to know who was going
to take Wayne Gretzky's spot as one of the best scorers.
</P>
<P>
   The answer would come in the statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Well, coming into this weekend, Los Angeles Kings forward Luc
Robitaille was second in the NHL in scoring with seven goals and
three assists.
</P>
<P>
   Luc Robitaille?
</P>
<P>
   There isn't a mistake. Heck, he's only 20 goals short of tying
Maurice ``Rocket'' Richard's total of 544. ``I didn't know that,''
Robitaille said. ``That certainly was the guy, you know, he's
certainly a special player. He's more than a player to most of us
back there. To be near him in any kind of statistic is pretty
special. It certainly would be an honor if I could pass him.''
</P>
<P>
   The honor is even bigger considering where Robitaille had fallen
during his three non-LA seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He began his career with the Kings in 1986 and in his first
eight seasons he had 803 points, including a 63-goal, 62-assist
season in 1992-93. But in 1994-95, he went to Pittsburgh and then
spent the following two seasons after that with the New York
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996-97, he played in 69 games and amassed 48 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were tough years in New York,'' Robitaille said. ``You
know, it was one of those situations where I didn't get injured for
like eight or nine years in a row. Then suddenly, for like three or
four years in a row, I got injured every time I turned around, it
seemed like. It was just a tough situation there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then, yet, I learned a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Luc Robitaille that returned to the Kings last season and
started this season on such a tear wasn't the same one that left.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't a 50-goal scorer anymore, but then again hardly anybody
is.
</P>
<P>
   What is a good goal scorer nowadays?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. You'd have to go to arbitration and find out,''
Robitaille joked. ``I don't know what the title is, but I do know
that scoring 30 goals today is a lot different than the way it was
seven or eight years ago. It's a lot harder.''
</P>
<P>
   He almost a fourth of the way there.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:In quotes Chicago Blackhawks coach Lorne Molleken on
the effect getting sucker-punched in the left eye on Sept. 25 by
Washington general manager George McPhee has had on him and the
Blackhawks:
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation with Washington took some focus away from what
we wanted to do. Maybe our intensity level dropped a bit. ... The
Washington thing was very, very hard. Rather than focusing on the
team, the focus was on that. I'm still wondering why it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars forward Jamie Langenbrunner on the team's 25-minute,
closed-door meeting after Wednesday's 2-0 loss to San Jose:
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of meetings around here.''
</P>
<P>
   San Jose Sharks coach Darryl Sutter on his goalie Steve Shields,
who stopped 51 shots against Nashville and had a 141-minute,
46-second scoreless streak this week:
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone called and said if Boston pitched Pedro Martinez every
game, they'd win every one. That's how I feel about Steve
Shields.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Around the NHL From the get-over-it files: As the
banner commemorating the Buffalo's Eastern Conference playoff
championship reached the rafters of Marine Midland Arena during its
home opener on Oct. 8, the 18,690 Sabres fans in attendance started
chanting, ``No goal, no goal, no goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The outburst, of course, was in reference to Stars winger Brett
Hull's Stanley-Cup clinching goal in overtime of Game 6 of the
Stanley Cup Finals. Buffalo contends Hull's skate was clearly in
the crease and the goal shouldn't have counted. The NHL changed the
rule during the off-season, a good time for Sabres fans to maybe
move on.
</P>
<P>
   The last undefeated team in the NHL no longer is undefeated.
When Phoenix defeated Ottawa, 4-3, on Thursday, the Senators became
like everybody else. Of course, the league isn't without winless
teams. The Buffalo Sabres, the Boston Bruins, the Philadelphia
Flyers and the Chicago Blackhawks have yet to defeat anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Fax machines all over the NHL were buzzing this week. Edmonton
forward Bill Guerin said since the Oilers can't afford to sign him
they need to trade him. Edmonton general manager Glen Sather wasn't
talking, but that didn't stop Guerin's camp from jamming the fax
lines announcing his availability. The problem? Sather is ornery
and has time on his side. The issue? Guerin wants $3.5 million a
season. The Oilers are offering $2.5 million. He made $1.5 million
last season. Look for this to drag on for a while.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Inside the numbers \Nsubheds:Faster scoring Between
debate about injuries to big-time players and suspensions, the
actual game of hockey has been lost. Yet, according to numbers
compiled by the Elias Sports Bureau, the game has actually been
higher-scoring and faster-paced than last season. Here's a look at
how the first 13 days of last season compare with the first 13 days
of this season: Category 1999 1998 Goals per game 5.2 4.6 Shots per
game 56 54.5 Penalty minutes per game 31.4 36.5
nn
</P>
