<SLUG> BC-REEVES-INSIDERS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS RANGERS FANS SILENT IN FACE OF BREAKING UP TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Until proved otherwise, I'll consider Rangers fans'
generally apathetic reaction to the potential breaking up of their
team a case of Post-Yankees Shock Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain the universal yawn when owner Tom Hicks,
less than 24 hours after the Rangers had faded meekly into the
October night for a second consecutive season, announced that
sweeping changes are coming for next season, including the likely
trading of Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   That's future ``Hall of Famer'' Juan Gonzalez, in case you've
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Hicks' response was just your typical knee-jerk reaction
to another devastatingly disappointing Rangers October, but he
sounds like he's serious.
</P>
<P>
   So get ready to say goodbye to the team that just won a
franchise-record 95 victories and won the American League West for
the third time in four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, here are a few questions to mull around while we wait
for general manager Doug Melvin to start gutting his team:
</P>
<P>
   Q _ How do you trade your two-time MVP and cleanup hitter, let
your second baseman, third baseman and center fielder become free
agents, talk about trading your first baseman/DH (Lee Stevens),
replace at least three of them with rookies and convince your fans
that now you're ready to beat the Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   A _ Can you say 85 wins and goodbye playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   Q _ Since the payroll might drop by as much as $15 million, this
means a big cut in ticket prices, right?
</P>
<P>
   A _ Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   Q _ Does this mean that Hicks, portrayed as the first real
``Daddy Warbucks'' the Rangers have ever had, likes the Stars more
than he does his baseball team?
</P>
<P>
   A _ I know, the Stars won the Big One and the Rangers only won
division titles three of the past four years. If Mike Hargrove can
be fired after winning five consecutive division titles,
everybody's vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Q _ Has anyone with the Rangers asked Rafael Palmeiro, who
thought he was signing a five-year deal with a perennial contender,
how he feels about the team trading Gonzalez and the other proposed
changes?
</P>
<P>
   A _ I didn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   Q _ Finally, if the Rangers trade Gonzalez, who drives in their
only run every October?
</P>
<P>
   A _ Oh yeah, I forgot. We won't have to worry about October.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, I'm not saying that the Rangers don't need to shake things
up some. But with 11 free agents already on the roster, including
Todd Zeile, Mark McLemore and Tom Goodwin, change was already
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not even totally opposed to trading Gonzalez _ though I get
this sick feeling in the pit of my stomach when I think about him
playing somewhere else _ if the right deal (solid starting pitcher,
decent young outfielder and at least one hotshot prospect) is out
there.
</P>
<P>
   I'd just feel better about it if that decision hadn't been made
while the bitter taste of another Rangers failure against the
Yankees was still sour in everyone's mouth.
</P>
<P>
   One lesson Hicks could learn from Jerry Jones: Never let your
money get mad. Have we already forgotten how much better it is to
get to the playoffs, no matter how brief the stay, than it is to
not get there at all?
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Greer for the defense No one was more astounded at the
criticism he received for his defensive play against the Yankees
than was Rusty Greer, who lost a line drive in the lights in Game 1
and couldn't catch up to Scott Brosius' double off the wall in Game
2. It was that drive, dissected on TV replays, that brought most of
the criticism down on the Rangers' left fielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why that play was ever an issue,'' Greer says.
``When the ball was hit, I thought I had a play on it. I got a good
jump on it. Halfway there, I thought I could get it. Three-quarters
of the way there, I still thought I had it. It just flat beat me to
the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like I jumped and then it hit the wall. It hit
before I could get there. I jumped because I was in no-man's land.
I'd already committed and couldn't back out. But as it turned out,
I had no chance.''
\Nsubheds:Raffy rejects ESPN ESPN approached Rangers first baseman
Rafael Palmeiro about doing some color analysis during the ALCS,
but he rebuffed the offer because the invitation came when the
Rangers were down 0-2 to the Yankees and he didn't want to be
thinking about anything but Game 3.
\Nsubheds:It's a stickup Besides the $2 million upfront fee that
TCU will fork over to become a member of Conference USA, the Frogs
must also compensate other league members for lost revenue in its
first five years, due to the conference financial pie being divided
up in smaller pieces with the addition of another team. That
stipulation didn't faze TCU's commitment, a source close to the
negotiations says, because the school figures the extra money
brought in by more TV appearances, wider national exposure, etc.,
makes it a wash.
\Nsubheds:No golden tones One more reason to hate New York: Robert
Merrill can't sing any more. Somebody needs to tell him.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, I know, he still sings better at Yankee Stadium than the
Rangers play there.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Wilt no dummy Memory lane: Remember when Wilt
Chamberlain was going to climb into the ring to fight Muhammad Ali?
He wisely changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the time Wilt made a cameo appearance as a
warrior captain in ``Conan the Barbarian''. His assignment: Make
sure the king's daughter reached her destination safely and with
virginity intact. Insert 20,000 laughs here.
</P>
<P>
   May all of Wilt's free throws hit nothing but net.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Millennium curse Sign at Yankee Stadium during Game 2
of the Yankees-Red Sox series: ``The Curse of the Bambino is Y2K
compliant.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:A time to boo Giants linebacker ``Jessie Armstead''
has asked fans, as a personal favor, to try to refrain from booing
the team's offense until halftime against the Cowboys tomorrow
night. After that, it's fair game. ``If they ain't clicking by
halftime,'' Armstead says, ``it's off my back and I take that favor
back. Just don't boo me.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:`Marv'elous NFL TV analyst Marv Levy on whether Tampa
Bay's coaching staff has been too restrictive on quarterback Trent
Dilfer: ``You have to be able to take some chances. If Michelangelo
had wanted to play it safe, he would have painted the floor of the
Sistine Chapel.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Sick with the `Philly's' ``The Philadelphia
Inquirer'', quoting a caller to a local radio talk show the day
after Michael Irvin was injured: ``The only thing that would have
made me happier is if it would have been a coffin, not a stretcher,
coming out.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe fans in Philadelphia should get annual frontal lobotomies
like the rest of us get flu shots.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Top `Hoosier' gone ``Hoosiers'', released in 1987, is
one of my top five all-time favorite sports movies. Gene Hackman
was brilliant as the relentless, driven coach of Hickory High in
rural Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was inspired by the tiny Milan High School team of
1954, which won the Indiana state championship competing against
much larger schools. Hackman's character was loosely based on head
coach Marvin Wood, who died last week at 71, a victim of bone
marrow cancer.
</P>
<P>
   One more standing O', please, for Coach Wood.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Revo's rimshots
</P>
<P>
   One question for The Official Timekeeper: Aren't Jesse Ventura's
15 minutes about up?
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks owner Ross Perot Jr.: ``It's going to take something
odd for me to make a \Rcoaching\S change in the middle of the
season.'' Something odd? Hasn't Junior noticed that the Mavericks
already employ more international peacekeepers than the United
Nations?
</P>
<P>
   Just in case you were wondering, Wilt Chamberlain was nicknamed
``The Big Dipper'' because he had to duck under low-hanging pipes
in the gym where he learned to play basketball as a kid, not
because of the alleged sexual exploits he once bragged about.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance at that Cowboys-Eagles game last weekend: ``66,6''69.
No wonder the Philly crowd was acting a little devilish.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers president Jim Lites has been spotted at the team's
instructional league camp in Florida. Perfect. I suggest starting
with, ``This is a baseball ...''
</P>
<P>
   This just in: The rest of the American League West has voted to
unanimously support Tom Hicks' decision to nuke the Rangers.
Hmmmmm.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
