u s BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-BOS &LR;      10-17 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS LIVE ANOTHER DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The . . . Mets live. The . . . Mets live.
</P>
<P>
   Mets first baseman John Olerud had been struggling at the plate.
But he broke out in a big way Saturday &UR;  &LR; night at Shea Stadium. And
as a result, New York stunned the Atlanta Braves, 3-2, to avoid a
sweep in the National League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Was it a breakthrough game, Mets manager Bobby Valentine was
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't win, obviously it doesn't allow us to play
(Sunday),'' Valentine said. ``That makes it a great breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have been a resilient team all season and they did it
again Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   They were nearly knocked out of the playoff picture by the
Braves when they lost five of six games in late September.
</P>
<P>
   They still face a huge task. But at least they get to play
another day.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux will be on the mound for the Braves Sunday, opposed
by Masato Yoshii of the Mets in a pitching rematch of Game 1, won
by Atlanta, 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were down, 2-1, and staring down the end of their
season after Brian Jordan and Ryan Klesko finally got to starter
Rick Reed for consecutive home runs to open the eighth inning. Down
to their final four outs, the Mets were left to face fireballing
lefthander John Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Cedeno led off with his third single, but Rey Ordonez
popped up a sacrifice bunt for the first out.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Remlinger relieved starter John Smoltz and struck out Benny
Agbayani. But a walk to Melvin Mora put two men on.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker came on to face Olerud, who struck out against the closer
in Games 1 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   On a 1-and-1 pitch, Cedeno and Mora pulled a double steal to
move up to second and third.
</P>
<P>
   Three pitches later, Rocker made his first mistake of the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fastball, down and away,'' he said. ``Right where I wanted
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Olerud went after it. Topped it. And it headed up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Ozzie Guillen couldn't reach the ball with his glove.
Olerud had a two-run single and the Mets had a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good hitter,'' said Rocker. ``He didn't hit it well.
But he hit it well enough. It's kind of that old saying, he hit it
where we weren't. He didn't get a good piece of it, but he got it
through. It counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Armando Benitez came on in the ninth and closed the Braves out.
Guillen lined out to right field, Gerald Williams flied out to
right, and pinch hitter Keith Lockhart struck out to end it.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud had just two hits in 13 at-bats in the series when he
came up in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   And he crushed a Smoltz offering for a solo home run to right
field and a 1-0 Mets lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves, who turned Game 2 around over the course of just
a few pitches, did it again.
</P>
<P>
   Reed was cruising along with a one-hitter until the eighth.
Jordan crushed the first pitch of the inning for a homer to
left-center field. Reed threw a ball to Klesko before the first
baseman hit a fastball out the other way.
</P>
<P>
   Three pitches, two home runs, and the Mets' 1-0 lead was
suddenly a 2-1 hole. That was it for Reed, and Turk Wendell got the
Mets out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   But things were looking mighty bleak.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt about it,'' Reed said. ``But (Olerud's hit) squeaked
through. At a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   A very good time for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they must win Sunday to send the series back to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to beat us three more times and they've only
beaten us four times all year. Yes, I'm still confident,'' Rocker
said.
</P>
<P>
   But at least the Mets are alive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
