<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASSELBECK-DEWALT COMBINATION A LOCK FOR BC 
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-PITTSBURGH-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was a doubleheader of delirium.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day the Red Sox _ playing a few stops down the Green
Line _ resuscitated their playoff hopes with a resounding thumping
of the Yankees, Boston College's football team gave new life to its
season with a 20-16 victory over the Pittsburgh Panthers
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night before 33,527 at Alumni Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing missing from the celebration of BC's fifth
victory was Lou Bega's ``Mambo No. 5'' over the sound system.
</P>
<P>
   Scratched as the starter because of a mild right shoulder
separation, quarterback Tim Hasselbeck came off the bench with
10:17 remaining in the third quarter when Brian St. Pierre suffered
a concussion and threw the winning touchdown, a 36-yarder to
Dedrick Dewalt with 1:48 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that, for once, we made a play when we
needed a play,'' said BC coach Tom O'Brien, whose Eagles improved
to 5-1, 2-1 in Big East. ``A great catch by Dewalt down the
sideline and then the defense really came up big there in the last
series. We hung around and we hung around. When the opportunity
came we made a play, and that's the difference in the football
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasselbeck completed 13 of 24 for 202 yards and two touchdowns
to outshine Pitt sophomore David Priestley, who relieved starter
John Turman and completed 20 of 30 for 291 yards and one touchdown.
Priestley was harrassed by a rabid BC defense _ in particular
senior tackle Chris Hovan (8 tackles, 2 sacks, 1 forced fumble, 2
hurries). Hovan and company pressured Priestley, particularly on
Pittsburgh's last series, which ended when a 26-yard completion to
Antonio Bryant on fourth and 28 from the Pitt 10 came up short.
</P>
<P>
   Hasselbeck twice connected with Dewalt (5 catches, 90 yards) for
touchdowns, including a 35-yard strike that lifted BC to a 13-13
tie with 1:54 left in the third quarter. But Nick Lotz gave the
Panthers a 16-13 lead with 13:17 to go on a 25-yard field goal, his
third of the game after converting a pair of 29-yarders. Hasselbeck
then touched off the wild celebration by hitting Dewalt with the
winner.
</P>
<P>
   When he dropped back on the play and saw Dewalt facing press-man
single coverage, Hasselbeck tried to look off the safety at
midfield ``and push him as far to the left as I could with my
eyes,'' he said. ``Once I felt like I needed to get rid of the
ball, with the protection letting up, I knew where I was headed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just one of those things, where I just trusted that he
was going to be there. I knew he was going to be there for me.
Shoot, Ded and I have done it about 300 times when no one's been
looking, so it was about time we did it when someone was.''
</P>
<P>
   Dewalt, sitting next to Hasselbeck, smiled in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pretty much saw the same thing as Tim,'' Dewalt said. ``I
just knew it was press-man coverage and I knew if I could win at
the line (of scrimmage) then it would be 6. I knew Tim was going to
make a great throw and I knew I just had to do my part and make the
catch.''
</P>
<P>
   It absolved Dewalt of a drop he had three plays earlier when he
and Hasselbeck tried to connect from 55 yards out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That ball went right through my hands,'' Dewalt said. ``I
hadn't forgotten about the play, but I knew I had to make something
big because I didn't want to go back to my room tonight thinking
about that same play. So I knew I had to do it not just for myself,
but for the team and the defense because they played a hell of a
game tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Hovan led the charge of BC's defensive brigade, which held the
Panthers to 391 yards total offense and stepped up its play when
Priestley tried to engineer a last-minute drive. Priestley found no
refuge in the pocket when he was sacked on back-to-back plays,
forcing the fourth and 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this was the most excited locker room since I've been
here,'' Hasselbeck said. ``Even the Hawaii game, when Chris (Hovan)
and I were freshmen (in 1996). It's a good lift for us, because one
thing Coach O'Brien said was, `Don't let Temple beat you twice,'
meaning don't dwell on last week. We didn't do that and now we've
got to get ready, because we've got some really tough opponents
(Miami and Syracuse the next two weeks) coming up.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, hopefully, this will give us a little momentum.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
