<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-OILERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS RUN OUT OF GAS IN EDMONTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ If there was anything flatter than the
prairie between here and Calgary, it was the Los Angeles Kings
during critical stretches of Saturday night's 5-4 loss to the
Edmonton Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly they had a chance to win in the final seconds after
Glen Murray scored his third goal of the game and the Kings pulled
goalie Stephane Fiset. But for the first time this season they
could not outhustle the fatigue of starting the year with seven
games on the road.
</P>
<P>
   They were outshot 15-3 in the second period when the Oilers
rallied from a one-goal deficit. And when the Kings tied the game
early in the third on Murray's second goal, Edmonton responded with
two goals in the next six minutes to regain the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care when the winning goal was scored,'' said captain
Rob Blake, whose power-play goal with 8:33 left cut the Oilers'
lead to 4-3. ``This game was lost in the second period. We didn't
have anything during that time and that is when they took over the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a game that could have sent the 4-2-1 Kings home as the
talk of the town. With the Staples Center set to open for hockey
Wednesday night with a game against Boston, the team's surprising
start has given them the air of a playoff contender.
</P>
<P>
   No one was using fatigue as an excuse, certainly not coach Andy
Murray. He wants accountability to be this team's legacy, not tired
legs. The flight from Calgary after Friday night's 4-1 victory was
45 minutes and the players could have been in bed before midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, for the first time this season, the Kings trailed
heading into the final period. And they could see it coming.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Kings were the aggressors in the first period when
Murray gave them the lead with a power-play goal, tipping in a
drive by Garry Galley from the point with Edmonton's Christian
Laflamme off for charging.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt great to finally get it,'' Murray said. ``There were
plenty of chances this season, but they just hadn't gone in. I knew
if I kept working, one would go in. I guess they come in bunches.''
</P>
<P>
   But after the first 20 minutes Saturday, the Kings suddenly were
skating in sand and failing to make passes. Against Edmonton
(2-2-2), one of the league's quickest teams, they were regularly
beaten to the puck.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Smith and Alex Selivanov scored in the second to give
Edmonton a 2-1 lead. Smith's was on a screen shot, Selivanov's came
on the power play with Blake off for interference with just over
two minutes left in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Murray tied the game, but defenseman Tom Poti gave Edmonton the
lead with his first goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Just over a minute later, Daniel Cleary blew past Donald
Audette, skated behind the Kings' net and planted a wrap-around
goal past Fiset, who has played all but one period so far this
season.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, when Cleary walked up to Fiset untouched and scored
the eventual winning goal with less than seven minutes to play, it
was clear the Kings were drained.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we have to work through,'' said Glen Murray.
``I'm not buying that we were tired, but we only played 40 minutes
tonight. We learned you can never even take a period off.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Saturday, Murray was the only member of the first two
units without a goal. He watched Friday night as linemates Audette
and Bryan Smolinski scored their first goals of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Those two had taken over that game, allowing the Kings'
productive first group a night off. But Saturday, first liners Luc
Robitaille, Ziggy Palffy and Jozef Stumpel were stopped again.
Stumpel had two assists and Palffy one, but both were missing in
the second period when the momentum shifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look back at the trip and I saw a lot of good things,''
Blake said. ``But a game like this reminds you that there still is
a long way to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
