<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUNNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATADORS PUTTING UP A GOOD FRONT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After going through several combinations on the
defensive line, Cal State Northridge found one that worked in
Saturday's 36-14 win over Sacramento State.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors went with quickness instead of bulk, replacing Sean
Beard (5-foot-10, 290 pounds) with Erik Gardner (6-6, 240).
Gardner, Jason Mageo (6-0, 249) and Shawnbay Jones (6-3, 265)
combined for eight tackles and pressured Sacramento State
quarterback Ricky Ray.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have found a defensive front and scheme that fits us,
personnel-wise,'' said CSUN interim head coach Jeff Kearin.
</P>
<P>
   Ray was sacked three times and hurried several others. He threw
two interceptions in the first quarter, including Mel Miller's
record-breaking 90-yarder for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were `defensive-pressure' interceptions,'' Kearin said.
``Those were team interceptions all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones got a few hits on Ray early and said he could see a
pattern developing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressure early was getting into (Ray's) head,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   First with a bullet: Miller's interception was the first of his
two-year CSUN career. He broke the school's second-oldest
individual defensive record: Jack Burkett's 88-yarder came on Oct.
19, 1963, one month before the assassination of John Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't just going to fall down on the ground,'' Miller said.
``I was hoping to score.''
</P>
<P>
   Broken record: Jaumal Bradley is proving to be one of the best
running backs in the Big Sky. Bradley had 132 yards on 30 carries
Saturday, giving him 446 yards in four games.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's per-game average is 111.5 yards, and he's the first
CSUN tailback to rush for more than 100 yards in three consecutive
games since Robert Trice did it in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can somehow be a threat running the ball ... we can play
with anybody,'' Kearin said.
</P>
<P>
   Injury report: The Matadors had two offensive linemen go out of
the game with injuries on successive plays in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Nick Longshore, the starting left tackle, went down
with a shoulder injury and starting center Julio Alcala left with a
sprained ankle. Both players are expected to start this week.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley bruised a knuckle on his right hand late in the game,
but the injury is minor.
</P>
<P>
   Big kick: Fittingly, a CSUN alumnus became the second person to
win the $10,000 punt, pass and kick contest during halftime. Rod
Shinko, 31, won the money after kicking a 25-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Shinko played tight end at CSUN in 1988 and '89.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
