<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-SACRAMENTO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE SMACKS SACRAMENTO STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The sound of the pounding was all around them, and
all they could do was sit in their cramped locker room and take the
emotional abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a year later, Cal State Northridge's football players
answered Sacramento State for the Hornets' postgame taunting of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   And they answered emphatically.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors threw the Big Sky Conference standings for a loop
with a 36-14 victory over the Hornets in front of a homecoming
crowd of 5,183 at North Campus Stadium on Saturday. CSUN improved
to 3-3, 2-2 in the conference, and Sacramento State dropped to 4-3,
2-3.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the CSUN players left the field without shaking hands
with the Hornets. That's how badly they resented the taunting that
took place after last year's 35-21 upset loss at Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have a rival in the Big Sky,'' said safety Steve Forte,
who had a first-quarter interception that set up a field goal.
``They were banging on the walls, the doors, making a lot of noise.
We didn't want them to come down and do what they did to us last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Jaumal Bradley agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very excited about playing Sacramento State after the
humiliating loss last year and the embarrassing things they did to
us after the game,'' he said. ``They ran us out of the stadium,
literally.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors didn't let that happen with an inspired defensive
performance against one of Division I-AA's top offenses. Sac State
didn't approach its per-game average of 38 points and Charles
Roberts, the nation's leading rusher, was held almost 20 yards
below his average of 185 per game.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, who had 231 yards against CSUN last year and already
had 1,112 this season, had a quiet 167 on Saturday. He didn't have
two consecutive long runs and never dominated a drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave up some yards but we were resilient,'' defensive
lineman Shawnbay Jones said. ``It was going to be hard for us to
contain (Roberts), but we did it.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense did it by eliminating the silly mistakes that had
made most of the first five games unbearable for the coaching
staff.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive linemen didn't buckle against a bigger offensive
line, the linebackers didn't let Roberts out of their grasp and the
defensive backs rarely were beaten.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN sacked quarterback Ricky Ray three times and intercepted
him twice; Ray entered the game with just three interceptions in
151 attempts this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really, really proud of the defense,'' CSUN interim head
coach Jeff Kearin said. ``They responded to a challenge. I've been
as critical of (the players) as anybody, and they've been critical
of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the ones who believed in themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The festive crowd _ CSUN's largest of the season _ were
believers after the first quarter. The Matadors took a 17-0 lead
and dominated the stat sheet, outgaining the Hornets 121-50 and
holding the ball for almost four more minutes (9:21 to 5:39).
</P>
<P>
   The week before, the Matadors took a 10-7 lead at Montana, then
went into the tank in the second quarter. That didn't happen this
time, and Terrence Jones' 74-yard touchdown pass from Marcus Brady
_ CSUN's longest offensive play this season _ made the lead 23-6
with seven minutes left in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Matadors) came in with emotion,'' said John Volek,
Sacramento State's head coach. ``Somewhere along the line, we lost
our emotional edge. They brought the fight to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a senior, overcame a dropped pass on a sure touchdown on
CSUN's first play to have a career-best nine catches for 141 yards.
Freshman Joe Gilliam, starting in place of injured Aaron Arnold,
had eight receptions for 99 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Five different players scored touchdowns for the Matadors,
including Bradley, who had a career-high 132 yards. CSUN rushed the
ball 43 times and had the ball almost 10 more minutes than
Sacramento State.
</P>
<P>
   If not for Roberts' 28-yard run with a minute left, Bradley
would have had the better game, at least statistically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my defense I wanted to out-rush (Roberts),'' Bradley
said. ``Some people looked at me like I was crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN improved to 3-0 at home this season and the completeness of
the win put Brady in a good mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we can go out and party,'' he said. ``We can enjoy the
rest of the night. No more moping around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
