<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUNSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE DEFENSE DEFENDS ITSELF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ So what's all this stuff about Cal State
Northridge having the worst defense in the country?
</P>
<P>
   Try telling that to Sacramento State, which was averaging 43
points a game through five weeks, then managed just a pair of
touchdowns in a 36-14 loss to the Matadors on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Or how about Sacramento State's Charles Roberts, the nation's
leading rusher. Roberts was a non-factor Saturday, despite gaining
167 yards. The majority came after the first half _ with a good
chuck coming on a meaningless last-minute drive _ and he never did
reach the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge continually pressured Ricky Ray, forcing him into two
early interceptions, one of which was returned for a school-record
90-yard touchdown by Mel Miller.
</P>
<P>
   The worst defense in the country?
</P>
<P>
   Northridge is ranked last among NCAA Division I-AA teams, once
giving up 456 yards rushing to Eastern Washington, and then 402
yards passing to Montana. But for one week, at least, the Matadors
corralled the second-best offense in the Big Sky Conference and now
have a cornerstone from which to build.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was as good of a defensive effort as I've seen since I've
been here,'' said Matadors coach Jeff Kearin. ``Especially with how
we've been playing and with some of the things that have been
exposed in certain areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The key was getting an early lead, then stopping Roberts, who
came in averaging 185 yards per game. That forced the Hornets to
throw the ball.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike past weeks when Northridge got burned through the
air, this time a relentless pass rush and sound play in the
backfield kept Sacramento to a manageable 276 yards _ 91 of which
came on one play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we worked as a unit, we had everything clicking,'' said
Miller, whose long touchdown return broke a 36-year old school
record. ``We played as one unit, and we got the job done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-99 0206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
