<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY CLEARS THE AIR DURING SAN DIEGO TRIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The mini-camp in San Diego this week seemed
to bring the Los Angeles Galaxy closer together.
</P>
<P>
   After an eight-month season of highs and lows, Los Angeles is
ready to test its mental preparedness when it plays Colorado today
at the Rose Bowl in the opener of a first-round, best-of-three
Major League Soccer playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid checked his team into a San Diego hotel
for three days and they returned to Pasadena on Thursday with a
fresh outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the time of year when it really counts. It's
do-or-die,'' said Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman. ``Our going to
San Diego was a team-building exercise so that we're mentally
focused. We're going into this thing as a unit, instead of as
individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   The camp had its effect on everyone. The players were allowed to
offer opinions or air frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   Mauricio Cienfuegos started to scribble what he wanted to say in
English but finished with an impassioned plea in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Sigi did the right thing,'' Clint Mathis said. ``He's
trying to get more team unity right before going to the playoffs
and it's working. And just to get us a breather from L.A. really
showed how much he cares about this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is much work to do on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado arrives in desperation. The Rapids were on their way to
the Western Conference title before they self-destructed.
</P>
<P>
   They have won one of the past 10 games in regulation. They have
scored only three goals in their past 13 matches. And worse, they
have gone scoreless for an MLS-record 499 minutes _ and counting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't read into all that stuff too much,'' Mathis said.
``Sometimes, you bring your own luck. This is the same team we
split two games with this season. It will come down to the same
things: Who's willing to work harder and who's willing to do what
it takes to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-99 0208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991017.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9528 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-USCSIDE-LADN     10-17 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC HAS NO ANSWER FOR SLIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ Quarterback Mike Van Raaphorst had as much
trouble explaining USC's pathetic offensive performance in the
second half as he did leading it after the Trojans' 25-24 loss to
Notre Dame on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how the offense could disappear in the second half and
score only three points after scoring 21 in the first half, Van
Raaphorst was unable to provide an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked again how the offense stalled, the normally placid Van
Raaphorst became a little angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm done playing psychologist. We didn't execute,'' he said.
``It's frustrating, you know. I'm sorry. I don't mean to come up
with an attitude, but it was a big game, and we lost and I'm ticked
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst was probably upset because, for the second
straight week, he had to answer questions about negative plays.
Last week, USC coach Paul Hackett pretty much singled him out for
fumbling a snap on fourth down as the Trojans were trying to come
back against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Van Raaphorst had to explain how he fumbled again,
while trying to pass in the third quarter. He was hit by Notre
Dame's Ron Israel, and the Irish recovered and eventually scored a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, USC had a sure touchdown when R. Jay Soward
broke 10 yards behind the defense on a flea-flicker play. But Van
Raaphorst's pass died and the ball fell at Soward's feet.
</P>
<P>
   On USC's final possession, Van Raaphorst underthrew tailback
Frank Strong, then had a fourth-down pass deflected.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the plays that are remembered, especially with the
strong-armed Carson Palmer unable to play because of a broken
collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to analyze anything right now,'' Van Raaphorst
said. ``I don't know. I'd love to have the answer but I don't right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Hackett seemed to come up with an interesting theory on why
the offense _ and Van Raaphorst _ struggled. He claimed the wind
shifted dramatically in the fourth quarter. Instead of being at
USC's back, it was in its face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely remarkable. It just completely shifted,'' Hackett
said. ``Someone elbowed me, and said, `Now they've changed the wind
too.' That is what happens when you play at Notre Dame Stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Hackett quickly added that a change in wind would
only affect USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind doesn't matter with (Notre Dame quarterback) Jarious
Jackson because his arm's so strong,'' Hackett said. ``But with Van
Raaphorst it does. The wind is very important because of the ball
he throws. It kind of floats.''
</P>
<P>
   People just seem to notice Van Raaphorst's shortcomings. Never
mind that he set a career-high in yardage (298) and tied
career-high in completions (23) and attempts (41) against the
Irish.
</P>
<P>
   The only numbers that mattered were the three points that USC
scored in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't make first downs,'' Van Raaphorst said. ``That's
what happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
