r s BC-FBN-NFL-INJURY-RISK-T     10-17 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-INJURY-RISK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL PLAYERS SIDE WITH REWARDS OF THE GAME OVER RISK OF INJURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Daryl Johnston remembers watching Michael Irvin run a quick
slant-in for the Cowboys at Philadelphia on Sunday, a play that
Johnston has seen Irvin run a thousand times.
</P>
<P>
   This time, after a seemingly routine tackle, Irvin lay
motionless on his back, still clutching the football. Johnston's
world stopped. He could hear his own breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Move something, Michael, move ``something'','' Johnston
remembers saying to himself.
</P>
<P>
   The reality of the sport had reared its ugly head again: Michael
Irvin wasn't moving anything.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 20 minutes passed. As Irvin was lifted onto a flat board
and placed on a stretcher, he could feel movement in his hands for
the first time since the hit. Another five minutes ... finally
movement in his legs as Irvin was being taken by ambulance to a
downtown Philadelphia trauma center.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin is considered lucky because he can feel his 2-year-old
son's tiny hand inside his hand as they walk together. Never has
such a small hand felt so big to the 33-year-old Irvin, who has won
three Super Bowls, played in five Pro Bowls and has set every major
receiving record in Cowboys history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all understand the risk that comes with our jobs,'' said
Irvin. ``Mike Modano, myself and a lot of other guys. ...''
</P>
<P>
   But is the risk of winding up on a stretcher _ or not being able
to feel your son's hand _ worth the reward of playing this game?
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it is,'' said Johnston, an 11-year veteran who was
placed on ``injured reserve/out for the season'' last month at the
urging of spine specialist who found through a magnetic resonance
imaging (MRI) the early stages of a second herniated disk in 23
months.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1997, Johnston underwent surgery to have the C-6 and
C-7 vertebrae fused. The latest bulge is just above that fusion, at
C-5 and C-6, or two fingers width above the bone at the base of the
cervical spine. Even a frightening injury, however, isn't always a
deterrent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have things in life that I never would've had without
football,'' the 33-year-old Johnston explained. ``Nobody in this
room ever thinks of a catastrophic injury, I can assure you of
that. You know there's the potential to be injured when you walk on
the football field. But you can't let that be in your mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We laugh about it ... this isn't a contact sport; it's a
collision sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston and wife, Diane, are expecting the couple's first child
in January. Last week, Johnston began some light weight-training
and said that he will evaluate his future at the end of this
season.
</P>
<P>
   There is almost an oath of silence that is taken among NFL
players when it comes to their own vulnerability. The mere speaking
of it, even the mere thought of it, is considered taboo.
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith, in his 10th season with the Cowboys, received neck
and back sprains when he landed on his head while diving over the
pile in the 1996 season-opener at Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously there are risks in this game,'' said Smith. ``There
are risks from the day you step on the football field. There also
are risks walking out of here and driving down the street.
Everywhere you go, there are risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you just don't think of it in terms of, `OK, I run the
risk today of getting out of my bed, walking out of my house,
getting in my car, driving down the street, and having a truck
blast me from the side.' You just don't think about it like it. You
come in here, you get dressed and you treat it like a normal day.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Johnston: ``Everybody in this locker room understands that
there are certain things that you are going to deal with in life
because you played the game of football.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have had their share of career-threatening, and in
some cases career-ending, injuries to the neck, head and back.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Jay Novacek, a five-time Pro Bowler for the Cowboys
(1990-96) missed the entire '96 season with a degenerative back
condition before retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Charles Haley, now with the 49ers, underwent a
microscopic lumbar discectomy before the Cowboys' 1994 season,
missed five games in '95 because of a disk injury, and has retired
and unretired a couple of times since.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, quarterback Steve Young met with his
neurologist this week to seek answers about his future. Young
received his fourth concussion in three seasons Sept. 27, and has
been suffering from postconcussion syndrome ever since. There is
speculation that he might retire this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that I can't risk the future,'' Young told reporters
this week. ``I have a whole life ahead of me, and I don't want to
miss any of that, so I know that's very important. And the risks
that you face playing football have to be weighed in ... but I'd
really like to play football.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Drew Dossett, a Dallas spine specialist who performed
Johnston's surgery two years ago and is now treating Irvin for his
spinal injury, said that football players constantly face the
``risk vs. reward'' issue. But these are highly paid athletes, so
the question gets tougher to answer the longer we ask it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot to consider,'' said Dr. Dossett, who was a
linebacker at the University of Southern California in 1979 and
1980. ``If I offered you dinner at Del Frisco's to walk across the
street, you'd say, `Hmm, not much risk, good benefit, OK, I'll do
it.' Now if I offered to take you to McDonald's to walk across LBJ
Freeway at rush hour, you'd said, `High risk, not-so-good benefit,'
and probably wouldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   So every injury situation is different. But the game is the same
for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came into the league in 1989,'' said Johnston, ``there
were maybe one or two 300-pound guys on each team, and I don't even
know if everybody had one. Now there are 10-12 300-pound guys on
each team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become a year-round business. Players are conditioning,
lifting, working out in the off-season, and that's creating a
bigger-stronger-faster football player, which in turn makes for
more violent collisions. Then you put these guys on \Rartificial\S
turf ... and don't tell me it doesn't matter. We have an injury
called `turf toe.' We never had `grass toe' when the game was
played only on grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just basic physics. The speed, the impact and the force
created on these fields is drastically increasing.''
</P>
<P>
   And so are the career-threatening risks.
</P>
<P>
   Dossett compares the head-and-shoulder impacts frequently
incurred in football with that of ``walking on a concrete floor
with a pair of hard-soled shoes and two bad knees'' for the rest of
us.
</P>
<P>
   ``The energy must be transmitted somewhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dossett understands both sides _ treatment and recovery. A torn
anterior-cruciate ligament in his left knee ended his career. After
what he called ``two failed ACL reconstructions that were done back
in the Dark Ages, 1979 and 1984,'' he entered medical school.
</P>
<P>
   He has compiled a list of ``five tips'' that can help players
avoid spine injuries in a sport that is becoming increasingly more
and more problematic:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Don't play football.''
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Be blessed with good genetic structure.''
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Develop strong neck muscle to dissipate the energy \Rfrom a
blow to the head, back or shoulders\S.
</P>
<P>
   4. ``Learn excellent technique.''
</P>
<P>
   5. ``Luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, even in medical terms, it's a risk.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
