<HEADER>
A9532 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     10-17 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA DEFENSE MAY BE IN NEED OF FACE-LIFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Early Saturday the tectonic plates did a
jagged nip-and-tuck job in Ludlow. In a matter of seconds the earth
visibly altered its appearance in the region, proving anew that in
Southern California face-lifts aren't just the domain of the aging
and the narcissistic.
</P>
<P>
   They are all the rage, literally, from the ground up.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, we'd like to suggest some cosmetic surgery
for the UCLA defense, which looked haggard in a 17-0 loss to Cal at
the Rose Bowl on Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking about anything earth-shaking. With only minor
alterations, the defense that faces Oregon State next week could
look decidedly younger.
</P>
<P>
   We can't promise the procedure will be painless. It'll hurt
senior defensive backs Ryan Roques and Eric Whitfield to be cut out
of the starting lineup like they were moles or something.
</P>
<P>
   But the ugly truth is, UCLA isn't going anywhere _ not even to
Oahu for the Aloha Bowl _ unless its tightens up its defense. We're
not saying Roques and Whitfield were the only ones to blame for the
breakdowns that begat the Bears' first and final touchdowns.
However, they are the ones with the least amount of time left to
atone for their mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   By promoting, say, freshmen Audie Attar and Lovell Houston to
starters, UCLA wouldn't necessarily be surrendering the season and
they just might be saving it.
</P>
<P>
   The worst thing that could happen is Attar and Houston repeat
the mistakes of their elders and learn lessons that will prove
valuable one, two and three years (instead of just weeks) down the
road.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine Attar or Houston looking any more helpless
than did Roques and Whitfield _ three-year lettermen, both _ on the
27-yard scoring pass from former Hart High standout Kyle Boller to
fellow freshman Joe Echema midway through the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Echema managed to slip in behind Roques in zone coverage and
Whitfield was a couple of steps late getting to the ball.
</P>
<P>
   That gaffe might have been forgotten if not for the stunning
33-yard run by Cal sophomore tailback Saleem Muhammad in the fifth
minute of the fourth quarter, with the Bruins still only one quick
strike from tying the game at 7.
</P>
<P>
   On a third-and-25 call, Muhammad got the ball and ran right up
the middle. He trampled Roques and left Whitfield grasping at air
on his merry way into the end zone for the score that put the Bears
up 14-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears converted another third-down play on their next drive
and capitalized with an 18-yard field goal that grounded any hopes
the Bruins harbored of pulling off the kind of comeback Notre Dame
had earlier in the day at home against USC.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins (3-4, 1-3) would do well to say a prayer of gratitude
to the Irish for rendering their ineptitude the secondary story of
the day in greater L.A.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA secondary's deficiencies can't be solved overnight
because they were three years in the making. In 1995, 1996 and 1997
the Bruins recruited nine defensive backs (three in each class). Of
those nine, only Whitfield and Roques are leaving fingerprints on
this season.
</P>
<P>
   The others are either riding the bench, lining up at linebacker,
injured (see Jason Bell) or, in the case of junior Marques
Anderson, watching from the stands in street clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is in the midst of a one-quarter suspension levied as a
result of two off-field disciplinary incidents. ``It's hard,''
Anderson said as he surveyed the Bruins' locker room after the
game, ``because I've not only hurt myself, I'm hurting the team.
Ryan and Eric are doing their best, we just need more depth at DB.
When I come back, I've just got to try to make up for it by making
a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Until that time arrives next fall, Toledo and defensive
coordinator Bob Field have to figure out a way to smooth over those
big-play wrinkles that are becoming a real eyesore. It says here
they should let their lineup pens be their scalpels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's on the spot more than I am to have the right guys in
there,'' Field said. ``Do you ever get to a point in the season
where you say there's too much water under the bridge and get ready
to play guys for next year? That would be the head coach's call.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course. It's Bob Toledo's shoulders on which the success or
failure of the team ultimately rests. As dusk settled over the Rose
Bowl on Saturday, Toledo sounded like he might be ready to lighten
his load.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may come to the point if it seems the seniors might not be
performing, it's time to look at other people,'' Toledo said,
heaving such a heavy sigh we half expected the door he was
approaching to shut from the gust.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult because the seniors have put a lot of time into
the program.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a fickle thing, time: Sometimes it confers wisdom and
sometimes it just causes age spots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
