r s BC-SOC-GALAXY-SCHMID-LAD     10-17 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-SCHMID-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHMID MAKING GALAXY OF A DIFFERENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Los Angeles Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid has seen
it all in 20 years as a head coach.
</P>
<P>
   He's seen his share of know-it-all kids, like Paul Caligiuri,
Seth George, Zak Ibsen, Ante Razov and Joe-Max Moore, who made his
19 years at UCLA more challenging than he ever could have imagined.
</P>
<P>
   He's seen 16-year-old players lie to get out of training, then
call him when they needed to be bailed out of jail. And he's seen
parents try to get him fired.
</P>
<P>
   But seeing and believing have been the key to Schmid's
considerable success.
</P>
<P>
   He learned much of what he knows through watching other coaches.
Then he made believers of his players.
</P>
<P>
   He would watch UCLA basketball coach John Wooden scold Bill
Walton in Bruin practices at Pauley Pavilion. He followed coach Pat
Riley during his championship runs with the Lakers in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1984 Olympics in L.A., Schmid was in charge of
coordinating soccer practice sites for Brazil, France, Yugoslavia,
Italy and all the others. But he used the opportunity to study
training methods and learn the behavioral patterns of different
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   The son of German parents who moved the family to the United
States when he was 5, Schmid became friends with German World Cup
icons Lothar Matthaeus and Jurgen Klinsmann, often pursuing their
advice. And he spends quiet evenings reading about some of the best
coaches soccer has ever produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watch guys like Riley or Wooden, you're not watching
the plays, but how they motivate,'' Schmid said. ``You want to know
how these guys put their presence on the practices.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid said he once asked Klinsmann what he liked about certain
coaches and what he remembered most about training sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he liked a coach he could be personal with, like Franz
Beckenbauer,'' Schmid said. ``And what he loved about Beckenbauer's
training sessions were the five-vs.-five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in my conversations with (U.S. national coach) Bruce
Arena, it always seems like the best teams play a lot of
five-vs.-five. You can hide in nine-on-nine or eight-on-eight, but
you can't hide in a small game. And it has everything -- finishing,
attacking, defending and intensity. It's a great mini-game.''
</P>
<P>
   The five-on-fives and other motivational tools helped make
Caligiuri and Schmid's other UCLA players believers. They also
helped many climb to the next level.
</P>
<P>
   Caligiuri, now one of Schmid's players on the Galaxy, still
remembers UCLA's 1985 national championship, which took an
NCAA-record eight overtimes to win. Caligiuri said he marveled at
the way Schmid had the Bruins prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had a feeling when you stepped on the field you were
better than those other guys,'' Caligiuri said. ``And during the
course of the game, you never had the sense of fear that you could
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because losing drives Schmid crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate losing,'' said Schmid, who was 322-63-33 and won three
national championships at UCLA. ``People always ask what motivates
me . . . it's losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine coaching a team that is .500. I coached one
team in my life -- a junior varsity soccer team -- that was below
.500.'' he said. ``Ever since, I've never had a team that didn't
win at least 65 percent of their games -- I would have trouble
accepting that.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid still has trouble accepting any loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other night, when we lost to Dallas, was very tough on
me,'' said Schmid, recalling the Galaxy's 3-2 loss after they
squandered a 2-0 second-half lead in the team's next-to-last,
regular-season match. ``I was telling my girlfriend that now is not
a good night to come over.
</P>
<P>
   ``What got me through the night was looking forward to the next
day. Losing just refocuses me and gets me honed in on not let it
happening again.''
</P>
<P>
   There was one time when Schmid was at UCLA when the Bruins lost
three consecutive during a tournament in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked into the locker room and said we will not lose four
in a row,'' Schmid said. ``I said, if we lose four in a row, I'll
quit. We ended up winning, 1-0, and went to the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   That willingness and confidence, more than anything, are what
Schmid, 46, brought to the Galaxy when he took the reins from
Octavio Zambrano on April 22.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid turned down the Galaxy job in 1996, and said no to Kansas
City and San Jose for roughly the same reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be candid, the offers were there, but financially, it made
no sense to give up what I had for a situation in the MLS,'' Schmid
said.
</P>
<P>
   But with the urging of new billionaire owner Philip F. Anschutz
and Galaxy president Tim Leiweke, Schmid was finally convinced that
this was the right time to leave UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   And what he has done is take a group of whiners with inflated
egos and turn them into a disciplined platoon.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, the Galaxy overcame its poor start and reeled in
Colorado, Chicago and Dallas to finish 17-9 under Schmid and
capture the Western Conference title.
</P>
<P>
   But Schmid admits this is where the real test begins. The Galaxy
opens its first-round, best-of-three playoff series with Colorado
at 4:30 p.m. today at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Before the NCAA playoffs at UCLA, Schmid would often put his
team in hotels the night before a big match. Some nights, he would
have his captain pick a movie and the entire team would go see it.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Schmid took the Galaxy to San Diego for a
three-day mini-camp. Aside from training, the team had group
discussions. Some players spent mornings by the beach, others
played cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was relaxing,'' Schmid said. ``But, most of all, it was
setting a tone that this is the second phase. During the season,
when we travel, we don't get a lot of quality time together. This
was our opportunity to really get together, especially people who
don't ordinarily share their time with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   It had an impact on defender Danny Pena.
</P>
<P>
   ``In (Schmid's) eyes, I think this was more of a concentration
camp,'' a smiling Pena said. ``But without a doubt, the team became
even closer than we had been in the past. We all had a good time
together when we were with ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect what Sigi's trying to do. He's trying to prepare us
in every way possible to give us an advantage in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just one way Schmid has molded a group that had problems
communicating under Zambrano.
</P>
<P>
   ``With players, there is nothing you can really say or do,''
Schmid said. ``Because the only thing they are really going to
respond to is starting or not starting. The ultimate rewards are
hollow, in that regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is not to promise players something
you can't deliver. Do not raise expectations unrealistically
because they will do it on their own. You have to be up front. They
might not agree, but you have to make sure they understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid understands the importance of winning a championship, but
won't let the fear of losing his job or anything else interfere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I worry about not making it to the finals? No,'' Schmid
said. ``Pressure to me is not pressure. Pressure is the challenges
you are willing to accept.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have enough confidence in our team that we can get there.
But if you keep pressuring everyone and say you have to get there,
then all it becomes is a burden. We all want the same thing, that's
the easy part.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
