<SLUG> BC-FBC-KEISSER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHLAND FOOTBALL FALLS APART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to football, Los Angeles has the same title as one
of the TV season's new shows: Wasteland.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough that L.A. is disenfranchised when it comes to
the NFL. Now we're watching both of our usually prominent college
football teams stumble over their cleats.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday at the Rose Bowl, UCLA fans had nothing to cheer while
watching the Bruins suffer their first shutout since September of
1994, 17-0 against Cal. Indeed, the lone hooray of the day came
when the public address system blared the message that Notre Dame
beat USC, 25-24.
</P>
<P>
   This state of affairs doesn't inspire anyone to buy tickets for
the USC-UCLA game Nov. 20. With the Trojans at 3-3 and Bruins at
3-4, the chances are both teams will go bowl-less this holiday
season. That odd parlay has only hit once since 1980 (in 1996), and
both teams were on probation back in '80
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's performance Saturday was the ugliest of the Bob Toledo
era. This wasn't a ranked team shutting down the Bruin offense,
just one of the many Pac-10 also-rans in a year being called one of
the Pac-10's worst.
</P>
<P>
   The stats were bloody. The Bruins netted 168 yards, their lowest
since a loss to Arizona State in 1992. Of their 55 plays, the
Bruins threw 20 incomplete passes, two intercepted passes, and had
nine running plays result in a loss. The running backs as a group
netted 20 yards in 15 rushes.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' best play was Cory Paus ducking Cal's pass rush and
running for his life. The Bruin offense went three and out in six
of seven possessions in the first half, and the one exception
featured a 27-yard Paus scramble. Paus also had a 31-yard scramble
on the Bruins' longest, and last, drive of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kicked our fannies,'' said Toledo. ``We played as poorly
on offense since I've been here. We couldn't make a first down,
much less score. We couldn't run, Cory struggled early, and he got
rattled and couldn't hit his passes. He's going through some
growing pains.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating,'' said Paus, who threw for 332 yards
against Oregon a week ago. ``I didn't have a lot of time, and when
I did, I couldn't hit my passes. After every (three and out)
series, I kept thinking things had to get better. It just created
more urgency to get a first down, and they just weren't coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins began the season with some left over glow from the
Cade McNown era, but perhaps things were fated to go like this.
Most of McNown's linemen left with him. Receivers Danny Farmer,
Freddie Mitchell and Brian Poli-Dixon have been hurt, with the
latter now gone for the season. Plus, tailback DeShaun Foster has
been suffering from injuries and what looks like the sophomore
jinx.
</P>
<P>
   The defense returned six seniors and many starters, but that
wasn't necessarily a good thing considering last year's origami
defense. Add the poison of the handicapped parking saga and you
have all of the dynamics of a 3-4 season.
</P>
<P>
   The priority for Toledo and the Bruins is to find as many
positives as possible the balance of the season, and not let any
bitterness linger in the locker room. The Bruins almost got through
a chaotic '98 season before the Miami and Wisconsin debacles sent
some offense versus defense disagreements to the fore.
</P>
<P>
   Things can spin out of control much faster when you're losing
games you should win.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, for example, said he will handle his quarterback Paus
``delicately.'' Paus, who had his moments against Oregon and
Arizona State, was throwing air balls all afternoon, and by the
fourth quarter he appeared to be bailing on his pass options and
hitting the road prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very fragile right now,'' said Toledo. ``I don't want
this to destroy him. This is part of the learning process. We
couldn't run the ball, and the defense teed off on him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruin defense had every reason to be frustrated. It was on
the field for 38 of the game's 60 minutes, and as games go in the
defenseless Bruin era (1996-99) 20 points or more allowed now in 31
of their last 42 games, including six games of 40-plus the unit
played better than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``When things don't go your way, you can't point fingers,'' said
Bruin defensive end Kenyon Coleman. ``If you do, you usually get
three more fingers pointed back at you. Win or lose, we do it
together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we were out there for a long time today,'' said safety
Eric Whitfield. ``But we can't live off saying we stopped Cal most
of the time. We made some mistakes out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Four large ones, in fact, that led to all of the Bears' points.
The defense blew zone coverage on Kyle Boller's 26-yard TD pass in
the first quarter after a Bruin turnover. After Cal took four
five-yard penalties on an early fourth quarter drive, the defense
gave up a 39-yard pass on a second-and-26 and then a 33-yard TD run
up the gut by Saleem Muhammad on third-and-25 situation.
</P>
<P>
   Needing the ball back quickly, the Bruin defense then allowed
Cal's butterball fullback Joshua White to break a third-and-one
plunge for 62 yards, setting up Cal's final points on a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still a young team,'' said Toledo. ``But there comes a
point where you've got to do something about it.'' No. One can't
always depend on USC scores.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
