<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9535 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-IRVINE-COLUMN-LAD     10-17 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-IRVINE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOLLER SHINES FOR CAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kyle Boller's dream came to fruition albeit with a twist on
Saturday when he stepped onto the grass at the Rose Bowl to
quarterback a college football team.
</P>
<P>
   The team he was quarterbacking was wearing a darker hue of blue
than the powder blue that his childhood favorite UCLA wears. But
Boller, who was one of three Southern California quarterbacks on
last season's Best in the West team while at Newhall's Hart High,
said he's happy California became the team of his dreams when UCLA
chose to sign J.P Losman.
</P>
<P>
   However, the dream couldn't have had the beginning that reality
threw at Boller on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   With a crowd of 55,559 looking on, more than 100 who were
friends and family members, Boller took his first snap against the
Bruins, rolled right and whistled the ball down the field into the
arms of UCLA defensive back Eric Whitfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weird opening up with a pick,'' chuckled the 6-foot-4,
200-pound Boller, who had three interceptions in 454 attempts as a
prep senior. ``That's not the way I visualized it.''
</P>
<P>
   While we're on the subject of visualization, he probably also
didn't see two more interceptions, two sacks, eight offensive
penalties for 40 yards and several pass attempts that looked like
they were thrown by an 18-year-old true freshman playing in his
sixth collegiate game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was times that he didn't look sterling,'' Cal coach Tom
Holmoe said after his team came into Pasadena and stunned the
Bruins, 17-0. ``But he did look like the starting quarterback of a
team that won 17-0.''
</P>
<P>
   The final numbers 9 of 20 for 113 yards were far from sterling,
but there were a few times when it was easy to see why he received
eight votes from the 10 Best in the West voters.
</P>
<P>
   Boller stood calmly in the pocket in the first quarter and found
fellow freshman Joseph Echema for a 27-yard touchdown and a 7-0
lead. And it was Boller who calmly connected with Sean Currin on a
39-yard pass on second-and-26 with just over 11 minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   But it also was Boller who chased down an errant shotgun snap
three plays after the completion to Currin and blindly threw the
ball toward the end zone in the area of two Bruin defenders. Cal
receiver Ronnie Davenport prevented an interception, but was called
for pass interference on the play.
</P>
<P>
   It also was Boller who calmly made sure his socks looked good at
the same time the 25-second clock was winding down to zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a young kid,'' Holmoe said. ``What can you say? On one
hand, you want to spank him. On the other hand, you want to kiss
him. Fortunately, we ended up kissing him at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmoe, who is a father of four, has plenty of experience
disciplining kids - both at home and on the job. Probably no team
in the Pac-10 has as many true freshman playing significant minutes
than the eight the Bears played on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing freshmen included Hawthorne graduate Echema
catching four passes for 44 yards, Joe Igber darting for a
team-high 113 yards on 20 carries, and Scott Tercero, a 6-5,
280-pound Loyola graduate, playing every snap at left guard.
</P>
<P>
   It also included Daniel Nwangwu filling in at defensive tackle,
Atari Callen taking some snaps at defensive back and Narbonne
graduate Nnamdi Asomugha, Cameron Bunce and Calvin Hosey playing
special teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down the road,'' Boller said, ``this will be an awesome group.
Once everybody gets on the same page, we could be very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Igber is really good right now. The 5-8, 190-pound fireplug from
Honolulu ran for 35 yards on his first touch in the opener against
Rutgers and celebrated his first start last week by rushing for 116
yards on 18 carries in a loss to BYU.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't sure if I was ready when the coaches asked me to
contribute,'' Igber said. ``Once I gave it a shot, I came to the
realization I could help. I don't know if it's conscious,
subconscious or unconscious, I just do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting classes are a funny thing. Boller was widely
recruited, but Echema and Igber weren't. And Cal's incoming
freshman crop was thought to be behind UCLA and USC, and possibly
behind a few other Pac-10 schools. Holmoe immediately put this
group on the field because of necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing because they deserve to play,'' Holmoe said.
</P>
<P>
   Only time will give a true indication on which school inked the
best freshman class. But, at least for now, Holmoe's crop is paying
dividends and he wanted to make sure future prospects in Southern
California noticed his team Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognized that,'' Holmoe said when told there were plenty
of potential recruits watching on Saturday. ``It's always important
to come down to L.A. and play well. This is a big recruiting base
for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
