<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALCS-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON GLEE PARTY: ROCKET FIZZLES AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON - For more than a decade, there has been a pile of
evidence mounting against Roger Clemens, most of it kept very
hush-hush by baseball people. Now the whole world knows.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is as fine a regular-season pitcher as there is, but
those are the months occupied from April to September. In October,
when true big-game reputations are made, Clemens has been nowhere
to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   His performance in Game 3 of the American League Championship
Series on Saturday further perpetuates Clemens' inability to answer
the bell when it matters most.
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse for the suddenly stunned New York Yankees
was the humiliating final score: Boston 13, New York 1. With Boston
winning its first game of the series behind all-planet pitcher
Pedro Martinez, the best-of-seven series is no longer a rout.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, pitching with strained muscles in his back, was able
to shut down the mighty Yankees offense with what he described as
``nothing.'' It was a brilliant performance from the best pitcher
in the game at this moment.
</P>
<P>
   But the focus of this game was on the best pitcher of
yesteryear, Clemens, who mowed through opponents for 13 seasons in
Boston before bolting town three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' second pitch of the late afternoon slammed off the base
of the right-field fence. His seventh pitch sailed over the Green
Monster and into the net in left-center field. By the time he had
faced his 15th and final batter, Clemens had given up six hits and
needed 61 pitches to record the six outs he managed to get.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how much he insisted this was exactly like any other
game, the truth is this was nothing like any other game Clemens has
pitched in.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander dearly wanted to return to Fenway Park and
massacre his former club. Instead, the Red Sox strangled him,
embarrassing the five-time Cy Young Award winner to a point where
bringing up his postseason failures is now a completely valid
topic.
</P>
<P>
   On a nearly flawless New England evening, Clemens wilted under
the intense pressure that only Fenway Park can bring. The Fenway
Faithful were out in full force, ready to add that incessant
chanting to help distract their once-favorite son.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment Clemens took the long jog from the visitors
third-base dugout to the right field bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raw-ger! Raw-ger! Raw-ger!'' they sing-songed as Clemens
warmed up before the game. It only got worse once the Red Sox
started wrapping him like a 50-year-old batting practice pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   One particular Red Sox fan walked around holding up a T-shirt
that read, ``Hey Roger, would you leave your wife if another woman
offered you more?''
</P>
<P>
   These fans, arguably the most loyal in the game, remain stung by
Clemens' departure after the 1996 season, taking Toronto's
four-year $31.5 million offer and spurning Boston's four-year offer
worth $24 million.
</P>
<P>
   That was bad enough for these fans. But when Clemens came out
and said he thought he had a better chance to reach the World
Series with the Blue Jays than with Boston, well, that let all of
New England know they could now officially turn on Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   The once-glorious relationship Clemens enjoyed with New
Englanders was forever damaged beyond repair. If that weren't bad
enough, Clemens then basically orchestrated his trade from Toronto
to the fiercely hated New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   With Clemens wearing enemy pinstripes, war was officially
declared, which may have been appropriate since many here think
Clemens is nothing more than a mercenary, willing to sell his
services to the highest bidder and forgoing the strong allegiances
that had been built up.
</P>
<P>
   The Rocket was yanked from the game after retiring just six
batters. He left trailing, 4-0, but wound up being tagged for a
fifth run when reliever Hideki Irabu (whom Clemens repeatedly
referred to as ``High-deki'' during his post-game press conference)
served up the game's second home run with one of Clemens' runners
aboard.
</P>
<P>
   It was sweet revenge for this community, one that considers Red
Sox baseball on par with the most fervent religion. They don't play
around in these parts, not when it comes to the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Both of Boston's local newspapers led their baseball playoff
sections with stories highlighting Clemens' playoff failures.
Clemens' two playoff wins have occurred 13 years apart and each
time against a brain-dead opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' first playoff win came in Game 7 of the 1986 ALCS
against California. While that may sound like it was a big-time
victory, remember the Angels were one strike away from reaching the
World Series in Game 5 before Boston's Dave Henderson's game-tying
home run in the ninth led to an extra-inning win. In addition, the
Angels, who never recovered, had fallen behind, 7-0, after four
innings in Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' other postseason victory occurred last week when he
blanked a spooked Texas Rangers club, pitching seven scoreless
innings in a 3-0 victory in Game 3 of a three-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   In neither game did the opponent put up much of a fight. Clemens
earned some points for being a stand-up guy in the post-game press
conference. But there was no denying all came in garbage time.
</P>
<P>
   As early evening took effect over New England and the Old Towne
team was about to wrap up its 13-1 victory, the crowd began mocking
the ``Let's Go Yankees'' chant with ``Where is Roger?''
</P>
<P>
   The way the pitching rotations are set up in this series, a
possible Game 7 would again match Clemens against Martinez at
Yankee Stadium. The Yankees better hope they can put away the Red
Sox before then.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Clemens' armor could forever be pierced. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Gomez can be reached at (602) 444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
