<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9555 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FAMILY-REUNIONS18-COX     10-17 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-REUNIONS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A guide to family reunions
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In every family, requisite events such as
weddings and bar mitzvahs provide ample opportunities to get
together. Oftentimes, however, attendance at these happy milestones
wanes, giving way to attendance at a spate of funerals. (Some of my
relatives are recognizable only when sitting in a folding chair and
wearing black.)
</P>
<P>
   Family reunions muster the clan on neutral territory sans a
scripted occasion _ such a relief. While there is no escaping
familiar tensions, reunions are less structured than other events
(no mother of the bride, no godfather, no dyed-to-match shoes).
Family reunions are a chance to catch up on news, swap a few lies,
gawk at recent additions and celebrate a sense of, well, family _
magically bringing annual holiday photographs to life.
</P>
<P>
   Varied as the families themselves, these gatherings may be
simple potluck suppers or weeklong, activity-packed occasions
featuring day trips, water skiing and talent shows.
</P>
<P>
   Gather around the fried chicken and potato salad, it's time to
plan your next family reunion with some help from the Greig Files.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN DOES A GATHERING URGE OCCUR?
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually when children appear,'' says Myra Quick, continuing
education program developer at the University of Memphis, who
teaches a course in family reunions, ``because there is something
in us that wants to know more about where we come from.''
</P>
<P>
   The reunion urge may be sparked by a milestone birthday of a
senior family member, a medical necessity or an interest in
genealogy. Being a part of something larger than yourself is
curiously satisfying
</P>
<P>
   OH, MY GOODNESS, WHERE TO START?
</P>
<P>
   With a location and a list.
</P>
<P>
   How about the holiday card list _ or any list for that matter _
and a few stalwart relatives. If this is the first family reunion
of your kin, you are in luck. There is nothing to compare it with,
so it is destined to be a success. Planning the gathering is a
chance to celebrate a family's talents. For example, cousin Fred,
author of that ghastly, gushy December news epistle, would make a
trustworthy family correspondent. (Aren't you sorry you laughed at
his last effort?)
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ninkovich's ``Family Reunion Handbook'' covers all the bases
(and some of the outfield). Pick up a copy at a local bookstore.
Many of Ninkovich's tips are also on the Web at
www.reuniontips.com.
</P>
<P>
   Some families even develop a Web site for planning and comments.
The Hoelscher-Buxkemper family of Austin, which gets together in
even-numbered years, has a site that includes a page on lost
relatives. See hostville.com/hoelscher for ideas on your own family
Web page.
</P>
<P>
   HOW BIG CAN THESE GATHERINGS GET?
</P>
<P>
   Big. Reunions are inclusive. Invite in-laws and outlaws.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the list seems monstrous, take heart. No way to
``out-reunion'' the historic Busse family. In 1998 this clan
gathered to celebrate 150 years. More than2,400 members descended
on Grayslake, Ill., and, in addition to making memories, made it
into the Guinness Book of World Records. Busse clan members live
everywhere, Texas to Taiwan to Turkey. Descendants of each of the
original six family lines sported color-coded T-shirts at the
reunion.
</P>
<P>
   DOES THIS HAVE TO RIVAL A ROYAL WEDDING?
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. It is a reunion, not a reception. A simple supper
will do. Members who participate in event planning and execution
automatically buy into its success. Let others contribute and
participate. Shredding cole slaw for 60 is a bonding experience.
</P>
<P>
   If family members are traveling a distance to get together
(committing dollars and time), consider a multiday event. The
University of Memphis' reunion guru, Myra Quick, says every age
group should have activities _ gin rummy to golf, swimming to
charades.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT GOES ON AT THESE REUNIONS?
</P>
<P>
   Other than staring at each other and wondering just how
recessive the weirdo gene is? You name it. Reunions can have talent
shows and religious services, skits and genealogy lessons, costume
banquets and three-legged races, photo taking and photo swapping.
</P>
<P>
   Children love to play with cousins, adults enjoy a relaxed visit
and teens circle each other and act cool. Between the ogling and
cooking, family members learn a lot about each other. Reunions are
particularly enlightening to those who marry into a family.
Activities often become the identifier of the reunions (the year
Jimmy brought his second wife named Mitzy, the year cousin Eddie
first donned a toupee and became ``Eddie the rug,'' etc.)
</P>
<P>
   WHEN IS THE REUNION A SUCCESS? When the family leaves,
trumpeting, ``When is the next reunion?'' advises reunion teacher
Quick. Ignore the naysayers. Better yet, crown these negatrons the
next reunion chairperson. Likely suspects? The
well-it-seems-to-me-ers who second-guess every decision.
</P>
<P>
   REUNION COMMANDMENTS
</P>
<P>
   _ Start early _ a year in advance is almost too late.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lock in a date and a site.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not try to accommodate everyone. It can't be done.
</P>
<P>
   _ Form a committee of two to three dependable relatives to act
as decision-makers and a clearinghouse for information.
</P>
<P>
   _ Assign jobs/draft volunteers. Bare-bones jobs include address
keeper, correspondent, registration, projects chairperson, food
coordinator, social director (for adults, kids and teens),
photographer, set-up, name tags, gifts, prizes, finances, updates
and newsletters, and cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make list/send invitations with as much detail and lead time
as possible.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make costs clear to everyone so there are no surprises at
registration.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get money upfront (these are relatives, after all).
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep family informed of changes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Follow up periodically with those who have taken on jobs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Announce plans for the next reunion before everyone departs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
