<P>
   CLINTON-AGENDA _ WASHINGTON _ After accusing his Republican foes
on Capitol Hill of turning their backs on the rest of the world,
undermining the national economy and attacking the nation's
teachers, police, environment and the poor, President Clinton
suddenly shifted gears. ``I want to work with Congress,'' Clinton
said Thursday, standing beneath the crystal East Room chandeliers
during an hourlong White House press conference. ``We can put an
end to reckless partisanship, to gimmicks and gamesmanship.''
(Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH CLINTON-DATA
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED FRIDAY in Washington (w) and Political (p)
categories.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-DEMS _ Mike Taylor's phone rang soon after he barely
lost his first race for Congress last year. Democratic leaders, who
had ignored his campaign in North Carolina's 8th district, had an
urgent message: Please run for Congress. Taylor is the kind of
candidate upon whom Democrats are relying to make up 5 seats and
give them control of the House in 2000. We look at what's at stake
in the close race for control of the House. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE _ WASHINGTON _ Electronic commerce is likely to grow
tremendously during this year's holiday shopping season, but that
growth may painfully spotlight the problems that still face
consumers shopping on the Web. The problems include the
availability of merchandise, security and convenience of home
deliveries, procedures for returning merchandise, and the possible
loss of significant tax revenue to states and cities.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: An illustration by Atlanta will be posted on the Cox
server.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE-ADVICE _ WASHINGTON _ Millions of Americans are
expected to go on line in coming weeks to shop for Christmas
presents. Consumer advocates worry that these Web newcomers won't
understand the possible pitfalls of shopping in cyberspace.
(Geewax, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE-DATA _ Graphics material.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: MOVED Monday, Oct. 11 in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-READERS _ WASHINGTON _ Sifting through more than 1,000
books to choose the 10 with the greatest appeal to teens who are
``reluctant readers'' wasn't easy, says Diana Texier Herald, a
writer from Grand Junction, Colo. In the spirit of Teen Read Week
(Oct. 17-23), she reveals how her committee of the Young Adult
Library Services Association did its job. (Mollison, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TEEN-LIST _ The top 10 books for teens who are ``reluctant
readers.''
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Tuesday, Oct. 12.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JAMAICA-HIGHTECH _ MONTEGO BAY, Jamaica _ Sun, sand and ...
software? Already known as one of the Caribbean's top resorts,
Jamaica's glittering Montego Bay is now home to an educational
program aimed at churning out software engineers. INDUSA, an
Atlanta-based company, and Furman University of Greenville, S.C.
have teamed up to create the Caribbean Institute of Technology,
which will turn out its first crop of software technicians in
December. The innovative program is aimed at stopping Jamaica's
brain-drain and weaning the country away from its tourism-based
economy, while providing badly-needed software engineers for the
booming high-tech field. (Williams, Cox News Service). 30. WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wednesday, Oct. 13 in the (i) International and (f)
Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-EUROPE _ MUNICH, Germany _ The electronics giant Siemens,
flattened in World War II, now links Europe from the Atlantic to
the Urals with high-speed servers. Siemens is emblematic of the
high-tech surge in Europe, which is 10 years ahead of the United
States in mobile communications and is catching up in computers and
the Internet. (Glass, Cox News Service). 28.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wednesday, Oct. 13 in (i) international and (f)
financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLPRAYER _ On Tuesday, Oct. 19, the 11th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals hears what legal experts call a highly important school
prayer case out of Jacksonville. School prayer in this case
involves graduation ceremonies in which the senior class elects
representatives to give ``messages'' at the commencement exercises.
But prayer is often the message and a lawsuit claims that the
establishment clause should not be thrown out by majority rule. The
full 12-member court sits to hear the case; it already vacated a
3-judge panel's opinion that found the practise unconstitutional.
(Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   RAMSEY-WRAP _ ATLANTA _ Will justice ever come in the killing of
JonBenet Ramsey? After a three-year investigation that cost $2
million and a 13-month grand jury probe that came up empty-handed,
is there even hope? As with everything else in the JonBenet
mystery, opinions differ, and some experts insist bringing the
little girl's killer to punishment remains a long shot.
(Croft/Schneider/Goode, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
