<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9643 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHARITIES-TAXES-INTER     10-17 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARITIES-TAXES-INTERNET-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX RETURNS OF CHARITIES TO BE POSTED ON THE WEB
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Va., Md., Wash., Minn., Calif.)  (nk) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The detailed tax returns that charities file annually with the
federal government are to be posted on the Internet beginning
Monday, giving quick and easy access for the first time to
comprehensive details on how charities use their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is, by far, the most important development ever in making
charities accountable and making their finances transparent,'' said
Virginia Hodgkinson, a founder of the National Center for
Charitable Statistics in Washington, who spent two decades in an
often lonely quest to make financial data on charities widely
available.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of exposing charity finances to widespread scrutiny is
being financed by charities themselves _ notably the Ford, Kellogg,
Mellon foundations _ and the Web site is operated by another
charity, Philanthropic Research Inc., of Williamsburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The scrutiny of all charities, these organizations say, will
ultimately bring major changes to the financial practices of the
$700 billion charitable world, just as increased public access to
financial data of publicly traded companies has transformed the
business world.
</P>
<P>
   Donors will be able to quickly compare the Cancer Research
Institute in New York, which spends 91 percent of its revenues on
research, with the Walker Cancer Research Institute of Aberdeen,
Md., which spends 83 percent on fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on the verge of a whole new era of nonprofit
accountability,'' said Arthur W. Schmidt Jr., president of
Philanthropic Research, the charity that is posting the so-called
information returns, Form 990's, on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 990 will move rapidly from being this obscure, obnoxious
reporting document to something informative and acceptable, and
transform itself into a useful document,'' Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   For a half-century, all charities, which fall under Section
501(c)(3) of the tax code, as well as most other nonprofit
organizations, like trade associations, have been required to file
990's with the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   The returns include detailed information, such as how much of
the money taken in goes directly to charitable services and how
much to pay individual top officers, directors and consultants. But
few people, even among nonprofit executives, were aware that the
990's are public records. Often, the only way to get copies of
returns was from the IRS, which typically involved delays of up to
six months.
</P>
<P>
   A small industry of charity watchdogs has long used the 990's
and other documents to rate the performance of charities for
donors, though only a narrow segment of the charity world was ever
scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   Since June, Congress has required all charities to make their
990 returns readily available. The law, however, has been widely
ignored by charities, many of which delay, claim ignorance or just
refuse to comply, according to tests conducted this year by
students at Baruch College in New York, Evergreen State University
in Seattle and other schools.
</P>
<P>
   Now anyone with Internet access can examine these returns.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Williams, the IRS official in charge of the project, said:
``Right from day one we thought it was an excellent idea. Congress
wants the 990's open to the sunshine, and wants them available as
quickly and easily as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the simple pie charts that charities often include in
solicitations to show how they use gifts, these returns show how
much revenue came from donations, fees and government; they also
list the organization's debts and investments, and detail overhead
and fund-raising costs.
</P>
<P>
   The first 140,000 of the 220,000 or so returns are available
now, without charge, at www.guidestar.org, and the rest will be
posted before year-end. The most recent returns will be posted,
mostly for 1997 and 1998, though some dating to 1992 will be
included for charities that have not filed since then.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The site also provides a synopsis of each charity's finances and
an explanation of the Form 990.
</P>
<P>
   (Congress does not require 990 reports from several hundred
thousand other charities _ religious organizations, federally
chartered organizations like the Red Cross or groups with less than
$25,000 in annual revenues.)
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The site will soon include a data base with each of the hundreds
of individual facts on each Form 990, allowing computerized
comparisons of charities by type, size and location. Over the
years, as the data base grows, it will also allow examination of
long-term patterns.
</P>
<P>
   While anyone can view the reports, a minority of Americans
probably will, said Russy D. Sumariwalla, co-chair of the Aspen
Institute's Nonprofit Sector Research Fund. The site's main value,
he added, will be in the scrutiny that nonprofit executives will
apply to peers and competitors, which he said should result in more
efficient use of charity dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The Urban Institute, the Washington researcher that runs the
National Center for Charitable Statistics, is giving the IRS nearly
$1 million over five years to enable the agency to scan the 5
million or so pages of charity returns annually onto 400 CD-ROM's.
(By comparison, the entire Encyclopaedia Britannica easily fits on
just one.)
</P>
<P>
   The IRS needed the cash infusion to do the work because, after
years of budget cuts, some of its charity records were a shambles.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Ford, Rockefeller Brothers Fund and other foundations have
made grants to Philanthropic Research to have each line on every
Form 990 keypunched into a data base. Philanthropic Research must
raise $2 million a year to continue the data entry until the IRS
accepts electronically filed reports from the charities, now
scheduled for 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, a handful of charities have followed the lead of the
California Community Foundation in Los Angeles in posting their own
990's on the Internet. In addition, a variety of Web sites run by
nonprofit specialists active in the cyber-accountability movement
have posted small collections of 990's, such as one devoted to AIDS
charities, and the attorneys general of California, Minnesota and
13 other states have begun posting 990's and similar reports by
charities in their states. But none of these efforts comes close in
scale or comprehensiveness to the Guidestar site.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hodgkinson, the charity statistics expert who laid the
groundwork for the Web site effort, said the increased access
should benefit donors and legitimate charities alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal was for the public to be able to get that information
in a minute because the more transparency charitable organizations
have the better,'' Mrs. Hodgkinson said, adding, ``and, I believe,
transparency will result in more contributions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
