<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9647 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANIMALS-BOOK-REVIEW-N     10-17 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANIMALS': A SCIENTIFIC SLEUTH IN PURSUIT OF ANIMAL MYSTERIES
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone has surely heard of dogs that somehow know when their
owners are coming home. In the typical case the pet goes to the
front door and waits as long as half an hour for the arrival of the
expected. When you hear such reports you think the dog must be
responding to a smell or a sound or a vibration or daily routine or
some subliminal cue from those present in the house. When you are
assured that none of these could be the case _ the routine varies;
the animal is sometimes alone; neither smell nor sound nor
vibration can transmit itself very far in the heart of a busy
metropolis or from a car with its windows closed _ you shrug and
disbelieve or pass the story off as inexplicable.
</P>
<P>
   Rupert Sheldrake, a biochemist and former research fellow at the
British Royal Society, has gathered hundreds of such reports of
mysterious behavior in his new book, ``Dogs That Know When Their
Owners Are Coming Home: And Other Unexplained Powers of Animals.''
They concern not only dogs, but also cats, parrots, horses,
monkeys, sheep, guinea pigs, rabbits, chickens _ chickens?! _ and
even humans.
</P>
<P>
   His stories involve not only pets anticipating arrivals, but
also a cat that knows when its master is telephoning (and then
knocks the receiver off the hook and meows into the mouthpiece),
animals that seem to know when they are nearing home, creatures
that apparently can warn of events like epileptic fits,
earthquakes, storms and air raids, and dozens of other cases of
uncanny behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover Sheldrake painstakingly sets about to refute all the
more obvious explanations. Aside from arguing persuasively that
none of the five senses could have been involved in many of these
events, he describes experiments with coordinated video cameras
seeming to show that the animals often responded to their owners'
decisions to leave for home. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   What is Sheldrake's explanation for these incredible
occurrences? As he trained as a scientist at Cambridge University
and took a Ph.D. in biochemistry, he came to feel, he writes, ``a
great gulf ... open up between my own experience of animals and
plants and the scientific approach that I was being taught.''
</P>
<P>
   So after years of work in biochemistry and cell biology he
returned to the world of pets he knew as a child and developed the
theory that the social bonds between animals and between animals
and humans are ``not just metaphorical but real, literal
connections.'' These bonds, as he suggested in one of his previous
books, ``The Presence of the Past,'' are an example of a class of
fields called morphic fields, from the Greek word morphe, meaning
form.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morphic fields,'' he writes, ``hold together and coordinate
the parts of a system in space and time, and contain a memory from
previous similar systems.'' He continues, ``The process by which
this memory is transferred from past to present is called morphic
resonance, involving an influence of like upon like across space
and time,'' like ``iron filings in a magnetic field,'' and
communicating by a form of telepathy, meaning literally ``distant
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sheldrake this morphic resonance accounts not only for how
dogs know when their owners are coming home, but also for how birds
flock, fish school, insects colonize, monarch butterflies migrate,
pigeons home, cats comfort old people and how a dog he knows about
sniffed and tried to bite off a lesion on his owner's leg that
turned out to be cancerous.
</P>
<P>
   Telepathy? Premonition, even? Are we really to believe this? Why
not, Sheldrake asks, if so much evidence abounds?
</P>
<P>
   A truly scientific outlook would entail trying to account for
this evidence instead of practicing what he calls ``compulsive
skepticism,'' as so many of his antagonists seem to do.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he adds, in the new reality that quantum physics has
revealed _ where, for instance, the observer is linked to the
observed, and where particles from a common source retain a
mysterious interconnection so that what happens to one is instantly
reflected in the other _ why shouldn't animals (and humans, too) be
in touch with a world where time flows forward and backward and
everything is interconnected?
</P>
<P>
   If Sheldrake gets you to wonder if there are more things in
heaven and earth than are dreamt of in Horatio's philosophy, wonder
is about all he evokes, as his text is somewhat labored and
repetitious. There aren't even many good animal tales, one dog
anticipation story being pretty much like the next. The best
anecdote concerns a bonobo, or pygmy chimpanzee, at Twycross Zoo in
Warwickshire, England, who was poking members of the public with a
long bamboo cane she had somehow got hold of. When her keeper
thought of getting it away from her by offering her one of the four
cakes she had bought for tea, the bonobo instantly snapped the cane
into four pieces, thinking to make a deal for all four cakes.
Whether the ape was being telepathic here or not, she was certainly
smart.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his book, Sheldrake urges his readers to carry out
their own experiments with their animals and send him the results.
In this spirit, I have been directing heavy thoughts to the older
of our two cats and what I want to know is, if he is as bonded to
us as he seems _ which could be described in Sheldrake's terms as
by morphic hoops of steel _ how come, despite all the disapproval
we have expressed, he still sharpens his claws on our ruined couch
whenever we are out of the room and never when we are present?
</P>
<P>
   So much for human-to-animal telepathy around our place.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dogs That Know When Their Owners Are Coming Home: And Other
Unexplained Powers of Animals''
</P>
<P>
   By Rupert Sheldrake.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 352 pages. Crown Publishers. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
