<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 16:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9648 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GORE-NH18-COX     10-17 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NH18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE TO FOCUS EFFORTS ON NEW HAMPSHIRE
 &HT;    350&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Big Labor behind his campaign in other early
states, Vice President Al Gore is turning his attention to a
suddenly neck-and-neck New Hampshire primary race with former Sen.
Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is scheduled to travel Monday to Dover, N.H., to receive
the endorsement of the Granite State's popular Gov. Jeanne Shaheen.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first of three trips in the next two weeks the vice
president plans to make to New Hampshire, where his once formidable
lead over Bradley in opinion polls has evaporated. He plans to
spend seven full days in the state, culminating in his first
side-by-side appearance with Bradley on Oct. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the upcoming events are designed to get Gore closer to
voters, in hopes of establishing what he described last week in an
interview with The Washington Post as ``a very personal connection
and line of communication.''
</P>
<P>
   After securing the endorsement of the AFL-CIO labor federation
last week, Gore has the luxury of concentrating on New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa, which will hold its presidential caucus just eight days
before New Hampshire's first-in-the-nation primary, has more union
households than New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we can turn out a vote quicker in Iowa,'' said
Steve Rosenthal, the political director of the AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement is also expected to help Gore in other major
states with early contests, including New York, California and
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen's endorsement of Gore is not unexpected. Her husband,
Bill, is the chairman of the Gore presidential campaign in New
Hampshire, and he has long joked about having some influence over
the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working on her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the timing of the Shaheen endorsement is unexpected, coming
much sooner than Gore campaign aides were talking about this
summer. They had anticipated an endorsement closer to the Feb. 1
primary.
</P>
<P>
   But this summer, Bradley trailed Gore by double digits in most
state polls. Polls taken last month show the vice president
slightly ahead of Bradley in some polls and slightly behind in
others.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Because much of the party establishment in New Hampshire has
been backing Gore, Bradley has worked quietly to organize a
grass-roots campaign in the state. Hundreds of student volunteers
for Bradley have been fanning out across the state to knock on
doors and canvass support.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear just how influential Shaheen's endorsement and her
political organization will have on the presidential race in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Gov. John Sununu used his political organization to
rescue Vice President George Bush's flailing Republican campaign.
But in 1996, Pat Buchanan won the GOP primary even after Gov. Steve
Merrill endorsed Sen. Bob Dole, adding to New Hampshire's legacy of
giving momentum to insurgent candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
