<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9651 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AFFINITY-INTERNET-NYT     10-17 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFINITY-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAPPING CONSUMER LOYALTY MAY BE BOON FOR PROFIT-HUNGRY NET SERVICE
PROVIDERS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By REBECCA FAIRLEY RANEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before his favorite football team started an Internet service,
Brett Fennell jumped from one online service to another. But when
the Baltimore Ravens offered Internet access with premium
information about the team, Fennell found a provider he plans to
keep.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does he get a chance to buy tickets ahead of the
general public, but he also receives statistics about the team
before the numbers reach the newspapers _ a great advantage in his
fantasy football league.
</P>
<P>
   Fennell, a 29-year-old who develops e-commerce strategies for
Airtouch Cellular in Atlanta, said the service allowed him to
choose the information that would be sent to him online.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really like all the sales pop-up stuff that came with
all the other services,'' he said. ``The Ravens information is what
I want to get hit with.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Fennell's e-mail address and start-up page end with
raven.nfl.com, the Internet service provider, or ISP, he logs into
is PSINet. The Ravens are one of about 30 organizations that have
deals with PSINet to market an Internet service under the
organizations' own names.
</P>
<P>
   Tapping into consumers' loyalty to a group, a school, a team or
myriad other organizations or institutions could prove a boon to
profit-starved Internet service providers. Some analysts and
executives predict that in coming years these so-called ``affinity
ISP's'' will become the dominant way Internet services attract
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The attraction for the affinity groups is that they get a useful
marketing tool, and if they attract enough subscribers, they earn a
slim profit on each subscription.
</P>
<P>
   Any entity with followers, from church groups to rock stars, is
a likely candidate. David Bowie was one of the first celebrities to
create an Internet service; part of the appeal for subscribers is
that he drops in for online chats from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   Though the models vary, in most cases the affinity groups
receive their Internet service at a wholesale rate, then make money
on subscriptions by charging customers a higher rate. The affinity
groups also take a percentage of profits from products sold through
the service.
</P>
<P>
   Affinity ISP's represent a major savings in marketing costs for
Internet providers, reducing typical marketing costs of between
$100 and $150 to enroll each new subscriber to nearly nothing.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, increased subscriber loyalty can also cut the high
cost of churn. These days, Internet service providers can count on
losing one subscriber out of five in the course of a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, it's all about the customer relationship,'' said Zia
Daniell Wigder, an analyst for Jupiter Communications. ``All of
these players are trying to lock in the customer relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Early research shows that Internet users welcome the concept.
More than 47 percent of online households would switch to an
affinity service if offered incentives, according to a consumer
survey conducted by Jupiter Communications in March.
</P>
<P>
   That is why AT&AMP;T and the Concentric Network Corp., like PSINet,
are aggressively courting partners for affinity services as a way
to compete with America Online, which has more than 18 million
subscribers and 40 percent of the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're deadly serious about this being a very important part of
our Internet strategy,'' said Bruce Jackson, vice president of
Global Offering Management for AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   The company recently helped begin two high-profile affinity
programs: free Internet access from United Parcel Service and a
Spanish- and Portuguese-language Internet service for Star Media
that crosses national boundaries in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Ravens hope to build community through their own
Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of view it as the ultimate fan club,'' said Kevin
Byrne, a spokesman for the team. ``We're going directly to our best
fans without going through the filter of the media.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the service is marketed as a way for fans to get news
about the team before it hits the newspapers. Subscribers are
offered the same level of information as the news media receive.
And in addition to priority access to tickets, they can chat with
coaches and players.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens, now in their fourth season, have built a large
audience to whom the Internet service can be marketed. The first
target group was the 25,000 season ticket holders, followed by
leads from the 70,000 tickets that go to single-game ticket buyers.
For each subscription, the team receives $1 a month.
</P>
<P>
   So far, since April, fewer than 5,000 people have signed up for
the service. But the appeal has gained momentum since July, when
the team offered subscribers live video feeds from training camp.
During a three-day trial, 1,000 people downloaded the live feeds.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the ISP's that have moved aggressively into the affinity
market appear to have attracted a small proportion of their total
subscribers through such partnerships. PSINet's 30 groups,
including the Ravens, have brought in what one executive described
as ``the high tens of thousands'' of new customers. Concentric,
which has been in the affinity business since 1997, reports
bringing in 70,000 subscribers that way, while AT&AMP;T says it has
signed on about 120,000 subscribers through affinity services.
</P>
<P>
   Affinity groups, however, face potential pitfalls. Generally
they must guarantee to sign up a minimum number of subscribers to
secure discounted rates. If the groups fail to deliver the
subscribers in six to eight months, the rates increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten thousand would be a runaway success for an affinity,''
said Harry Lalor, director of wholesale management for PSINet. ``We
ask for 5,000.''
</P>
<P>
   With fewer subscribers than that, he said, the model is not
feasible.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, if the e-mail server crashes, customers are most
likely to blame the group whose name is on the service.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, more and more organizations are willing to take
those risks.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Parker of Lubbock, Texas, started a small affinity service
with several Internet partners last year. Parker put $3 million
into the company, a filtered service called Clean Web, and targeted
the Christian market. After spending $1.5 million on magazine
advertising, he attracted only 5,000 subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is changing his marketing strategy. He is putting
together a deal to provide a specialized affinity Internet service
for Women of Faith, a national women's Christian organization
similar to Promise Keepers. The numbers look encouraging: The
organization has 600,000 members, and 67 percent of them use the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Considering this kind of potential, Parker recently presented a
plan to investors that showed a way to deliver 500,000 subscribers
in 5 years. He could approach that figure just by signing a deal
with Women of Faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are successful in converting a lot of them over,'' he
said, ``it doesn't take a lot of time to reach those kinds of
numbers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-99 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991017.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9652 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AFFINITY-INTERNET-ART     10-17 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFINITY-INTERNET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAPPING CONSUMER LOYALTY MAY BE BOON FOR PROFIT-HUNGRY NET SERVICE
PROVIDERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 repeating to add art note   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
