   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL &LR;  (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ASTHMA _ This is the other inner-city epidemic: asthma. The
burden of AIDS on the poor and minorities has been well documented.
Asthma is less deadly; it claims about 5,000 lives in this country
each year, fewer than a third of those deaths attributed to AIDS.
Yet the death statistics do not begin to tell the story of how an
unprecedented _ and unexplained _ explosion in asthma cases is
suffocating the nation's poorest urban residents, especially
children. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-POVERTY (Indianapolis, Ind.) _ The Census Bureau wants to
rewrite the formula it has used for 34 years to set the poverty
line. It proposes to raise the line to $19,500 from $16,600 for a
family four. The change would greatly increase the percentage of
Americans recognized by the government to be living in poverty. By
Louis Uchitelle. (With a graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-SPANISH-BOOM (New York) _ How the influx of Hispanic people
in New York has created a boom in Spanish classes for non-Hispanics
for business and personal use, even for toddlers. By Mirta Ojito.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DEAD-LOBSTER _ Lobsters are dying all over Long Island Sound
and nobody knows why. By David Barstow.
