<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Oct. 18, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having brought large amounts of rainfall and gusty winds to
parts of Florida and the Southeast Seaboard, the remnants of
Hurricane Irene will move to the northeast Monday, passing south of
Long Island. Ahead of this system, winds will increase to gale
force at some spots on the coast, while showers, some of which will
be heavy, will cross much of the Middle Atlantic and New England
coasts.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front will sweep through the Northeast, bringing much
cooler and drier air to the Ohio Valley and into northern New
England. Temperatures will remain in the 50s over much of the Ohio
Valley, while readings will struggle to get out of the 40s in the
higher elevations of the Northeast. It will also be rather breezy
in the Northeast, adding to the noticeable chill. Skies will clear
across this region Monday night, allowing temperatures to plummet
once the sun sets.
</P>
<P>
   In the Southeast, cooler air will filter into many locations,
bringing a break from humid conditions. Meanwhile, another cold
front will cross the Middle West, accompanied by some rain and snow
showers over the northern Plains. Farther west, a surge of cold air
moving to the south along the front range of the Rockies will bring
chilly readings and scattered patches of light snow.
</P>
<P>
   Showers will likely develop in Texas, where a jet stream
disturbance will pass overhead. There could even be an isolated
rumble of thunder. Meanwhile, offshore flow over the Pacific Coast
will bring warm readings and abundant amounts of sunshine from
California to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Irene's Rains
</P>
<P>
   In southern Florida, Hurricane Irene will be remembered for its
rain, not its winds. The highest official sustained wind speed was
66 mph at a buoy near Key Biscayne. The threshold for hurricane
force winds is 75 mph. However, rainfall was prodigious and
flooding was extensive. Rain totals of 7 to 14 inches were common,
with a maximum official value of 17.45 inches at Boynton Beach.
Although a few prior hurricanes have produced higher single-point
rainfalls, the total volume of rain from Hurricane Irene over
southern Florida rivals any hurricane on record there. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
