<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9664 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TELECOM-CONVENTION-NY     10-17 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-CONVENTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLIONS IN THE NAME OF A GREAT PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., in 3rd graf, a plus sign should be set in type between
Telecom 99 and Interactive 99 where the words (plus sign) now
appear.) 
(nk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ $250 million. $1 billion. $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In the telecommunications industry these days, those are not
generally considered breathtaking amounts, what with $5 billion
takeovers becoming routine and $50 billion deals no longer
uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps it was not surprising that upwards of $3 billion was
among the informal estimates circulating here about how much was
spent on Telecom 99 (plus sign) Interactive 99, the International
Telecommunication Union's quadrennial confab. After all, the low
end of the range represents only $1,250 for each of the estimated
200,000 people who showed up.
</P>
<P>
   What was surprising was how little corporate news was generated
by all those dollars. Aside from the myriad announcements of arcane
new communications products, there were almost no publicized
financial or strategic deals of note.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, that hardly means the event was a bust. It is entirely
necessary, in fact, for every communications equipment vendor of
size to be there _ and to spend a lot of money, because it is an
incredible marketing opportunity. More countries, around 190,
belong to the International Telecommunications Union than belong to
the United Nations _ of which the ITU is an offshoot. And it
appeared that almost all of the members sent delegations, each of
whose members might have authority over the routine $10 million and
$50 million contracts that are the lifeblood of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, the ITU itself, with its broad power to shape
international technical standards, can be seen as a major client.
At least some of the almost 1,200 exhibitors here are jockeying for
influence in various ITU standards proceedings and may believe that
ignoring the organization's show is not the way to acquire clout.
</P>
<P>
   As a marketing forum, Telecom is best known for the extravagant
booths built by the biggest of its exhibitors. In fact, while
everyone here refers to them as booths, they are anything but. They
amount to indoor buildings, with elevators, kitchens and conference
rooms, in addition to the standard product demonstration areas. The
four-floor, 9,000-square-foot ``booth'' of Lucent Technologies
Inc., for instance, housed a lounge featuring a grand piano (and
player). Even so, Lucent's pavilion appeared smaller than that of
the Nortel Networks Corp. of Canada, which flanked it on one side,
and positively dwarfed by that of Alcatel SA of France on the
other.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the real shmoozing does not even happen at the
booths. The big equipment vendors (and some carriers) appear to
spare little expense in bids to impress current and potential
clients, government figures and journalists at lavish evening
events away from the convention center.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday night, for instance, Lucent sponsored the ITU's
official member states dinner and hired John Barry and Natalie Cole
for a musical performance before a buffet dinner at a cavernous
converted power plant straddling the Rhone River. Unfortunately,
the video display above the stage was plagued by ugly glitches, but
that was fixed before the two performed again the following night
before Lucent's client dinner (a sit-down affair).
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone by its arch-rival, Nortel invited more than
1,000 clients and friends to a private performance on Monday by
Diana Ross at the performance hall at Geneva's Casino. Before the
show ended, Ms. Ross sashayed through the crowd, dancing with a few
of the flushed attendees. There were surely many happy customers.
</P>
<P>
   But the most extravagant event of the week was the Cisco Systems
Netaid concert. Held on Oct. 9 in the Palais des Nations, the U.N.
European headquarters, the Geneva concert featured the actor
Michael Douglas as master of ceremonies and included musicians like
Bryan Ferry and Ladysmith Black Mambazo.
</P>
<P>
   Meant to combat poverty around the world and to promote the
Netaid Web site, the Geneva event was produced concurrently with
concerts in Giants Stadium in the Meadowlands in New Jersey and at
London's Wembley Stadium. But it undoubtedly carried a different
flavor from the other two concerts. While the London and New York
audiences appeared filled with young people who might have had a
few beers in the parking lot before the show, the mature audience
in Geneva wore ties and sipped Champagne before and after the show
in a space dominated by eight living statutes _ silent men and
women in white body paint slowly posing on pedestals.
</P>
<P>
   In video clips shown to the audience before the music began,
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, President Clinton and British
Prime Minister Tony Blair called Cisco's anti-poverty Web effort
unprecedented. But what really appeared unprecedented was Cisco's
ability to persuade three world leaders of such stature to promote
the image of a for-profit corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Truly ironic were some of the mundane communications hassles
presented at Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 10, for instance, shortly after the show's official
opening, a U.S. journalist unskilled in Swiss communications tried
to make a local phone call to his hotel to check for messages.
Stymied by a public pay phone that did not appear to accept coins,
he asked advice from a staffer at the information booth in the
conference's media center and was told that while phones were
available in the working press room, they required the use of
calling cards that could be purchased only across the road within
the convention hall itself.
</P>
<P>
   After purchasing a $14 card and returning to the press room, the
reporter was informed by a different member of the media team that
regular calling cards would not work on the press phones. Instead,
would he like one of the special, and free, cards being offered to
reporters for use in the press room?
</P>
<P>
   After accepting the new card and making the call to his
``five-star'' hotel downtown, the reporter was informed that the
hotel staff not only could not transfer him to his hotel voice
mail, but also could not determine if any messages were waiting
without going into his room and dialing into the system from there.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder cell phones are so popular in Geneva.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
