<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9665 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DANCE-PLAY-ART-2TAKES     10-17 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-PLAY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW A HIT DANCE PLAY EVOLVED, CORDIALLY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not long ago, in the early hours of a Manhattan
morning, the choreographer Susan Stroman wandered into an
underground pool hall that turned into a swing club after midnight.
What caught her eye in the sea of black-clad couples swirling in
the smoky darkness was a single dancer in a yellow dress.
</P>
<P>
   The woman would step up to the dance floor as a song was
beginning and nod or shake her head at the various men asking to be
her partner. Then, after holding everyone's attention with her
nervy grace, she would disappear into the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   What came out of this was ``Contact,'' the dance-theater piece
that opened on Oct. 7 the Mitzi E. Newhouse Theater in Lincoln
Center. In The New York Times Ben Brantley called the production
``a sustained endorphin rush of an evening, that rare entertainment
that has you floating all the way home.'' And because of those
words, as well as other strong reviews _ The New York Post called
it ``a beautiful, sexy and witty danse noire,'' Variety
``exhilarating,'' Newsday ``thoroughly original'' _ the show is now
sold out through its run, which concludes on Jan. 2, and it is due
to move to the Tony-eligible Vivian Beaumont in March.
</P>
<P>
   How the unconventional piece that is ``Contact'' came to life
turns out to be a surprisingly untortured tale of making theater, a
process often hindered by internecine politics and creative
differences. It demonstrates that in an age of corporate theater
ownership and risk-averse mega-musicals, it is still possible to
create a small gem that proves to be incandescent.
</P>
<P>
   While nonprofit institutions like Lincoln Center Theater are in
theory not supposed to worry about the bottom line, in reality they
have budgets to meet and boards to satisfy, so every one of them
has at one time or another harbored hopes of spawning the next
``Chorus Line,'' which had the Joseph Papp Public Theater earning
money for years.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of success is like winning the jackpot, and the money
goes right back into running the theater because there are no
investors to repay. ``Contact'' appears to have the potential to be
such a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be a theater-altering experience, this,'' said Bernard
Gersten, the executive producer of Lincoln Center Theater. ``The
ground shifts.''
</P>
<P>
   Although a hubbub now surrounds ``Contact,'' it all started
considerably more quietly. Andre Bishop, the artistic director of
Lincoln Center Theater, just called Ms. Stroman one day last year,
said he had admired her work in the Broadway productions ``Steel
Pier'' and ``Crazy for You'' and invited her to develop an original
project at his theater.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stroman immediately called her friend John Weidman _ who
wrote the book for ``Pacific Overtures'' and another Stephen
Sondheim musical, the forthcoming ``Wise Guys'' _ and asked him to
collaborate. ``John has a contemporary wit about him,'' Ms. Stroman
said. ``He loves dance, and not all writers love dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stroman said that at their first meeting she told Weidman
about her swing club experience, about the woman in the yellow
dress who ``knew some man was going to dance with her, and she was
going to change that man's life.'' The collaborators were off and
running.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really connected over this one image,'' Weidman said. ``It
seemed like a rich place to start to talk about relationships at
the end of the '90s in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The creators were also inspired by the Ambrose Bierce short
story ``An Occurrence at Owl Creek Bridge,'' in which a spy who is
about to be hanged escapes his noose in a dream.
</P>
<P>
   The creators at first considered doing a conventional musical.
But Weidman said that as they developed the character of Michael
Wiley for the segment called ``Contact'' _ an advertising
copywriter fails at a suicide attempt and stumbles into a swing
club where a dancer in a yellow dress gives him reason to live _
they soon settled on a piece defined primarily by movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The character came from a world that was all about language,
and language was something that failed him,'' Weidman said. ``He
was going to have to escape from language to get saved.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stroman said she chose an eclectic array of music _ the list
includes Robert Palmer's ``Simply Irresistible,'' Dean Martin's
``You're Nobody Till Somebody Loves You'' and the Beach Boys' ``Do
You Want to Dance?'' _ to suit the different moments of the
miniplay. She also said she wanted the music to be on tape, not
live, so it would sound as it would in a club.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stroman and Weidman mounted a workshop of ``Contact'' at
Lincoln Center for Bishop, Gersten and other invited guests in
February. The playlet, featuring many of the current performers,
was enthusiastically received.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made your pulse race,'' Gersten said. ``The metaphor
affects me very deeply: can't dance, can't live.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Because ``Contact'' was only an hour, Bishop encouraged the
creators to flesh it out. Ms. Stroman and Weidman decided to
develop the theme of swinging further in all its meanings, with
``Contact'' as the second act and two shorter pieces for the first.
They also decided to have more dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the production opens with ``Swinging,'' a playful, bawdy
dance inspired by the Fragonard painting ``The Swing.'' It features
two men and a woman doing everything you can imagine it is possible
to do in elaborate clothing on a remarkably resilient swing, all
amid a sylvan setting designed by Thomas Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   This is followed by ``Did You Move?'' with Karen Ziemba as a
woman dining with her abusive husband in an Italian restaurant in
Queens in the 1950's. She can escape her oppressive marriage only
in her dancing fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ziemba, who has worked with Ms. Stroman before, said the
role kept evolving. ``I create stuff every night; it never stops,''
she said. ``It's all about what I'm feeling inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stroman has become known for presenting dancers who think
and have inner lives, for creating choreography that is organic
rather than merely cosmetic, for using movement to advance the main
story rather than decorate or distract from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never a separation: here are the steps, here is the
acting,'' said Deborah Yates, who plays the girl in the yellow
dress. ``There's no movement without a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the supporting characters in ``Contact'' as well as
the main players have built characters with what Ms. Stroman called
back stories. The couples dining at tables surrounding Ms. Ziemba,
for example, have good marriages, Ms. Stroman said; one pair is
getting engaged that evening, the other is expecting a second
child. (Seeing a pregnant woman dance on stage seems an innovation
in itself.)
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Ms. Yates said she developed a character history for
her role, deciding where the girl in the yellow dress comes from,
what her real name is and other details that never get explored on
stage. ``I think this piece supports that kind of complexity,'' Ms.
Yates said. ``It's a role that uses all of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the reviews, this kind of preparation paid off.
Brantley compared Ms. Yates to Grace Kelly, saying she projected
``the requisite fire of wistfulness beneath the icy exterior.''
</P>
<P>
   To give the characters these levels, Ms. Stroman said, she had
to find dancers not only with technical proficiency but also with
emotional depth and a gutsy confidence. ``The people who are in
`Contact' are fearless,'' she said. ``And that really makes a star
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Most are dancers who can act. In the case of Boyd Gaines, who
plays Michael Wiley, and Jason Antoon, who plays the husband in the
second piece and the bartender in the third, they are actors who
can dance.
</P>
<P>
   At the auditions Ms. Stroman asked dancers to repeat a swing
routine with different qualities in mind: flirtatious, aggressive,
drunk, disinterested.
</P>
<P>
   When rehearsals began, she said, she developed the characters'
personas after watching them move with various partners. ``I could
see who connected, who didn't connect, who had an aggressive
connection with each other, who didn't fit,'' Ms. Stroman said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Sean Martin Hingston, who appeared in ``Crazy for
You'' and has been a guest star on the HBO series ``Sex in the
City,'' has a strong sensuality, Ms. Stroman said. Therefore his
character in ``Contact'' dances provocatively with Ms. Yates. On
the other hand Jack Hayes, who was in ``Steel Pier'' and
``Chicago,'' conveys more class and therefore dances with a more
formal romantic elegance.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way Ms. Stroman integrated the dancers' contributions.
``Somebody will be goofing off, and she'll see a brilliant moment
of humor in it,'' Ms. Yates said. ``She takes everybody's strength
and uses it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like any rehearsal process, there were hurdles: getting used to
performing in the round rather than on a traditional proscenium
stage, perfecting the timing so that dancers do not drop one
another or collide. There was the time, for example, that Ms.
Ziemba came riding out on the dessert cart and careered into the
cigarette lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``They dance within inches of each other,'' Ms. Stroman said.
``So someone who is off six inches will crash and have a domino
effect. It's a tight puzzle.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the technical glitches, like the fact that the
costume designer, William Ivey Long, had to change Ms. Yates'
arresting yellow dress nine times for various reasons _ one was too
slippery, another too sheer _ getting it right just 48 hours before
opening night. (There is now a yellow dress shrine in the wardrobe
room, featuring all the failed versions.)
</P>
<P>
   And because the production somewhat defies definition, the
producers were not sure quite what to call it, finally settling on
``a dance play.''
</P>
<P>
   As excited as they are about the show's reception, those
involved with it insist that creating ``Contact'' was its own
reward, that it was heady to help turn nothing into something.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop said the process reminded him of the lyric ``Look, I made
a hat/Where there never was a hat'' from ``Sunday in the Park With
George.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, we made a show,'' he said, ``where there never was a
show.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-99 1653EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991017.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9667 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LINUX-PROLIFERATE-NYT     10-17 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINUX-PROLIFERATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORTERS OF LINUX WORRY THAT COMMERCIALIZATION COULD BRING CHAOS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Graying nerds who recall the Balkanization of Unix into a slew
of incompatible operating systems may be reliving history with the
proliferation of Linux brands.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Unix once promised to be the lingua franca of open
systems, the Linux operating system, itself a variant of Unix, has
been held out as standard for the open-source movement. But there
is growing concern that just as the Unix world slid into chaos like
a modern Tower of Babel, the commercialization of Linux will lead
to systems that cannot understand each other.
</P>
<P>
   Open systems promised to free computer users from the software
tyranny of hardware systems like the IBM's mainframes and the
Digital Equipment's minicomputers.
</P>
<P>
   Open-source software is based on the concept of making a
program's underlying code freely available and readily modifiable
by anyone. It has been promoted as a way of challenging the
dominance of the Microsoft's Windows.
</P>
<P>
   But fear and greed have a way of derailing good intentions. Unix
was created in 1969 by Kenneth Thompson and Dennis Ritchie at
AT&AMP;T's Bell Laboratories; the first popular variant, Berkeley Unix,
came along 10 years later, and it was followed by sundry
variations: Sun's Solaris, Hewlett-Packard's HP-UX, IBM's AIX,
Silicon Graphics' Irix. Some shared code but could not run the same
applications. Thus, programs like Web server software must be
rewritten for each Unix brand.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Linux grew out of the GNU Project, an effort to
create a free, Unix-like operating system. GNU created many
critical components of the system, but it lacked a kernel _ the
core piece regulating the movement of data _ until Linus Torvalds,
the Finnish programmer, created one in 1991 and named it after
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Although Linux and the GNU components can be downloaded free,
more than 22 companies today sell GNU/Linux software. The best
known are Red Hat, Suse, Turbo Linux, Caldera Systems and Mandrake
Soft. Last week, Silicon Graphics, VA Linux Systems and O'Reilly &AMP;
Co., a publisher of computer books, announced a plan to sell Debian
GNU/Linux, considered by some to be the purest version.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, these companies were founded largely on service
models, giving information technology managers someone to call _ or
blame _ when things went wrong. But each also packages Linux
differently, adding its own set of software tools for tasks like
diagnosing problems and maintaining networks. With so many
companies struggling to differentiate themselves, some experts say
incompatibilities are inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say that Balkanization is not as possible with Linux as
it was with Unix because Linus and the guys are controlling it,''
said Maureen O'Gara, publisher of Client Server News, a trade
publication. But some vendors, she said, ``are more inclined to
chase money and less inclined to share all their toys with their
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have some proprietary stuff they've developed and are
reluctant to put it in the public domain,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Others disagree. ``Only the trade press is really squeaking
about this,'' said Eric S. Raymond, president of the Open Source
Initiative, a programmer group, because it makes a good story hook
when you have nothing real to write about and the advertising
department is pressuring you to make closed-software vendors look
good.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond added: ``The actual Linux developers know better.
Fragmentation isn't going to happen, because developers outside of
the Linux distributors effectively control all the key pieces.''
That is because Torvalds and a small group of his colleagues
control the Linux standard and subject all modifications to peer
review.
</P>
<P>
   But Linux vendors are already pointing fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``One where you might see a problem is Caldera, because they see
part of their value added in proprietary tools they have licensed
from third parties,'' said Bob Young, Red Hat's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Benoy Tamang, Caldera's vice president for marketing, counters:
``We have produced a product that combines the best of open-source
and commercial packages; we are doing Linux for business. We do add
to it commercial packages that allow business users to easily
integrate it.''
</P>
<P>
   For example. he said, Caldera adds parts of Netware, Novell's
popular network operating system, which has long been an industry
standard for large corporations.
</P>
<P>
   There are also debates about which public domain tools to
include in a Linux distribution, as devotees prefer to call these
commercial packages. The biggest split is over two competing
graphical user interfaces: KDE, the oldest and the more mature, and
Gnome, an alternative introduced by the Free Software Foundation,
sponsor of the GNU Project, and Red Hat.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to head off further conflicts, nearly all the
Linux vendors have joined the Linux Standard Base project, whose
goal is to increase compatibility and insure that software will run
on any compliant Linux system. The project aims to define the core
functions of Linux by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Quinlan, chairman of the Linux Standard Base, said that so
far, most Linux developers have no incentive to introduce
incompatibilities, which was not the case with Unix. Most Unix
vendors, he pointed out, ``were selling a hardware platform of
their own, so right off the bat you had a hardware
incompatibility.''
</P>
<P>
   There ``wasn't a huge advantage'' for different hardware makers
to cooperate, he said, whereas for the most part Linux runs on
machines using Intel microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible that sooner or later there will be a conflict
between adding functionality and compatibility,'' Quinlan
acknowledged, but he added, ``It's not high on my list of
worries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-99 1656EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
