<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TVGUIDE-BUYER-MEDIA-A     10-17 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVGUIDE-BUYER-MEDIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKER OF ON-SCREEN GUIDE FOR TV HAS EYE ON FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A decade ago, Henry Yuen couldn't program his
videocassette recorder. Now he is vying to become the Bill Gates of
television.
</P>
<P>
   Yuen, 51, is the front-runner in the race to provide on-screen
program guides, which could be the first thing viewers see when
they turn on their television sets, as well as whenever they check
schedules. In a future of 500-channel digital television, some
analysts say, such on-screen guides could become as ubiquitous and
important for television as Microsoft's Windows operating system is
for personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   It is ``the remote control of the next generation of television
viewing,'' said Yuen, who has a doctorate in applied mathematics
and a law degree.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, his company, Gemstar International Group, emerged
from relative obscurity by agreeing to acquire the larger TV Guide
Inc. for $9.2 billion in stock. TV Guide is mainly known for
publishing the television-listing magazine, but it has also been
one of Gemstar's main rivals in providing such electronic program
guides. With the combination, some analysts say, Yuen is taking a
big step toward Gates-like dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years from now I expect that most of the major TV, VCR
and set-top-box manufacturers on planet Earth will be loading
Gemstar's technology into their equipment in the factory,'' said
John Corcoran, an analyst with Stephens Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Gemstar has already had one hit product, the VCR Plus. Born in
1990 out of Yuen's frustration at his inability to record a
baseball game, VCR Plus lets consumers record a program by entering
a code number that is printed in the television listings in more
than 1,800 publications around the world.
</P>
<P>
   But that business is near saturation and Gemstar's future lies
with its programming guides.
</P>
<P>
   These are not the painfully slow scrolling lists that cable
television customers now see _ though those guides are produced by
TV Guide, so they will eventually be Gemstar's, as well. Gemstar's
guides are interactive, allowing viewers to scroll through program
listings several days in advance, or to search by categories like
movies or sports. Once a program is highlighted, viewers can press
a button to have it recorded or to have the television set turn on
automatically.
</P>
<P>
   High-end television sets that show Gemstar's program guide
whenever they are turned on are already being sold by Thomson SA,
Sharp and others. Gemstar's technology is also used in the
on-screen guide offered by the DirecTV satellite service, which is
owned by General Motors. And the company has licensed its
technology to Microsoft and America Online, which are developing
guides for services combining television and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Gemstar's leverage comes from its patents, and it is not shy
about enforcing them. Reproductions of the patents, encased in
glass frames, are hung on the walls of the company's headquarters
instead of artwork.
</P>
<P>
   While license fees from set manufacturers are lucrative, the
bigger potential is to sell advertisements on the program guide,
and, eventually, to use it as a gateway to electronic commerce.
Yuen's eyes light up as he runs through the assumptions: Viewers
will check the program guide four times an hour and view three
pages each time. Multiply by the seven hours a day the television
is on and by 2 million sets sold by the end of the year. The
result: 168 million page views a day. ``This is larger than
Yahoo,'' Yuen exulted, referring to the Web portal.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have given Gemstar, which has 200 employees, an
Internetlike valuation of $7.5 billion, with Yuen's 13.7 percent
stake, including options, worth about $1 billion. Unlike most
Internet companies, though, Gemstar is highly profitable, with net
income of $73.9 million, or 66 cents a share, on revenues of $166
million in its last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   But cable television operators have posed a roadblock to Yuen's
plan. Reluctant to cede control of on-screen real estate, they have
often used guides supplied by TV Guide or builders of cable set-top
boxes.
</P>
<P>
   So Yuen is merging with TV Guide, giving TV Guide's major
shareholders, News Corp. and Liberty Media, the cable TV
programming unit of AT&AMP;T Corp., stakes of 20 percent each in
Gemstar. ``With this merger, we pretty much should have the
blessing of the entire cable industry and there should be no war,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast. Gemstar is still locked in patent litigation with
cable set-top-box makers General Instrument, Scientific-Atlanta and
Pioneer Electronic, which are developing their own on-screen
guides. On Wednesday, arbitrators ruled in Gemstar's favor in one
case against General Instrument, which expects to have to pay $25
million to $36 million in compensatory damages plus additional
punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the merger itself will be difficult to execute because
of hostility between Gemstar and TV Guide, which had been suing
each other for six years. Last year, TV Guide's predecessor
company, United Video Satellite Group, tried to buy Gemstar in a
hostile takeover that Yuen fought off. Gemstar's stock has since
more than tripled from the price offered by United Video, allowing
Gemstar to turn the tables. The merger agreement stipulates that
Yuen cannot be removed as chief executive for five years.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest challenge could be that the entire 500-channel
digital television era will arrive slowly, if at all. Even it does,
consumers might not like the guides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-99 1709EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991017.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9673 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-COYOTES-BO     10-17 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-COYOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES PUT BRUINS ON ICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ When the Bruins headed west on their six-game sojourn,
they knew every game was going to be difficult. That certainly has
proven to be true.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were playing their third game in four nights and it
showed as they dropped a 2-1 decision to the Phoenix Coyotes
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It was just the latest in a long line of disappointments this
season as Boston fell to 0-5-3, 0-2-1 on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' lineup has been like the finger in the proverbial
dike. If they plug one hole, another opens. When some players are
going well, such as Jason Allison and Dave Andreychuk, too many
others aren't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's uncalled for,'' said defenseman Kyle McLaren. ``We can't
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaren said there's not enough desperation in the dressing
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain guys need to pick it up,'' he said. ``Without
mentioning any names, I think they know who they are. Everybody
knows what they have to do on the ice and if they're not doing
their jobs, something is wrong. The 20 guys we put out there are
not working together for 60 minutes. There are lapses in their
games and it's costing us.''
</P>
<P>
   The game didn't start well for the Bruins. They spent the first
period back on their heels and pinned in their own end, thanks to
relentless pressure by the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix outshot Boston, 14-4, in the first 20 minutes and, if it
hadn't been for goalie John Grahame, who got the start over Rob
Tallas, it's likely the Bruins would have been in a deep hole.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, nearly 13 minutes into the game, the Coyotes had a
12-2 shot advantage and the Bruins couldn't get anything going.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes captain Keith Tkachuk, who was a force all night, had a
golden chance at the eight-minute mark when he drove in from the
right circle, but Grahame made the stop.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes continued to dominate at the start of the middle
period, though the Bruins picked up their play in the late going.
Joe Thornton had a terrific opportunity when he took a lead pass
from Sergei Samsonov and charged up the left wing. He drilled a
shot, but goalie Mikhail Shtalenkov, who is handling the netminding
duties during Nikolai Khabibulin's contract dispute, blocked it
with his pads.
</P>
<P>
   At 15:01, the Bruins started to get their offense in gear.
Allison had a breakaway on the right side. He tested Shtalenkov
with a forehand shot from in tight that was headed for the top
right corner, but the goalie snared it with his glove.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins broke through on the power play at 15:59. Allison,
behind the net, skated toward the right post, stopped, took a
stride the other way and passed to Andreychuk, who banged it past
Shtalenkov at the left post for the 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   That prosperity lasted for exactly 1 minute 9 seconds before the
Coyotes tied it on a goal by Tkachuk. The Medford native, who
barreled all over the ice, earned his second goal of the season at
17:08. Travis Green flipped a backhand pass from the right boards
to Dallas Drake in the right circle. Drake relayed it right to
Tkachuk, who fired an offspeed shot that caught Grahame off guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he fanned on it a bit,'' said Grahame. ``I thought
it was going to be a rocket, so I overplayed it. I was kind of out
and it went underneath my arm.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' fortunes only got worse early in the third period
when the Coyotes went ahead, 2-1, at 1:08.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk set it up, backhanding a pass from the right circle past
defenseman Darren Van Impe and right to Green, who rapped it past
Grahame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go out there and perform,'' said McLaren, clearly
frustrated. ``If we're not performing, something has to be changed
or looked at.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
