<HEADER>
A9675 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANGER-THEATER-REVIEW-     10-17 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGER-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANGER': MARRED BY WRONGHEADED PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(jw) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Perhaps it's a simple matter of an actor who hasn't
been told when to back off, but Reg Rogers pushes so hard in ``Look
Back in Anger'' that the play seems to cower in the corner whenever
he enters.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear from past productions that Rogers has theatrical
savoir-faire: one had only to see his Tony-nominated performance as
Ned Seton, the woebegone lush of Circle in the Square's 1995
rendition of ``Holiday,'' to have been convinced that he was a
young man with a future.
</P>
<P>
   But his Jimmy Porter, the terminal malcontent of John Osborne's
mid-century study of torpor and pessimism in the English Midlands,
is a scenery chewer of the highest order. It is as difficult to
watch his work here as it was a bona fide pleasure to catch him in
``Holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   Only at the beginning of Act II, when Jimmy is offstage, does
the drama have a chance to breathe. Upon his return the
overarticulated vowels and exaggerated contortions return to the
stage, too, turning snarling, working-class Jimmy into a sniveling
twit and obliterating any hope that this revival by the Classic
Stage Company will absorb an audience with the ferocity of Jimmy's
penchant for defaming whatever it is he cherishes.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers' accomplice is a director, Jo Bonney, who encourages her
leading man's suffocating excesses. The result is an unbalanced
production that italicizes the play's dated quality, its rather
dowdy plot and its intolerable lapses into cuddliness. (What's with
the cutesy pet names that Jimmy and his wife, Alison, give each
other?)
</P>
<P>
   Peter Hall, the well-known director, once observed that Osborne
demonstrated ``an amazing ability to draw into himself all the
sicknesses of the moment,'' but in Ms. Bonney's production, you
wait in vain for a hint of what Hall was referring to. As Rogers'
wrongheaded Gielgud-ish accent suggests, this is an ersatz England
ruled not by postwar blues but by dialect coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look Back in Anger,'' which opened Sunday night, takes place
entirely in the living room of the shabby flat occupied by Jimmy,
Alison (Enid Graham) and Jimmy's Welsh friend Cliff (James Joseph
O'Neill). Alison and Cliff are joyless bystanders to _ and
occasionally victims of _ Jimmy's tirades about the futility of
modern British life. He's a resentment-filled monster and an ideal
distillation of the soul-crushing institution with which Osborne's
drama is obsessed, the British class system.
</P>
<P>
   The conjuring of the ``sickness'' of this obsolete system is the
play's most entertaining feature, and the playwright's disgust is
the source of all of its friction. In the Classic Stage revival,
though, virtually all of the tension is defused.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four leading characters, only Angelina Phillips passes
handsomely into Osborne's crumbling world. She plays Helena,
Alison's stuck-up friend, who comes to the Porters' apartment to
occupy a spare bed. Helena, it first appears, is everything Jimmy
despises about the country. She's haughty, rigid, dismissive. Ms.
Phillips has a nifty way of seeming both aloof and intrigued, a
kind of veiled threat at large in the Porter household.
</P>
<P>
   An idle threat she is not: when Alison leaves, Helena takes up
with Jimmy, revealing him for the dependent hypocrite he is. In the
play's great reversal _ a moment of surprise at the ironing board
that is, alas, undermined by Ms. Bonney _ Ms. Phillips' Helena
comes across as the most engagingly complex character of the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Graham and O'Neill, in roles originated by Mary Ure and Alan
Bates, offer fairly colorless portrayals. But then they're pretty
much defenseless against the onslaught of Rogers' Monty Pythonesque
zeal. (Given his prior success with the retiring Ned, Rogers may be
better at passive than aggressive.)
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to judge from this production how well ``Look
Back in Anger'' holds up 43 years after its celebrated London
debut. On the evidence provided by the Classic Stage Company, the
play is less an oil portrait than a Polaroid snapshot. No wonder
the set designer, Narelle Sissons, fashions a backdrop to resemble
a large, yellowing photograph, curling at the corners: the
impression the evening makes fades quickly, too.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LOOK BACK IN ANGER
</P>
<P>
   By John Osborne; directed by Jo Bonney; sets by Narelle Sissons;
costumes by Kaye Voyce; lighting by James Vermeulen; sound by Ken
Travis; fight director, J. Steven White; production stage manager,
Janet Takami; general manager, Jason Loewith. Presented by the
Classic Stage Company, Barry Edelstein, artistic director; Beth
Emelson, producing director. At 136 E. 13th St., East Village,
Manhattan.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Reg Rogers (Jimmy Porter), James Joseph O'Neill (Cliff
Lewis), Enid Graham (Alison Porter), Angelina Phillips (Helena
Charles) and Michael Lombard (Colonel Redfern).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
