<SLUG> BC-FORD-REORGANIZE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD CREATES REGIONAL JOBS AND SHUFFLES ITS EXECUTIVES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ After five years of experimenting with a complex
management structure that gave managers global responsibility for
certain functions, like worldwide small car development, Ford Motor
Co. plans to return on Jan. 1 to a more traditional organization in
which many executives will have regional responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen senior executives at Ford will change job titles then,
the auto maker announced on Friday. The management shuffle was
driven partly by concern about Ford's poor performance in Europe
and South America and partly by the company's desire to grant more
autonomy to overseas managers to groom them for top jobs later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this as a great opportunity to develop business leaders
for the 21st century,'' said David Murphy, vice president for human
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Trotman, Ford's chairman and chief executive until the
end of last year, created the current system of functional
responsibility five years ago to encourage the company's sometimes
feuding bureaucratic fiefs in Europe and North America to work
together more closely.
</P>
<P>
   Trotman's management structure reflected the company's desire to
produce global cars that could be mass-produced cheaply and sold
worldwide instead of making separate models for each continental
market. But the first global car, sold as the Mondeo in Europe and
the Ford Contour and Mercury Mystique in the United States, came
out as the European and American markets were diverging. The
American versions were criticized as too small and will be replaced
next year with a car-based sport utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The new structure will create a new position unthinkable under
the old structure: vice president for European vehicle development,
to be filled by Martin R. Leach.
</P>
<P>
   Jacque A. Nasser, Ford's current chief executive and president,
also appointed Henry D.G. Wallace, a group vice president, to
become the company's next chief financial officer on Jan. 1,
replacing W. Wayne Booker, who remains vice chairman for
international initiatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
