</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FOX-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX STUDIO PULLS ITS ADVERTISING TO PUNISH HOLLYWOOD TRADE PAPER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Like many relationships in Hollywood, the one
between the trade papers _ Variety and The Hollywood Reporter _ and
the movie studios is an odd one. The papers need studio
advertisements to survive. And the studios need the trade papers to
promote their latest deals, spin the news and learn what rivals are
doing.
</P>
<P>
   In this sometimes strained symbiosis, studios hold the economic
leverage but haven't used it for years. Until last week.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual move, 20th Century Fox stopped all movie studio
advertising in The Hollywood Reporter indefinitely, a move intended
to damage the trade paper financially. Though executives at the
studio, which is owned by News Corp., insisted that the decision
was based on long-standing unhappiness with the way the trade paper
was covering Fox, editors at The Hollywood Reporter, and just about
everyone else in town, said that the reason for the economic
boycott was simple: studio anger at the caustic comments in the
newspaper about the new Fox film ``Fight Club,'' which opened on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is a violent fantasy about men who pummel each other
and go to physical extremes because they view their lives as
miserable.
</P>
<P>
   What enraged Fox executives were two Hollywood Reporter articles
about the movie in the last two weeks. One brief article, written
by Anita M. Busch, the newspaper's editor, and Thom Geier, a
reporter, said that the openings of the film in Los Angeles and New
York had been disastrous. Producers and agents were quoted,
anonymously, as saying the big-budget movie was ``loathsome,''
``absolutely indefensible'' and ``deplorable on every level.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in a prominently displayed column, Ms. Busch said
that the movie ``has drawn more gut anger from the industry than
I've ever heard.'' Ms. Busch added: ``And for good reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Busch said that the film ``will become Washington's poster
child for what's wrong with Hollywood. And Washington, for once,
will be right.'' She wrote: ``The film is exactly the kind of
product that lawmakers should target for being socially
irresponsible in a nation that has deteriorated to the point of
Columbine,'' a reference to the high-school shootings in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Fox followed with an economic boycott. Several rival studio
marketing chiefs said that Fox would never take such a step against
a big newspaper like The Times Mirror Co.'s Los Angeles Times,
which printed a devastating review of the movie on Friday but is
hardly as vulnerable to studio pressures as a trade paper.
</P>
<P>
   And they said that because the studio had taken pride in the
movie's provocative nature, and admitted that it would polarize
audiences, Fox should not respond angrily to condemnations of
``Fight Club.'' ``It's part of the bargain to get attacked when you
make this kind of movie,'' one marketing executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Dowling, the publisher and editor in chief of the
newspaper, told his staff at a Monday meeting that Fox had warned
him of ``consequences'' as a result of the ``Fight Club'' coverage,
according to a participant. The potential loss of hundreds of
thousands of dollars for The Hollywood Reporter could have a direct
impact on raises, bonuses, travel and other contingencies, people
close to the newspaper said. The paper is owned by the Dutch
company VNU, which also owns trade magazines like Billboard and
Adweek.
</P>
<P>
   Dowling and Ms. Busch declined to discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, the message sent to The Hollywood Reporter,
and its rival, Variety, which is owned by Reed Elsevier Inc., was
unmistakable. Both newspapers depend for their survival on nearly a
dozen film studios and production companies and, to a lesser
degree, television network advertising. In fact, the trade papers
earn a hefty share of their income from November to January, during
the Academy Award season. That's when studios with Oscar-hopeful
films spend as much as $700,000, and perhaps far more, on campaigns
in each of the trade newspapers. Television studios may also allot
about $300,000 a year in trade paper advertising, mostly for the
Emmys, though HBO spends far more.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, both newspapers earn hundreds of thousands of
dollars a year on ads placed by studios that appeal to the vanity
of stars and filmmakers by congratulating them on their newest
films and latest honorary awards.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a Hollywood studio used leverage against a trade
paper was in 1992, when Paramount stopped advertising in The
Hollywood Reporter for at least four months after a series of
articles that said, essentially, that the studio was using
exploitative advertisements for the film ``Juice,'' about Harlem
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, Paramount took another unusual step. A studio
spokesman said Paramount, now a unit of Viacom, would halt all
company advertisements in Variety because of a scathing review of
the film ``Patriot Games.'' The editor of Variety, Peter Bart, sent
a letter to Paramount executives, saying that the review, by Joseph
McBride, ``was, to put it in a word, unprofessional,'' and that the
critic ``will not review any more Paramount films.'' Bart later
said the review was politically biased and did not address the
artistic merits of the film, which negatively portrayed the Irish
Republican Army. McBride later left the newspaper. Eventually, the
advertising issue faded, though Bart said that the studio actually
never stopped advertising.
</P>
<P>
   But the studios learned the limits of their power in 1993. At
the time, The Los Angeles Times was told by Columbia Studios, owned
by Sony, that it was not welcome and that the studio was weighing a
halt of its advertising in the newspaper, then $5 million a year.
The reason? A Times article said that a research screening with
poor results had taken place of ``Last Action Hero.'' The studio
said no such screening took place.
</P>
<P>
   The studio demanded a correction and an assurance that the
journalist who wrote the story would no longer cover the studio.
The newspaper held its ground. Within a few days, the issue
fizzled. Michael Cieply, a producer at the studio, termed it ``a
tempest in an Evian bottle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
