<DOCNO> NYT19991017.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9688 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     10-17 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Jane Smiley &LR; , a novelist who says she doesn't wear makeup and
doesn't have ``any gowns, bikinis, pink high heels, floral
accessories or feminine furniture,'' is a Barbie doll believer.
Smiley's two daughters were big Barbie fans, she writes in a
``Barbie Chronicles'' essay reprinted in Ladies' Home Journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my daughters were to learn certain Hollywood inspired
essentials of American womanhood, it wasn't going to be from me,
but from Barbie.'' Barbie is every girl's traditional heroine,
claims Smiley: Nancy Drew, Cinderella, Sleeping Beauty and Beauty
of ``Beauty and the Beast.'' All TV and movie blondes are Barbies,
as is the prettiest girl in school. ``A girl has to have a Barbie
doll in order to decide whether she herself wants to be a Barbie.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbie represents instant gratification, and every Barbie is
sooner or later discarded, writes Smiley. Barbie isn't cuddly;
she's built to be toyed with, manipulated. ``All this aids in a
girl's making up her mind about who she is and what she wants. That
Barbie is a genius.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -In an interview on the occasion of her 40th birthday, which was
Friday, the  &UR; Duchess of York  &LR; said that her former brother-in-law,
 &UR; Prince Charles &LR; , seems to have broken off their formerly fond
relationship. ``We used to have fun,'' she said, ``And what about
kindness? Forgiveness? And the boys! I'm not allowed to see the
boys and I really miss them. I love  &UR; William &LR;  and  &UR; Harry &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   - Before last week's opening of a show by  &UR; Chris Ofili &LR; , New
York Mayor  &UR; Rudolph Giuliani &LR; 's favorite artist, at the Gavin Brown
Gallery in Manhattan, all five works _ at $50,000 each _ sold. The
artist used elephant dung in place of jewelry in the portraits of
women.
</P>
<P>
   - Pianist &UR; Peter Mintun &LR; , having finished his summer gig at the
Carlyle in New York, reports that Manhattan skyscrapers were
floodlit in pink for the Pink and Black ball at the Plaza Hotel.
The party was all about the ``Eloise'' books that Simon &AMP; Schuster
is republishing, and which a company called itsy bitsy
Entertainment will turn into a movie. The books were illustrated by
Mintun's friend  &UR; Hilary Knight &LR; , who was an honored guest at the
Plaza party and will be in the Bay Area to sign books on November
8.  &UR; Kay Thompson &LR; , who wrote the books but always refused
permission for their re-publication, died last year.
</P>
<P>
   - Former New York Times columnist  &UR; Anna Quindlen  &LR; has a new gig
at Newsweek, which celebrated the event last week with a party at
the elegant Four Seasons in Manhattan. The New York Post's  &UR; Neal
Travis &LR;  wrote that he could ``only watch in awe.'' Travis recalled
that 20-something years ago, when Quindlen was a reporter at the
Post, she was assigned to work with him, ``but she lasted only a
week. `Is this the way it's going to be?''' he says she asked.
```You get the byline and I do the legwork?' When I said that was
about it, she quit and the process of the beatification of Saint
Anna began.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Chris Jehle &LR;  says he was most amused by  &UR; Fran Lebowitz &LR; 's
talk at Herbst Theatre Thursday night, and wonders if ``the mouse
scampering around the floor of the Dress Circle all evening'' was
equally entertained.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CALLING ALL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Los Angeles sound artist  &UR; Marina Rosenfeld &LR; 's Sheer Frost
Orchestra aims ``to break down the rigid patriarchy-dictated
borders between performer and audience by promulgating
`post-feminist anti-virtuosity.''' In plain English, Rosenfeld is
inviting women with any level of musical skill to bring electric
guitars and bottles of nail polish to the Forum at Yerba Buena for
an open call and rehearsal on November 3. The resulting Sheer Frost
Orchestra will perform the next day.
</P>
<P>
   - Disney Pictures is looking for a pudgy boy between 9 and 12
years old who looks like  &UR; Bruce Willis &LR; , for the ``The Kid,'' which
is to begin shooting in Los Angeles in January. Hair and eye color
can be changed, says casting agency director  &UR; Laura &LR; 
 &UR; Folger &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``(Marilyn Manson) is close-ended. There's nothing open-ended
about him. There are no gray areas. He's so tightly-bound and
defined that it's not terribly interesting. It's very American.
Americans are Puritan. They like things to be laid out for them so
there is no misunderstanding of what's going down.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; David Bowie  &LR; in Gear magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
