<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bear Stearns Securities to Pay $3.5 Million More
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns Securities, which processes securities transactions
for thousands of smaller firms, has agreed to pay an additional
$3.5 million to cover losses incurred by customers of A.R. Baron, a
defunct brokerage firm whose trades it cleared.
</P>
<P>
   The payment settles the claims against Bear Stearns brought by
the trustee appointed to liquidate A.R. Baron. It brings to $42
million the total fines, restitution and court costs the firm has
agreed to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Nisource Raises Bid for Columbia
</P>
<P>
   Nisource, a large Midwestern utility, has increased its bid for
Columbia Energy Group, a large natural gas company in the East, to
$74 a share in cash, or $6.2 billion, Nisource said over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A `Fight Club' Counterpunch
</P>
<P>
   In the sometimes strained symbiosis between Hollywood studios
and the trade papers Variety and The Hollywood Reporter, the
studios hold the economic leverage but haven't used it for years.
Until last week. In an unusual move, 20th Century Fox stopped all
studio advertising in The Hollywood Reporter indefinitely because
of caustic comments about the new Fox film ``Fight Club.'' One
article, written by Anita Busch, the newspaper's editor, and Thom
Geier, a reporter, said that the openings of the film in Los
Angeles and New York had been disastrous. And in a column, Ms.
Busch said that the film ``will become Washington's poster child
for what's wrong with Hollywood. And Washington, for once, will be
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford to Revamp Its Organization
</P>
<P>
   After five years of experimenting with a complex management
structure that gave managers global responsibility for certain
functions, like worldwide small car development, Ford Motor plans
to return to a more traditional organization in which many
executives will have regional responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Linux Seen Going the Way of Unix
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Unix computer operating system once promised to be
the common language of open systems, Linux, itself a variant of
Unix, has been held out as the standard for the open-source
movement. But there is growing concern that just as Unix slid into
chaos, the commercialization of Linux will lead to systems that
cannot understand one another.
</P>
<P>
   Team Concept
</P>
<P>
   Marketing Internet access under the name of a group, school,
team or other organization could prove a boon to profit-starved
Internet service providers. Some analysts and executives predict
that these so-called affinity service providers will become the
dominant way Internet services attract subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   A Naked Attempt for Attention
</P>
<P>
   A small protest group, despairing of getting attention for its
concerns about Year 2000 readiness of nuclear power and weapons
systems, paraded naked through downtown San Francisco earlier this
month. The march was led by Patch Adams, the iconoclastic
physician, and Helen Caldicott, a noted figure in the antinuclear
movement. It slowed traffic, made headlines and was ignored by
police. It also generated plenty of conversation among Year 2000
campaigners.
</P>
<P>
   SBC to Set Up Fast Web Links
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications intends to announce Monday that it will spend
$6 billion over three years to deploy high-speed Internet
connections, people close to the company said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
