<DOCNO> NYT19991017.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9708 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAMAICA-POLITICS-700&AMP;     10-17 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMAICA-POLITICS-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A KILLING SHOCKS JAMAICANS INTO SOUL-SEARCHING 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSTON, Jamaica _ When robbers murdered an 85-year-old woman
in her Kingston home in August, what has become a routine crime in
violent Jamaica soon had extraordinary repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   For the victim was Rose Leon, a successful businesswoman and
former Cabinet member, and her death set off a wave of confessions:
not by sullen-faced killers, but by Jamaican politicians suddenly
eager to apologize for creating a culture that encouraged violence
as a campaign tactic and self-interest as a ruling tenet.
</P>
<P>
   Men armed by rival parties turned grass-roots politics into
block-by-block warfare in the 1970s and 1980s. The politicians no
longer control the gunmen, but many Jamaicans lament today's random
criminal chaos as the sorry legacy of the turbulent rivalry between
the Jamaica Labor Party and the People's National Party.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Leon was a beloved figure whose own political career
spanned decades of service to both parties. So, when a stunned
nation anguished over her murder, the grief also touched off a
spontaneous act of contrition from the widow of former Prime
Minister Michael Manley.
</P>
<P>
   Beverley Anderson Manley, a host of ``The Breakfast Club,'' a
radio talk show, gave voice to what many people had quietly
thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the middle of paying tribute to her, I said that anything
that I might have done that in any way contributed to what Jamaica
is today, wittingly or unwittingly, that I totally apologize to the
Jamaican people,'' she said. ``I thought about how we got to a
stage where you could have not only a woman prominent in society
but also an elderly woman, an icon who served our country, be
killed by some young guys. How did we get into such a stage of
anarchy? I knew the nature of our politics. I was married to a
party leader. I couldn't say I didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Her candor prompted her co-host, Anthony Abrahams, who was a
minister of tourism and information in the administration of
Manley's rival, former Prime Minister Edward Seaga, to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   Abrahams said he was willing to talk about troubling events
during his long association with Seaga's Jamaica Labor Party,
provided he was given immunity. Next, Dudley Thompson, a former
minister of national security, came on the show and apologized for
his 1978 comments about the Green Bay Massacre, where soldiers
killed several suspected gang members. Thompson, who became
security minister shortly after the killings, had said then that
``no angels died at Green Bay.'' Later, he learned that the victims
had been set up and lured to their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Insofar as those words mean I approve of the killings, I
abjectly apologize,'' he said. ``But it is an apology for something
I said, not a confession for something I did. Whoever did it has to
make their own confession.''
</P>
<P>
   Other mea culpas _ more minima than maxima _ have followed,
although few details of past misdeeds have emerged.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The confessional wave has caught enough of the nation's
imagination to prompt a call for a truth and reconciliation
commission along the lines of that in South Africa, so politicians
can account and atone for the past and usher in a new era.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were part of the process,'' Abrahams said. ``We are part of
a failed state and as such we failed the country. With all the
opportunity I had, I just slipped into the political system without
really bucking it.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has yet to propose just how a truth commission would come
into being, much less function. So far, Prime Minister P.J.
Patterson and Seaga have rejected any such panel, saying that their
parties have corrected their errors and that there are more
pressing issues facing the country than to rehash the past.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a coalition of religious leaders sponsored a national
``Bawl Out'' this month to denounce the violence and corruption of
the past. And Carolyn Gomes, a pediatrician who helped establish
Jamaicans for Justice, an advocacy group that is studying how such
a commission would work, said the people were capable of deciding
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the country is desperate for some voice of truth and
accountability,'' she said. ``You can't begin a process of healing
until you admit the truth and stop finger pointing.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The confessions have spawned accusations. Abrahams' radio show
started questioning events under the Seaga administration, most
recently his party's generous help with a failed agricultural
project that was run by a reputed Israeli mobster who was later
convicted in South Florida of money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   Swiftly, the wall across the street from where the show is
broadcast was spray painted with taunts cryptically suggesting that
the hosts have some secrets they may want to keep hidden. Abrahams
dismissed the graffiti and innuendo as the kind of assault too long
accepted in Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear there has been a tribal nature to the politics,''
he said. ``In Jamaica, if a politician is caught doing something
wrong, all he has to do is think of somebody on the other side who
did something similar and that's the end of the argument.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Whether the debate generates more than radio ratings remains
uncertain. Trevor Munroe, a political scientist who has also
apologized for his role in advising the doomed government of
Grenada's prime minister, Maurice Bishop, said the discussion has
emerged too quickly, without any sort of consultation or
legislative guidance. He contrasted it with the South African
process, which grew out of that nation's transitional constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reflected reconciliation at the highest level in terms of
power sharing and that is a different process than confession as a
means of recrimination,' he said. ``I don't think the confession
process here was preceded by any amount of networking. Here we
began more spontaneously, hence it added a new dimension, political
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters are skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in an environment where politicians are lambasted all
over the place,'' said Aeden Earle, an earth scientist. ``They want
to position themselves as part of the new political breed. They
want to distance themselves from the violence of the '70s, so they
make a half-hearted confession and say they're man enough to admit
to it. It's an attempt to prolong their credibility over the medium
term.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Levy, an insurance company manager, said the commission
was a good idea, but he saw it vanishing with each day of partisan
accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lost opportunity,'' he said. ``I don't think people
understand half of the rottenness in our politics. And they need to
understand it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
