<SLUG> BC-TV-VHI-BOWIE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STORYTELLERS': A DAVID BOWIE WHO TAKES IT LIGHTLY
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Check local listings
for broadcast time in your area.) 
(rk) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Bowie, that fey chameleon of pop music, has metamorphosed
into a giggly middle-aged man in clunky boots and an oversize
sweatshirt. At least that's the character he has elected to offer
as himself for the latest segment of the VH1 series
``Storytellers.''
</P>
<P>
   Light years from Ziggy Stardust, Bowie settles comfortably into
the show's format, an informal and-then-I-wrote monologue
punctuated with songs that recall a few phases of his varied
30-year career. In place of the sexually charged poseur of the
past, Monday night's hour presents a bemused, self-deprecating
52-year-old survivor who moves lightly from anecdote to tune,
backed by a smoothly professional band and the sound of synthesized
strings.
</P>
<P>
   The young instrumentalists, backup singers and audience members
all gaze at him reverentially. But even if you know that Bowie
carries the credentials of an international icon, it's hard to
understand from the evidence at hand what all the fuss was about.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was about 14,'' Bowie says, ``Eartha Kitt and D.H.
Lawrence were some of my favorite bedtime reading.'' This
revelation helps introduce one of Bowie's recent songs, called
``Thursday's Child,'' which was also the title of Ms. Kitt's
autobiography. (No, there is no ballad here about Lady Chatterley.)
Hearing ``Child'' and another ``song of newness,'' as Bowie puts
it, ``Seven'' (``I've got seven days to live my life or seven ways
to die''), you can conclude that his current passion is for
easy-listening anthems. No more scary monsters?
</P>
<P>
   The dark complexities of the past are acknowledged at the show's
end, when Bowie sings ``Word on a Wing,'' from his ``Station to
Station'' album of 1976. Those were ``singularly the darkest days
of my life,'' he says, and the song ``was a call for help.''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling it now, however, he can't help smiling. And like the
Cheshire cat's, Bowie's smile is what lingers when he's gone. In
close-up, it is infectious, something that can't quite be shared in
a recording or concert. Television does have its uses.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `VH1 STORYTELLERS' David Bowie
</P>
<P>
   VH1, Monday night at 10
</P>
<P>
   Bill Flanagan, executive producer; Amy Fazekas, producer;
Michael Chloe, director. A production of VH1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
