</P>
<P>
   JAMAICA-HIGHTECH _ MONTEGO BAY, Jamaica _ Sun, sand and ...
software? Already known as one of the Caribbean's top resorts,
Jamaica's glittering Montego Bay is now home to an educational
program aimed at churning out software engineers. INDUSA, an
Atlanta-based company, and Furman University of Greenville, S.C.
have teamed up to create the Caribbean Institute of Technology,
which will turn out its first crop of software technicians in
December. The innovative program is aimed at stopping Jamaica's
brain-drain and weaning the country away from its tourism-based
economy, while providing badly-needed software engineers for the
booming high-tech field. (Williams, Cox News Service). 30. WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wednesday, Oct. 13 in the (i) International and (f)
Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-EUROPE _ MUNICH, Germany _ The electronics giant Siemens,
flattened in World War II, now links Europe from the Atlantic to
the Urals with high-speed servers. Siemens is emblematic of the
high-tech surge in Europe, which is 10 years ahead of the United
States in mobile communications and is catching up in computers and
the Internet. (Glass, Cox News Service). 28.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Wednesday, Oct. 13 in (i) international and (f)
financial categories.
