<SLUG> BC-SCI-ASTHMA-L-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTHMA BECOMES AN EPIDEMIC AMONG CITY CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: A shorter version of this story, slugged SCI-ASTHMA-S, is
being sent. A related story, on methods of treating asthma, will be
sent tomorrow for papers of Oct. 19.) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphics are
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The asthma epidemic visited Children's National Medical Center
one recent Friday, the day after a furious rainstorm kicked up
allergens all over Washington. By 9 a.m., the emergency room, where
children come in more often for failing lungs than for broken
bones, was jumping. Harried nurses barked orders for the pharmacy
to send more drugs. In bed after bed, young faces, all
African-American, were buried under clear plastic breathing masks.
</P>
<P>
   John Thompson, a skinny, bright-eyed 8-year-old, was there,
watching Richard Scarry videos while sniffing steroids to relax his
swollen airways. His mother, who had taken a bus and three subway
trains to get to the hospital, lost her pay that day. She had
already used all her sick leave to care for two asthmatic children.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Mosley, an athletic 13-year-old with a mouthful of braces,
rested quietly in a room around the corner; he had woken up at 4
that morning, gasping for breath.
</P>
<P>
   Next door to Kyle lay Burnell Ramsey II, 9. He was weak,
frightened and curled up in the fetal position under a thin white
hospital sheet. His worried father gently stroked the boy's
forehead after a nurse said Burnell's lungs had partly collapsed.
His mother wept softly as a doctor tried to comfort her; the doctor
had made it all the way through medical school with asthma, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the other inner-city epidemic: asthma. The burden of
AIDS on the poor and minorities has been well documented. Asthma is
less deadly; it claims about 5,000 lives in the United States each
year. Yet the death statistics do not begin to tell the story of
how an unprecedented _ and unexplained _ explosion in asthma cases
is suffocating the nation's poorest urban residents, especially
children.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid rise of asthma, in this country and in developed
nations around the world, is one of the biggest mysteries in modern
medicine. The most striking increases, experts say, have occurred
in Australia, where about one-quarter of all children have received
a diagnosis of asthma.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the number of asthma sufferers has more
than doubled from 6.7 million in 1980 to an estimated 17.3 million
in 1998, according to the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention in Atlanta. Of these, 4.8 million are children. Experts
say the increase is real. Although doctors do a better job of
diagnosing asthma now than they did in years past, that does not
entirely explain the upward trend.
</P>
<P>
   The epidemic cuts across racial and socioeconomic lines; white
youngsters who live in suburbs are hardly exempt. The prevalence of
asthma is slightly higher among blacks than among whites.
Scientists suspect that the difference may be explained at least in
part by genetics.
</P>
<P>
   But when public health officials measure rates of hospital
admissions, emergency-room visits and deaths, they find that black
and Hispanic patients, particularly those who are poor, shoulder a
much heavier burden.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows why the disparity is so great, but experts have
some ideas. The poor tend to have less access to regular medical
care, are less able to afford the medications they need and are
more likely to be around environmental ``triggers'' that set off
asthma attacks. Also, some researchers have found, families already
under great stress are less able to cope with the complicated daily
regimen that asthma demands.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma, a chronic, incurable disease of the airways, is
characterized by intermittent episodes of wheezing, coughing and
breathlessness. During normal breathing, air flows freely in and
out of the lungs. But during an asthma attack, the lining of the
airways swells, muscles around the airways tighten and mucus clogs
the tiny air tubes in the lungs, making breathing difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks can be set off by pollen, dust and dust mites,
cockroaches, stress, cold air, tobacco smoke, irritating chemical
smells, mold and mildew, respiratory infections and exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma sufferers can live a normal, unrestricted life, doctors
say, if they get the proper medication and stick to the daily
treatment and monitoring that the disease requires. But many
patients do not get the medical supervision they need or do not
follow their drug regimens properly, and so, despite new and highly
effective drugs to treat the disease, hospital admissions for
asthma are increasing.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, there were 15,000 hospital admissions of
children 14 and younger for asthma in 1997 _ the last year for
which figures were available _ up from 9,275 in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   At Children's National Medical Center, Dr. Ben Gitterman,
director of ambulatory and community pediatrics, sees these
statistics in his practice. ``We are seeing lots and lots of kids
with lots and lots of asthma,'' Gitterman said. ``We are seeing
kids on more treatments who have more access to medications, but
they're sick.''
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, the patients are members of minorities. In
1995, the most recent year for which the government has figures,
blacks were two to three times as likely to die of asthma as
whites. That same year, African-Americans paid four times as many
visits to emergency rooms for asthma as did whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very concerning,'' said Dr. David Satcher, the U.S.
surgeon general. Referring to his office's year 2000 goals for
improving the nation's health, Satcher said, ``Asthma is one of the
areas where we are moving in the wrong direction.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to reverse the trends, the government is stepping
up asthma research. In May, Donna Shalala, the secretary of health
and human services, announced that the department would develop ``a
strategic plan'' for research into the causes of asthma and ways to
lessen the burden on minorities and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   In his proposed budget for next year, President Clinton has
included $50 million in grants for states to test methods for
improving the health of children with asthma who are enrolled in
the Medicaid program. That is in addition to the $118 million the
National Institutes of Health plan to spend on asthma research.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Clinton administration has made eliminating racial
disparities in disease one of its health priorities, asthma is not
on the list of six illnesses the government has identified for the
first five years of the program. That is not because the racial gap
is insignificant, the surgeon general said, but because experts
have no idea how to narrow it within the five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the real issues is: Why are we seeing this increase in
asthma? And we don't know the answer to that,'' Satcher said.
``Until you understand why you have the increase, and you have
documented it, it is very hard to say you have a strategy that is
going to make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Battleground
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is the disparity more evident than in the Bronx and
Harlem, in New York City, where a recent study found that the rate
of hospitalization for asthma was 21 times higher than that in more
affluent parts of the city, a disparity that surprised even experts
who are familiar with asthma trends.
</P>
<P>
   Here, school nurses run six-week asthma education classes for
8-year-olds, and enrollment is overflowing.
</P>
<P>
   Children routinely tuck inhalers, the little pumps that convert
asthma medication into an inhalable mist, into their backpacks so
they can take puffs before gym class. (Asthma is so prevalent that
some states, including New York, have begun passing laws allowing
children to carry the medication with a doctor's permission,
bypassing the usual requirement that drugs be administered by a
nurse.)
</P>
<P>
   At the Bilingual Bicultural Mini School on 109th Street in East
Harlem, the medicine cabinet in the nurse's office is filled with
inhalers, and two nebulizers _ machines that administer emergency
breathing treatments _ are tucked in a corner, just below an asthma
awareness poster.
</P>
<P>
   Ann-Nancy Murphy, a nurse practitioner from Mount Sinai Medical
Center who works at the public elementary school under a pediatric
health program, said she needs both machines; sometimes two
children have emergencies at once.
</P>
<P>
   The school's director, Lourdes Arroyo, says some students miss
as much as four weeks of school each year because of asthma, which
she describes as ``an assault on the children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The time that is lost from the classroom, you can't recover
that time,'' Ms. Arroyo said. ``With kids that are coming in with
several strikes against them to begin with, this just complicates
matters.''
</P>
<P>
   In these neighborhoods, asthma has so skewed the perception of
healthy children that several mothers said they considered it a
mark of success that their asthmatic youngsters had never been
``intubated,'' kept alive by breathing machines.
</P>
<P>
   That attitude troubles officials at the New York City Department
of Health. ``Our major concern,'' said Dr. Andrew Goodman,
associate commissioner, ``was that people were accepting a level of
symptoms as being, quote, normal.''
</P>
<P>
   So, two years ago, the department began a childhood asthma
initiative. But easing asthma, officials said, is much more than a
matter of providing good medical care. It requires the help of
educators: Teachers are now being taught about asthma. It requires
pest extermination: The housing authority, Goodman said, is
participating in a project to reduce cockroaches and interior mold.
</P>
<P>
   It requires surveillance: The health department also plans to
collect data on new kindergartners so officials can better track
patterns in asthma. And it requires negotiation: Goodman said his
agency had persuaded distributors of medical devices to sell
``spacers,'' plastic tubes used with asthma inhalers, to pharmacies
at a cost below the Medicaid reimbursement level, so that patients
will not have to pay extra.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional way to deal with a disease is to have a doctor
and a patient working together to make sure they are on the right
medicines and so forth,'' said Louise Cohen, who directs the
initiative, which costs taxpayers $6 million a year. ``That is
necessary but insufficient around asthma. There is a whole set of
social support that needs to be built.''
</P>
<P>
   Although city health officials say they are working on improving
medical care for children, critics say the city fails to provide
the primary medical care that poor children need.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you cannot at the end of the day provide the medical care
that you have educated people about, you have only completed half
the bargain and you end up with some very frustrated families,''
said Dr. Irwin Redlener, president of the Children's Hospital at
Montefiore Medical Center in the Bronx. ``We get patients coming to
us who have learned from the public education campaign who say to
us, `But we need a doctor.'''
</P>
<P>
   And some community leaders complain that the city is not doing
enough to address one trigger in particular, outdoor air pollution.
There is some scientific evidence that diesel exhaust can worsen
asthma by making people more sensitive to other allergens, said Dr.
Patrick Kinney, an environmental health expert at Columbia
University. Goodman said the city's position was that diesel and
other outdoor pollutants should be reduced ``to the extent
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Bronx, a group of environmental activists called We
Stay/Nos Quedamos has seized on the evidence that diesel exhaust
can exacerbate asthma and is organizing teen-agers to count the
number of trucks that rumble through the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to come up with some kind of paper trail,'' said
Jolanda Garcia, the founder of We Stay. Ms. Garcia presides over
the truck counting from a tattered storefront with yellowed lace
curtains on Courtlandt Avenue. Her 27-year-old son died two years
ago from asthma. She contends that pollution killed him.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Causes
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, scientists would have agreed with Ms. Garcia that
diesel exhaust and other pollutants might be causing the asthma
epidemic. Now, they believe the picture is more complex. To begin
with, asthma cases are surging as pollution levels are declining.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Fernando Martinez, director of the Respiratory Sciences
Center at the University of Arizona in Tucson, said scientists did
not think pollution was the sole cause of the disease, a finding
that he said came from a ``natural experiment'' conducted in
Germany after the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to look at two populations, East and West Germans,
with similar genetic backgrounds but different environments, to
determine whether different living conditions could be associated
with different rates of disease. Experts assumed that asthma would
be more prevalent in the more heavily industrialized and polluted
East. But the study found just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   The German study helped scientists to see that whatever caused
asthma was probably separate from what triggered asthma attacks.
Typically, asthma appears before age 6. ``If we are going to
understand not what triggers asthma but what causes asthma,''
Martinez said, ``we have to look at the first years of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, scientists are focusing on genetics. This month, a team
at Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory in California reported the
discovery of two genes that contribute to the development of
asthma. Researchers are also looking at what happens to the immune
system in early life.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most talked-about new theories is that the rise in
asthma is related to improved hygiene. The idea is that babies are
less likely to be exposed to viruses and bacteria, and without that
exposure, their immune systems do not mature fully. The result is
asthma.
</P>
<P>
   That might explain why people who live on farms, or in rural
areas, are less likely to develop asthma than people in cities.
Perhaps, said Dr. Sonia Buist, an asthma expert at Oregon Health
Sciences University in Portland, it is because people on farms are
more likely to be exposed to soil organisms, and that exposure
somehow immunizes them against asthma.
</P>
<P>
   ``A century ago,'' Dr. Buist said, ``most people walked around
with a load of worms or parasites, and the immune system became
pretty good at dealing with them. As hygiene has increased and the
water system has improved, we have done away with all that priming
of the immune system.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists know that asthma often develops along a pathway;
early in life, the immune system is ``sensitized'' to allergens and
pollutants that trigger asthma attacks. If sensitization never
takes place, they reason, asthma might never occur.
</P>
<P>
   At Columbia University, researchers are trying to determine when
sensitization happens. They are enrolling 480 pregnant women who
will carry air-quality monitors for two days in the third
trimester. Their babies' umbilical-cord blood will be analyzed, and
the infants will be followed for five years to see who develops
asthma.
</P>
<P>
   It is an ambitious study, the first of its kind, said Dr.
Frederica Perera, who directs the university's Center for
Children's Environmental Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are interested in prevention,'' Perera said, ``and
prevention means going younger and younger until you can stop the
process, and not waiting until children are using inhalers at the
age of 5 or 6. But there was very little information on early life
exposures, even those occurring in the womb.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Challenges
</P>
<P>
   Until scientists learn more about prevention, doctors and nurses
are left to teach patients how to manage the disease, through
proper medication and changes in their environment. But that is
proving more difficult than anyone anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, federal health officials recommended the daily
use of inhaled corticosteroids to control asthma in people with
moderate or severe disease. Experts say the medicines can reduce
emergency-room visits, hospitalizations and deaths. But only half
the eligible patients use them, said Dr. William Busse, a professor
of medicine at the University of Wisconsin in Madison who helped
write the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major reason why we see kids here,'' Dr. Bruce Klein,
associate medical director of the emergency department at
Children's National Medical Center in Washington, said on the day
that John, Kyle and Burnell were treated. ``It strikes me as an
immense failure of the health-care system that an awful lot of the
asthmatics that we take care of are not being treated according to
those guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason, Busse said, is that the idea of asthma as a serious
chronic disorder that requires daily medical management is
relatively new, and many doctors have not yet accepted it. Another
is that pediatricians do not like to prescribe, and parents do not
like to give, daily medicine to children, especially steroids,
which can stunt growth and cause other problems in high doses. And
a third is poor health care and inadequate insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Ollie Cunningham is a case in point. At 45, she is the mother of
nine children, ages 4 through 22. Seven have asthma. The family,
which lives in an immaculate two-story, three-bedroom house in the
southwest corner of Washington, has no health insurance. Mrs.
Cunningham's husband, Anthony, is a maintenance man and earns too
much to qualify for Medicaid, the government health plan for the
poor.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Mrs. Cunningham said, she made so many frantic
trips to the emergency room at D.C. General Hospital, the city's
public hospital, that the doctors there knew her by name. Each trip
brought the terror of cradling a child who could not breathe. And
each brought a new worry: the bills.
</P>
<P>
   The family ran up such a tab, nearly $10,000, that D.C. General
began garnishing Anthony Cunningham's wages, his wife said.
Sometimes she borrowed money for the children's medicine. If two
children were given the same prescription, she would fill one and
have them share.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say this kind of crisis management is the worst form of
asthma care. It is expensive, and patients do not get the benefits
of steady monitoring from a doctor who knows them.
</P>
<P>
   The Cunninghams eventually received regular medical care,
although it was short-lived. In 1996, having worn out her welcome
at D.C. General, Mrs. Cunningham tried another emergency room, the
one at Howard University Hospital. There she was introduced to
Ellie Thornton, an asthma counselor.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Thornton was hired as an outgrowth of the Inner City Asthma
Study, a government-sponsored research project in which Howard
University participated.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dr. Floyd Malveaux, an asthma expert at Howard, the
study found that by working closely with families, counselors could
dramatically reduce children's asthma symptoms. If the parents
smoked, for instance, the counselor could persuade them to enroll
in a course to stop. If cockroach infestation was a problem, she
might arrange for pest control.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Thornton met the Cunninghams, she enrolled them in a
free asthma clinic that Howard was running at the time. For the
first time, the children had regular medical care. And their mother
got an earful of asthma education.
</P>
<P>
   The family's house had wall-to-wall carpeting, which attracts
dust mites; Anthony Cunningham ripped it out. Mrs. Cunningham
stopped using air freshener; she had no idea it was a trigger. The
Cunninghams got rid of their cat. They learned to keep the windows
shut when the pollen count was high, and borrowed money to install
air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   The toughest battle, Mrs. Cunningham said, was over her
husband's smoking. ``I told him, `You can't smoke around the
kids,''' she said. ``That was a shock. He smokes outside now.''
</P>
<P>
   But the help the Cunninghams received is not always available.
``I would love to have a nurse, or someone who could sit down with
families and spend more time with them exploring what makes their
child's asthma difficult to control and how they could improve
it,'' said Dr. Robert Fink at Children's National Medical Center.
But, Fink said, ``I don't have the money.''
</P>
<P>
   At Howard, the free clinic was open for only a year, although
the hospital recently obtained grant money and intends to reopen it
within the month. Mrs. Thornton, however, is still on board. She
counsels families from a two-room office furnished with a couple of
desks and chairs and an old baby swing. Her goal, she said, is to
shut the ``revolving emergency-room door.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Cunninghams, at least, she seems to have succeeded.
Although the family still has no insurance, and no regular medical
care, emergency-room visits are much less frequent now, and the
children's school attendance has improved. Mrs. Cunningham said she
feels more comfortable leaving home now. Recently she took a job to
help pay medical bills. Last year the children saw a dentist for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's made it better for every member of the family,'' Mrs.
Cunningham said, ``even the ones who don't have asthma.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
