<HEADLINE>
THREAT OF UNREST LOOMS OVER INDONESIAN ELECTION
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ The banners read ``Megawati or revolution''
and there are many people here who believe that they are not only a
threat but a prediction.
</P>
<P>
   Megawati Sukarnoputri, the standard-bearer of Indonesia's
political opposition, won the most votes in a parliamentary
election last June. But she could be elbowed aside in a hard-knocks
battle for the presidency that will be decided on Wednesday by a
ballot in the national assembly.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens and the voters are deprived of the outcome of
Indonesia's first free election in a generation, Sarwono
Kusumaatmadja, a former Cabinet minister, predicted that ``the
country will be thrown into total chaos _ total civil chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   The incumbent interim president, B.J. Habibie, is fighting hard
to keep his job, moving an unsympathetic assembly to a standing
ovation Sunday as he defended his record and threw himself on their
mercy.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all humility, I appeal for forgiveness for all my
shortcomings and for my inability to reach perfection,'' he said in
an emotional overture to a once subservient assembly that now has
the power to make and break kings. ``I am not some extraordinary
being who came down from the heavens to turn hopes into
realities.''
</P>
<P>
   Habibie is doing far more than pleading. His supporters have
been twisting arms and making deals within the 700-seat assembly,
working to gain allies and narrow the margin with Megawati's party,
from 153 seats to 120, that resulted from the June election.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Megawati has infuriated many political analysts
with her passivity, remaining aloof from the political battle and
making few public statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hanging on a very fine balance,'' Sarwono, the former
Cabinet minister, said of the presidential competition, which also
includes a third candidate, Abdurrahman Wahid, a prominent Muslim
leader. ``Outside pressure is now crucial to the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The pro-Megawati pressure is coming from all sides: from
students, from the poor, who see Megawati as their savior, and from
much of the country's elite, including executives at the stock
exchange, who staged their own rally last week.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of civil unrest is one of Megawati's strongest cards
in a nation where violence simmers constantly. And although she has
in the past refused to call her supporters into the streets for
fear of bloodshed, they are there now in large numbers, warning of
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Save Indonesia from chaos: Habibie has lost the right to be
president,'' read a banner at a rally Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It was the students, with their obstinate rallies, who forced
the crisis that brought down Habibie's predecessor, Suharto, in May
1998. And their continuing street rallies have helped keep a
reformist agenda alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pressure group par excellence,'' one foreign diplomat called
them. ``They are an important part of the political equation.''
</P>
<P>
   Now a new element has joined them in daily rallies that have
focused on the Parliament building, where the national assembly is
meeting to choose the president: thousands of poor people, who form
the base of Megawati's constituency.
</P>
<P>
   They are controlled by a strange private militia of supporters
of Megawati, wearing red berets and black paramilitary uniforms
resplendent with red insignia, patches, piping, buttons and braid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ready to die if she is not elected president,'' said
one militia member, Goenawan, a 45-year-old rice farmer who had
traveled from Surabaya at the far eastern tip of the island of
Java. ``We won't make it back to our villages; only our names
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressing one palm down on the other in illustration, his friend,
Entan Djayarasa, 50, said, ``Megawati stands for us little people
who are always being stepped on.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of demonstrators wearing the white headbands of a
multiparty group of supporters of Megawati were also proud to
describe themselves as ``little people.''
</P>
<P>
   They hurried to interrupt each other as they described the
attributes that drew them to Megawati, who is the daughter of
Indonesia's founding president, Sukarno.
</P>
<P>
   ``She never comments on anything,'' said Muhamad Amirudin, 30,
who has a low-paid job with a small manufacturer. ``She doesn't
talk a lot like the other politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Zakaria, 21, who is one of Indonesia's millions of unemployed
young men, agreed. ``She's very quiet,'' he said. ``She's not too
ambitious.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridu Ibrahim, 31, a slaughterhouse worker, explained, ``We don't
want a leader with too much theory.''
</P>
<P>
   Suwarno, a 55-year-old farmer from eastern Java, drew applause
from the little group when he said, ``I've come here to represent
the small people, like farmers, so our voices are not forgotten.
Megawati stands for us small people, so we owe her our support.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was a little doubtful about the notion of a revolution if
she fails to become president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what will happen if she loses,'' Suwarno said.
``As for me, the rainy season is coming and I have to go home and
plant corn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
