<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOURNAL EDITOR WEIGHS CNN OFFER  
 LEGENDARY CURMUDGEON  
 PLATINUM PORTAL FOR THE RICH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Paul Steiger, the managing editor of The Wall Street
Journal, is considering an offer from CNN to take the helm of the
network's financial news outlets _ including the troubled CNNfn
financial network _ which have been without their own leader since
the departure of Lou Dobbs in June.
</P>
<P>
   Steiger's talks with the network, a unit of Time Warner Inc.,
have been going on in stutter-step fashion for weeks, according to
people who have spoken with both parties in the negotiations.
Steiger, The Journal's top newsroom executive, has discussed the
scope and authority of the new job with CNN's president, Ted
Turner. He has discussed his options with Peter Kann, the chief
executive of Dow Jones &AMP; Co., The Journal's parent.
</P>
<P>
   If he decided to make the switch, Steiger, who is 57, would be
leaving the command of about 600 journalists at the nation's
premier financial newspaper, whom he has led for the last seven
years, to assume control of a staff of 300 at both CNN and CNNfn.
</P>
<P>
   The financial network reaches fewer than one-fifth of the 68
million homes reached by its chief rival, CNBC. And since Dobbs
left to start his own World Wide Web site, the lines of authority
over CNN's financial coverage have been unclear.
</P>
<P>
   But if Steiger made the move, he would follow a
newspaper-to-cable-TV path blazed by Tom Johnson, CNN's chief
executive, who was the publisher of The Los Angeles Times in the
early 1980s _ a period when Steiger was that newspaper's business
editor. The job of heading both CNNfn and the financial news
segments of the main cable channel and its Web site ``is truly an
international job, when there are few international jobs left,''
said one person who has talked to both sides in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring in Steiger's calculations may be the fact that it has
been rare for any managing editor of The Journal to move to the top
of the corporate ladder at Dow Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Steiger referred telephone calls about his discussions to
Richard Tofel, the Dow Jones spokesman, who, when asked for a
comment, would say only ``Pass.'' Sue Binford, a spokeswoman for
CNN, also declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   But the assumption that Steiger was about to leave permeated The
Journal's newsroom Friday. Among the names mentioned as possible
successors are Daniel Hertzberg, who is one of two deputy managing
editors, and, from elsewhere inside Dow Jones, Steven Swartz,
editor in chief of Smart Money, and Paul Ingrassia, the president
of Dow Jones Newswires.
</P>
<P>
   _ FELICITY BARRINGER
</P>
<P>
   Mythic City Editor Is Brought Back to Life
</P>
<P>
   In a year fixated on the millennium, a 65th anniversary does not
amount to much. But as an artifact of its time, the reissue of
Stanley Walker's classic 1934 book, ``City Editor'' (Johns Hopkins
University Press), has its moments as a saucy explication of the
Depression-era newspaper world. It's a baseline for how far we've
come and how far we haven't.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Walker was city editor of The New York Herald Tribune.
Before television and the flight of readership to the suburbs, city
editors were mythic figures around town, unforgiving tribal leaders
known for a thick brand of curmudgeonliness. Or, as Walker wrote,
the city editor was ``a chilly, monstrous figure, sleepless,
nerveless and facing with ribald mockery the certain hell which
awaits him.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker, by reputation, was a cut above the average misanthrope.
In his forward to the book, Alexander Woollcott described him as
``the most notable city editor of his time,'' endlessly fascinated
by ``the changeless and ever-changing Baghdad which is the
territory of his staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Walker's observations seem quaint. Decades before Evian,
liquor was an issue in newsrooms, though even then its use was
beginning to wane. But, in Walker's day, there was also a familiar
sense of foreboding. Chains were buying up independent newspapers,
and many worried that, with the growth of the wire services, the
entire industry was becoming homogenized.
</P>
<P>
   There was also worry about the great experiment _ the tabloid.
The Daily News, after its birth in 1919, had confounded all
skeptics and become a raging success. Where would this all lead?
</P>
<P>
   The public relations industry was spinning out of control.
Walker wrote: ``New York, where even the simplest projects must be
carried out with as much indirection, hocus-pocus and skulduggery
as human ingenuity can devise, is the natural home of the press
agent. The city undoubtedly has more press agents, if the disguises
of all of them could be penetrated, than it has working
newspapermen.''
</P>
<P>
   This was at least three decades before political correctness.
But Walker was not above linking journalistic traits to ethnic
traits. He called Irishmen, by and large, the best newspapermen
around. About Jews, he said: ``Jewish reporters are impossible to
classify; some are cloddish, some brilliant, some level-headed,
some itching with messianic afflictions, some profligate, and some
closefisted and scheming. One thing surely may be said about them:
most Jews know enough not to drink too much.''
</P>
<P>
   He also grappled with that great new giant of media _ radio. Was
it a threat, or a boon? Were radio reporters just pretty voices or
were they up to the job?
</P>
<P>
   His take:
</P>
<P>
   ``Radio eventually will drive many newspapers out of business.
Radio news will become more reliable. Newspapers, certainly the
stronger ones which survive the struggle, will become better. Some
day (it is scientifically possible now) some sort of television
device will bring a complete newspaper to the customer over the
wire. Whatever happens, the public can't lose. And the reporter
can't lose. That gentleman, whether on the air or at his
typewriter, will always have his work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Worth Strives to Be Internet-Oriented
</P>
<P>
   Pssst...Hey, you _ rich guy. Need a house in the Hamptons? A
Gulfstream jet? Want to buy one online?
</P>
<P>
   W. Randall Jones thinks that wealthy Americans are willing to
shop online for everything from charter flights to duplex
apartments _ and he's shifting the focus of his magazine company to
do just that, joining the wave of publishers turning their
attention to the Internet. Jones said last week that Capital
Publishing, the company of which he is chief executive, will now be
known as the more Internet-oriented Worth Media.
</P>
<P>
   Early in 1998, Jones had said he wanted to expand his print fief
_ which then consisted of Worth, Civilization, Equity and The
American Benefactor. But late last year, Jones folded The American
Benefactor and this year he said that the quarterly Equity would be
published twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at how we could expand this company,'' Jones said.
``If you're running a magazine and it's cooking on all burners, you
could get a valuation of twice the revenues. When you're doing that
with a working Internet strategy, you can get 200 times revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   With a $5 million investment from Dawntreader, an Internet
venture fund, Jones will build what he calls ``a platinum portal
for the rich'' _ Worth.com, which he will introduce next spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think of a day or a week in the life of a wealthy
person, we want to be the portal they go to to meet all their
needs,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   One impact of the reorganization: Joe Armstrong, Capital's group
publisher and a former publisher of New York and Rolling Stone, has
resigned. ``I am still in love with print,'' Armstrong said, ``and
I really want to be in a company where print is big and important,
the principal focus. Call me a fish swimming against the tide.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-99 1824EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991017.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9723 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-AFGHAN-MASSACRE-ART-2     10-17 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFGHAN-MASSACRE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN 100,000 TALES OF TERROR IN FORGOTTEN AFGHANISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAZARAK, Afghanistan _ Those who only had their houses burned or
crops destroyed often apologize because their story is not bad
enough. They are sheepish about complaining.
</P>
<P>
   And so they lead the way to the worse off, the irretrievably
broken or the unbearably sorrowful _ the children with parents who
were murdered as they watched or the men whose wives were carried
off screaming or the old woman whose story no one is sure of, but
she has been sobbing for two months now, fingering a red flower
embroidered on a pink cloth.
</P>
<P>
   Afghanistan's ruling Taliban militia, along with thousands of
Pakistanis lit with the fervor of jihad, went on a destructive
spree this summer, killing wantonly, emptying entire towns,
machine-gunning livestock, sawing down fruit trees, blasting apart
irrigation canals. It was a binge of blood lust and mayhem
described with consistent detail by witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Among the survivors are an estimated 65,000 refugees who have
escaped to the Panjsher Valley, a nape of land nestled within the
rugged Himalayan peaks of the Hindu Kush. Huddled in makeshift
tents fashioned from cloth and plastic, relentlessly foraging for
firewood, they are free for now from their tormentors but not yet
safe from the famously deep snows and furious winds of the winter
soon to come.
</P>
<P>
   On July 28, the Taliban began a long-anticipated summer
offensive. The militia, which has been on a largely unstoppable
march since 1995, wanted to take command of the 10 percent to 20
percent of the country not yet under its control.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   This time, they attacked in three places, sending their main
juggernaut into the Shamali Valley just north of Kabul. More than
6,000 soldiers rolled through towns and villages in what survivors
describe as a well-coordinated assault supported by tanks,
artillery and aerial bombardments.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The onslaught was overpowering, but after a week, as the Taliban
celebrated victory, they were stunned by a night-time
counterattack. The opposition forces of Ahmad Shah Massoud, their
lone remaining nemesis, hit back, springing ambushes and slaying
hundreds _ perhaps more than 1,000 _ of the Taliban forces, who
reportedly suffered even more losses in a disorderly retreat.
</P>
<P>
   It was a military triumph, but much of the land recovered was
already ruins and scorched earth.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did they have to kill my cows and goats, and why cut down
the mulberry trees and stomp through my garden?'' asked Mohammad
Kasim, 59, a refugee who now lives here in the town of Bazarak, his
home a tent of thin and porous blankets held up by branches.
</P>
<P>
   Kasim is a man with a long angular face topped by a turban and
completed with a thick under-hang of beard. He had the anxious,
bewildered look of someone terrified of the future. ``We have
nothing now except for God,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nafas Jon, 45, a gaunt, tired woman with six children, has taken
sanctuary along with 1,000 others in Bazarak's small, decrepit
school. ``The Taliban took my husband out of the house and cut him
down,'' she said evenly. ``They were killing everyone who looked
young, thinking they must be soldiers. I screamed then and I cry
now. We have nothing left.''
</P>
<P>
   She sat in a space made private by cloths hung from rope, a
hovel barely three-feet high. ``We returned once to see our
house,'' Mrs. Jon said, pausing a few seconds to frame the memory
in her mind. ``The ceiling is now on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Guldara, Saraykhoja, Bagram, Karabagh: from these and other
towns to the north of Kabul, dozens of refugees _ interviewed
independently _ had much the same story to tell, of people shot in
their homes, fires everywhere, beatings, abductions, mass flight.
</P>
<P>
   To them, the Taliban's purpose was obvious. Afghanistan, for
thousands of years one of the great crossroads of Asia, has endured
invasions and migrations that have left it a demanding
anthropological puzzle of ethnicities and tribes. The Taliban are
largely ethnic Pathans and they wanted to not only rid the area of
ethnic Tajiks, whose resistance to them has been steadfast, but to
leave their enemies with nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The militia's leaders have explained their summer rampage
differently, calling it a humanitarian act. They insist that
Massoud's forces _ the so-called United Front _ have used these
towns as redoubts for launching attacks. The populace lived in
constant danger.
</P>
<P>
   To ``save'' the citizenry, the Taliban forced most of them to
flee; others were trucked to Kabul, the nation's capital, or the
city of Jalalabad. Some 12,500 displaced people _ more than 8,000
of them children _ are living in the compound of the closed Soviet
embassy in Kabul, according to a U.N. report. More than 2,000 Tajik
men are locked within the cramped stone caverns of Kabul's
Pul-i-Charki Prison, said a spokesman for Massoud.
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 130,000 refugees in all, the largest
concentration of them here in the Panjsher Valley. For two and a
half months now, they have been pondering the devastation to their
earthly possessions and growing fixated on the icy challenge to
their survival that lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   International aid groups have been late to mobilize, apparently
unsure of whether the refugees could go back home _ or if those
homes still stood. The agencies are now swiftly setting up shop,
dividing the tasks: shelter, fuel, bread, blankets, medicine.
</P>
<P>
   This has not been a high-profile crisis because this is no
longer a high-profile place. In the 1980s, the West lavished
attention _ and weapons _ on Afghan warriors charging down from the
mountains to match the might of the invading Soviet army. These
days, few people are watching.
</P>
<P>
   Afghanistan is remote, distanced further by 21 years of war that
have reversed the course of modernization. Indeed, much of the
necessary aid must be carried over a single overland route from
Tajikistan. It requires a journey of up to 10 days on a narrow,
unpaved road pocked with ruts huge enough to swallow a car.
Momentous effort will be needed merely to keep the high-altitude
mountain passes from becoming snowbound.
</P>
<P>
   ``If both sides would agree not to shoot at aircraft, we could
have an airlift,'' said Fayyez Shah, who heads the U. N. team in
Bazarak. ``Or a humanitarian corridor could be opened on some other
roads.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Afghan government _ the one driven out of Kabul in 1996 and
still recognized by most of the world _ continues to operate, if
feebly, here in the nation's far northeast. Kamaluddin Nasami, its
planning director for the refugee crisis, said he is grateful for
the help of the aid agencies but is frustrated by their delays.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tell me the road is unsafe, but tell me where and we will
make it safe,'' he said. ``The fighting is not on the road; it is
to the sides of the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The refugees also complain. They are receiving wheat for bread,
and some have the use of bright blue plastic tarps courtesy of the
U.N. But the nights are cold, the children undernourished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each organization comes and makes a list and then nothing
happens,'' said Gulam Said, who lives amid a collection of 100
tents along the turbulent current of the Panjsher River. ``What
shall we do? Every week, we have two children die.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The air here teems with tragedy. The accounts of the refugees
rival those of Kosovo, the horror only lessened by its numbing
repetition.
</P>
<P>
   With fighting still going on, and the deserted towns still along
the front lines, the extent of the death and destruction is
impossible to measure. Individual stories cannot be confirmed by
first-hand observation. They are supported only by the uniformity
of their particulars.
</P>
<P>
   People are eager to tell these stories, their personal losses
now a vital part of their identity.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the many clusters of tents, Mohammad Wali, a
round-faced 10-year-old boy, poked his head through a crowd and
called out, ``They shot my father and I saw it.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He said there had been a hard knocking on their door. His father
nervously walked toward the gate. The men outside fired
Kalashnikovs. With his father dead, he ran back inside as fast as
he could. His mother, he said, ``needed to know about it right
away.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Shakar Gul, her arms around her nephew's waist, said the boy,
Gules Tan, is 3. ``His father was killed, and his mother was taken
away,'' the aunt said.
</P>
<P>
   She sat on a rock and occasionally lifted the cloth that covered
her head, the traditional chadar, to conceal her face. ``He cries
out, `Where is my mother?' '' she said. ``We tell him she has gone
away but will come back soon. In time, God willing, he will forget
her.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lida, 15, like many Afghans, uses only one name. She was wearing
a purple dress with paisley decorations, and while her eyes were
moist, she refused to let tears escape to her smooth cheeks. Her
younger sisters had designated her to speak for the family.
</P>
<P>
   She said, ``At first, they took my brother Sardar and my father
pleaded, `Do not kill my only son,' and then after they shot
Sardar, my father cried so much they shot him, too.''
</P>
<P>
   People wandered out of the ragged, homemade tents to serve up
their grief. A man scavenged through his pockets to find the tiny
snapshot of his murdered son. A weeping woman, Najila, 20, said her
parents were killed by a bomb as they drank tea. ``They had been
discussing how we were going to run away,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Akbar Shah, 50, said his sister died as their family fled toward
the valley, part of a flood of terrified people walking and
stumbling on the cramped road: ``She was OK, she was coming with
me. Then someone yelled, `Run, the Taliban are coming!' and
suddenly she just sat on the dirt, her heart stopped and she fell
over.''
</P>
<P>
   The Panjsher Valley was a two-day journey on foot from their
ruined homes. As refugees rushed across the crowded bridge near Gul
Bahar at night, they could not help but jostle each other. Many
fell off, grasping at the empty air, going down through the
darkness onto the rocks and water below.
</P>
<P>
   Zaker, a 12-year-old boy in a torn brown sweater, said he, too,
lost his father to the Taliban's busy Kalashnikovs. Then his mother
tumbled off the Gul Bahar bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listened for her voice for a long time, and then went on,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tajiks speak a dialect of Persian called Dari. Their
attackers, they said, spoke not only Pushtun, the tongue of the
Pathans, but Urdu and Punjabi, languages more commonly spoken in
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Mullah Mohammad Omar, the Taliban's supreme leader, had called
upon Muslims in madrasahs, or religious schools, to join the jihad.
Thousands of students in neighboring Pakistan share the Taliban's
puritanical interpretation of Islam. They were openly bussed across
major border crossings and given weapons training.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the refugees, Sardar Agha, 28, a man in a
wheelchair, insisted that some of his attackers were foreigners.
``I know Afghans,'' he said. ``They were not Afghans.''
</P>
<P>
   Some made other distinctions. Taliban army regulars enforced
cultural taboos, smashing TV sets and ripping apart music tapes.
Newer recruits, whether Afghans or Pakistanis, were more likely to
be thieves, a few refugees said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd bust into your house, hold a gun to the head of your
children and demand either money or guns,'' said a woman from
Kapisa province, a former literature professor. She asked for
anonymity because she had relatives still in Kabul. ``If you
complained to the Talibs, they'd tell you that they didn't control
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the refugees here may be poorer than they were, but not
all are poor. A few escaped by car, their most valued possessions
tethered to the roof with rope.
</P>
<P>
   Some families from Bagram, confessing prosperity, had several
hand-made oriental carpets stacked against their tent walls, and
others to make soft floors atop the stony soil.
</P>
<P>
   But there are not many comforts to purchase in the Panjsher
Valley. In Bazarak, there is no telephone service. Electrical power
comes only from private generators, and the fuel to run them is
exorbitantly priced. The river is both a wash basin and a toilet.
</P>
<P>
   Basic shelter for the refugee multitude has been left to ACTED,
a French charity. The agency has a plan: Public buildings will be
insulated. Damaged houses will be repaired. Twenty-five hundred
``survival cells'' will be built _ simple dwellings with walls of
stone and mortar, windows of plastic sheeting and roofs of bamboo.
Building is just getting started. The planners hope it will be
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Priority will be given to the hundreds of families now living in
mosques, which need to be vacated. With the weather getting cold,
men no longer want to say their prayers on the rooftops of their
holy places.
</P>
<P>
   Bazarak's mosque is a modest yellow building, a single open
space with a green carpet. Fifty-one families are living there.
Outside, women feed wood chips into cooking fires, their heads bent
to the ground, their breath used to stoke the embers.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby is the town's school. Many of its desks have become the
undersized walls for cave-like spaces. Hanging blankets often
separate one family from the next. The largest room has the
appearance of a multi-colored maze.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the small spaces, near an open doorway, a woman named
Anita, 35, spoke of the death of the youngest of her eight
children. The girl's name was Farastha, age 1. The child began to
cry and quiver when the Taliban bombardment began and never seemed
to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``She died of fear,'' the mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Twilight had come, and the school was growing dark. Anita pulled
close one of her small children and buttoned his sweater. The wind
had stirred, sweeping down as it does from the mountains at night,
another reminder of the winter day by day creeping near.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
