<DOCNO> NYT19991017.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9725 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-COLLEGE-REPORT-NY     10-17 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLLEGE-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOOK TOWARD THE COLLEGE FOOTBALL FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two of the most memorable predictions in my lifetime have been
intoned by Jon Landau and Beano Cook. Back in the 1970s, Landau was
a rock critic who listened, watched, and was moved enough by a New
Jersey singer-songwriter to declare him the ``rock'n'roll future.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, Beano Cook was a television sports pundit who
watched, listened and was moved enough by a Notre Dame quarterback
to say that the kid would win an unprecedented three Heisman
Trophies.
</P>
<P>
   Landau was right about Bruce Springsteen and went on to manage
and produce some of the Boss' albums as well as to become a wealthy
and influential music impresario on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Cook was dead wrong about Ron Powlus, who never came close to
winning one Heisman, but Beano remains an entertaining presence on
cable television.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the penthouse and outhouse addresses of prognosticators
in mind, there's a couple of educated (mostly) predictions to make
now that the1999 college football season is beyond the halfway
point.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term: First, Tommy Bowden and the Clemson Tigers
won't roll over for Bobby Bowden when Daddy and Florida State goes
to South Carolina this week to win his milestone 300th game and
keep the Seminoles' on track for the national title.
</P>
<P>
   Second, like Kansas State last year, Virginia Tech will now be
discovered by the national media, ridiculed for its soft schedule
and roil the Bowl Championship Series rankings down to the final
week of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In the medium range: The Big Ten title race is brutal, muddled
and will change each Saturday as upstarts surge and front-runners
stumble.
</P>
<P>
   Finally looking long. As long as Notre Dame remains the most
galvanizing college football program in America, and Steve Spurrier
remains the game's most galvanizing coach, Spurrier-to-Notre Dame
will remain a constant and most sizzling rumor in all of sports.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the prospect of Bowden meeting Bowden to become only
the fifth Division I-A coach to reach 300 victories isn't as warm
and fuzzy as it looked before the season. The Seminoles (7-0, No. 4
in The New York Times computer rankings) are getting more attention
for the legal saga of wide receiver Peter Warrick than they are for
their recent play.
</P>
<P>
   With the one-time Heisman front runner sidelined by suspension
for a second week while awaiting to somehow depose of a felony
grand theft charge, Florida State struggled to a 9-3 halftime lead
over lightly regarded Wake Forest Saturday before putting a 33-10
victory in the books.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play great, but we came away with a win,'' said
Chris Weinke, who completed passes to 10 receivers for a
career-high 354 yards. ``We will have to be sharper for 60 minutes
the rest of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   His team's poor performance rattled the elder Bowden who knows
he must get by a budding genius in Tommy if he intends to join Joe
Paterno, Amos Alonzo Stagg, Bear Bryant and Pop Warner in the
stratosphere of the college game's honor roll next week. ``We
weren't sharp tonight. We'd better be sharp next week or we'll get
our butts whipped.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bowden, meanwhile, has taken the remnants of a team
that was 3-8 last year and transformed them into a respectable 3-3
_ including a victory over Virginia and a three point loss to
Marshall (No. 12 in the NYT computer rankings) by turning the
offense into an aerial circus. Last year, he showed he could do
more with less by leading Tulane to a 12-0 record and might just
delay his father's 300-win game ball from arriving at the College
Football Hall of Fame for another week.
</P>
<P>
   But immediately brace to hear a lot about the Hokies of Virginia
Tech. They are 6-0, No. 2 in the NYT computer rankings and totally
annihilated Syracuse Saturday, 62-0, hanging the Orangemen with the
largest shutout loss by a ranked team in the history of the
Associated Press media poll. ``Some people may still be a little
bit doubtful, but Syracuse was the (AP) 16th-ranked team in the
nation. To beat a ranked team like this, it should say a lot,''
said Hokies receiver Andre Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Frank Beamer has built a fine program on defense and
special teams that has played on New Year's day bowls in five of
the last six years. Virginia Tech fans will hear a lot about a soft
schedule that already has featured James Madison, University of
Alabama-Birmingham and winless Rutgers, and only Miami remains with
legitimate upset potential. When the BCS releases its rankings
after this week's games, it will be interesting to see how the
eight computer rankings treat the Hokies' strength of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The prediction is that at the end of the season Virginia Tech
needs to be one of two undefeated teams in the BCS if they want to
play in the national title game. If Florida State, Nebraska and
Penn State go unbeaten _ or two of the three do _ Virginia Tech is
out of the Sugar Bowl because of their schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Ten race? Michigan survives the nation's toughest early
season ticket only to lose to undefeated Michigan State last week,
which loses Saturday to a Purdue team that lost the previous two
weeks at Michigan and Ohio State. What it means is that the Big Ten
is the nation's toughest conference and Penn State (7-0, No. 5 in
the NYT computer rankings) is going to have a very difficult time
winning out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have put 40 on the board. We had two field goals
blocked, we stopped ourselves inside their 25 all day. Stupid head
problems. We have to cut them out or it will catch up to us,''
conceded fullback Mike Cerimele, the Penn State fullback, after a
23-10 victory over Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   The prediction? It does catch up _ and either Purdue, Michigan
or Michigan State take down the conference's only undefeated team.
</P>
<P>
   Last but hardly least, the annual Spurrier to Notre Dame rumor
is in the air. It starts in the Southeastern Conference where fans
can't stand the flamboyant coach who regularly beats them. It is
embraced by the vast Notre Dame community which is tiring of Bob
Davie's reign.
</P>
<P>
   The prediction: When (If?) Spurrier takes over in South Bend,
the Fighting Irish win six titles in the coach's first 10 years and
the Notre Dame television contract increases to Olympic
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   That's one for you, Beano.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
