<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9726 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-MCCONNELL-PROFILE-ART     10-17 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCONNELL-PROFILE-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING OFF CAMPAIGN REFORM, WITH FIRST AMENDMENT'S SHIELD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ky., Ariz.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It has become one of the enduring rituals on
Capitol Hill:
</P>
<P>
   A bill to overhaul the nation's campaign finance laws is being
debated on the floor of the Senate. Its advocates and their many
allies on the editorial pages are in full cry, demanding change for
the sake of a cleaner, better, more democratic politics. And the
senior senator from Kentucky, Mitch McConnell, is doing his best to
block the bill.
</P>
<P>
   So it went last week: Cheerfully, with conviction, with no
apologies, McConnell stood in the well of the Senate, hour after
hour, swatting back arguments that the system is corrupt, that it
breeds cynicism, that it shuts out the little guy for the monied
special interests. ``I have sort of been the designated spear
catcher on this issue,'' McConnell said, somewhat proudly, during a
recent break in the debate, which is now focused on a proposed ban
on ``soft money,'' the unlimited contributions that go to the
political parties.
</P>
<P>
   Does he read what they say about him, all those editorial
writers who cast him as the dark knight, the enemy of reform?
</P>
<P>
   ``I read them,'' he said. ``I find them exhilarating. The more
they beat me up, the more I'm determined to try to prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   McConnell, 57, a Republican first elected to the Senate in 1984,
has been in this struggle for a very long time _ ``the point man on
this issue for our side since the late 1980s,'' as he puts it, and
intellectually engaged for longer than that. Not surprisingly, he
presents himself as the defender of the First Amendment, not of
corrupt, big money politics. It is not really about money, he
suggests, but about free speech.
</P>
<P>
   He delights in upending the conventional wisdom. ``Everyone who
runs against me thinks, `This is the way I'm going to beat this
guy,' '' he said, a small smile playing around his otherwise stern
face. (He was re-elected with 55 percent of the vote in 1996.)
McConnell says his message to the voters is simple: ``I don't think
the government ought to be in charge of how many of you can
contribute to my campaign, or how often I may speak, or what I may
say. This is all about whether the government can determine who
gets to speak, how much they get to speak, and when they get to
speak in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   He is scornful of past efforts at regulating campaign
contributions, arguing that the much-vaunted $1,000 limit on
individual contributions ended up benefiting ``the well-off _ Steve
Forbes _ or the well-known _ George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing wrong with the current system is the last
reform,'' McConnell said. ``And the last thing we need to do is
take that kind of nonsense any further.''
</P>
<P>
   Such arguments drive his opponents around the bend. ``I find the
disingenuousness of his comments breathtaking,'' said Charles
Lewis, executive director of the Center for Public Integrity.
``Every narrow, grubby thing that comes before Congress involving
money and power is usually cloaked with something noble and
majestic. He has found the First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   Many critics note that McConnell has a more than constitutional
interest in how the campaign finance laws work: An avid fund-raiser
and hard-ball political strategist, he is chairman of the National
Republican Senatorial Committee, and thus charged with protecting
and enlarging his party's majority in the 2000 elections. He argued
on NBC's ``Meet The Press'' on Sunday that Republicans needed
``soft money'' to level the playing field because so much of the
political discussion in the press, academia and Hollywood was
dominated by the left.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell flinches a little at the term ``career politician,''
noting that it has acquired a pejorative cast, but he has spent his
life in electoral politics. The son of a employee relations manager
for DuPont, McConnell was born in Alabama and raised in south
Louisville. His childhood was marked by polio, which he contracted
at age 2, and which kept him off his feet until he was 5. His
interest in politics came early; he was elected student body
president in high school and again at the University of Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   A portrait of one of his inspirations hangs in his Senate
office: a great uncle who was the elected Democratic probate judge
of Limestone County, Ala. But his biggest inspiration, he said, was
the late Sen. John Sherman Cooper of Kentucky; McConnell was an
intern in his office in 1964, when Cooper was supporting the
landmark Civil Rights Act in the face of vocal opposition back
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I liked about Sen. Cooper was his willingness to go
against the flow,'' McConnell said. ``It was not ever envisioned
that we would come up here and be a kind of rolling poll, or sort
of like that plant over there, that potted plant, and just sort of
accept input and do whatever the popular mood was at the moment.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   McConnell takes prickly offense at the prevailing wisdom that
the Senate is not the institution it used to be. The current
legislative struggle pits him against a fellow Republican, Sen.
John McCain of Arizona, who is seeking his party's presidential
nomination and has made cleaning up the campaign finance system a
central part of his platform. McConnell and his allies verbally
pummeled McCain this week for raising the notion that Congress has
been corrupted by special interest political money.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell said afterward, ``There's never been an exchange I've
been involved in on the Senate floor that's gotten me more pats on
the back from my colleagues on both sides of the aisle. For a
colleague who's running for president to make a cornerstone of his
campaign that this institution is corrupt, and then be called upon
to prove it and have no evidence whatsoever, is pretty galling to
those of us who work here every day.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who spent more than five years in a prisoner of war camp
during Vietnam, countered later, ``I've faced a lot tougher things
in my life than Mitch McConnell's temper tantrums.''
</P>
<P>
   McConnell, who has three grown daughters by a first marriage, is
now married to Elaine Chao, a distinguished fellow at the Heritage
Foundation and a former director of the Peace Corps in the Bush
administration. Asked how he spends his leisure time, McConnell
says, ``I have a great wife. We enjoy each other's company.''
</P>
<P>
   He also fishes and reads. But politics is clearly his passion,
and the political fray his favorite place to be. ``I'm proud of my
enemies,'' he said. ``If I had to be disliked by an organization, I
can't think of a better one to be disliked by than Common Cause.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
