<HEADER>
A9728 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SCI-ASTHMA-S-ART-2TAK     10-17 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ASTHMA-S-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTHMA BECOMES AN EPIDEMIC AMONG CITY CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: A longer version of this story, slugged SCI-ASTHMA-L, is
being sent. A related story, on methods of treating asthma, will be
sent on Oct. 19.) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphics are
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The asthma epidemic visited Children's National Medical Center
one recent Friday, the day after a furious rainstorm kicked up
allergens all over Washington. By 9 a.m., the emergency room, where
children come in more often for failing lungs than for broken
bones, was jumping. Harried nurses barked orders for the pharmacy
to send more drugs. In bed after bed, young faces, all
African-American, were buried under clear plastic breathing masks.
</P>
<P>
   John Thompson, a skinny, bright-eyed 8-year-old, was there,
watching Richard Scarry videos while sniffing steroids to relax his
swollen airways. His mother, who had taken a bus and three subway
trains to get to the hospital, lost her pay that day. She had
already used all her sick leave to care for two asthmatic children.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Mosley, an athletic 13-year-old with a mouthful of braces,
rested quietly in a room around the corner; he had woken up at 4
that morning, gasping for breath.
</P>
<P>
   This is the other inner-city epidemic: asthma. The burden of
AIDS on the poor and minorities has been well documented. Asthma is
less deadly; it claims about 5,000 lives in the United States each
year. Yet the death statistics do not begin to tell the story of
how an unprecedented _ and unexplained _ explosion in asthma cases
is suffocating the nation's poorest urban residents, especially
children.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid rise of asthma, in this country and in developed
nations around the world, is one of the biggest mysteries in modern
medicine. The most striking increases, experts say, have occurred
in Australia, where about one-quarter of all children have received
a diagnosis of asthma.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the number of asthma sufferers has more
than doubled from 6.7 million in 1980 to an estimated 17.3 million
in 1998, according to the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention in Atlanta. Of these, 4.8 million are children. Experts
say the increase is real. Although doctors do a better job of
diagnosing asthma now than they did in years past, that does not
entirely explain the upward trend.
</P>
<P>
   The epidemic cuts across racial and socioeconomic lines, but
asthma is slightly more prevalent among blacks than among whites.
Scientists suspect that the difference may at least in part be
genetic.
</P>
<P>
   But when public health officials measure rates of hospital
admissions, emergency-room visits and deaths, they find that black
and Hispanic patients, particularly those who are poor, shoulder a
much heavier burden.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows why the disparity is so great, but experts have
some ideas. The poor tend to have less access to regular medical
care, are less able to afford the medications they need and are
more likely to be around environmental ``triggers'' that set off
asthma attacks. Also, some researchers have found, families already
under great stress are less able to cope with the complicated daily
regimen that asthma demands.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma, a chronic, incurable disease of the airways, is
characterized by intermittent episodes of wheezing, coughing and
breathlessness. During normal breathing, air flows freely in and
out of the lungs. But during an asthma attack, the lining of the
airways swells, muscles around the airways tighten and mucus clogs
the tiny air tubes in the lungs, making breathing difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks can be set off by pollen, dust and dust mites,
cockroaches, stress, cold air, tobacco smoke, irritating chemical
smells, mold and mildew, respiratory infections or exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma sufferers can live a normal, unrestricted life, doctors
say, if they get the proper medication and stick to the daily
treatment and monitoring that the disease requires. But many
patients do not get the medical supervision they need or do not
follow their drug regimens properly, and so, despite new and highly
effective drugs to treat the disease, hospital admissions for
asthma are increasing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the most recent year for which the government has
figures, blacks were two to three times as likely to die of asthma
as whites. That same year, African-Americans paid four times as
many visits to emergency rooms for asthma as did whites.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to reverse the trends, the government is stepping
up asthma research. In May, Donna Shalala, the secretary of health
and human services, announced that the department would develop ``a
strategic plan'' for research into the causes of asthma and ways to
lessen the burden on minorities and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   In his proposed budget for next year, President Clinton has
included $50 million in grants for states to test methods for
improving the health of children with asthma who are enrolled in
the Medicaid program. That is in addition to the $118 million the
National Institutes of Health plan to spend on asthma research.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Clinton administration has made eliminating racial
disparities in disease one of its health priorities, asthma is not
on the list of six illnesses the government has identified for the
first five years of the program. That is not because the racial gap
is insignificant, the surgeon general said, but because experts
have no idea how to narrow it within the five years.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, scientists thought diesel exhaust and other
pollutants might be causing the asthma epidemic. Now, they believe
the picture is more complex. To begin with, asthma cases are
surging as pollution levels are declining.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Fernando Martinez, director of the Respiratory Sciences
Center at the University of Arizona in Tucson, said that scientists
in Germany had studied two populations, East and West Germans, with
similar genetic backgrounds but different environments, to
determine whether different living conditions could be associated
with different rates of disease.
</P>
<P>
   Experts had assumed that asthma would be more prevalent in the
more heavily industrialized and polluted East. But the study found
just the opposite. It helped scientists to see that whatever caused
asthma was probably separate from what triggered asthma attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, asthma appears before age 6. ``If we are going to
understand not what triggers asthma but what causes asthma,''
Martinez said, ``we have to look at the first years of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, scientists are focusing on genetics. This month, a team
at Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory in California reported the
discovery of two genes that contribute to the development of
asthma. Researchers are also looking at what happens to the immune
system in early life.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One of the most talked-about new theories is that the rise in
asthma is related to improved hygiene. The idea is that babies are
less likely to be exposed to viruses and bacteria, and without that
exposure, their immune systems do not mature fully. The result is
asthma.
</P>
<P>
   That might explain why people who live on farms, or in rural
areas, are less likely to develop asthma than people in cities.
Perhaps, said Dr. Sonia Buist, an asthma expert at Oregon Health
Sciences University in Portland, it is because people on farms are
more likely to be exposed to soil organisms, and that exposure
somehow immunizes them against asthma.
</P>
<P>
   ``A century ago,'' Dr. Buist said, ``most people walked around
with a load of worms or parasites, and the immune system became
pretty good at dealing with them. As hygiene has increased and the
water system has improved, we have done away with all that priming
of the immune system.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists know that asthma often develops along a pathway;
early in life, the immune system is ``sensitized'' to allergens and
pollutants that trigger asthma attacks. If sensitization never
takes place, they reason, asthma might never occur.
</P>
<P>
   At Columbia University, researchers are trying to determine when
sensitization happens. They are enrolling 480 pregnant women who
will carry air-quality monitors for two days in the third
trimester. Their babies' umbilical-cord blood will be analyzed, and
the infants will be followed for five years to see who develops
asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Until scientists learn more about prevention, doctors and nurses
are left to teach patients how to manage the disease, through
proper medication and changes in their environment.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, federal health officials recommended the daily
use of inhaled corticosteroids to control asthma in people with
moderate or severe disease. But only half the eligible patients use
them, said Dr. William Busse, a professor of medicine at the
University of Wisconsin in Madison who helped write the
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   One reason, Busse said, is that the idea of asthma as a serious
chronic disorder that requires daily medical management is
relatively new, and many doctors have not yet accepted it. Another
is that pediatricians do not like to prescribe, and parents do not
like to give, daily medicine to children, especially steroids,
which can stunt growth and cause other problems in high doses. And
a third is poor health care and inadequate insurance coverage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-99 1833EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991017.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9731 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CENSUS-POVERTY-ART-11     10-17 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-POVERTY-ART-1100(TRIMS)(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDEFINING WHAT IT MEANS TO BE POOR IN AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The Census Bureau has begun to revise its
definition of what constitutes poverty in the United States,
experimenting with a formula that would drop millions more families
below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau's new approach would in effect raise the income
threshold for living above poverty to $19,500 for a family of four,
from the $16,600 now considered sufficient. Suddenly, 46 million
Americans, or 17 percent of the population, would be recognized as
officially below the line, not the 12.7 percent announced last
month, the lowest level in nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   A strong economy has undoubtedly lifted many families, but not
nearly as many as the official statistics suggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certainly our opinion, and the opinion of every
researcher we have talked to, that something should be done to
update the poverty measure,'' said Edward Welniak, chief of the
Census Bureau's Income Statistics Branch.
</P>
<P>
   Fixing a poverty line has always been a subjective endeavor. The
current formula was created for President Lyndon B. Johnson to keep
score in his ``war on poverty'' and has remained unchanged since
1965 except for adjustments to allow for inflation. It is based on
a minimal food budget that no longer represents U.S. eating habits
or spending. The Census Bureau's new Experimental Poverty Measures
are an effort to determine what poor people must really spend on
food, clothing, housing and life's little extras.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no scientific way to set a new poverty line,'' said
Rebecca M. Blank, dean of the School of Public Policy at the
University of Michigan. ``What there is here are a set of judgment
calls, now being made, about what is needed to lift people to a
socially acceptable standard of living.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Sociologists and economists who study what people must earn to
escape poverty in the United States place the line even higher than
the Census Bureau's experimental measures, which were published in
July and are now the focus of a growing debate. They put the
threshold for a family of four somewhere between $21,000 and
$28,000. That is partly because the bureau's criteria, based
largely on a study by the National Academy of Sciences, do not
allow extra cash for emergencies _ to fix a car, say, or repair a
leaky roof, or to buy health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary Americans, in opinion polls, draw the poverty line
above $20,000, saying it takes at least that much, if not more, to
``get along in their community,'' to ``live decently'' or to avoid
hardship.
</P>
<P>
   But a higher threshold means government spending would have to
rise to pay for benefits that are tied to the poverty level, like
food stamps and Head Start programs. That would require an
incursion into the budget surplus that neither Republicans nor
Democrats seek.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the White House, which would have to authorize
a change in the poverty formula, is proceeding cautiously. ``We
have at least a couple of years more work to do,'' an
administration official said, passing the decision for redefining
poverty to the next administration.
</P>
<P>
   For Crystal McConnell and Austin Johnson, an Indianapolis
couple, the poverty line, in their view, is definitely north of the
$22,250 they expect to earn this year _ even in Indianapolis, where
incomes and living costs closely match the national average.
</P>
<P>
   The couple do not seem poor. They live in a rented brick
bungalow in a neighborhood of similarly modest, well-kept homes.
The brightly colored plastic toys of their two sons are strewn
about the living room, which is furnished comfortably with
faux-leather sofas placed around a glass and wood coffee table.
</P>
<P>
   But on a recent visit, the refrigerator was nearly empty. Five
small packages of pork chops and chicken parts had to serve as the
centerpiece of family meals for the next 11 days, when there would
again be money to buy food.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go to my mom's after church sometimes for lunch and, during
the week, sometimes for dinner,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 24, and Ms. McConnell, 22, have full-time jobs. As
commuters and workers, occupying a home in a presentable
neighborhood, they hardly fit American images of hardscrabble
lives. But poverty licks at them.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is without health insurance, which he considers beyond
the family's means. Once his provisional job as a load planner _
balancing the weight of cargo loaded onto jet aircraft _ becomes
permanent, company health insurance will kick in. Meanwhile, the
family is going into debt.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McConnell has health insurance from her employer, a
community center where she is a caseworker. But she did not have
insurance last year and still owes a hospital $630 for
emergency-room treatment of her foot, injured in a car accident.
</P>
<P>
   Housing, like health insurance, is a big hurdle. The poor are
twice as likely as the nonpoor to rent rather than own their homes,
according to a Labor Department study.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   That is the pattern in Indianapolis, a city whose housing costs
are right at the median nationally. When the poor do buy homes,
subsidies often grease the way, as they will for Florence Farmer, a
36-year-old single mother of two sons. The West Side Development
Corp., publicly subsidized, is renovating homes in rundown
Indianapolis neighborhoods and then giving away down payments for
them. Not many of the homes are available, but Ms. Farmer managed
to get one for $50,000, qualifying with her medical secretary's
income of $17,000, an amount $4,000 above the official poverty
level for a family her size. Her mortgage payment, $416 a month _
the maximum she says she can afford _ will be almost the same as
what she now pays to rent a two-bedroom house.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Ms. McConnell are struggling to stay in a
neighborhood with a good public school for their elder son, Cyrin,
who is 4. They moved to their three-bedroom bungalow in January,
paying $600 a month in rent, a sum Ms. McConnell says they cannot
really afford. The October rent came due on the first of this month
and was paid, but not the utilities, which were also due. The
couple gambled that gas and electricity would not be cut off before
their next paychecks, in midmonth. The nation's poor are four times
as likely as the nonpoor to have their utilities cut off, the Labor
Department found in its study.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana Economic Development Council, concerned about the
proliferation of low-wage service jobs, has produced ``basic
needs'' budgets for families here. The council concluded, for
example, that a single parent with one or two children, working
full-time, needs $20,700 to stay out of poverty _ not counting
child care costs.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Schrock, a researcher for the council, which works to
attract companies and new jobs to Indiana, said: ``We have to
understand where the economy is moving in terms of job creation,
and it is unrealistic to think that we will move away from the
creation of lower-wage jobs in the service and hospitality
industries.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns played no role in creating the poverty formula now
in use. Seeking good numbers in his ``war on poverty,'' Johnson
resisted setting the initial poverty threshold too high. Finally he
approved a formula based on a food budget designed to barely
provide sufficient nutrition _ and then only if ``the housewife is
a careful shopper, a skillful cook and a good manager who will
prepare all the family's meals at home.''
</P>
<P>
   To arrive at a poverty threshold, the bare food budget was
multiplied by three; at the time, food was one-third of the average
family's purchases. Today it is about one-fifth, but neither the
formula nor the original food budget has ever changed.
</P>
<P>
   The new thinking has several facets. It redefines income to
include for the first time noncash income like food stamps and rent
subsidies. It puts child care and other work-related expenses in a
separate category because they vary so much from family to family.
And it tries to determine what a low-income family must spend not
only to survive but to preserve a reasonable amount of
self-respect.
</P>
<P>
   A telephone is considered essential. So is housing in good
repair. Clothing is no longer just to keep warm or covered; looking
decent is a critical status symbol today. That is why Isaac Pinner,
a 16-year-old ninth grader and his sister Lea, 12, and in the
seventh grade, insist they are not poor.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the living room of their rundown rented home with
their mother, Julie Pinner, a 35-year-old receptionist and clerk,
they resent her decision to talk to a reporter about poverty. ``I
get what I want,'' Lea said, and her brother agreed. ``Why talk to
us?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by their clothes, they do not seem poor, although their
mother's income of $15,500, including a rent subsidy, while higher
than the official poverty line for a single mother with two
children, puts the Pinners right at the dividing line in the Census
Bureau's experimental measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think I am richer than I am,'' said Ms. Pinner, who noted
that the gas was turned off recently when she could not pay the
bill. She also lacks money to fix her car.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Ms. Pinner said of her children, ``he wears the latest
Nike brand shoes and she the latest Levi's. I like them to look
nice, and here in the ghetto there are standards of dress. If they
don't dress up to the standards, other kids tend to pick on them. I
am not the only poor person who dresses her kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Most proposed definitions of poverty include a car _ an old one,
to be sure _ which is deemed necessary not only to get to work but
for an occasional outing, or to drive to a supermarket. ``Not
having a car is a big dividing line between the poor and the not so
poor,'' said Christopher Jencks, a sociologist at Harvard's Kennedy
School of government.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, poor families here own used cars, but they
are often at risk. Austin Johnson, for example, says he cannot
afford car insurance. Neither can Nevada Owens, who is also short
of money to fix a flat tire. She drives her 1985 Delta Oldsmobile
with a spare doughnut tire permanently on the back rear wheel. The
car was a gift from her church, but the cost of gasoline for this
guzzler eats up 7 percent of her $17,300 in annual income.
</P>
<P>
   Her income, from welfare, food stamps, rent and tuition
subsidies and a $3,000 gift from her mother, puts Ms. Owens, a
single mother, and her three children just above the official
poverty line. But at 21, studying to be a licensed practical nurse,
she needs the car. The course work requires her to travel from her
school to two different hospitals, about 25 miles a day.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the Saturday outing in Ms. Owens' old car, which
she drives to her grandfather's home in a rural area outside the
city _ the one family luxury. ``We have a cookout,'' she said,
``and the kids play on the swings and my mother comes over _ she
lives two doors away. We have a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
