<HEADLINE>
FLOOZ GETS HELP FROM WHOOPI GOLDBERG  
 A BEAUTY ON THE BOARD  
 Y2K WARRIORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Va.)  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The actress Whoopi Goldberg has just signed on to be the chief
promoter of a form of online gift currency. By using her celebrity
in exchange for stock in the company, Ms. Goldberg adds her name to
a list of cyberrepresentatives that already includes the former
``Star Trek'' actor William Shatner and the tennis star Anna
Kournikova.
</P>
<P>
   The Goldberg deal involves ads on television, radio and
billboards that feature the actress promoting Flooz, a new
Web-based gift certificate system that the company with the same
name hopes will someday become a household word.
</P>
<P>
   The company gets its name from a slang term for money in the
Mediterranean region, according to Robert Levitan, co-founder of
Flooz Inc., which is based in New York. Previously, Levitan was
co-founder of the iVillage online network for women.
</P>
<P>
   Flooz works much like any gift certificate except that it is
redeemable only online, at least for now. Some 60 online merchants
have already signed up as stores that accept Flooz, including
Godiva chocolates, Tower Records and Fogdog Sports. Eventually,
Levitan said, people will also be able to redeem Flooz in
conventional stores.
</P>
<P>
   To give Flooz, someone enters a credit card number in a form on
the Flooz.com Web site and specifies how much they want to give.
Flooz then establishes a Flooz account in the recipient's name and
notifies the recipient of the gift by e-mail. The recipient then
receives a Flooz account number, which can be used for making
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Levitan said the company approached Ms. Goldberg because her
public image was consistent with that of Flooz.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both irreverent, hip and fun but also trusted and
respectable brands,'' Levitan said. In exchange for lending her
name to Flooz's ad campaign, Ms. Goldberg has become the company's
largest shareholder outside its founding circle and financing
group, Levitan said, declining to discuss specific figures.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
<P>
   Trying to Draw Eyes to a New Web Site
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of cybercelebrities, Cindy Crawford, who has turned
heads on the fashion runway, will now try to draw eyes to a Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   The model has been named to the board and given stock in Estyle
Inc., a privately held start-up that sells baby goods and clothing
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie McCartney, founder and president of the Los Angeles
company, insisted that Ms. Crawford was not acting as a mere
celebrity spokeswoman but as a bona fide strategic partner,
advising on strategy and using her contacts with designers. ``We
really see her as a very savvy, very smart businesswoman,'' Ms.
McCartney said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Web site, babystyle.com, includes Cindy's Corner,
in which the model writes of her favorite fashionable maternity
clothes and recommends baby products based on her three and a half
months of experience as a first-time mother.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Crawford, 33, agreed to join Estyle when she was approached
while pregnant. ``Being really in the moment of that, I really
believe in the project,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Far from being an experienced businesswoman, though, Ms.
Crawford said she was learning a lot from board room discussions
about distribution, fulfillment and different classes of stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my business college,'' said Ms. Crawford, adding that
her modeling jobs at Revlon and other places rarely gave her the
chance to participate in business decisions. ``Occasionally, I get
to put my 2 cents in about where the advertising should go,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Crawford is also on the board of 24 Hour Fitness, a health
club chain, and has her own fan Web site, cindy.com. She said
models must make preparations while they are in their prime for
when they are older and no longer in high demand.
</P>
<P>
   Strategic partnering aside, some of Ms. Crawford's duties at
Estyle cannot seem unfamiliar. Last week, she walked down a red
carpet as hostess at the company's coming-out party.
</P>
<P>
   _ ANDREW POLLACK
</P>
<P>
   Brief Flurry Over Year 2000 Bug
</P>
<P>
   Activists calling for more aggressive preparations for Year 2000
computer disruptions have been extremely frustrated at the general
apathy they have encountered and, as a result, the increasing
difficulty of getting media coverage for their message.
</P>
<P>
   That frustration boiled over on Oct. 3 in San Francisco, where a
small protest group, despairing of getting attention for their
concerns about Year 2000 readiness of nuclear power and weapons
systems, decided to parade naked through downtown.
</P>
<P>
   The brief march was led by Dr. Patch Adams, the iconoclastic
physician who inspired the recent movie based on his life, and
Helen Caldicott, a noted figure in the antinuclear movement. It
slowed traffic, made headlines and was ignored by police. It also
generated plenty of conversation among Year 2000 campaigners
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more extended reflections came from Jay Golter,
acting president of the Northern Virginia Y2K Community Action
Group, who apparently has not lost his sense of humor despite the
many months of being ignored by most of his neighbors. In his
organization's latest newsletter, Golter wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``Many aspects of Y2K organizing have been demoralizing. In my
own case, when our group started, I had suspected that I had a face
made for radio. When I had the opportunity to call in to the WAMU
radio show `Public Interest' during a program they did on Y2K, I
could listen to the audio file of that program. I then realized
that I have a voice made to be a writer. However, an entire
lifetime of experiences has led me to understand that I have a
physique made to be fully clothed.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, after describing the news from San Francisco and referring
the newsletter's readers to Web sites with further coverage, Golter
concluded: ``I still believe that nudity is a weapon in our public
relations arsenal that should remain sheathed. However, if any of
you decide otherwise, be sure to let me know in advance where and
when you will be demonstrating this large `measure of devotion' to
the cause. I'll be the guy wearing dark glasses, or a mask, or a
bag over my face, or...''
</P>
<P>
   _ BARNABY J. FEDER
</P>
