<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-COWBOYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS HOPE TO REVERSE MONDAY NIGHT FORTUNES AGAINST AN OLD
NEMESIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys have not been a welcome sight, and ``Monday
Night Football'' has not been a welcome forum during the past three
decades of Giants football.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1970, the Cowboys have won two-thirds of the meetings
between the teams. Frequently, by a lopsided score. The Giants,
meanwhile, have not won on ``Monday Night Football'' in five years.
They have, in fact, rarely played well across 29 years on Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   With the Giants struggling, a confluence of the two _ Dallas on
Monday night _ may not be what the Giants need right now. But the
National Football League schedule makers can be cruel.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, they team up these longtime rivals. The Giants
(2-3), desperate for a victory, have never beaten Dallas (3-1) on
``Monday Night Football.'' Ever.
</P>
<P>
   Not in seven attempts dating to 1971.
</P>
<P>
   And in those seven games, the Giants have been outscored by
188-82.
</P>
<P>
   If this is a developing complex for the Giants, coach Jim Fassel
and his players aren't letting on.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I think and worry about those things,'' he said with a thin
smile, ``it'll make me nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel wasn't sure he was even going to mention to his players
the history between the clubs on the NFL's biggest regular-season
showcase.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I tell these guys, here's the record on Monday night _ it's
got to change,'' Fassel said. ``Do I want them to be walking around
going: `Oh and seven, oh and seven?'
</P>
<P>
   ``That sets them back mentally. You're right, I guess you can't
ignore it. But then again, I'm not going to make a big deal of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Giants linebacker Jessie Armstead didn't know the Giants had
failed to beat the Cowboys in a Monday night game, but it doesn't
shock him either.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're America's Team,'' Armstead said of the Cowboys.
``Maybe they've got our number on `Monday Night Football.' But it
ain't got in my head. I doubt it's in anybody's head. You go out
and play football.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers might not matter if the Giants hadn't played so
poorly on national, prime-time television in general lately. The
Giants haven't won on prime-time television since 1995, which is
another 0-7 streak.
</P>
<P>
   They have been outscored in those games, 169-92.
</P>
<P>
   It has been suggested to the Giants that teams like the Cowboys
that play more often on national television might be more
accustomed to the experience. The Cowboys have won 11 of their past
15 times on Monday night. Overall, they have played on Monday night
56 times, more than any team except Miami, which has made 62
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' Monday night record is 33-23.
</P>
<P>
   But quarterback Kent Graham had a twist on that theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason those teams are on `Monday Night Football'
more often,'' Graham said. ``They're good teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel had a variation on the same theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like that old saying in football,'' the coach said.
``People ask: `How do you win on the road?' The answer: Take a good
team with you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants seem eager to play on the Monday night stage, even if
it hasn't been kind to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know everybody is watching,'' defensive end Michael
Strahan said. ``All your friends are at home watching. I think it's
great _ the Cowboys, national television. We might need something
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not surprisingly, most successful Giants seasons in the
past three decades, including some of their most memorable ones,
have included Giants victories over the Cowboys _ especially a
sweep of the two games the teams play every year.
</P>
<P>
   The only times the Giants swept the season series with the
Cowboys this decade was in 1997 and 1990. The Giants won the NFC
East each season.
</P>
<P>
   Other times the Giants have won both games against Dallas: 1962,
1963, 1984 and 1988 and 1989. The Giants went to the NFL
championship game in 1962 and 1963; they qualified for the playoffs
for the first time in 21 years in 1984, and they won the division
in 1989. In 1988, the Giants won 10 games but didn't make the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But there is an ominous flip side to measuring the Giants by the
Cowboys. Excluding the Giants early-season victory over the Cowboys
in 1997, the teams' first meeting of each season since 1990 has
been a Dallas victory.
</P>
<P>
   If you add the scores of those games: Dallas 217, Giants 70.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel might be right. Mentioning the history between these
clubs might not be a good idea for his team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
