<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SELFISH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS STRUGGLING WITH AN OLD PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. _ The same New York Knicks who nearly collapsed
under selfish play last season have been giving in to their
spotlight cravings again, running the court as if they were models
on a runway.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, they came prancing down the floor here on Saturday
night, looking to woo everyone with their spinning, brazen moves to
the basket. Whether it was Latrell Sprewell flying in against three
Cleveland Cavaliers defenders only to have his circus shot blocked,
or John Wallace careening through the paint without a passing
thought, the Knicks showed how quick they are to fall back on their
old me-first habits.
</P>
<P>
   So far, this style has the Knicks beginning their defense of the
Eastern Conference title with preseason losses to Philadelphia and
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our two problems are work, and playing together,'' coach Jeff
Van Gundy said after the Knicks shot 34.8 percent, and allowed the
Cavaliers to shoot 45.7 percent, in an 82-68 loss. ``So we've gone
through this before.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, it took the dismissal of general manager Ernie
Grunfeld and nearly missing the playoffs to snap the Knicks to
attention and change their ways. At least for the moment, the
Knicks have forgotten how they found each other along the path to
the NBA finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at this point either we think we're better than we are
or we think we're going to play well just because we practice hard
or we talk about things,'' said Allan Houston, who led the team
with 17 points on 5-for-12 shooting. ``We have a sense of everyone
trying to contribute, but they're trying to do it in the wrong way.
When we play good, we play unselfishly and play together. On both
ends, we're not doing that. It's a secondary thought instead of a
primary thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite rule changes designed to nudge scores higher, the Knicks
have averaged just 73 points in their two losses. Against
Cleveland's second and third teams, the core group of Houston,
Sprewell, Kurt Thomas, Marcus Camby and Charlie Ward lost ground in
the last four minutes by forcing shots, failing to pass and going
for the big steal instead of the smart defensive play.
</P>
<P>
   No one looked more out of sync than Sprewell. After being named
the starter at small forward before the game, Sprewell, in his
first action of the preseason, did not pass up a shot no matter how
ill advised. He ended the night 5 for 19 with 10 points over 40
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you want to call it overanxious,'' said
Sprewell, who had driving layups blocked twice in the first half.
``Whatever it is, I need to make that adjustment. I usually get
space when I go up. It's preseason. I have time to make the
adjustment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
