<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-COLTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCAS STARTS, STARS, FALTERS AND GETS HURT AS JETS FALL TO COLTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ In this season of the unthinkable for
the New York Jets, they lost another game Sunday , another
quarterback, and, apparently, any realistic chance of salvaging the
campaign that many fans believed would end at the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Lucas discovered at 10:30 Sunday morning he would be
starting his first National Football League game at quarterback,
while Rick Mirer was shocked to learn he was benched just as he was
preparing to suit up.
</P>
<P>
   ``How was I supposed to know my job was in jeopardy?'' asked
Mirer.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas led the usually moribund Jet offense to a 13-0 lead over
the fast-improving Colts.
</P>
<P>
   But as time ran out, with the Colts leading by 16-13 following a
series of Jets' errors, Lucas desperately scrambled and was hauled
down. And then a 292-pound defender rolled over his left ankle.
Lucas is now lost with a sprained ankle for at least next week's
game at Oakland, the Jets have fallen to 1-5, they are 0-3 in their
division and Mirer will get the ball back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's really hard for me right now to express how bad I
feel about what's going on,'' said coach Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I can say that hurt us other than the obvious
interception were penalties.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas will be the seventh Jets' starter to be sidelined at least
a game because of an injury. Despite his losing effort, he did
provide the spark that Parcells needed to kindle an offense that
had not produced a touchdown in two of Mirer's four starts after he
took over from the injured Vinny Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the change, which he said he didn't decide on until
Saturday night, Parcells replied, ``I thought we could get impetus,
which we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, at the end, it was Lucas' inexperience that put the Colts
in position to kick the winning field goal after an offside on a
Colts' punt had allowed the visitors to keep alive a drive that
tied the game.
</P>
<P>
   These pivotal plays sank the Jets, who have hung on because of
their defense the last two weeks. But there is no resiliency now on
the club to overcome errors. They have been in a funk since losing
quarterback Vinny Testaverde in the opening game.
</P>
<P>
   Leading 13-10 in the closing seconds of the third quarter, the
Jets lined up for the expected Colts' punt on fourth-and-three. But
Jason Ferguson lined up offsides. The 5-yard penalty kept the drive
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Peyton Manning moved them to the 1, the defense halted
Indianapolis, but Mike Vanderjagt's 18-yard field goal tied the
score.
</P>
<P>
   Two drives later, though, Lucas, who had been stymied much of
the game after the early lead, started to hand the ball to Curtis
Martin. Five straight runs brought the Jets to the Indianapolis 3.
It was first down. Victory loomed _ a victory that would have at
least put the Jets in position to get to .500 by midseason.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells called for a pass play. The Jets have not been very
good on fourth-and-one and third-and-short near the goal line all
season. That is why, said Parcells, he called for the pass.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas saw Keyshawn Johnson in the end zone. But instead of
tossing it high enough out of harm's way to the 6-foot 3-inch
Johnson, the inexperienced Lucas _ he had thrown seven passes in
his career before Sunday _ sailed one chest-high to the big
receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Jeff Burris got to it before Johnson, and picked it
off at the goal line while Johnson waited. Burris returned it 55
yards. It set up Vanderjagt's winning 27-yard field goal with 14
seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Jets' last chance and Lucas' sack by defensive
tackle Ellis Johnson, who landed on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blew it with the interception,'' Lucas said later from the
trainer's room. ``Life goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a crushing denouement to a game that had started brightly
and dramatically for a couple of New Jersey guys.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas (from Harrison) and Wayne Chrebet (Garfield) grew up 15
minutes apart. Lucas was getting the benefit of Chrebet's first
start of the season following his broken left foot in an exhibition
game.
</P>
<P>
   The very first play of the game was a pass to Johnson for 18,
but by halftime Lucas had connected with Chrebet five times. For a
change, the punchless Jets were punching out first downs and
converting on third.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Lucas led them across midfield the first five times
they had the ball. They needed points to have breathing room
against the American Conference's highest-scoring team.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' opening drive resulted in a 43-yard field-goal attempt
by John Hall that hit the left upright. The next drive led to a
45-yard Hall field goal and a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hall kicked still another one, from 39 yards, and it was 6-0. On
the opening drive of the second period Lucas and Martin led the
Jets to the Colts' 18, from where Lucas threw his first big-league
touchdown _ to Richie Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   It was now 13-0 before the Colts mounted any offense. This they
did quickly, with Manning drilling a 22-yard scoring pass to
Terrence Wilkins.
</P>
<P>
   Back came the Jets, down to the 37 _ close enough for the
strong-footed Hall to attempt a field goal. But on a third-down run
Martin was tackled for a 7-yard loss.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas was unable to do much the rest of the game, but the
defense and special teams kept the Jets' on the verge of victory.
</P>
<P>
   After a first half in which he hit on 14 of 19 passes, Lucas
connected on only two of his last 11. He didn't find Chrebet in the
second half. Martin's best rushing day of the season _ 23 carries
for 128 yards _ failed to take them far enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
