<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9770 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SEXNET18-COX     10-17 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEXNET18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online offenders lure youth for sex talk, acts
 &HT;    By Susan Spencer-Wendel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In the courtroom, Calvin Dodd, sporting
a charcoal suit, maroon paisley tie and wire-rimmed glasses, fit
the profile: Internet-fed sex offender.
</P>
<P>
   When the 43-year-old professional pleaded guilty last month, he
joined a growing group of clean-cut men with clean criminal records
caught in Internet dragnets. More and more, their online plans to
meet young girls and boys are being foiled by police learning to
use the Net just as well as those who abuse it.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly kept in check by their social or professional lives,
the men now sit home browsing through an enormous selection of
child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are out there lying in wait, having never been tickled
like that before,'' sexologist Susan LaFehr Hession said.
</P>
<P>
   The tickling of Dodd, who told the court he worked at Office
Depot's corporate headquarters, took place at the computer in his
Boynton Beach bedroom. There, police say, he downloaded child
pornography and began exchanging messages with someone he believed
to be a 13-year-old girl. The girl was really a Palm Beach Gardens
police detective.
</P>
<P>
   In their first online chat, Dodd began describing what he'd like
to do to ``her'' and, of course, vice versa, according to police
records. Soon, the two planned a rendezvous at a Shoney's parking
lot.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd missed the meeting. He later told the girl via computer
that his car's water pump broke. Nonetheless, police got a warrant
to search his home, seized his computer and found sexually explicit
computer photo files. They also found the receipt for the repaired
water pump.
</P>
<P>
   James Fortier of West Palm Beach, a development assistant at the
Kravis Center, had a similar case, except his car was working just
fine.
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon in February, the 40-year-old _ known as
``thefortres'' on America Online _ drove to a local Publix to meet
his new AOL acquaintance, ``sagster002.'' Online, sagster002,
supposedly a 15-year-old boy, had sounded eager to have sex.
Fortier promised to bring some beer and let the teen drive the car.
</P>
<P>
   Fortier parked his maroon Honda Accord with tinted windows in an
empty part of the lot and waited for the introduction. What he got
was: ``Detective Mike Bowman, Palm Beach County Sheriff's Office.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE THAN `JUST TALKING DIRTY'
</P>
<P>
   Inside the sheriff's office complex, the ``tickling'' detectives
work in a windowless, cool room. Two years ago, the Computer Crimes
Unit had three unsophisticated desktops. Now, there are file
servers galore, forensic diagnostic machines, compact disc writing
machines, and laptops dotting desks all around.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the unit's detectives, Sean Fitzpatrick and David
Hill, log onto various Internet service providers to go ``fishing''
_ dangling their assumed identities as children in places where
sharks will bite.
</P>
<P>
   Once someone engages them in conversation, they begin to tiptoe
the legal line between expressing interest in sex and actually
proposing it. One of the exchanges between Fortier and the officer
(sagster002) went like this:
</P>
<P>
   sagster002: I bet you can teach me alot
</P>
<P>
   thefortres: yes I can.....do you want to learn?
</P>
<P>
   sagster002: I know alot
</P>
<P>
   sagster002: i'm trying to find my friend i met on here last week
</P>
<P>
   sagster002: he was 36
</P>
<P>
   thefortres: cool......did you 2 get together?
</P>
<P>
   sagster002: yep twice
</P>
<P>
   sagster002: he picked me up at school
</P>
<P>
   thefortres: did you have sex?
</P>
<P>
   sagster002: yepper
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing is remembering I'm a 12-year-old girl,'' the
30-year-old Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   He reads Teen Beat magazine, listens to rap artists such as DMX
and Outcast, and talks with teens whenever he can. Fitzpatrick says
watching television is a great help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gotta be able to say `Oh my God! Brittany broke her leg!'''
the 33-year-old detective said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dodd said after his recent court hearing that he suspected
it might be a police officer. Phrases such as ``Can you expand on
that?'' tipped him off, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop him, though. ``I didn't think I was doing
anything wrong. I was just talking dirty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   CATCHING THE CULPRITS
</P>
<P>
   But for all the parking lot trysts police foil, an untold number
take place.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Coleman of Lake Worth _ ``SHAWN4LOVE'' on America Online
_ met his 11-year-old victim by chatting on AOL. The well-tailored,
clean-cut 25-year-old found out where she lived, and the two made
plans for him to visit her one January afternoon when there was no
school and her mother was at work, according to police records.
</P>
<P>
   The girl invited him into her bedroom. They looked at photo
albums, he offered to give her a massage and then proceeded to
commit three sexual acts considered felonies.
</P>
<P>
   When Coleman was arrested in February and questioned about
another girl he met online and had sex with, he said that he wasn't
sure of the girl's name because ``there had been so many.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people prosecuted in Internet cases by the Crimes
Against Children unit of the state attorney's office are like Dodd
and Fortier: men who arranged on the Internet to meet a child and
instead meet an officer. Offenders such as Coleman, caught after
the fact, are far fewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there are kids meeting up,'' said the unit's head,
Chuck Burton. ``It's just the tip of the old iceberg.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of cases prosecuted have ended in plea agreements.
Neither Dodd, Fortier or Coleman went to trial, presumably because
of the considerable evidence against them.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd and Fortier were put on sex-offender probation: Dodd for
three years, Fortier for five. Their probation includes registering
as a sexual offender, having no contact with children unless in the
presence of an adult who knows they are a sex offender and
restricting their access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman pleaded guilty to six felonies involving two girls and
could receive a sentence of 21 years. He remains free on a $75,000
bond until his January sentencing and is under the same
restrictions as Dodd and Fortier when it comes to contact with
children.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman is taking a chemical castration drug as part of
treatment he hopes will reduce his sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
