<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9775 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-PATRIOTS     10-17 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-PATRIOTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUARD COMES OFF BENCH TO LEAD DOLPHINS OVER PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBORO, Mass. _ It was early in the first quarter when Miami
quarterback Dan Marino flicked an 8-yard strike to wide receiver
Tony Martin. That play against the New England Patriots put Marino
over 60,000 passing yards for his career, making him the first
player to surpass that mark. Unfortunately, it was about the only
good thing Marino did all day.
</P>
<P>
   Age is clearly beginning to catch up with the 38-year-old
quarterback as his body slowly keeps breaking down. He was long
gone, sidelined with shoulder pain, by the time his replacement
rallied Miami to a 31-30 victory over the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Marino was suffering from muscle spasms in his
shoulder and neck area, and those pains continued into Sunday
afternoon against a solid Patriots defense. When a pass would leave
Marino's hands, it would die a quick death, taking a rapid dive
into the grass, like a pigeon trying to navigate a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was throwing change-ups,'' Marino said, ``and usually I
throw fast balls.''
</P>
<P>
   What became clear early in the game, after the Dolphins fell
behind 14-0, was that there would be no miraculous Marino comeback.
Instead, Marino's injury made it possible for his backup, Damon
Huard, to play the role of Superman.
</P>
<P>
   Damon who?
</P>
<P>
   This season has seen more quarterbacks come out of nowhere than
ever before, their resumes dotted with stops in cities like
Calgary, and paychecks earned from places like the Arena League.
Huard played his college football at the University of Washington,
last started a game in 1998 for the Frankfurt Galaxy of NFL Europe
and Sunday before 60,006 at Foxboro Stadium drove a stake through
the hearts of the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins trailed by eight points with just over nine minutes
remaining, but Huard led them on a thrilling comeback. One drive
ended with a a field goal, the last of six for the game by Miami's
Orlando Mare. Then Huard directed a 14-play, 59-yard drive in which
he was blitzed practically every down. No matter. His winning pass
went to Stanley Pritchett from 5 yards out with 23 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second straight week Miami had won on the road with a
late comeback, after rallying last week behind Marino against the
Colts. Miami won because of Huard's cool demeanor, Mare's six field
goals, and the Dolphins secondary holding Pro Bowl receiver Terry
Glenn to a startling zero catches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time Damon has played in a real NFL game,''
said Miami coach Jimmy Johnson. ``We believe in him. He's going to
be a great quarterback in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan is our quarterback,'' Johnson said. ``So I don't want any
controversy here. But if he's not 100 percent, we have Damon.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino, who does not get along with Johnson to begin with, may
be on a shorter leash than ever before now that Huard has
demonstrated he has ability.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Marino's ailing shoulder his passes were so slow and
soft that linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer, about as fast as a bull on
ice skates, stepped in front of one of them and took it 57 yards
for the touchdown. Like that, the Patriots were on top. Wham, bam,
thank you Dan.
</P>
<P>
   It had been two years since Marino left a game because of
injury. Huard at first did not fare better. One of his passes, also
in the first quarter, was intercepted by outstanding cornerback Ty
Law, who returned it 27 yards for the touchdown. The Patriots were
ahead 14-0 before the wind could ruffle one hair on Johnson's head.
</P>
<P>
   Miami stayed in the game because of Mare, whose 53-yard field
goal made the score 30-25 with 2 minutes and 45 seconds left. After
a Terry Allen run for one yard and two incomplete passes by Drew
Bledsoe (17 of 36 for 225 yards, one touchdown and one
interception), Huard took over, and calmly moved Miami down the
field with mostly short, controlled passes.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dolphins reached the 5-yard line fullback Stanley
Pritchett delayed going into his passing route, then bolted to an
open spot near the goal line. Huard laid the ball out and it was an
easy touchdown (the two-point conversion was an incomplete pass to
Oronde Gadsden). Having 2:10 to score and one timeout may have
seemed easy for Miami, since during practice Johnson has the team
run two-minute drills with only 1:40 and no timeouts.
</P>
<P>
   The entire game, on the sideline, Marino coached Huard, who
threw for 240 yards, keeping him calm and helping him with his
reads during timeouts. ``Danny was absolutely first class,'' said
Huard. ``He was there all day for me even when I was making
mistakes. He was telling me to hang in there and that we'd be in it
in the fourth quarter and not to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Huard's comeback was made even more remarkable considering what
he and his teammates overcame. First, there was the hostile crowd,
one of the more nasty in the league. Second, there were those two
Patriots defensive touchdowns. And third, New England had a
dizzying nine sacks, the most a Miami team has ever given up, one
shy of a New England team record, and the most for the Patriots
since 1979. Those are the kinds of odds Marino usually beats. Not a
guy named Huard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
