<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9781 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-PAKISTAN-RDP-1000(2TA     10-17 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-RDP-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUP LEADER RESTRUCTURES PAKISTAN'S GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TIM WEINER and STEVE LeVINE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ Pakistan's military ruler, saying his
nation had ``hit rock bottom,'' redrew its government Sunday night,
creating a military and civilian council to run the country and
giving no timetable for relinquishing the absolute power he seized
five days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling back from a confrontation that some feared could lead to
nuclear war, Gen. Pervaiz Musharraf said he would unilaterally
withdraw troops from India's border and pursue peace talks. He said
he would restrain nuclear weapons tests, although he did not
promise to refrain from them.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on national television for only the second time since
the armed forces seized power in a bloodless coup late Tuesday, the
general said he would ruthlessly pursue politicians and power
brokers ``guilty of plundering and looting the national wealth.''
And, in a rebuke to extremist Islamic parties, he warned clerics
not to stoke fundamentalist fevers for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   It was a passionate speech delivered dispassionately by an
expressionless soldier in full-dress uniform. Musharraf, 58, was a
near stranger to most of his countrymen until last week. But his
address, given first in English, then in Urdu, promised
``revolutionary steps'' to revive a near-moribund economy and
radical means to achieve them. If he succeeds, he may go down as a
hero in the history of a nation weary of politicians and promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty-two years ago, we started with a beacon of hope, and
today that beacon is no more,'' the general said. ``We stand in
darkness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our economy has crumbled, our credibility is lost, state
institutions lie demolished,'' he said. ``People who once were
brothers are now at each others' throats.'' Pakistan, he said, had
``a label of democracy, not the essence of it. Our people were
never emancipated from the yoke of despotism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shall not allow the people to be taken back to the era of
sham democracy, but to a true one. And I promise you I will, if God
wills it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even his supporters acknowledge that what Musharraf and the army
have done since Tuesday night _ overthrown the prime minister,
Nawaz Sharif, abolished Parliament, suspended the constitution and
re-created a government by fiat _ is illegal, unconstitutional and
essentially high treason.
</P>
<P>
   And some of those same supporters say there is no telling when
Musharraf might give up power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took Gen. Zia eight years to get out of this dilemma,''
said Ijaz ul-Haq, referring to his father, Gen. Mohammad Zia
ul-Haq, Pakistan's last military dictator. Zia seized power in
1977, ruled under martial law until 1985 and died in a plane crash
while still in office in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf said Sunday night that Pakistan was on the verge of
disintegration, and that he had risked the constitution to save the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not martial law, only another path to democracy,'' he
said. He said he would blaze that trail by replacing Parliament
with a six-member National Security Council. He said that the
council would include the chiefs of the navy and air force, and
four yet unnamed experts in law, finance, foreign policy and
national affairs, supported by a think tank of advisers. Under the
council would be a cabinet of ministers, also unnamed.
</P>
<P>
   The only remaining link to the old order will be President Rafik
Tarar, who held little power under the constitutional framework and
was a staunch ally of the ousted prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   To revive Pakistan's crumbling economy _ a mammoth task, given
the nation's near-insolvency and the way in which politicians and
their cronies use the treasury as their personal bank _ the general
said he would try to recover ``the looted national wealth _ a task
that will be ruthlessly pursued.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent history of nations like the Philippines and the
former Zaire, now Congo, where rulers stole billions and
impoverished their people, suggests that this will be a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the money has already been siphoned off'' to overseas
accounts, said ul-Haq, the deputy leader of the Muslim League, the
party of Sharif.
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf said that, in addition to prosecuting corrupt
politicians, he will force the wealthy to pay their taxes, which
will be a new experience for most, and will compel businessmen to
repay $4 billion in government loans that are overdue or in
default.
</P>
<P>
   He gave them an ultimatum: Pay up in a month, or go to jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice to the guilty is to return voluntarily national
wealth and bank loans and pay their taxes before the hand of law
forces them to do so,'' the general said. And he promised to make
his own assets and tax returns open to public scrutiny, an
unheard-of gesture in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   He offered an unexpected olive branch to India, four months
after leading troops in skirmishes against the Indian army in the
disputed territory of Kashmir. Sharif withdrew from the
confrontation in July at the urging of President Clinton, which
raised tensions between the Pakistani leader and his army to a
breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pakistan would welcome unconditional, equitable and
result-oriented dialogue with India,'' Musharraf said, and he
announced ``a unilateral military de-escalation,'' including ``the
return of all our forces moved to the borders in the recent past.''
About 30,000 Pakistani soldiers are stationed at the border with
India, in a tense standoff that has raised fears of the fourth war
between the nations since 1947.
</P>
<P>
   But Musharraf did not say that troops would be withdrawn from
the Kashmir area, where the border is disputed, and he pledged
support for ``our Kashmiri brethren.''
</P>
<P>
   (India reacted cautiously to the announcement, Reuters reported
from New Delhi. India's national security adviser, Brajesh Mishra,
asked whether he was satisfied, told the Star News television
channel: ``I am not going to say I am not satisfied,'' adding:
``But we will look at what he has said.'')
</P>
<P>
   Military men, politicians and political analysts said it
appeared that Musharraf, the chairman of the joint chiefs of staff,
planned to stay in power at least until the next scheduled election
in February 2002, and perhaps much longer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The former army chief, the retired Gen. Mirza Aslam Beg, who had
the opportunity to declare martial law when Zia died but held
elections instead, said Musharraf was right to seize power in the
way he did, but wrong not to say how long he would hold it or the
way he would wield it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wants to clean up the mess, he should have a very
undoubtful start,'' Beg said in an interview. ``He hasn't given a
good idea of the type of government he wants to form.''
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to gauge the reaction from the great mass of
Pakistanis Sunday night; most of the nation's 138 million people
are poor, with little real power, and no real voice in the nation's
politics.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Criticism came from Qazi Hussein Ahmed, the leader of
Jamaat-i-Islami, the nation's largest Islamic political party, who
said he was ``disappointed that the general did not expose the
names of those who looted the nation's wealth and did not offer any
electoral reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   But across the political spectrum of Pakistan's elite, the
people most likely to be hit in the pocketbook by the general's
proposed reforms, reactions ranged from cautious approval to
pleasant surprise to pure elation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never heard such a powerful, straightforward and honest
speech,'' said Sadruddin Hashwani, who owns some of Pakistan's
biggest hotels and an oil company. ``It is a turning point, a
chance to make a good country of Pakistan.''
</P>
<P>
   Ul-Haq, a potential future prime minister and the probable new
leader of the nation's most powerful political party, said: ``I am
both happy and sorry. Sorry because the speech should have been
given by someone with the mandate of the people _ that is, Nawaz
Sharif. Instead it has been given by an army general.''
</P>
<P>
   Javed AminKwhara, a landowner and farmer in Lahore, said he
worried that ``there was no mention of a time frame or a way to go
to the people with a referendum or something that would give people
more confidence. But there seems to be a consensus in the country
that you need a new political system.
</P>
<P>
   Najam Sethi, an outspoken newspaper editor, said: ``The general
has pulled these words from the agenda of the liberal
intellectuals. Most people will say, `What you say is right. Now
let's see what you do.''' But, he cautioned: ``This is not an
interim agenda. This is a two- to five-year agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehriyar Pataudi, senior vice president of Askari Commercial
Bank, called the peace offering to India ``the most intelligent
move I've ever seen a leader make in this country.'' He predicted
that the general's laying bare his personal finances would ``set an
example that might produce a different flock of politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf closed his speech with a prayer that he said he had
composed. He asked for ``the vision to see and perceive the true
from the false, the wisdom to comprehend the problem and find its
solution, the courage to do justice and the strength to do right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
