<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Oct. 19 and thereafter. All stories will move in the ``a'' national
and ``n'' California news files. For questions about stories,
please contact Mike McGarr at the Daily News at (818) 713-3470.
</P>
<P>
   LAUSD-BELMONT (Los Angeles) _ The scandalous Belmont Learning
Center _ the nation's most expensive public high school _ has
racked up at least $33.5 million in bills above the costs
previously disclosed by Los Angeles Unified officials. The hidden
encumbered costs bring the ``official'' cost of the Belmont project
to $159 million, about twice the district's original ``guaranteed
maximum price.'' By Beth Barrett and Greg Gittrich.
</P>
<P>
   LAUSD-ANGEL (Los Angeles) _ The Los Angeles Unified School
District could be saved by an angel. Nearly three months ago, the
district received a confidential proposal from the developer of a
curious angelic monument to buy the tainted Belmont Learning Center
property. The school board dismissed the idea in private without
taking a vote and has not notified an advisory commission weighing
the fate of the public works fiasco. But the developer says the
offer still stands. By Greg Gittrich.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINGSTEEN (Los Angeles) _ Review of the Boss' concert at the
grand opening of the Staples Center in Los Angeles, by the Daily
News music critic. Will most likely run late (after 10:30 p.m.
California time). By Fred Shuster.
</P>
<P>
   CHASENS (Los Angeles) _ Chasen's restaurant, where Ronald Reagan
proposed to his second wife and Jimmy Stewart held his bachelor
party, served up one last helping of Hollywood lore Sunday. The
famed gathering place for the movie industry's mightiest, which
closed in 1995, auctioned its restaurant equipment and nearly 60
years of memorabilia. The items included autographed pictures of
Frank Sinatra and Clark Gable, a telegram from Howard Hughes and a
booth favored by Alfred Hitchcock. By Dominic Berbeo.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO (Los Angeles) _ In a bold move to stem the sale of
tobacco to minors, Los Angeles is considering issuing revocable
licenses to all stores, supermarkets and gas stations that sell
cigarettes or cigars. The City Council has approved spending some
of the $1.5 million from settlements with the tobacco industry to
enforce the licensing program, and the City Attorney's Office is
drafting the law. By Dominic Berbeo.
</P>
<P>
   ALCOHOL (Los Angeles) _ Billboards for beer, wine and liquor
would be banned from most of Los Angeles, unless alcohol industry
attorneys win a hearing in court Monday. The attorneys contend the
law, which takes effect Oct. 23, infringes on their First
Ammendment rights to free commercial speech. The city, along with a
grassroots coalition of community organizations, argue the
advertisements have increasingly been aimed at minors, who cannot
legally purchase liquor. By Dominic Berbeo.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-BOXOFFICE (Los Angeles) _ Moviegoers chose revenge over
romance and mayhem as ``Double Jeopardy'' edged ``The Story of Us''
and ``Fight Club.'' Weekly box office figures, by Dave McNary.
(Will move in the ``f'' financial and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
