<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-VALENTIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: VALENTIN CAME FROM OUT OF NOWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The animated conversations about John Valentin took
place in the ancient newspaper offices of The Jersey Journal in
Jersey City 14 years ago. Every night, Larry Babich would shuffle
30 feet from the newsroom to the sports department and ask Mike
Hogan about Valentin's future. Hogan barely looked up from his
typewriter before telling Babich nothing had changed.
</P>
<P>
   Babich, a rewrite man for The Journal, was also coaching Jersey
City State College in 1985, and he thought that Valentin would be a
decent shortstop for that Division III school. Valentin had been a
solid high school player at St. Anthony, so a small college was a
logical place for him.
</P>
<P>
   But Valentin had another plan. Hogan, a sportswriter who coached
Valentin in high school, repeatedly told Babich that Valentin was
going to attend Seton Hall, the premier Division I university in
New Jersey, and try out as a walk-on. It was a gutsy decision by a
player who was barely recruited by anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll get lost at Seton Hall,'' Babich would bark to Hogan.
``If he comes here, he'll play.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan listened to the same recruiting pitch while his two
fingers pecked away at the keys. Finally, Hogan would stop typing,
look up and say again, ``The kid wants to go to Seton Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Because I was an intern at The Journal and because I had played
a couple of games against Valentin in high school and in summer
leagues, I was intrigued by these discussions. I knew Valentin as a
slick fielder with a powerful arm whose uniform pants were baggy
because he weighed 140 pounds. Seton Hall seemed like the wrong
choice for a slap hitter who was not even the best player on his
high school team. Like everyone else, I was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen years later, Valentin leaned back on a chair inside the
Red Sox clubhouse at Fenway Park, talking about his dramatic
ascension. It was 24 hours before he crushed Roger Clemens' 96 mph
fastball for a two-run homer as Boston pounded the Yankees, 13-1,
in Game 3 of the American League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   But Valentin, who has had a remarkable postseason with a .306
average, a team-record four home runs and 17 runs batted in, was in
a time capsule as he recalled choosing Seton Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in destiny,'' Valentin said. ``I believe that things
are going to happen if they're supposed to happen. I believe you'll
win if you're supposed to win and you'll lose if you're supposed to
lose. That's the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin went to Seton Hall but did not attend the first
practice because he was nervous about combining baseball with
classes. By the next day, the freshman relaxed and asked for a
tryout. Fifty other wannabes had the same brilliant idea.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Valentin's rise from an unknown walk-on to the
reliable and resilient third baseman for the Red Sox includes more
karma. If Valentin had not made the team, he would have stayed at
Seton Hall with his brother, Arnold, and, at 18, concluded his
baseball career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess,'' Valentin said, ``that would have been it.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, it is commonplace to watch the ALCS and ignore how
Valentin reached this elite level. If a player is talented enough
to make it to the major leagues, it is assumed that he has always
been great. Valentin was always solid. Greatness came later. Maybe
it was destined. One of Seton Hall's coaches scouted Valentin and
politely told Hogan that he was crisp defensively, but that Seton
Hall was not interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know that until later,'' Valentin said.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan had never discouraged Valentin and never told him the
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you should tell a kid they can't do something,''
Hogan said. ``If you do, they'll always wonder if they could
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin played one ``B'' game, immediately proved he was the
best fielder on campus and hurdled two incumbents to start at
shortstop. He lifted weights for the first time and bulked up to
185 pounds; he played on teams with Craig Biggio and Mo Vaughn, and
he was drafted by the Red Sox in 1988. Valentin is a .283 hitter in
seven-plus seasons, a good-quality professional player. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several reporters had finished asking Valentin about Pedro
Martinez and Clemens, so Valentin's voice was a bit giddier as he
talked about growing up on 16th Street in downtown Jersey City.
Valentin whacked baseballs on a concrete slab so nondescript it did
not have a name. It was just called the playground.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin smiled now, explaining how he is a pull hitter because
he never hit the opposite way for fear of breaking windows beyond
the playground. When I mentioned a tremendous player we both knew
who fizzled out, Valentin conceded he was fortunate to still be
playing baseball and confident about helping the Red Sox get to a
World Series for the first time since 1918. Valentin never expected
this. No one did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some kids I grew up with had great talent and they all went in
different directions,'' Valentin said. ``They went to the beach,
they chased girls. I didn't do that. All I wanted to do was play
baseball. Why? I don't know. I just did.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
