<HEADLINE>
HUMMING HYMNS, HERSHISER DOES IT HIMSELF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the year 2000 approaches, here's a look at some
of the interesting anniversaries that will occur this week in Los
Angeles sports history:
</P>
<P>
   __ Oct. 19, 1981: Rick Monday's ninth-inning home run lifts the
Dodgers past the Montreal Expos 2-1 in the decisive game of the
National League Championship Series on a cold, rainy night in
Montreal. Fernando Valenzuela combines with Bob Welch on a
three-hitter to win it.
</P>
<P>
   __ Oct. 19, 1960: In the first game representing Los Angeles,
the Lakers lose in Cincinnati 140-123.
</P>
<P>
   __ Oct. 20, 1988: In Oakland, Orel Hershiser limits the
Athletics to four singles and wins Game 5 of the World Series 5-1
to give the Dodgers an improbable championship. Hershiser, who also
won Game 1, is the Series MVP. He later goes on the ``Tonight
Show'' and sings the religious hymns that he had been humming to
himself between innings.
</P>
<P>
   __ Oct. 21, 1973: The Rams' Fred Dryer is the first in NFL
history to record two safeties in one game during the team's 24-7
win over Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   __ Oct. 22, 1950: The Rams set an NFL regular-season record with
a 70-27 win over the Baltimore Colts.
</P>
<P>
   __ Oct. 24, 1984: The Kings trade Charlie Simmer to Boston,
breaking up the ``Triple Crown'' line that included Marcel Dionne
and Dave Taylor. The three had skated together since Jan. 1979.
</P>
<P>
   __ Birthdays: Wednesday: Former Dodgers outfielder and current
broadcaster Rick Monday (54). Thursday: Former Dodgers shortstop
and manager Bill Russell (51). Friday: Former Kings star Butch
Goring (50) and former UCLA football coach Dick Vermeil (63). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
