<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPRS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS EXHIBIT SIGNS OF LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The NBA won't be playing with live ammo for
another 16 days, but the Los Angeles Clippers aren't about to
apologize for what amounts to a pair of ``paint-ball'' victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for these guys to think they can win while
staying within the system,'' said Coach Chris Ford in reference to
weekend exhibition triumphs in Toronto and Chicago. ``But we still
have a ways to go. We certainly can't feel smug.''
</P>
<P>
   No, but the Clippers also won't be feeling typically unarmed
when the regular season begins.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie swingman Lamar Odom provided evidence that he may be the
truth during a 25-point, 8-rebound effort vs. the Raptors on
Friday. Guard Derek Anderson, acquired in the deal that turned
Lamond Murray loose on Cleveland, added 20 in that game, then
pitched in 19 at Chicago on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's providing the kind of play I hoped that I was getting,''
Ford said of Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Another virtual newcomer supplying big numbers is backup
center/forward Brian Skinner, who spent last season as a somewhat
dazed-and-confused rookie on the end of the Clipper bench.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Bulls, the 6-foot-9, 250-pound Skinner scored 13
points, tracked down 11 rebounds and blocked 7 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an absolute monster last night,'' Ford said. ``It was
something to see.''
</P>
<P>
   But his production is not all that surprising to those who saw
Skinner at almost every voluntary off-season workout the Clippers
sanctioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really worked in the off-season,'' Ford said. ``And he's
grown tremendously in his knowledge of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Fast breaks: Point guard Eric Murdock, whose injured ankle
has kept him in street clothes for the three exhibition games,
participated in Sunday's light workout in Carson. Ford said today's
workout would determine Murdock's status for Tuesday's exhibition
game at Phoenix. ... A sore knee cut Maurice Taylor's minutes
Friday in Toronto, but whistles kept him on the bench for much of
Saturday's game. ``He was going to play his normal minutes
Saturday,'' Ford said, ``but he got into foul trouble.'' Foul
trouble reached epidemic proportion in Chicago. ``They were just
silly touch fouls,'' the coach said.
</P>
</TEXT>
