<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOODS18-COX     10-17 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Irene brings more rain, worries to eastern N.C.
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, N.C. _ Hurricane Irene drenched eastern North
Carolina with torrential rains Sunday, threatening more flooding in
a region still reeling from historic floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
   The storm had dumped more than 6 inches of rain late Sunday on
eastern North Carolina, and forecasters predicted that the Cape
Fear, Neuse and Tar rivers would crest again. The Cape Fear, in
particular, was expected to crest 20 feet above flood stage later
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Irene initially was expected to come ashore near the South
Carolina line Sunday night, but then it picked up speed and tacked
to the northeast, a path that may guide it along the coast. By
nightfall, it was 115 miles south-southwest of Wilmington, moving
northeast at 14 mph.
</P>
<P>
   A hurricane warning was posted from north of Edisto Beach, S.C.,
to Cape Hatteras. A tropical storm warning was in effect north of
Cape Hatteras to Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   No deaths had been reported in association with the storm in
North Carolina by Sunday night. Irene was blamed for seven previous
deaths, five in Florida and two in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The latest drenching comes a month after North Carolina's worst
natural disaster, Hurricane Floyd, caused record flooding. Floyd
was blamed in at least 49 deaths and damage estimated at $6 billion
or more.
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks earlier, Hurricane Dennis had soaked eastern
North Carolina, leaving many areas vulnerable to the 20 inches of
rain Floyd dumped Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all storm weary, but we can't ignore this storm. It's
very dangerous and has the potential to cause lots of damage,''
said Robert Carver, spokesman for the State Emergency Response Team
in Greenville, N.C. ``The ground is saturated still because we had
a massive flooding event and the rivers are already fairly high.
We're concerned the water is going to build up again, and it's very
likely we could have additional flooding.''
</P>
<P>
   With winds of 75 mph, Irene churned up the North Carolina coast
early Sunday and forced the evacuation of several beach communities
after North Carolina Gov. Jim Hunt declared a state of emergency,
the third in two months.
</P>
<P>
   State officials prepared for the hurricane by activating 300
National Guardsmen, opening 39 Guard armories and putting 10 water
rescue teams on standby in anticipating of flooding. The American
Red Cross opened 43 shelters in 21 counties.
</P>
<P>
   Officials opened three shelters in Duplin County, north of
Wilmington. By midafternoon, 60 evacuees had arrived, compared with
600 to 900 who sought refuge during recent hurricanes, said Carson
Smith, the county's emergency management coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that as winds began gusting, more people would
evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a savvy bunch of people down here, based on
experience,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   In Brunswick County, emergency officials opened three shelters,
but only 80 people had arrived by 6 p.m. Cecil Logan, director of
the county's Emergency Management Agency, said he was pleased that
Irene appeared to be taking an eastward jog.
</P>
<P>
   Pitt County officials opened three additional shelters Sunday.
Officials there were also concerned that fatalities would arise
from people driving on dangerous roads or going out to survey the
damage.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency in Greenville closed its
centers Sunday and today, anticipating that the storm would make
travel conditions hazardous. The agency set up disaster recovery
centers across the state to help residents recovering from
Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA will reopen its centers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keeping people out of harm's way is always our first
priority,'' said Federal Coordinating Officer Glenn Woodard.
``Potential storm water run-offs and local flooding from Hurricane
Irene could pose a risk to people seeking assistance as well as to
recovery workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials issued a flash flood warning for a 100-mile-by-50-mile
stretch of eastern North Carolina straddling Interstate 95 between
Fayetteville and Rocky Mount. Gale-force winds were measured at the
coast, and a tornado was reported by radar over Jacksonville on
Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   By early afternoon Sunday, water was filling ditches and
covering low-lying roads, some still lined by soggy carpet,
furniture and other debris from Floyd. Eighteen miles north of
Wilmington, water lapped at the shoulder of I-40, along a stretch
flooded by Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   The National Hurricane Center in Miami said there was a chance
Irene might skirt the North Carolina coast without coming ashore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too close to call,'' said meteorologist Bill Frederick.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina clung to that hope late Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears we are not going to get as much rain as had been
originally forecast,'' said Bill Clontz, with the New Hanover
County Emergency Operations Center in Wilmington. ``We think we
have come out of this in the best possible scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Irene dumped enough rain to add more misery to
flood-socked residents.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are having to evacuate temporary housing _ that's the
kind of year it's been,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the thousands of people who lost their homes during
Floyd have moved into more than 300 government-provided travel
trailers in Pender and several other counties. Other victims bought
travel trailers, moved in with relatives or friends or made other
temporary arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Then along came Irene, forcing the evacuation of the displaced,
many who had lost practically everything.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can only imagine the frustration and anxiety I have seen on
people's faces, having to move again into shelters and not knowing
what they will find when they go back,'' state public safety
secretary Richard Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only thing I saved was an eating table,'' said Maurice
Kelley, 27, a logger in the Duplin County community of Rivenbark
Town.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd's flooding of the Northeast Cape Fear River ruined
Kelley's mobile home, and he and his wife, Carol, bought a
37-foot-long travel camper.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley put it atop a hill to avoid future flooding. But he
didn't feel safe staying in it during Irene, so he and his family
spent the weekend at his in-laws.
</P>
<P>
   In Rocky Mount, 300 people returned to a shelter after Irene
forced them to evacuate their campers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I fear the next step we're going to make is in the ground,''
said 37-year-old Fannie Lewis. ''You can run, but you can't hide.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution and Nichole
Monroe of The (Greenville, N.C.) Daily Reflector contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
