<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THIS TIME JETS LOSE MORE THAN A GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Not long after Ray Lucas arrived in the
New York Jets locker room Sunday, he was on cloud nine; he would be
a starting quarterback for the first time since he was at Rutgers
in 1995. But when he finally returned to the locker room after the
16-13 loss to the Colts, he was on crutches.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the Jets had found a quarterback, they lost him.
</P>
<P>
   Life's been like that for the Jets' quarterbacks this shattered
season. Vinny Testaverde has been on crutches ever since he tore an
Achilles tendon in the season opener. And now Lucas, sacked by
defensive tackle Ellis Johnson on the last play of the game, is on
crutches with what the Jets are describing as a sprained left
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``More X-rays will be taken Monday,'' said Dr. Elliott Hershman,
a Jets orthopedist. ``We'll know more after those X-rays.''
</P>
<P>
   Notice that the Jets were not saying if the X-rays were negative
or not, so Lucas' injury could be worse than a sprain. But things
can't get much worse for the Jets, who are 1-5 and now must turn to
the demoted Rick Mirer at quarterback with punter Tom Tupa as the
backup for next Sunday's game in Oakland and probably beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to get a little spark,'' Parcells said, alluding
to why he chose Lucas to start. ``I made the decision late Saturday
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells had considered switching quarterbacks after last Monday
night's 16-6 loss to the Jacksonville Jaguars, then on Wednesday he
announced, ``Mirer starts'' against the Colts. But throughout the
week Lucas got 50 percent of the snaps in practice and Sunday he
got the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had practiced all week for Mirer,'' said Colts linebacker
Cornelius Bennett, ``but we knew about the running threat of
Lucas.''
</P>
<P>
   That running threat helped Lucas, who completed 10 of his first
14 passes for 87 yards, directing the Jets to a quick 13-0 lead
early in the second quarter. Slowly but surely, the Colts created a
13-13 tie, but in the fourth quarter five consecutive rushes by
Curtis Martin moved the Jets to a first-and-goal at the Colts'
3-yard line with less than 5 minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   On first down, Lucas looked left and threw a floater toward wide
receiver Keyshawn Johnson, but cornerback Jeff Burris intercepted
and returned it to the Jets' 45. Ten plays later, Gary Vanderjagt
kicked the winning 27-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining the choice of the pass that was intercepted
instead of having Martin run again, Parcells talked about how
``we've been stopped on short-yardage'' all season. He would not
blame Lucas, saying ``It's hard for me to see the angle; it was a
good play by them.'' But a more experienced quarterback would have
zipped that pass deeper instead of floating it.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas later told a Jets' official, ``I blew it with the
interception and life goes on.'' By then he was in the trainer's
room on crutches.
</P>
<P>
   The interception recalled Lucas' insertion into the 1997 finale
in Detroit when a victory would have put the Jets in the playoffs
in Parcells' first season as their coach. With his three quick
completions, the Jets appeared about to extend their 10-6 lead, but
then he threw an interception and was benched. The Jets eventually
lost, 13-10.
</P>
<P>
   For these Jets, the playoffs no longer exist. With what was a
difficult schedule anyway, they will be lucky to somehow win three
or four more games.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells' choice of Lucas was not surprising considering his
choice of words about Mirer after last Monday night's loss: ``I'm
not saying anything about Rick Mirer; I'm sure he's doing the best
he can.'' If Parcells had thought Mirer was capable of more, he
would have been openly critical. If not at that postgame news
conference, then during the week.
</P>
<P>
   By absolving Mirer, the coach had to be already thinking about
the change that surprised Mirer because Parcells hadn't even
mentioned the possibility during the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw this coming,'' said Mirer, who sounded more
confused than annoyed. ``The first time I spoke to him since last
week was 10:30 this morning when he told me Ray was starting. I
hadn't been told anything, so I didn't act like anything had
changed, but I can't worry about my feelings. It's not personal.
I'm not blaming anybody for what I've done or haven't done.''
</P>
<P>
   In two of Mirer's four starts as Testeverde's successor, the
Jets failed to score a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the sun's going to come up tomorrow,'' Mirer said, ``and
I'm going to be there to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   And he'll see it as the Jets quarterback again, at least until
Ray Lucas gets off his crutches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
