<SLUG> BC-EXP-NY-LOBSTER-DEATHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERY DEEPENS IN DEATH OF LOBSTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marine experts suspect that a mysterious pathogen may
have killed tens of thousands of lobsters in Long Island Sound this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   The die-off, described as the worst to hit Long Island Sound in
nearly a decade, has alarmed hundreds of lobstermen in New York and
Connecticut, and it has prompted extensive laboratory testing by
state and federal environmental officials.
</P>
<P>
   While cautioning that much more lab work needed to be done,
Gordon Colvin, the marine resources director of the New York
Department of Environmental Conservation, said Sunday that
water-quality tests had eliminated two possibilities _ pollution
and low levels of oxygen in the water.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that blood samples taken from lobsters did not
provide any solid evidence of gaffkemia, a common and often fatal
bacterial infection in lobsters.
</P>
<P>
   The working hypothesis, he said, was that some other bacterium
or virus was killing the lobsters, which became sluggish before
dying, although they otherwise appeared normal.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few weeks, officials in New York and Connecticut
have taken blood from lobsters and sent it to several laboratories,
including the University of Arizona in Tucson, the Food and Drug
Administration in Washington and the National Marine Fisheries
Service in Milford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there is no reason to fear eating lobsters from the
Sound, said Byron Young, chief of the finfish and crustacean unit
of the New York Department of Environmental Conservation. No one
has reported getting sick after eating lobster, and cooking
lobsters in boiling water would kill any microbes, Young said.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who fish the Sound, the problem is that too many
lobsters are already dead by the time they are pulled from traps.
In recent weeks, some lobstermen have stopped fishing altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just basically a losing proposition,'' said Robert
Eberhardt, a 52-year-old lobsterman who works out of Northport, a
harbor village on the North Shore of Long Island. ``Between fuel,
bait and crew, you come out behind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
