<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-SHEPHERD-NYT     10-17 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SHEPHERD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEAN SHEPHERD, A RACONTEUR AND A WIT OF RADIO, IS DEAD
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Fla., Ill., Ind., Ohio)  (nk) 
 By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jean Shepherd, the New York radio raconteur and author whose
rambling jazzlike monologues on the air puzzled many but delighted
fans over two decades, died Saturday. He was believed to be in his
70s.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin Zwilling, his friend and business adviser, said in a
statement that Shepherd died of natural causes at 3:20 a.m. in LeeMemorial Hospital near his home in Sanibel Island, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd was best known most recently for his tart narration of
the 1983 film ``A Christmas Story,'' a fond if slightly dyspeptic
evocation of Christmastime in 1940s Indiana, told from the point of
view of Ralphie Parker, 9, whose dream Christmas present is a Red
Ryder BB gun.
</P>
<P>
   With its grouchy parents, confrontations with schoolyard bullies
and a child's hapless tongue frozen to a flagpole, the film has
become a staple of holiday television. It was adapted from ``Red
Ryder Nails the Cleveland Street Kid,'' one of the stories in
Shepherd's best-selling 1966 book, ``In God We Trust, All Others
Pay Cash.''
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd spent 21 years on WOR-AM in New York City beginning in
1956. But in recent years, he performed infrequently on radio, the
last time in September 1996 on WFAN-AM in New York with his friend
Zwilling.
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd was a king of talk radio before it was known as talk
radio, and his style was of a piece with his sure pacing and flat
Midwestern accent. Typical was his description of children walking
to school in the winter: ``Kids plodded ... through
forty-five-mile-an-hour gales, tilting forward like tiny furred
radiator ornaments, moving stiffly over the barren clattering
ground with only the faint glint of two eyes peering out of a mound
of moving clothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyhood memories of small-town characters would be transformed
by Shepherd's comic exaggeration: ``Big Al was wedge-shaped; pure
sinew, gristle, and covered with a thick, bristly mat of primitive
fur. Numerous broken noses had reduced his nostrils to
blow-holes,'' he wrote of a college football player in ``A Fistful
of Fig Newtons'' (Doubleday &AMP; Co., 1982).
</P>
<P>
   A magazine writer once described Shepherd as a ``philosopher
without portfolio'' and a wit who never told a joke. He described
himself as a humorist rather than a comic. ``A humorist looks
outward and sees the world,'' Shepherd said. ``A comic looks inward
and sees himself.''
</P>
<P>
   On radio, he developed a wide Northeastern following, which a
reviewer writing in 1970 in The New York Times described as a
``cult of intense proportions.'' The reviewer went on to describe
the cult's typical rituals: ``the suburban college student, with
the bottle of Chianti, a girl, a pizza, parked by the edge of Long
Island Sound, listening to Jean Shepherd's nightly WOR radio
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd talked little about his private life. Accounts differ
on when he was born in Chicago. His date of birth has been given
variously as either July 21 or July 26, in years ranging from 1921
to 1929. He grew up within commuting distance of Chicago, in
Hammond, Ind., which he called ``Hohman'' in his stories.
</P>
<P>
   Zwilling said Shepherd's third wife, Leigh Brown, his agent and
producer, died last year after 21 years of marriage, that they had
no children and that ``there were no survivors.''
</P>
<P>
   But Randall Shepherd, 48, telephoned The Times on Saturday
night. He identified himself as the son of Shepherd and his first
wife, the former Joan Laverne Warner, who lives in Princeton, N.J.
The younger Shepherd said that his father left him and his mother
when Randall was 6, shortly before his parents divorced in 1957.
His sister, Adrian Shepherd, now 42, was born shortly after
Shepherd left the family, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went out of his way not to acknowledge that he even had
us,'' said the younger Shepherd, a film editor in Irvington, N.Y.,
who described their relationship with their father as estranged.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Shepherd said he was not aware of his father's
second marriage to the actress Lois Nettleton in 1961, which ended
six years later. The son said he did not know whether his uncle,
also named Randall Shepherd, was still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Jean Shepherd told interviewers that he had many
odd jobs, including mail boy in a steel mill and an equipment
installer in the U.S. Army Signal Corps. He said he attended, but
did not graduate from, Indiana University before starting in radio
at WSAI in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   His reflections were often mordant. In a 1975 radio performance,
Shepherd closed with this observation: ``Can you imagine  &UR; 4,000
 &LR; years passing, and you're not even a  &UR; memory &LR; ? Think about it,
friends. It's not just a possibility. It is a certainty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
