<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TORRE REMAINS CALM IN THE EYE OF THE STORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Red Sox were strutting, the Boss was lurking and a
cell phone was ringing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That for me?'' Joe from Brooklyn asked. Assured it was not, he
said: ``You never know.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees manager knows how many native New Yorkers and a
certain Ohio-born Floridian react when the other team gets noisy
and palms get sweaty in the midst of a baseball playoff series.
Vinny from Queens and Mike from Montclair and George from Tampa
start dialing respective outlets, voicing their displeasure,
envisioning doom.
</P>
<P>
   But not the Captain of Calm, Joe from Brooklyn, county of Kings.
``When we set the pitching, we made decisions,'' he said after Game
3 of the American League Championship Series when a reporter probed
for a sign of Roger Clemens-caused panic. ``We have no reason to
change that.''
</P>
<P>
   No reason to project a jittery front because the Red Sox didn't
faint after losing the first two games, and pounded 21 hits in Game
3, and because the Yankees bats had, at best, been pedestrian in
the series, and the mere thought of Pedro Martinez in a potential
Game 7 was, until further notice, looming over them like a
sharpened sword.
</P>
<P>
   No reason to sit light-hitting Joe Girardi Sunday night in Game
4, or move the aching and slumping Paul O'Neill down in the order.
No reason to worry that a left-hander, Andy Pettitte, was on the
loose in a pivotal game at a time when the Red Sox had scored 45
runs in their three previous games at Fenway Park. No reason to
show them signs of alarm just because they beat the Yankees
Saturday like a drum and George from Tampa happened to be in sight
of reporters for the first time in the series.
</P>
<P>
   New Englanders were inching toward making their hearts available
at the risk of having them broken again. They were opening their
arms to embrace the Red Sox as destiny's team at the expense of the
hated Yanks, with George from Tampa and the rest of the callers one
defeat away from putting finger to speed dial.
</P>
<P>
   Joe from Brooklyn said he was not worried, or stressed out. He
was, at the risk of sacrilege, enjoying himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you do this, the more fun it is,'' he said. ``For
sure last year, after winning 114 games, you felt sort of obligated
to have to go to the World Series and win. Otherwise people would
have downplayed what you accomplished. This is more fun, and maybe
I have approaching it that way because where I was six months ago
and knowing what was going on in my body and my life.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when everyone but the army is part of the big-event
crowd control, Joe from Brooklyn has become the chief of the
anti-hysteria police. He is the wise paternal face of New York
sports. That has always been his nature, his approach, since he
took managerial control of a team long fueled by panic and fear.
</P>
<P>
   Now he works a few months removed from believing he'd been
handed ``a death sentence'' upon being diagnosed with prostate
cancer last spring. He operates in his fourth Yankees season
boosted by the capital of his two World Series championships, the
perfect steward for a team that has won with style and class.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the season of second guessing, Joe from
Brooklyn floats above the jerking knees, not having every decision
analyzed like a nuclear arms treaty. Others are always one move
away from facing the tribunal of baseball geniuses. What was Bobby
Cox thinking Sunday, trying a suicide squeeze with the bases loaded
and two strikes on his hitter, the pitcher? If you have a week, we
can get started on Bobby Valentine or Buck Showalter, the genius
who double-switched his best player out of his team's elimination
game.
</P>
<P>
   If it had been Valentine _ who invites second guesses the way
politicians do soft money _ who had sent an anxious Clemens into
Fenway for such disastrous results, he would have surely had some
explaining to do. Is this entirely fair? Another manager might have
factored the potential fallout into a decision of pitching a
left-hander in Fenway when he didn't have to.
</P>
<P>
   Not Joe from Brooklyn, who is not worried about the
sportswriters or the callers or even George from Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very compassionate man when you do lose,'' Joe from
Brooklyn said of his boss. ``I think he's a tougher taskmaster when
you're winning, to keep you from taking your eye off the finish
line. When you lose, he's there to support you.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Joe from Brooklyn could believe this about George from
Tampa and the tough New York critics. Only he could be so relaxed
Sunday night, in the face of all this Fenway fuss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
