<DOCNO> NYT19991017.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9822 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NATURAL-CHILDBIRTH-2T     10-17 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATURAL-CHILDBIRTH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT CHILDBIRTH DEBATE: DRUG-ASSISTED, OR NATURAL? 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last Saturday, as a long morning of labor dragged
into afternoon, Elba Quinones soaked in a warm tub at an outpatient
birthing center in Greenwich Village, trying to ease her pain. Her
contractions came every three minutes. And when they intensified,
her screams at times became primal. Once she howled to her husband
that she couldn't take it anymore.
</P>
<P>
   An hour and a half later, after leaving the warm water, pacing,
squatting and reclining on the room's two-poster queen bed, Ms.
Quinones gave birth to Omar Rafael, her first child. She promptly
announced that she had made the right decision: to experience
childbirth naturally, without drugs _ extreme pain and all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was better than I expected,'' she said, in her postpartum
glow. ``I am glad we chose to come here for this type of birth.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Quinones, 30, a clinical social worker who lives in
Brooklyn, is no anti-medication ideologue. She and her husband,
Alberto Toro, researched their options carefully, visiting several
hospital delivery rooms before choosing the Elizabeth Seton
Childbearing Center on West 14th Street, where the preference for
natural childbirth is a guiding philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   But by enduring labor without drugs, Ms. Quinones has placed
herself distinctly on childbearing's margins, at least among
American women. Last week, a study released by Dr. Joy Hawkins,
director of obstetric anesthesia at the University of Colorado
School of Medicine, showed that the number of women in labor who
received regional anesthesia _ spinal or epidural injections to
numb the pelvic region _ soared between 1981 and 1997. The surge,
documented by a survey of 750 hospitals, was particularly evident
in large hospitals, where the percentage of mothers receiving such
injections tripled, to 66 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hawkins attributed the increase to the ability of
anesthesiologists to ease labor pain with smaller doses of medicine
and fewer side effects than in years past.
</P>
<P>
   Although that report has not yet been presented in a
peer-reviewed paper, the news made national headlines and spread
quickly among midwives and natural-birth advocates. Of the several
dozen interviewed for this article, none doubted the report's
findings, but most voiced frustration that drug-free childbirth _
which experienced a resurgence as feminism took hold in the 1960s
and '70s _ is now being widely shunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's upsetting that it's taken such a shift, because I see
natural childbirth as such a wonderful thing to be part of,'' said
Catherine Clark, a midwife whose two children were born at home.
``The further we get away from it, the less we know ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The reaction to Dr. Hawkins' study underscored an apparently
deepening polarization among women over how childbirth should be
experienced by healthy, low-risk women.
</P>
<P>
   Even as medicated births become far more common, midwives point
out that the number of women who deliberately seek natural
childbirth has also climbed, though the rise is less sharp and the
percentage of women having such births is in only the single
digits.
</P>
<P>
   Willing to face the pain of labor, eager to avoid drugs they
worry are harmful or unnecessary, or seeking an alternative to the
impersonal care they associate with large hospitals, these women
are turning to nurse-midwives in increasing numbers. From 1989 to
1997, the number of women in the United States whose births were
attended by midwives nearly doubled, from 3.7 percent to 7 percent
of the roughly 4 million births each year, according to the
Maternity Center Association, a nonprofit organization based in
Manhattan that promotes prenatal care and education.
</P>
<P>
   While not all midwife-attended childbirths are drug-free, fewer
than one in five involves anesthesia, data provided by the
Maternity Center Association show. And midwives say the increasing
demand for their service is evidence of dissatisfaction among a
segment of women with the trend Dr. Hawkins identified.
</P>
<P>
   ``The camp that I am part of is losing this battle at this
moment,'' said Rebecca Hamilton, clinical director at the Elizabeth
Seton center. ``But I believe there is a resistance movement, in
that there is a natural movement that is going against the dominant
cultural paradigm.''
</P>
<P>
   Midwifery is especially well established in New York state,
where 10.8 percent of deliveries in 1997 were attended by certified
nurse-midwives, according to data provided by the state's
Department of Health. In New York City, the percentage reached
12.6.
</P>
<P>
   And birthing centers in the city, both free-standing and in
hospitals, report delivering more babies than in years past. The
Elizabeth Seton center, which is affiliated with St. Vincent's
Hospital and Medical Center two blocks away, projects 316 births
this year, up from 205 in 1998; in May the 20-month-old birth
center at Bellevue Hospital Center had its busiest month ever,
delivering 41 babies.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new mothers who have created these increases, the
decision to avoid anesthesia is rooted in many strongly held
convictions. For some, it is an extension of strong feminist
beliefs and an urge to experience what they say is the most
profound physical experience of a woman's life. ``It's just a
remarkable rite of passage,'' Ms. Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   The transforming experience of childbirth, these women say, is
compromised by pain-numbing drugs and the medical equipment that
accompanies them. Anesthesia, for instance, typically requires a
woman in labor to be connected to a fetal monitor, an intravenous
tube, a blood pressure cuff and perhaps a pulse monitor and urinary
catheter. The drugs and the equipment reduce mobility and can bring
a degree of discomfort, some natural-birth advocates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a much greater fear of having a needle stuck in my
spinal area, and being strapped to all these monitors, than I did
about having to worry about enduring pain my body is made to
handle,'' said Bridget Goodbody, 36, who gave birth naturally to
her first child, Abigail Zoe, on July 4.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For others, the decision to avoid anesthesia has cultural roots.
This is particularly evident in some immigrant communities, where
families come from countries where hospital-based births are
unusual, and epidural anesthesia all but unheard of. At the
Bellevue Birth Center, roughly half of the women choosing midwives
are of Asian descent, and perhaps another third are Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these women come from countries where they are just
not used to the idea of having medicated births,'' said Karen
Baldwin, the center's director of midwifery services.
</P>
<P>
   Other women worry that mothers who opt for anesthesia are
compromising a baby's alertness and ability to breast-feed during
the first days after birth, although the topic has been scarcely
studied. ``If you go to lactation conferences, you'll find that
almost all lactation consultants believe there is a direct
correlation between having an epidural and poor and disorganized
suck reflexes among newborns,'' said Jan Wenk, a certified
lactation consultant.
</P>
<P>
   And some midwives also said the increase in epidurals means
women have less chance to enjoy the intimate participation of
family and friends during delivery. While many hospital delivery
rooms allow a limited number of guests during a physician-attended
birth, midwives strive for a more inclusive approach than drug-free
delivery can allow.
</P>
<P>
   Jeannine McCullagh, 69, said her daughter, Kathleen, had a
natural childbirth in July that allowed her family to bond in a way
that would be impossible in a medicated birth.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years ago, Jeannine McCullagh gave birth to Kathleen after
24 hours of labor. She was separated from her husband and numbed at
the waist by spinal anesthesia. She remembers seeing her newborn
daughter briefly. Then she fell asleep.
</P>
<P>
   This July, when Kathleen McCullagh gave birth to her first
child, Jeannine was with her in the birthing center. Kathleen
delivered in the shower, hot water splashing on her back. Jeannine
cut the umbilical cord. Everybody was touching one another. ``When
I got home to tell my husband about it, all I could do was cry,''
Ms. McCullagh said last week. ``We just didn't have these kinds of
experiences in my time, before the women's movement changed
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Dr. Hawkins' study illustrated, women who strive for a
drug-free delivery remain a decided minority. And some natural
birth advocates say they understand why other women opt for
anesthesia, even if they shun it for themselves. ``As soon as my
contractions started, I was like, `Oh, I get it,''' Ms. Goodbody
said. ``The pain was intense.''
</P>
<P>
   They also say that a natural childbirth is not an option for a
variety of mothers with risk factors, including premature labor, a
history of health problems or a fetus with abnormal heart tones.
</P>
<P>
   But natural childbirth advocates also worry that Dr. Hawkins'
study suggests that many women are choosing drugs before reviewing
their options, and examining the possible side effects of
anesthesia, including headaches, disorientation, slowed labor,
fever and backache.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more women are just saying, `Oh, I'll have an
epidural,''' said Joan Liebmann-Smith, assistant executive director
of the Maternity Center Association. ``They make this decision
ahead of time, without really considering the risks and benefits of
it. I think that's very odd.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Birnbach, director of obstetric anesthesiology at St.
Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center on the Upper West Side, said
worries about medicated pain relief are often overstated, in part
because some are based on data culled from days when
anesthesiologists applied larger doses. Some midwives, he said, are
scaring patients unnecessarily.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 90 percent of the women giving birth in delivery rooms
at St. Luke's have epidurals, he said, and he sees high
satisfaction and few side effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The midwifery point of view is the point of view of a vocal
minority, not the dominant point of view of women in America,''
Birnbach said, and added that though natural births are on the rise
in a small segment of the population, Dr. Hawkins' study shows that
``the vocal minority,'' for the moment, has lost the middle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
