<HEADER>
A9827 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-OBSERVER-SP     10-17 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-OBSERVER-SPIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BEWARE OF SPIES WHO THINK THEY CAN BE SMART VENTURE
CAPITALISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By PHILIP TAUBMAN 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The CIA Agency has worn many disguises and operated countless
front companies, but until now it has never established a Silicon
Valley venture capital firm. The decision to set up the nonprofit
investment company, named In-Q-It, is outlandish. Maybe the Federal
Bureau of Investigation would like to get into the banking business
or the Secret Service would like to spin off a subsidiary that
provides personal security for celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   But at least credit the CIA for creative thinking, and for
trying to revive a long and often successful tradition of
encouraging new technology. Though the agency is better known for
running covert operations and producing intelligence estimates,
sometimes to its discredit, the CIA over the decades has quietly
been a pioneer in aerospace and electronics. I have been reviewing
that history in recent months, and find several models that might
serve the agency well as it seeks to stimulate the production of
computer hardware and software that can help it absorb and analyze
a daily tidal wave of intelligence information.
</P>
<P>
   Much about the old ways of doing business would be unacceptable
today. When the agency set out in 1954 to build the U-2 spy plane,
it drew money from the CIA director's contingency account and sent
a check to the home of the plane's chief designer, Kelly Johnson,
who worked for Lockheed. He moved the money through a fake company
and Lockheed employees assigned to the project traveled under
fictitious names. Congress knew almost nothing about the whole
enterprise. Equally stringent secrecy was employed a few years
later when the agency set out to produce the first photo
reconnaissance satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Such clandestine practices are unnecessary for the kind of
computer advances the CIA now seeks to develop, something the
agency recognizes in openly establishing In-Q-It. But the
pioneering spirit and effective leadership that characterized early
Cold War projects would be useful today. Richard Bissell, best
known for his direction of the failed Bay of Pigs invasion of Cuba
in 1961, was a skillful manager of technology projects for the CIA
during the Eisenhower administration. He delegated authority,
encouraged innovation and suppressed bureaucracy, habits that are
in short supply in Washington today. The U-2, which required
numerous innovations in aircraft design, fuel chemistry and camera
technology, was ready for operation ahead of schedule and under
budget.
</P>
<P>
   These projects also inspired a level of collaboration between
the government, scientists and private companies that would be good
_ if difficult _ to duplicate today. A common desire to enhance
American security encouraged this kind of cooperation, as did the
example of similar work in World War II. The Vietnam War left many
scientists understandably wary of defense projects, and the allure
of making millions in cyber enterprises keeps many of the most
imaginative computer engineers and software designers from working
on government contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge facing the CIA is to find a way to encourage the
invention of new computer technologies without imagining that it
can create a nimble venture capital firm. Investing public funds in
fledgling, high-risk companies is not a sound use of federal
dollars. Even if potential losses can be limited, the CIA, with its
reflexive preference for secrecy, ought not to be subsidizing a
venture capital company in the freewheeling entrepreneurial world
of Silicon Valley. In a democracy, intelligence agencies should not
be independent operators in the private sector, even through the
use of an outside board of directors, the case with In-Q-It.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the nature of technological innovation and the
government's role in supporting it has changed substantially since
the 1950s. Especially in the rapidly advancing frontiers of
computer science, the private sector has so outdistanced the
government that military and intelligence agencies are now largely
dependent on research breakthroughs that are beyond their ability
to direct or to control. In theory, the inventive culture of
Silicon Valley is so fluid and serendipitous that the traditional
Washington practice of paying a specific company to produce a
particular product is unlikely to yield the kind of technology the
CIA seeks.
</P>
<P>
   That does not leave the CIA helpless. Instead of relying on its
venture capital company, the CIA should closely track advances in
the computer field. When potentially beneficial ideas are spotted,
the agency can invest in their development by contracting with the
companies involved. This would still give the agency a chance to
encourage innovation at an early stage. Such an approach would
require more supple procurement procedures, something that the
agency and Congress ought to be able to devise.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to take today's lumbering federal agencies and
turn them into engines of innovation. But the challenge the CIA has
identified _ making more rapid use of new technologies _ is
critical to the effectiveness of the nation's intelligence and
defense agencies. Putting the CIA in the venture capital business
is not the answer. But the impulse to step outside bureaucratic
conventions is right. The agency might find some helpful ideas in
its own accomplishments a generation ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-99 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
