<HEADLINE>
CSUN TO FACE ANOTHER ROAD TEST IN MONTANA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was the comeback game of the season. Or was it
a mirage?
</P>
<P>
   Now comes a real test for the Cal State Northridge football
team.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors, who soundly beat Sacramento State 36-14 Saturday
afternoon at North Campus Stadium, make their second trip in three
weeks to the state of Montana this Saturday, this time facing
Montana State in Bozeman.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN is 3-3, with all three wins coming at home. An 8-year-old
can figure out Northridge's record on the road this season. The
coaches and players need look no further than Sacramento State to
see what separates a contender for the Big Sky Conference
championship from the champion.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets, who were ranked No. 23 in Division I-AA by The
Sports Network, haven't won a game away from home this season. In
two Big Sky road games, CSUN has lost concentration and played
catch-up in losses at Eastern Washington and Montana.
</P>
<P>
   ``No team other than Kansas has completely knocked us off the
ball and hurt us,'' CSUN interim head coach Jeff Kearin said after
Saturday's game. ``We played at a high level the whole game
(against the Hornets), which is something we haven't done this
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Three factors worked in CSUN's favor. The Matadors excelled in
these key areas:
</P>
<P>
   __ Time of possession.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors, who had a season-high 43 rushing attempts, had the
ball almost 10 full minutes more than Sacramento State, including a
significant advantage in the fourth quarter _ thanks to a 16-play,
77-yard drive that took 7 minutes, 16 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Easily the longest drive in terms of time this season, it could
have been one of the longest since the school went to the
run-and-shoot offense five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best defense is a good offense,'' Kearin said, ``to keep
that guy off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy'' is Sacramento State running back Charles Roberts,
the nation's leading rusher entering the game. By controlling the
clock, the Matadors didn't allow Roberts and the Hornets to get
into rhythm on offense.
</P>
<P>
   __ The time-of-possession disparity didn't suddenly make the
Hornets offensively clueless. Sacramento State entered averaging 43
points per game and was able to shock CSUN temporarily with a
91-yard touchdown pass from Ricky Ray to Lamont Webb in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   That play was a blip on the radar screen, though, in proportion
to how the Matadors' defensive performed. The importance of
tackling, lost on some of the CSUN players prior to this week, was
crucial against Roberts, who rarely made a defender miss.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Foster Andersen should clip and save the
video of some of the tackles on Roberts for future use.
</P>
<P>
   __ Most important, CSUN started quickly, taking a 17-0 lead in
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time the Matadors had led by so much so early,
and the effects were easy to see. CSUN quarterback Marcus Brady
said he was relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't put pressure on us,'' Brady said, about dominating
the first quarter, ``where we had to go out and score every
time.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CSUN STATUS REPORT &QL; 
GAME: 6 &QL; 
RESULT: CSUN 36, Sacramento State 14 &QL; 
THIS WEEK'S GPA: 3.4 &QL; 
CUMULATIVE GPA: 2.62 &QL; 
NEXT GAME: at Montana State &QL; 
QUARTERBACKS &QL; 
Returning to the form that has made him so successful in just 1{
seasons as the starter, Marcus Brady threw 39 passes without an
interception. His completion percentage _ 72 percent _ was his
second-best this season but not by much. &QL; 
A &QL; 
RUNNING BACKS &QL; 
Statistic of the day: Jaumal Bradley has set a career-best rushing
total in each of the four games he's played this year. He had 132
yards on 30 carries against Sac State. As a team, CSUN had 43
carries, the most in recent memory. &QL; 
B+ &QL; 
RECEIVERS &QL; 
Responded _ emphatically _ after poor game the week before. Had
only a few drops and only mistake was Terrence Jones' personal foul
for taunting a defender on his way into end zone on 74-yard TD
pass. &QL; 
A &QL; 
OFFENSIVE LINE &QL; 
Sac State was second in Big Sky in rushing defense, but this unit
stepped up and helped Matadors control the clock. Brady was rarely
pressured, and sacked just twice _ after two starters went out with
injuries. &QL; 
B &QL; 
DEFENSIVE LINE &QL; 
Set tone early by pressuring QB Ricky Ray on two of Hornets' first
three plays. CSUN was supposed to be dominated by Sac State's
massive offensive line, but that didn't happen. &QL; 
B+ &QL; 
LINEBACKERS &QL; 
Brennen Swanson is back. The Buchanan Award candidate had two sacks
and had first-contact on Charles Roberts several times. Lewis
Blanton had his best game of season (four tackles), but Cos
Abercrombie was so-so. &QL; 
B- &QL; 
DEFENSIVE BACKS &QL; 
The most prominent heroes of a defensive effort that erased some
memories of early-season collapses. Rahman Sparks, Steve Forte and
Chazz Moore combined for 26 tackles and Forte and Mel Miller had
INTs. They need to preserve this performance in a time capsule. &QL; 
A &QL; 
SPECIAL TEAMS &QL; 
Weren't really much of a factor while the rest of the team
dominated. Had two extra-point attempts blocked and Hornets
averaged 25 yards per kickoff return. No costly mistakes, though. &QL; 
C+ &QL; 
COACHING &QL; 
Defensive coordinator Foster Andersen gets most of the credit, but
he would agree the players finally played to their abilities.
Played up the revenge factor well in practice without sounding
corny. &QL; 
A &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
