</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NIGERIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NIGERIA'S PROMISING START 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, Oct. 18:
</P>
<P>
   When former Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo was inaugurated as president
of Nigeria in late May, he took over a once-prosperous nation that
had been reduced to misery by a series of larcenous military
regimes. In the late 1970s, Obasanjo was himself Nigeria's military
ruler, although the first to turn over power to a civilian. In
1995, Gen. Sani Abacha, the country's most ruthless leader, jailed
Obasanjo for three years. But he remained close to the military and
won elections this year bankrolled by some of Nigeria's most
nefarious officers. There was reason for skepticism about his
intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Obasanjo _ who is to receive Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright later this week _ has won over many of his
critics, distancing himself from his former military allies, taking
important steps to combat corruption and restoring political
freedoms. He is now beginning economic reforms. With one important
exception _ the troubles of the oil-producing Delta region _
Obasanjo has awakened hopes that Nigeria's slide can be halted or
reversed.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Obasanjo's actions are not only symbolically important
but can also reduce the chance of yet another military coup. On
June 10 he fired 93 high-ranking officers, including all who
recently occupied political posts. Obasanjo also canceled all
contracts awarded by the military government in 1999, which saw
billions of dollars in sweetheart deals. He has established three
commissions to investigate corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria is freer than it has been in years. A bustling civil
society operates without fear, and unions are regaining influence.
A new commission that will hold hearings and collect reports on
serious human rights abuses has only limited powers, but it is led
by respected activists.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo's efforts to revive the economy have been blessed by a
sharp rise in the price of what is virtually the country's only
product, oil. He has chosen a capable economic team, which has
begun to reverse Nigeria's pariah status with international
lenders. His most visible and popular achievement to date has been
to end an absurd gasoline shortage that kept drivers waiting in
line, sometimes overnight, for expensive gas.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage was caused by corrupt manipulation of oil supplies.
Fighting corruption is Obasanjo's most important and difficult
challenge. State treasuries are so looted that many cannot pay
$20-a-month teacher's salaries. Obasanjo has proposed an
anti-corruption bill and measures to cut middlemen out of state
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   But Obasanjo, sadly, has shown little interest in one necessary
measure to combat corruption and several other problems, including
a new relationship between Nigeria's states and its central
government, which controls most of the country's revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is seen most dramatically in the Niger Delta. Oil
money goes to the central government, where it disappears. The
oil-producing Delta gets virtually nothing back to alleviate
desperate poverty or clean up environmental destruction. This has
radicalized many in the Delta. Youth gangs have kidnaped oil
workers and sabotaged production, which has cost Nigeria billions
of dollars. Security forces have responded with hundreds of
killings.
</P>
<P>
   In early June, Obasanjo met with Delta community leaders. But
his conduct and his proposals show that he sees the region mainly
as a security problem. Without more local say over oil money and
how it is spent, the Delta could explode. Obasanjo's greatest
contribution to Nigeria's stability may eventually be his
willingness to reduce his own powers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
