<HEADER>
A9845 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-17 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: KEEPING THE FAITH  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)  (js) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dominant religion in Indiana for most of this century has
been basketball. The houses of worship more often than not were
funky, rundown arenas that offered the faithful a rocking, roaring
escape from the hard life and cold nights in places like Muncie and
Fort Wayne and French Lick and Logootee.
</P>
<P>
   So much of professional basketball as we know it today was
forged in the rituals of those nights. The names float easily to
the surface. John Wooten, Larry Bird, Oscar Robertson, Isiah
Thomas, Walt Bellamy, Rick Mount, Bobby Knight, Reggie Miller . . .
</P>
<P>
   A team coached by a man named Marvin Wood became the national
symbol of the Indiana basketball experience. Wood, who died last
week at the age of 71, was the coach of the high school team from
tiny Milan, Ind., that won the 1954 state championship when it
defeated mighty Muncie Central High School in a thriller, 32-30.
Milan's improbable journey to a championship was portrayed in the
1986 movie ``Hoosiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week I talked to one of the greatest (some say the
greatest) of all the players to go through the Indiana experience,
Oscar Robertson. He grew up in Indianapolis and went to the
all-black Crispus Attucks High School. For many years Catholic
schools and black schools were banned from the state tournament,
but that had changed by the mid-'50s. Young Robertson and his
Crispus Attucks teammates were virtually unstoppable. They won a
combined 62 games against only one loss in 1955 and 1956. The team
won the state championship both years, and during one stretch it
won a record 45 games in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson is 60 now and not nearly as well known as his
extraordinary achievements in high school, college and professional
basketball might indicate. He said he is in good health (he donated
a kidney to his daughter a couple of years ago) but would like to
lose a few pounds. I had called him to ask how he felt about the
way basketball has changed over the past half century.
</P>
<P>
   He immediately lamented the commercialization. ``If you look at
basketball today, everything is marketing,'' he said. ``Even as
great as Michael Jordan was on the court, he was more popular off
the court.''
</P>
<P>
   And while some people can handle an over-emphasis on money and
marketing, he said, there are many who cannot. ``I feel there are
guys today who don't really care whether they win or not,'' he
said. ``And I think management often doesn't care, as long as they
can market their product and make the money.''
</P>
<P>
   His concern was ironic because as the president of the Players
Association Robertson led a court fight that paved the way to free
agency and much higher player salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money changes people,'' said Robertson, whose first pro
contract, in 1960, was for $33,000 a year. ``I don't mean that as a
criticism; that's just the way it is. I'm glad the players are
making more money now because I think it will help their families
in the long run. I think it's great to have the opportunity to make
the money they're making. But it does change people.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Basketball Association, like most of this society,
is indeed obsessed with marketing. It is trying at the moment to
adjust to the post-Michael Jordan era. Five new arenas are opening
this season, including a new home in Indianapolis for the Indiana
Pacers. If you want to get a sense of the extent to which the sport
itself has been overshadowed by marketing considerations, consider
that the Pacers' new arena, the Conseco Fieldhouse, is the only one
of the five that scheduled a basketball game as its opening
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   A Celine Dion concert opened the Pepsi Center, home of the
Denver Nuggets. Bruce Springsteen opened the Staples Center, home
of the Lakers and the Clippers in Los Angeles. The country singer
Vince Gill opened the Philips Arena in Atlanta. And Gloria Estefan
will do the honors at the American Airlines Arena in Miami on New
Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   At least it's still largely about basketball in Indiana. The
Conseco Fieldhouse (yes, they're all named after corporations) has
been designed to evoke memories of those ancient arenas that
nurtured the true faith for so many fans over so many decades. It
opens early next month with a ceremony honoring the 50 greatest
players in the state's history, and a game between the Pacers and
Boston Celtics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
