<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' HOPES FADING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA's Rose Bowl chase ended at Arizona State. Its
Holiday Bowl hopes probably disappeared Saturday afternoon in a
17-0 loss to California. An El Paso New Year's Eve seems remote,
which leaves Christmas in Hawaii and not much else.
</P>
<P>
   The postseason possibilities are dwindling by the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather go to Hawaii than El Paso anyhow,'' one player
said.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the Bruins (3-4, 1-3) are in the bowl picture until
their sixth defeat. Based on Saturday's performance, that could
come in two weeks _ after a trip to Oregon State and a visit by
Arizona. Yes, the two-time defending Pac-10 champs could be
eliminated from bowl contention before November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't go to a bowl my freshman year (1996) and I definitely
want to go to a bowl game as a senior,'' fullback Durell Price
said. ``For this to happen is uncalled for. Everybody has to check
what's in their gut for the rest of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   If they check the Pac-10 bowl contracts, here's what they'll
find:
</P>
<P>
   __ The second-place team goes to San Diego for the Dec. 29
Holiday Bowl against the Big 12's third-place finisher.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have one chance for second, but it's microscopic:
They must win their remaining games (unlikely but possible) and
hope several teams collapse. If UCLA somehow climbs into a
second-place tie, its name value and fast finish could entice the
Holiday brass. But don't count on it.
</P>
<P>
   __ The Pac-10 ships its third-place team to El Paso for the Dec.
31 Sun Bowl against the Big Ten's fifth-place finisher.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the Bruins need to win out for a chance. Since the league
expanded to 10 teams in 1978, no 4-4 team has finished higher than
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   __ The fourth- and fifth-place teams head to Hawaii for the
Aloha and O'ahu Bowls on Christmas Day. (Bowl officials determine
which teams play in which games.)
</P>
<P>
   Because of distance and the Christmas kickoff, the Hawaii games
depend on television ratings, not ticket sales. That makes UCLA an
ideal participant. All the Bruins have to do is win three of their
last four.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they could lose three of four. Or they could win all
four. Or lose all four. After seven games, the Bruins are as
unpredictable as they were Sept. 1. Their performance varies not
from week to week but from play to play.
</P>
<P>
   That's not surprising for a young team, especially a young team
with injuries and a rookie quarterback. Of the 44 players on the
two-deep, only 11 are seniors.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday, for the first time since a Nov. '96 trip to
Washington, the Bruins were manhandled at the line of scrimmage _
and that irked them more than the final score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm (angry),'' Price said. ``We take pride in being
tougher than our opponents. When a team shows it's tougher than
you, it (makes you angry).
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought my lunch pail for the game _ that's what I was
gearing myself up for. We knew we'd have to bring our hard hats and
lunch pails and maybe even call out for dinner, because it was
going to be a long, tough game. We knew that. We didn't respond.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
UCLA STATUS REPORT &QL; 
GAME:7 &QL; 
__ RESULT: Cal 17, UCLA 0 &QL; 
__ RECORD: 3-4 &QL; 
__ THIS WEEK'S GPA: 1.43 &QL; 
__ CUMULATIVE GPA: 2.45 &QL; 
__ NEXT WEEK: at Oregon State &QL; 
Quarterbacks: &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cory Paus was pressured all day but wasted great opportunities with
INT and fumble. Drew Bennett's only pass was awful. &QL; 
F &QL; 
Running backs: &QL; 
Bruins sorely missed DeShaun Foster's ability to break tackles.
Keith Brown (21 yards) was no factor. Jermaine Lewis (minus-4
yards) needs to run like Cal freshman Joe Igber. &QL; 
F &QL; 
Receivers: &QL; 
Not much these guys can do except get open and hope the passes are
catchable. Mike Seidman's last-minute drop could have ended the
shutout. &QL; 
C+ &QL; 
Offensive line: &QL; 
What line? When coach Bob Toledo says, ``Football is a game of
one-on-one. You have to beat your man and we didn't beat our man,''
he's talking about these guys. &QL; 
F &QL; 
Defensive line: &QL; 
Don't be fooled by Cal's modest point total. Bears were averaging
94 yards rushing but got 248 on UCLA. What's more, the front four
had one tackle-for-loss and no sacks against the Pac-10's worst
offensive line. &QL; 
C &QL; 
Linebackers: &QL; 
Tony White played his best game (two sacks, seven tackles) and
Robert Thomas was solid again. Shoulder injury to Ali Abdul Azziz
could be a problem; Bruins need his speed. &QL; 
B+ &QL; 
Secondary: &QL; 
Fifth-year seniors couldn't make plays. Ryan Roques, Eric Whitfield
and Joey Strycula were burned on long passes and missed tackles on
long runs. Time for a lineup shuffle? &QL; 
C &QL; 
Special teams: &QL; 
Nate Fikse had as many punts (nine) as Paus had completions.
Special teams didn't lose game for Bruins, but they didn't make big
plays, either. &QL; 
C &QL; 
Coaching: &QL; 
Bruins were whipped physically more than outcoached, but 17-point
loss to a 13-point underdog is everyone's fault. Final month is
coaching staff's biggest test. Will Bruins regress, stagnate or
improve? &QL; 
D+ &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
