<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VERBAL BRUSHBACK, COMPOSED BY CLEMENS 
HURTING AND WILLING 
PSYCHED OUT 
OTHER KINDS OF PRESSURE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Boston Red Sox swung freely and comfortably against
Roger Clemens, and Clemens intimated afterward that if he pitches
against the Red Sox again in this series _ ``I hope I don't have
to,'' he added _ he will be ready to knock some hitters down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I need to expand,'' Clemens said Saturday, referring
to the strike zone. ``I just think some guys are just too
comfortable and it is not a great feeling to have. But I just think
some guys get too comfortable up there and you like to expand, and
it is something I need to do more of.''
</P>
<P>
   That's code for ``I need to knock hitters off the plate and make
them less comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't as if Clemens and Hideki Irabu, who relieved
Clemens, received any harsher treatment than some others who have
faced the Red Sox. Dating to the last two games here against
Cleveland in the division series, and including the first three
innings Saturday, the Red Sox had scored 37 runs in the span of 15
innings at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre spoke with Clemens Sunday afternoon, a
day after his two-inning performance. ``He's all right,'' Torre
said. ``No question, you can't say it doesn't bother you, because
you expected more of yourself than he gave yesterday. He wanted the
results to be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that's the good part of being a starting pitcher _ you
have a day to shake the fog out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurting and Willing
</P>
<P>
   To say that Pedro Martinez wears his heart on his sleeve has a
different connotation than usual. He is making no secret of the
fact that he is pitching in pain, and that he is sure there is
something honorable in this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am hurting,'' Martinez said, after he allowed just two hits
in seven innings in Game 3. ``I am hurting in every pitch I throw,
but you know, I manage to do it somehow and I am not going to quit
on doing it until I know I am not getting anybody out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the team needs me tomorrow and I can give them one out, I
am going to try to do it. It doesn't matter how much I hurt. If I
can throw the ball over, and get one out to get the team to win a
game, I am going to do it. That is what I am here for.''
</P>
<P>
   Psyched Out
</P>
<P>
   Since the fifth inning of a game Pedro Martinez pitched against
the Yankees in May, the Yankees have five hits in 61 at-bats
against him, with 35 strikeouts. Is Joe Torre concerned about
Martinez's dominance getting inside the heads of his players?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question it's in people's heads,'' Torre said.
``His ability is what it is. You can't deny that. You're just going
to have to find a way against a Pedro Martinez to adjust your
approach, and again, adjust what you do at the plate, and just
tough it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Kinds of Pressure
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez smirked when he was asked about the
possibility of feeling pressure in Game 5 on Monday, and discussed
how fans in Cuba had thrown rocks, tomatoes and ``anything they can
find'' on the field. Essentially, he said, the rowdiest fans at
Fenway Park would not unnerve him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you win, the opposite fans are going to try to beat you any
way they can,'' Hernandez said of pitching in Cuba. ``Then if you
lose, your own fans are going to try to kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre recalled how Hernandez pitched the most important game
of the 1998 season and never became rattled, when he beat the
Indians in Game 4 of the American League Championship Series last
year. Torre does not think Monday night will be any different.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's to scare him after leaving Cuba and, you know, we don't
know what size boat he came over on,'' Torre said. ``But, whatever
it was, it's still the fact that he had to slide out of the country
and hide somewhere and then be found and all this kind of stuff.
It's not the way we got to the ballpark, I know that. So for sure,
this is just a game for him.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JACK CURRY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
