<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, Oct. 18. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
LEARN (Phoenix) _ A University of Arizona junior learns biology and
psychology by talking to a parrot. An Arizona State University
student masters English composition, not from a book, but from
teaching disadvantaged kids. Seniors at Northern Arizona University
learn business by advising a Flagstaff music store on marketing
strategies. They're all part of a trend sweeping higher education
called learner-centered education _ a shift from passive learning
in lecture halls to active learning through independent discovery.
The concept is filtering through all levels of the state's three
universities, and has become the central focus of a yearlong
examination by the Arizona Board of Regents. Story by BEVERLY
MEDLYN. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BULLFIGHTS (NOGALES, Sonora, Mexico) _ Mario de la Fuente knows
that many Americans abhor blood sports, so he suggests they stay
home whenbullfighting returns to this border city next month.  &UR; De
la Fuente is banking on Americans filling most of the 5,000 seats
in his new round, very red arena with aluminum siding and clear
acrylic top. On Nov. 14, he will bring bullfighting back to Nogales
after a nearly 30-year absence, with events twice a month.
Bullfighting enjoyed its heyday in Nogales in the 1950s and early
'60s, when such celebrities as John Wayne, Gary Cooper and Sonny
Liston regularly attended Sunday afternoon corridas at an outdoor
stadium decorated with matador frescos. By MARK SHAFFER. Story will
move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   NEW&AMP;NOTABLE (undated) _ Anne Stephenson's capsule book reviews.
By ANNE STEPHENSON. Story will move in the ``E'' category.
</P>
<P>
   TUROW (undated) _ Review of Scott Turow's new book ``Personal
Injuries.'' By Anne Stephenson. Story will move in the ``E''
category.
</P>
