<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9861 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS-RAMS-COX     10-17 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-RAMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons fall to 1-5 as second shot at Rams turns into another
runaway
 &HT;    By Matt Winklejohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Falcons were looking for revenge and redemption in
their rematch Sunday with the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   All they got was a repeat whipping.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, after crumbling against the NFL's only unbeaten team
41-13, in front of a hostile Georgia Dome crowd of 51,973, they got
a lashing in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   This happens when a team goes from the Super Bowl to 1-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Coach Dan Reeves) came in and said if anybody wants to quit
let him know because he'll get 'em out right now,'' strong-side
linebacker Craig Sauer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he's questioning players; I have no idea,'' defensive
tackle Travis Hall said. ``I'm not in that boat, so I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' boat is taking on water fast. Every imaginable
thing that could go wrong has.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Chris Chandler's strained right hamstring was well
enough for him to play for the third time in six games. But for the
third time, he didn't finish, sidelined in the third quarter when
Reeves took him out because of flu-like symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   But it was an avalanche of mistakes that ruined the Falcons'
chances to prove last month's 35-7 loss in St. Louis was a fluke.
The Rams are now 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 10 penalties (and three turnovers). We just are not a
disciplined football team right now,'' said Reeves, who continues
to say publicly that his team's effort is not an issue. ``That is
my responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   There's more. In a season marked by miserable turnover ratio,
awful run defense and a poor running attack, the Falcons had all
three working _ against them. They gave up 189 rushing yards, while
rushing for 39. Both were the worst since a 35-28 loss at San
Francisco on Oct. 19, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons outgained St. Louis 316-283 and held an edge in time
of possession (31:12-28:48), but made mistakes at all the wrong
times. Three turnovers resulted in 13 St. Louis points.
</P>
<P>
   After the Falcons cut the lead to 14-7 in the second quarter,
the Rams' Tony Horne returned a kickoff 101 yards for a 21-7 lead.
After getting their first fumble recovery of the season, Atlanta
moved to the 9. But on first-and-goal, a Chandler interception was
returned 91 yards by Rams defensive end Grant Wistrom.
</P>
<P>
   Rams quarterback Kurt Warner had season lows of 111 passing
yards and one touchdown. But running back Marshall Faulk more than
made up for it, rushing 18 times for 181 yards.
</P>
<P>
   By the middle of the third quarter, fans began doing the
Tomahawk Chop in anticipation of the Braves' playoff game. The
Falcons' victory vibe has gone ka-poof.
</P>
<P>
   ``Year to year, the chemistry and karma of a team is always
different because the team is not exactly the same,'' right guard
Gene Williams said. ``We shoot ourselves in the foot all the time.
It seems like we've been lining up in front of a firing squad ...
and just getting blasted.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
