<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9862 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-N.Y.-LOBSTER-DEATHS-7     10-17 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-LOBSTER-DEATHS-750&AMP;ADD(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS ARE MYSTIFIED BY DEATHS OF LOBSTERS IN LONG ISLAND
SOUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (js) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marine experts suspect that a mysterious pathogen has killed
tens of thousands of lobsters in Long Island Sound this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The die-off, described as the worst to hit Long Island Sound in
nearly a decade, has alarmed hundreds of lobstermen in New York and
Connecticut and has prompted extensive laboratory testing by state
and federal environmental officials.
</P>
<P>
   While cautioning that much more lab work needs to be done,
Gordon C. Colvin, the marine resources director of the New York
Department of Environmental Conservation, said Sunday that water
quality tests had eliminated two possibilities _ pollution or low
levels of oxygen in the water. He added that blood samples taken
from lobsters had provided no solid evidence of gaffkemia, a common
and often fatal bacterial infection in lobsters.
</P>
<P>
   The working hypothesis, he said, is that some other bacterium or
virus is killing the lobsters, which become sluggish before dying
although they otherwise appear normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably have a different pathogen at work here,'' Colvin
said. ``We've pretty much ruled out environmental factors. It's a
question of trying to find someone who can help us determine if
there is a pathogen.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few weeks, officials in New York and Connecticut
have taken blood from lobsters and sent it to several laboratories,
including the University of Arizona in Tucson, the Food and Drug
Administration in Washington and the National Marine Fisheries
Service in Milford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there is no reason to fear eating lobsters from the
Sound, said Byron H. Young, chief of the finfish and crustacean
unit of the New York Department of Environmental Conservation. No
one has reported getting sick after eating lobster, and cooking
lobsters in boiling water would kill any microbes, Young said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the lobster is alive and kicking, there is no reason to
believe there is a problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who fish the Sound, the problem is that too many
lobsters are already dead by the time they are pulled from traps.
In recent weeks, some lobstermen have stopped fishing altogether.
``It's just basically a losing proposition,'' said Robert L.
Eberhardt, a 52-year-old lobsterman who works out of Northport, a
harbor village on the North Shore of Long Island. ``Between fuel,
bait and crew, you come out behind.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Jeff W. Carbone, the owner of Portland Maine Seafood Co. in
Huntington, N.Y., said he was mystified. ``I've never experienced
anything like it and I've been doing this for more than 30 years,''
he said. Carbone's lobster supply house holds up to 25,000 pounds
of live lobsters in its water tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them look like a perfect lobster,'' he said. ``They
cook fine. They eat good. Visually there's nothing wrong that you
can see. But they keep dying. They're dying every day, and the
scary thing is we'll never know how many didn't get in the traps.
How many are down there dead?''
</P>
<P>
   Marine experts say they are unsure of the full scope of the
die-off, which was reported late last week in several Long Island
newspapers. Offering what he described as a conservative estimate,
Young said ``tens of thousands'' of lobsters have died already,
with roughly eight of every 100 captured lobsters coming up dead.
Blue crabs and rock crabs, too, are dying, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Lobster boats first began reporting the deaths about six weeks
ago, particularly in the western third of Long Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Millions of lobsters are caught in the Sound each year, and
summer is the prime season for lobstering, an increasingly
important component of the local fishing industry. New York has 900
commercially licensed lobstermen, and lobsters now rate ahead of
clams as the state's most valuable maritime crop.
</P>
<P>
   For years, marine life in the western portion of the Sound has
been plagued by low levels of dissolved oxygen, which can be caused
by algae blooms. When lobster captains complained this summer of
small catches, many attributed the problem to poor oxygen levels.
But, Colvin said, oxygen levels had already returned to normal by
the time the die-off began.
</P>
<P>
   Deepening the mystery, he said, is the fact that other die-offs
have been observed several times this decade. ``We've had reports
of lobsters in this condition since 1990,'' Colvin said. ``It
usually starts in early autumn, and then it seems to end by late
October when the water gets good and cold. Last year's was worse
than the other years, until now.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It may be significant, he said, that microbial activity tails
off when the water cools, but the patterns of the lobster die-off
are difficult to read. In some parts of the Sound, such as the
waters off Greenwich, Conn., half the lobsters in a trap may come
up dead. Other times all the lobsters are fine.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the initial laboratory work has been done by Richard
Robohm, a microbiologist for the National Marine Fisheries Service.
He searched for evidence of bacteria in blood from 10 lobsters
recovered by Connecticut environmental officials. In nine of the 10
lobsters, he said, ``the blood looked fine.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the 10th lobster, he found evidence of bacteria. The
results, he said, suggest only one clear conclusion _ that more
testing must be done. ``It's a mystery,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
