<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-NOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Benitez too much for Braves to figure
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York _ As much attention as Braves closer John Rocker has
gotten this series, Mets closer Armando Benitez has been as tough,
if not more so. Until the 10th inning on Sunday evening, the Braves
hadn't touched him all season, going 0-for-26.
</P>
<P>
   So when Eddie Perez singled to left to start the 10th inning,
the Braves had to figure they were finally on to something. But
Benitez proved his nastiness when he retired Walt Weiss on a
strikeout after Weiss three times failed to get a bunt down before
finally fouling a ball down the first-base line.
</P>
<P>
   Ozzie Guillen had the best at-bat of the postseason against
Benitez Saturday night, coming a few feet foul of a home run to
right field and eventually flying out to deep right. But pinch
hitting in the 10th, he popped out to Mike Piazza for the second
out, and Gerald Williams grounded out to Edgardo Alfonzo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really sit on one pitch,'' said Keith Lockhart, who
struck out looking against Benitez to end Saturday night's game.
``First you've got to see it. You'd still have trouble hitting if
he went up there and told you fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ozzie had our best at-bat against him yet,'' hitting coach Don
Baylor said. ``He got the head of the bat out there (expecting the
fastball). If he's going to be macho, you better be macho too.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson back
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Rickey Henderson show up on Sunday afternoon, he
started. Henderson was livid with manager Bobby Valentine Saturday
night after he was replaced in left field by Melvin Mora, but not
until he had already run out onto the field to start the eighth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson had walked out of the Mets dugout during the game,
reportedly telling his teammates, ``I'm outta here,'' implying he
meant more than just out of the dugout. But Valentine insisted
Henderson was there until the end in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to my coaches about that today, and the timing of
that was very bad and in particular for a player of Rickey's
stature,'' Valentine said. ``And I expressed those concerns to him
(Saturday). . . . Some of my coaches thought it was improper to
take him out at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said he was deciding who to get up in the bullpen, and
he forgot to tell Mora to go in, something that usually is handled
by his bench coach Bruce Benedict. But Benedict has been coaching
third base this series while Cookie Rojas served the fourth of a
five-game suspension for shoving umpire Charlie Williams in the
last game of the Division Series against Arizona. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Mets right fielder Roger Cedeno showed up at the ballpark with
back spasms, forcing him out of Sunday's starting lineup. He was
replaced by Mora.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been bothered now for about the last week,'' Valentine
said. ``But today he came in with a pretty severe spasm.'' Cedeno
later entered the game as a pinch-runner in the 15th inning.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker has appeared in 10 consecutive NLCS games, including
all six last year against the Padres and the first four of this
year's series against the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
