NYT-10-17-99 2221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991017.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9864 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS18-COX     10-17 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta loses to New York Mets in marathon
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sunday's Game 5 of the NLCS will be remembered as one
of the most interesting in postseason history. It will definitely
be remembered as the longest.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves appeared to have had the game won in the top
of the 15th inning after Keith Lockhart tripled to score Walt Weiss
for a 3-2 lead. But the New York's Todd Pratt walked with the bases
loaded in the bottom of the inning to tie the game, and Robin
Ventura followed with a grand slam to stun the Braves 4-3 and force
Game 6 Tuesday at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   The game, the longest postseason contest in major league
history, was filled with several pitching moves, botched bunting
attempts and a steady rain for most of the contest, which lasted
nearly six hours. The Braves very easily could have won it in the
13th inning after Lockhart got a two-out single off Octavio Dotel.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones followed him with a rip to right field for a
double on a hit-and-run, which would have put runners at the
corners for Brian Jordan, the Braves best clutch hitter.
</P>
<P>
   But Braves third base coach Ned Yost got greedy and blew it, by
sending Lockhart home despite Melvin Mora's clean play in right
field and good throw to the cutoff man in Edgardo Alfonzo. He
completed the deal with a good relay throw to Mike Piazza, who
nailed Lockhart easily for the last out of the 13th inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets and Braves had been knotted at 2-2 since the fourth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets took a 2-0 lead on Greg Maddux in the first inning on
some more John Olerud heroics. He got his third consecutive hit of
the series by taking Maddux deep to right field for a two-run
homer, his second in his previous three at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux got pushed around for another two hits to the next four
batters he faced but he put an end to that quickly. The only other
threat the Mets mounted on him came on a pair of Ryan Klesko errors
in the sixth inning. But Maddux got out of it by getting Rey
Ordonez to bounce his first pitch to Walt Weiss for a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones, who'd endured offensive misery for the first four
games of this series, chimed in with a two-run contribution to even
the score on Mosato Yoshii in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   He drove in his first run of the series with his first extra
base hit of the series when he doubled down the third base line to
score Bret Boone.
</P>
<P>
   After two days of offensive futility (6 for 56), Jones and the
Braves had finally started to get some hits, just not when they
needed them the most. The Braves stranded a dozen runners from the
fourth to ninth innings and Orel Hershiser started it off by
rescuing Yoshii, who had allowed four consecutive baserunners on
three hits and a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser made his first appearance of the NLCS and a lasting
impression when he struck out Andruw Jones, Eddie Perez and then
got Walt Weiss on a groundout to stop a Braves two-run rally. Those
three at-bats became the first in an 0 for 10 stretch for Braves
hitters with runners in scoring position going through the 10th
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
