<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9866 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-NLCS-SIDE18-COX     10-17 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-SIDE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York _ Hand it to the Braves bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox gave them the ball in the eighth inning Sunday
and they held the Mets scoreless until the 15th inning of a 4-3
loss to the New York Mets
</P>
<P>
   As a light rain fell in Shea Stadium during the longest major
league game in history, the bodies in the bullpen gravitated toward
the mound, then the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   And then there were none. Cox used all five of his relievers,
including three faces who hadn't been seen yet in the NLCS, as the
Braves and Mets engaged in a war of attrition. The Mets used nine
of their 11 pitchers, including starter Kenny Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin McGlinchy, a 22-year-old rookie making his first
appearance in the NLCS, got the win in 1 2/3 innings of work after
Keith Lockhart drove in Walt Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   After pitching 6 1/3 innings in the first four games of the
NLCS, the Atlanta bullpen more than doubled its presence in this
series, pitching what would have been almost a full game in any
under circumstances. In 14 1/3 innings, they have given up only one
earned run.
</P>
<P>
   Braves right-handed ace Greg Maddux pitched seven innings,
giving up seven hits, as well as two runs in the first on John
Olerud's second homer of the series. Olerud had previously hit a
grand slam off Maddux in his most recent appearance at Shea
Stadium, a 9-2 Braves loss on Sept. 29.
</P>
<P>
   But Maddux was almost forgotten as the afternoon game stretched
into the night and set a record for longest game in major league
baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Mulholland, a left-handed starter/reliever making his
first NLCS appearance, came in to begin the eighth inning. He gave
up a single to Olerud, struck out Mike Piazza, then Robin Ventura
hit into a double play. He had a strikeout in both innings.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Remlinger, another left-hander, took over in the 10th,
pitching in his fourth NLCS game. In two innings, he had two
strikeouts and his only lapse was giving up a hit to Ventura, who
had been hitless throughout the NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   To start the 12th, right-hander Russ Springer, also pitching for
the first time in the league series, issued the first walk of the
game to Benny Agbayani. But Springer made short work of the next
three batters, and he was through.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Cox, not knowing which inning would be the last,
decided it was time for John Rocker in the 13th. Rocker, a powerful
left-hander, made his 11th straight appearance in an NLCS game, and
already held the record.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker's war of words continued with the Mets fans. After
retiring the side, including Mike Piazza, he yelled to the crowd
above the dugout, ``I just struck out your best hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox asked Rocker how he felt, and the pitcher said he was good
to go. But Cox needed him only to face Robin Ventura. When Rocker
left the game after getting Ventura to fly out to center, Rocker
said ``Boo me.'' Then he booed the fans as he approached the
dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was McGlinchy's turn. McGlinchy, a big right-hander,
gave up a huge single to Shawon Dunston. Pitching coach Leo Mazzone
came out to tell McGlinchy to try to hold him at first as he faced
pinch-hitter Matt Franco. But Dunston stole second, and McGlinchy
walked Franco.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Rosen writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
