<HEADER>
A9867 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-RANGERS-THRASHERS     10-17 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-THRASHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYONE HEALTHY, RANGERS MOVE INTO TIE FOR FIRST
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This was what the Rangers' president, Neil Smith,
must have envisioned when he was engaged in his off-season spending
spree. Theo Fleury scoring goals. Four solid lines dividing ice
time. A healthy Mike Richter making tricky saves. And the Rangers
perched at the top of their division after just eight games.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are 4-3-1, tied with the Devils atop the Atlantic
Division, after their 4-1 victory over the expansion Atlanta
Thrashers Sunday night at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since opening night, Oct. 1 in Edmonton, the
Rangers were complete Sunday night. Not only was Richter in goal,
Valery Kamensky was back on the ice, too. And Fleury was doing
exactly what he is being paid $28 million over the next four
seasons to do: score goals.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury scored two on his first two shots to give him four on the
season. And Richter, in his first game in 15 days, sparkled in
goal. He stopped 30 of 31 shots for his first victory of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Rangers' fourth victory in their last five games.
</P>
<P>
   Everything had to feel right for Smith Sunday night other than
the Rangers' inexplicably punchless power play, which went 0 for 3
and is now 3 for 39 on the season.
</P>
<P>
   Richter, who has a slightly protruding disk in his lower back,
had missed the last five games; Kamensky, who has been bothered by
a stress fracture in his right forearm, the last six.
</P>
<P>
   Having all hands available enabled coach John Muckler to tinker
with his line combinations heading into the game. Kamensky skated
with Petr Nedved and Mike Knuble. Mike York centered a line with
Adam Graves and Fleury. Tim Taylor skated with Kevin Stevens to his
left and John MacLean to his right. And Manny Malhotra skated with
Darren Langdon and Todd Harvey to open the game, with Harvey back
at right wing, his experiment at left wing apparently over.
Langdon's presence on the ice for the opening faceoff precipitated
an immediate line change by the Thrashers. And just 14 seconds into
the game, Langdon and Atlanta's Matt Johnson were fighting behind
the play.
</P>
<P>
   The fisticuffs were evidently intended as a payback for Johnson,
whose hit on Jeff Beukeboom in Los Angeles last Nov. 19 _ when
Johnson was a member of the Kings _ helped lead to Beukeboom's
early retirement as a result of concussions.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a minute later, the Rangers went up 1-0 on Fleury's
third goal of the season. Muckler had not been pleased with
Fleury's play last Thursday, in a 5-2 thrashing by the Pittsburgh
Penguins. But Muckler had to be happy with the way Fleury, Graves
and York meshed on their first shift Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   It was Graves' work behind the Atlanta net that set up the goal.
Graves took out a pair of Thrashers on the play as they fought for
the puck along the end boards. York pounced on the loose puck, and,
from behind Atlanta goaltender Norm Maracle's right shoulder, York
fed Fleury alone in front. Fleury banged the pass home on a play
that Maracle barely contested. And it was 1-0 Rangers just 1 minute
8 seconds into the game on the Rangers' first shot of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides had eight shots apiece after one period.
</P>
<P>
   Richter, who looked sharp early, stayed that way. Atlanta took
nine of the first 12 shots in the second period, but Richter did
not allow any past him.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Rangers finally found a way to take advantage of their
special teams: they scored on the delayed penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved scored at 9:40, seconds after he had jumped on the ice as
an extra skater after Atlanta captain Kelly Buchberger had taken
down York behind the Atlanta net. With no stop in play because the
Thrashers could not touch up, the puck wound up on rookie
defenseman Kim Johnsson's stick near the blue line.
</P>
<P>
   Johnsson faked a shot, then slid a nifty pass to Nedved, who let
loose from above the left wing circle. The puck caromed off the
stick of Atlanta's Denny Lambert, who was reaching back from the
slot in an attempt to block the shot. Instead, Lambert redirected
the shot into the net. And Nedved not only had his second goal of
the season, but a point in each of his last five games.
</P>
<P>
   Less than four minutes later, Fleury struck again. This time, it
was on a two-on-one rush with York, after Graves had made a nice
neutral-ice pass to Fleury past a gambling Kevin Dean to set up the
odd-man rush down the ice. Fleury skated down right wing, made a
lovely move to pull the puck around Chris Tamer, as Tamer dived to
the ice in front of the Atlanta goal, then shot at Maracle. The
puck caromed off Dean's stick _ Dean was reaching out from the slot
behind the play in a vain attempt to block Fleury's shot _ and past
Maracle at 13:21 of the second. Fleury had his first multiple-goal
game as a Ranger.
</P>
<P>
   And the Rangers had a 3-0 lead over what looked like a tired
expansion team, one that was playing its third game in four days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
