<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9876 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-1STLD     10-17 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS PULL OFF ANOTHER MIRACLE, BEAT BRAVES IN 15 INNINGS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (CORRECTS to one out from two outs in 11th graf) 
(Eds: The following story is an added starter on The New York Times
front page)  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mets general manager Steve Phillips had wondered
Saturday why the Mets could not be the first team to come back from
three games down to win a best-of-7 playoff series. It could not be
harder, he figured, than hitting 70 home runs or pitching a perfect
game. Phillips did not factor in whether the feat _ which the
Braves failed to accomplish last year against San Diego in the
league championships _ would be any harder than completing a
marathon.
</P>
<P>
   But after nearly six hours, after nine of the 11 Mets pitchers
on the roster had made their way to the mound, after Bobby
Valentine had pinch hit for the last reliever he had left, the Mets
could actually walk home when Braves reliever Kevin McGlinchy
issued a bases-loaded walk to Todd Pratt to tie the game in the
bottom of the 15th inning and Robin Ventura, who was 1 for 18 when
he came to the plate, smashed a ball over the wall with the bases
loaded to end the game, 4-3, to force the series back to Atlanta
for a Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura was mobbed by his teammates and never made it past
second base, so he was credited with a single. Roger Cedeno scored
the winning run from third, but the rest of the base runners joined
in the celebration rather than crossing home plate.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are just the second team _ the Braves last year were
the first _ to win two games after being down 3-0 in a best-of-7
series. There is now seemingly no end to the Mets' improbable run
through the postseason. They have been nearly dead several times,
but Sunday night's resurrection _ after the Braves had scored in
the top half of the 15th off rookie reliever Octavio Dotel to take
the lead _ makes all the comebacks that came before seem minor by
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had numerous chances to blow the game open.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets took a 2-0 lead in the first inning on John Olerud's
home run _ he drove in all three New York runs in Game 4 and had
hit a grand slam off Maddux Sept. 29 _ but they stranded Mike
Piazza on first base with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Hamilton led off the second inning with a double, but he
remained at second, as did the Braves' Eddie Perez, who led off
their half of the third with a double.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fourth inning, Atlanta's first hitter, Bret Boone,
smacked a pitch from Masato Yoshii into left field. Rickey
Henderson, at the center of a controversy over his reaction to
being replaced in Game 4, did not break back for the ball until it
was too late. It went over his head and bounced off the wall for a
double.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones then slapped a 1-1 pitch down the third-base line.
It skipped over the bag and caromed off the wall in foul territory,
scoring Boone, and then rolled back into fair territory for a
double. Brian Jordan followed with a single to left that reached
Henderson on a bounce to tie the score at 2-2. Yoshii walked Ryan
Klesko on a full count to put two runners on with none out. But
Orel Hershiser, who had last pitched Oct. 8 when he threw an inning
of relief in a loss to Arizona in the division series, relieved
Yoshii and got out of the inning without allowing the Braves to
score again.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves and the Mets, who have each had trouble scoring in
this series, then had to work out of repeated jams to keep the
score tied. In the fifth, Gerald Williams hit a one-out double, but
was stranded. In the sixth, both teams had the bases loaded with
the help of errors by the opposing first basemen, and neither team
scored because of superb defensive plays.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves stranded their three when Maddux, with one out, tried
to squeeze Klesko home from third. But Hershiser's pitch was low
and away and the bunting Maddux missed the ball. Klesko had broken
from third and was almost halfway down the line when Mike Piazza
threw to to Robin Ventura. With Klesko caught between third and
home, Ventura threw to Hershiser along the line, and he made the
tag to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had an even better chance in their half of the sixth.
Piazza, leading off, hit a grounder to third. On Jones' throw to
first, Piazza stumbled over Klesko's leg and tumbled to the ground,
but was safe when Klesko dropped the throw. Ventura struck out, but
Melvin Mora _ starting in place of the injured Roger Cedeno _
singled to right, moving Piazza to second.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Hamilton, next up, hit a hard bouncer to Klesko. He threw
to second. The throw was high and wide, pulling shortstop Walt
Weiss off the bag, and the bases were loaded. But Rey Ordonez, 1
for 16 in the series as he came to the plate, swung at the first
pitch and grounded into a double play that ended the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves threatened again in the seventh, loading the bases
against a succession of four pitchers _ Hershiser, Turk Wendell,
Dennis Cook and Pat Mahomes. Mahomes got Andruw Jones to fly out to
left to end that inning.
</P>
<P>
   Back and forth they went, each team putting runners on, each
team failing to score.
</P>
<P>
   In the Braves' eighth, Weiss hit a one-out double and Jose
Hernandez, pinch-hitting for Maddux, struck out. After Gerald
Williams was intentionally walked, John Franco _ the Mets' fifth
reliever of the game _ coaxed Keith Lockhart, who had entered the
game earlier at second base, to ground out to first.
</P>
<P>
   Now it was the Mets' turn. Olerud singled off Terry Mulholland
to start the eighth, but was left there when Piazza struck out and
Ventura, 0 for 15 in the series at this point, grounded into an
inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Franco began the ninth by striking out Chipper Jones. Ventura
gave the Braves life when he couldn't hold onto a roller by Jordan,
which was ruled a hit. But Brian Hunter popped up when Franco threw
him a fastball on his fists and Andruw Jones struck out.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets went down in order in the ninth, sending the game to
extra innings, an appropriate way to extend a series filled with
closely contested, intrigue-filled games. There had been only one
other extra-inning game between the teams this season, and the
result was ominous for the Mets: the Braves beat them in 11 innings
on Sept. 30 and thought they were leaving the Mets for dead, two
games out of the wild-card slot with three games to play.
</P>
<P>
   That was the darkest day of the season for the Mets, the day
Hamilton admitted the season was on life support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
