<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After Cuba, `El Duque' can handle Boston fans
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He has faced the angry crowds in Santiago, in Havana,
even in his home province of Villa Clara where they turned against
him. Don't ask Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez about the hard times
and angry people he will see around Fenway Park as New York's
starter tonight in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Cuba, it used to be a little worse than here,'' Hernandez
said through translator (and Yankees first-base coach) Jose
Cardenal Sunday. ``They are very vocal, but in Cuba, it's a little
bit different. They throw tomatoes, throw rocks, throw everything
they can throw on the field. If you win, the opposing fans, they're
going to beat you any way they can. If you lose, your own fans are
going to try and kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence Boston's angry crowds, like the kind that tore into Roger
Clemens during Game 3, signify less of a challenge to Hernandez
more than any player still working the postseason. Here, at least
Hernandez is not pitching for his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think from El Duque's perspective, it's any
different,'' manager Joe Torre said. ``He pitched that game in
Cleveland last year (a 4-0 shutout win in Game 4 of the ALCS). I
mean, what's to scare him after leaving Cuba?
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't know what size boat he came over in, but
whatever it was, it still a fact he still had to slide out of the
country and hide out somewhere and this kind of stuff. It's not the
way we came to the ballpark. I know that. So sure, this is a
different game for him.''
</P>
<P>
   His record shows it. In four career postseason starts, Hernandez
is 3-0, having allowed three runs in 30 innings (0.97 earned-run
average).
</P>
<P>
   Offerman paying off
</P>
<P>
   The season started with Boston general manager Dan Duquette
dodging pitchforks from both fans and the industry itself for
handing a monster four-year $26 million contract to journeyman
infielder Jose Offerman. This October, Duquette doesn't here a
peep.
</P>
<P>
   While John Valentin and Nomar Garciaparra have received most of
the attention for the explosiveness in Boston's order, Offerman
quietly entered Sunday's game hitting .441 (15-for-34) in the
postseason, having gone 8-for-16 in three games against the
Yankees. Furthermore, he remains a .300 hitter against New York
since coming to the American League in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never feel comfortable when you face the staff the Yankees
have,'' he said. ``Maybe it's good luck for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Re-rotating?
</P>
<P>
   Despite Clemens' dismal performance in Game 3 (two innings, five
runs), Torre said he was not giving any thought to adjusting his
current rotation. Should the ALCS reach a seventh game, Clemens
would be re-paired with Boston's Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always concerned,'' Torre said. ``The bad part about
being a starting pitcher is you don't get a chance to get back out
there until five days later. Sometimes, that's good, because when
you can get beat up like he did yesterday, it gives you a day or so
to get the fog cleared out. Then you can start thinking about your
next start.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we set the pitching up, there is no reason for me to
deviate from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Some perspective: Pedro Martinez's current 17-inning postseason
scoreless streak is only the 10th-longest in baseball history, tied
with Boston's Jim Lonborg. He has more than a full game to go to
catch the record holder, Christy Mathewson, who threw 27 scoreless
innings in the 1905 World Series. . . . It is taking Garciaparra
longer to get back to the field after innings when he batted. The
Red Sox shortstop is wearing two different wraps on his sore right
wrist _ one for hitting, one for fielding. Trainer Jim Rowe must
change the tape job after every at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
