<SLUG> BC-BIOPATENT-MEDICINES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
BIOTECH FIRMS RUSHING TO PATENT GENE FRAGMENTS &HT;    By TOM ABATE
 &HT;    c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Biotech firms have sparked a controversy in
their race to discover and patent a type of gene fragment called an
expressed sequence tag.
</P>
<P>
   Genes are lengths of DNA that govern inherited traits like eye
color and influence our susceptibility to many diseases. More than
100,000 genes reside in the nucleus of every cell.
</P>
<P>
   But each cell may need only a few genes. The rest simply sit
dormant in the nucleus. When a cell activates a gene, scientists
say the cell expresses it. An expressed sequence tag, or EST, is
therefore a short length of DNA that does something in a given
cell.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists view ESTs as flashing lights that indicate which of
our genes may be important for cancer, heart disease or other
maladies. They reason that a gene expressed in a heart or prostate
cell must be important, otherwise it would be dormant.
</P>
<P>
   With this in mind, San Francisco Bay Area biotech firms like
Incyte Pharmaceuticals and Hyseq are vying with East Coast rivals
like Millennium Pharmaceuticals, Celera Genomics and Human Genome
Sciences to identify _ and patent _ ESTs as fast as they can.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value of EST patents is that they allow you to develop
diagnostic marker kits,'' said Incyte chief executive Roy
Whitfield. Patent holders would sell such kits to drug developers,
which would use the kits to zero in on genes of specific interest
and avoid getting lost in the genome maze.
</P>
<P>
   But some influential scientists think that ESTs should not be
patentable. This stems partly from the way ESTs are discovered. The
companies in the EST race run genetic samples through
DNA-sequencing machines. The machines automatically identify
expressed genes. But this process doesn't reveal what a gene does _
only that it does something.
</P>
<P>
   ``This involves very little effort and almost no originality,''
said Bruce Alberts, president of the National Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   David Botstein, chairman of the genetics department at Stanford
University and former scientific director at Genentech, said EST
patents could retard drug development. EST patent holders could
demand royalties from drug discovery firms, which might discourage
them from doing the work needed to fully understand a gene's
function and to use this knowledge to produce a drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is dangerous to go into a situation where you have these
potential blocking patents hanging over you,'' Botstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Incyte's Whitfield scoffs at such concerns. ``That is foolish.
It's a bogeyman that has been invented.'' He said it is in the
self-interest of EST patent holders to license broadly their
discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   But even some of his competitors in the EST race question
whether these fragmentary strands should be patented. Lewis Gruber,
chief executive of Hyseq, said he only applied for EST patents
after the Patent Office said it would look favorably upon such
applications.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone else is asking for it and you don't, you don't want
to shortchange your shareholders just because you didn't think it
was right,'' Gruber said.
</P>
<P>
   So, like its competitors, Hyseq is filing EST patent
applications. About 10,000 such applications have reached the
Patent Office thus far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have issued three (EST) patents,'' said Todd Dickinson,
acting commissioner of patents and trademarks.
</P>
<P>
   That's hardly a blistering approval rate, given that the first
EST patent applications were filed in the early 1990s. The
controversy surrounding ESTs has prompted the Patent Office to move
even more slowly than usual to issue these patents.
</P>
<P>
   But the office recently revised the 3-inch-thick book that
guides its patent examiners in reviewing EST claims, and Todd said
more EST patents ``will issue in due course.''
</P>
<P>
   But he rejected suggestions that the Patent Office will cause
trouble if it issues many patents on gene fragments. ``Other than
speculative concern, no one has shown any harm,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But San Francisco patent attorney Kevin Bastian wonders what
will happen when all those pent-up EST patents begin to issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very good chance for people to have conflicting
claims and not know it,'' he said. Bastian said two companies could
find different fragments of the same gene and win competing patents
_ something they'll discover only when they both try to enforce a
patent on the same gene.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be a big mess that the courts will have to
straighten out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the players vie to increase their EST stakes. ``The
more claims, the better,'' said Hyseq's Gruber. ``At the end of the
day, they may be valuable as bargaining chips.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
