<HEADLINE>
LEXICON PROVES HE'S NO COUNTERFEIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Kevin Modesti  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ A Daily Racing Form handicapper attached an
unkind word to a colt named Lexicon this week, dismissing him as a
``counterfeit'' contender for next month's Breeders' Cup Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Lexicon issued his reply on Saturday by beating heavily favored
Kona Gold in the Ancient Title Handicap at Santa Anita. A few
minutes later the 4-year-old's trainer had his say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's ever claimed this is the next Man O'War, but he's a
good, consistent horse,'' Richard Mandella said in the winner's
circle. ``The word `counterfeit' really offended me. I can tell you
some horses who are counterfeit. He's not one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Handicapper Brad Free had written, ``Only one of (Lexicon's) 18
starts remotely resembles a Breeders' Cup-quality effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it's two of 19.
</P>
<P>
   Lexicon and jockey Kent Desormeaux blazed 6 furlongs in 1:07.84
to break the record for the Ancient Title, the race that produced
Breeders' Cup Sprint winners Cardmania (1993) and Elmhurst (1997).
Lexicon ($8.40) opened a clear lead with quarter-mile splits of
21.92 and 44.16, was caught by Kona Gold and Alex Solis at the top
of the stretch but pulled away from the opponent who'd been
sidelined since March.
</P>
<P>
   The Nov. 6 Breeders' Cup Sprint at Gulfstream Park in Florida
will include a strong contingent from California, with Lexicon,
Kona Gold and Regal Thunder aiming to join Forestry, Big Jag, Enjoy
the Moment and Son of a Pistol in facing the best of the East and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Team California looks like this after three weekends
of preps for the eight-race, $13 million Breeders' Cup card:
</P>
<P>
   __ Classic: Budroyale, General Challenge and Old Trieste, 1-2-3
in Saturday's Goodwood; and Woodward-Jockey Club Gold Cup winner
River Keen.
</P>
<P>
   __ Distaff: Three-year-old Silverbulletday; Spinster winner
Keeper Hill; narrow Lady's Secret winner Manistique.
</P>
<P>
   __ Turf: Sayarshan and Bonapartiste, 3-4 behind Breeders'
Cup-ineligible horses in the Oak Tree Turf Championship.
</P>
<P>
   __ Mile: Silic and Brave Act, 1-2 in Saturday's Oak Tree Mile;
1998 Mile runner-up Hawksley Hill; Shadwell Mile winner Kirkwall;
Ladies Din, who, like Silic, is Julio Canani-trained; and
Ramona-winning mare Tuzla.
</P>
<P>
   __ Filly and Mare Turf: Yellow Ribbon winner Spanish Fern;
Canani's Caffe Latte.
</P>
<P>
   __ Juvenile: Dixie Union, likely favorite Forest Camp and Anees,
1-2-3 in the Norfolk; Captain Steve, winner of the the Breeders'
Futurity at Keeneland; California Sires winner Hugh Hefner.
</P>
<P>
   __ Juvenile Fillies: Heavy favorite Chilukki, Abby Girl and
Spain, 1-2-3 in the Oak Leaf.
</P>
</TEXT>
