<HEADER>
A9991 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SPACE-TOURISM-SFCHRON     10-17 1609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-TOURISM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CUSTOMERS LINING UP TO TOUR SPACE  &HT;     By TERRY NAGEL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ Move over, Neil Armstrong. Space tourism is about
to take off.
<P>
   Two U.S. tour operators are accepting reservations on suborbital
flights that are expected to lift off as soon as 2002. The
21/2-hour trips to the edge of space will be the culmination of
weeklong packages that immerse participants in space jargon,
subject them to G-forces, familiarize them with state-of-the-art
equipment and teach them to do triple somersaults at zero gravity.
</P>
<P>
   The trips aren't cheap, but they're selling briskly. About 145
people already have made substantial deposits or paid in full for
seven-day excursions to space with either Zegrahm Expeditions of
Seattle, which charges $98,000, or Space Adventures of Alexandria,
Va., which charges $90,000. The companies say thousands more have
expressed interest in going.
</P>
<P>
   Space travel for average citizens, which seemed imminent when
Neil Armstrong walked on the moon in 1969, never got beyond the
talking stage until a few years ago, when private companies started
figuring out how to make it happen. NASA didn't help; the agency
doesn't believe that its mission is to help taxpayers go to space.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology to take civilians up to space and back has
existed for a long time. It's just basically proving there is a
market and getting investors to put up money to build vehicle
systems and getting regulatory organizations like the (Federal
Aviation Administration) to grant licenses,'' said Scott
Fitzsimmons, vice president of Zegrahm.
</P>
<P>
   The current passion for exotic trips is adding to the momentum.
The Adventure Travel Society in Englewood, Colo., reported in June
that Americans spend $110 billion on adventure travel every year.
Those in search of the latest and greatest adventure spend tens of
thousands of dollars on unusual trips like climbing Mt. Everest,
diving in a submersible vessel beneath the ocean to see the Titanic
or visiting Antarctica aboard an icebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated by NASA's slowness in opening space to private
citizens, some space enthusiasts formed a foundation in 1996 which
is offering a $10 million prize to jump-start space tourism. Even
former astronauts have joined this effort: Byron Lichtenberg, who
flew on Space Shuttle missions 9 and 45 is one of the founders of
the X Prize Foundation. (He's also a senior adviser to Space
Adventures, along with ex-astronauts Buzz Aldrin, Owen Garriott,
Robert ``Hoot'' Gibson, Norman Thagard, Kathryn Thornton and
Charles Walker.)
</P>
<P>
   The X Prize will be awarded to the team that designs the first
private spaceship that carries three humans to a suborbital
altitude of 100 kilometers (62 miles _ the beginning of space as
defined by the Federation Aeronautique Internationale) and then
does it again within two weeks. All teams must be privately
financed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suborbital'' means traveling high enough to enter space but
not fast enough to go into orbit. It's the same type of flight that
the first American in space, Alan Shepard, took in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   The prize money is coming from private sources, most of whom
wish to be anonymous. Peter Diamandis, chairman and president of
the X Prize Foundation in St. Louis, said his group has raised more
than $5 million and expects to raise the rest within six months.
Part of the funding is coming from X Prize Platinum Visa cards
issued by First USA.
</P>
<P>
   The X Prize is modeled after the Orteig Prize, the $25,000 purse
that Charles Lindbergh won in 1927 (worth about $226,000 in today's
dollars). That prize inspired nine attempts to cross the Atlantic
Ocean before Lindbergh, an underdog who was berated as a ``flying
fool'' in the press, succeeded. Diamandis credits the Orteig Prize
and other early aviation prizes with paving the way to commercial
air travel.
</P>
<P>
   One of the X Prize board members is Erik Lindbergh, 34, grandson
of the famous aviator. Although he's trained as a commercial pilot
and flight instructor, he now works for two nonprofit organizations
and has a woodworking business on Bainbridge Island, Wash., where
he makes sculptures of rockets and planets. He signed on with the X
Prize Foundation, he said, because ``we need to have an economic
incentive to develop space.''
</P>
<P>
   Zegrahm Expeditions and Space Adventures aren't registered in
the competition, but both have formed alliances with some of the
contestants, which primarily are rocketmakers with a wide range of
experience. Fifteen teams have registered so far, and a 16th team _
the first from Russia _ probably will be announced next month.
Eleven teams are American, two are from England, one is from
Germany, and one is from South America.
</P>
<P>
   Diamandis won't speculate on who's ahead. ``The people who are
the front-runners today may not be the winners tomorrow,'' he said.
``About one-third of them are building hardware and flying
prototypes, a third have designs and are busy raising money, and a
third are trying to figure out how to get going.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the contestants is Vela Technology Development Inc. of
Vienna, Va., which has designed a two-stage Space Cruiser with a
reusable launch vehicle. Zegrahm is planning on using this craft.
</P>
<P>
   Space Adventures has partnerships with five of the X Prize
contestants: Pioneer Rocketplane of Ann Arbor, Mich., whose
Pathfinder vehicle uses both jet and rocket engines; Kelly Space
and Technology Inc. of San Bernardino, Calif., which will use a 747
jet to tow its Eclipse Astroliner to about 20,000 feet before
igniting rocket engines to climb to space; Rotary Rocket of Redwood
City, Calif., which already has unveiled its Roton, which takes off
vertically like a conventional rocket and lands using helicopter
blades; Scaled Composites Inc. of Mohave, Calif., which is
designing a two-stage vehicle using a composite aircraft as a
launch platform; and Bristol Spaceplanes of England, which flew a
scale model of its one-stage jet- and rocket-powered Ascender this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever gets there first is the one we'll use,'' said Emilene
Paat-Dahlstrom, director of programs for Space Adventures.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Space Adventures and Zegrahm are offering earthbound
adventures for space wannabes that allow them to experience
weightlessness, neutral buoyancy and g-loads at the Gagarin
Cosmonaut Training Center in Star City, Russia. The facility is the
Russian equivalent of the Kennedy Space Center. All Russian
cosmonauts train there, as well as astronauts from 17 other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Zegrahm has signed up about 20 people for its seven-day training
program, at $14,950 each, and will take the first group over on
October 24. Space Adventures already has taken individuals to
Russia for various components of the training, such as a
zero-gravity flight ($5,500) and a ride in the cockpit of a Russian
MiG-25 military jet ($11,900).
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of SPACE18 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Russia has a different attitude than NASA about training
civilians for space travel because the survival of its space
program depends on raising revenue. That's why cosmonauts floated a
giant Pepsi can outside the Mir space station and why Russia
recently agreed to put the Pizza Hut logo on a rocket.
</P>
<P>
   But NASA is beginning to shift its emphasis. NASA Administrator
Dan Goldin announced in late September that the agency wants
private industry to take over activities in the Earth's orbit, such
as the International Space Station, so NASA can get back to
exploring deep space &LR;  _ that is, establishing a moon base and going
on to Mars and beyond &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   NASA also participated in a two-year study with the Space
Transportation Association that concluded that serious national
attention should be given to the creation of a large in-space
tourism industry. The report, which was released in March 1998,
noted that Americans currently spend about $1 billion on visits to
space museums, space camps and other space tourism activities on
terra firma &LR;  _ a small portion of the $400 billion that U.S.
tourism takes in annually &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Bob Haltermann, executive director of STA's Space Travel &AMP;
Tourism Division in Arlington, Va., spends his days trying to make
space tourism happen. His nonprofit group has members who are
mostly rocketmakers; former astronauts Buzz Aldrin and Scott
Carpenter sit on the board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Haltermann recently cited a 1996 survey in which 1,200 people
were asked what they would be willing to pay for a two-week
vacation aboard a space shuttle that had all the amenities of a
cruise ship. STA concluded that the space-tourism market was close
to $1 trillion, or about $30 billion per year for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Penn, a senior project engineer with the Aerospace Corp. in
El Segundo, Calif., calls space tourism ``a chicken-and-egg kind of
problem.'' After studying the feasibility of space-tourism launch
systems, he concluded, ``To get people to fly, you need to get the
cost down, but to get the cost down, you need to get people to
fly.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``The trick is to design vehicles that are very
operable and very reliable that are designed for a very low
incremental cost per flight _ meaning they won't wear out soon and
they can turn around rapidly to fly again.''
</P>
<P>
   And when that happens, average citizens _ not just rich people _
will be able to rocket into space.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RESOURCES
</P>
<P>
   --Space Adventures, (888) 857-7223; www.spaceadventures.com.
</P>
<P>
   --Space Travel &AMP; Tourism Division of Space Transportation
Association, (703) 671-4116; www.spacetourism.org.
</P>
<P>
   --X Prize Foundation, (314) 533-2002; www.xprize.com.
</P>
<P>
   --Zegrahm Expeditions, (888) 772-2366; www.zeco.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-99 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
