<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9992 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LAD     10-17 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON DOESN'T BELONG AMONG GREATEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one can question Mike Tyson's ability to stir the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, even though it's clear he's nothing like the fighter
he once was, he remains boxing's biggest draw. His latest comeback
fight, against Orlin Norris on Saturday, will garner very high
ratings. Guaranteed. Clearly, he's among the all-time greats in
terms of marketability.
</P>
<P>
   However, where does he rank in terms of his BOXING ability?
</P>
<P>
   Some insist his awesome run through the heavyweight division in
the 1980s proves he's among the greatest ever. Others say he was
overrated from the start and the illusion was exposed later in his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Where does the truth lie? Somewhere in between.
</P>
<P>
   This much is certain: Tyson was far and away the best
heavyweight during his first stint as champion, from Nov. 22, 1986
_ when he stopped Trevor Berbick to win the WBC title _ to Feb. 11,
1990 _ when Buster Douglas did the impossible.
</P>
<P>
   His opponents, many of them petrified, were utterly unable to
cope with his unique combination of speed, power and ferocity, the
attributes that so thrilled boxing fans.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe he was the greatest fighter in history the night he
knocked out a terrified Michael Spinks in 90 seconds in 1988 and
they have an argument.
</P>
<P>
   For this, Tyson deserves credit. What more can be asked of a
champion than to decimate the best fighters in his division?
</P>
<P>
   That said, let's examine his division at that time and ask: Who
did he beat?
</P>
<P>
   Here's the list of his title defenses: Bonecrusher Smith,
Pinklon Thomas, Tony Tucker, Tyrell Biggs, Larry Holmes, Tony
Tubbs, Michael Spinks, Frank Bruno, Carl Williams and Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Not inspiring, huh?
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Holmes and Spinks, these fighters are
forgettable. And even Holmes and Spinks can't be considered
significant benchmarks because Holmes was old (38) and Spinks a
natural light heavyweight when they met the young Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   How would he have fared against a young Foreman? A young Liston?
A young Frazier? Not well by many estimations.
</P>
<P>
   Again, give him his due: Until Douglas, he beat those who were
put in front of him. However, his level of opposition doesn't help
his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Douglas fight and what followed is what MOST
adversely affects his place in history. He seemed to be unbeatable
until that night in Tokyo. SEEMED. That was the illusion.
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Liston, who had Tyson-like power, also seemed to be
unbeatable at one time. The same goes for George Foreman. And then
they met a guy by the name of Ali and it was clear they were as
human as anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Like Tyson, their careers were never the same after that first
defeat. Today, they are viewed as very good heavyweights but not in
the same class as the Dempseys or Louises or Alis.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson? Same thing. In his last 12 fights, including Douglas,
he's 9-3 and was knocked out twice.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas and then Holyfield (twice) proved that if you're not
afraid of him, don't stand in one place too long and have some
power, Tyson can be had.
</P>
<P>
   It happened three times, or at least 2{ times if you don't want
to count the ear-biting fight as a complete entity. That's a
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   However, here's an important question: Would this theory have
applied when Tyson was at his best? Probably.
</P>
<P>
   The best evidence we have is the Douglas fight.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Tyson had started his decline. His personal problems and
complacency certainly contributed to his downfall. It was then that
his bob-and-weave, punches-in-bunches style began to evolve into a
more simple, less effective brand of slugging.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Tyson was only 23 when he fought Douglas. 23!
Any way you look at it, at that age, he was at least NEAR his
prime.
</P>
<P>
   And look what Douglas, an inspired journeyman, did to Tyson that
night? He beat him up.
</P>
<P>
   Marciano never lost. Muhammad Ali wasn't beat up until very late
his career, when Holmes did it. Louis was beat up by Max Schmeling
as a youngster but came back to build arguably the greatest career
of any heavyweight. Holmes wasn't beat up until he was decrepit.
Foreman and Frazier were beat up but only by exceptional fighters.
</P>
<P>
   And, remember, Tyson was beat up THREE times. Holyfield pummeled
him in their unforgettable first fight and the second appeared to
be headed in the same direction when Tyson decided to take the
fight into his own mouth. And Holyfield did it when he was 34 and
35, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   That's three maulings before the age of 31 by a mediocre fighter
and an aging champion. Is that a great heavyweight?
</P>
<P>
   OK, again, Tyson's personal problems were key factors. When
one's life is falling apart, when one is in and out of prison, it's
monumentally difficult to focus on boxing. That's obvious.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is we're left to judge him by what he has done in the
ring. There are no ifs and mighta-beens when determining anyone's
impact.
</P>
<P>
   And, just as important, many boxers and other athletes have had
to deal with personal difficulties and have overcome them to
maintain a high level of excellence. Tyson hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Is that not one measure of greatness?
</P>
<P>
   Today, at 33, Tyson is no longer a terror in the ring. If he
fights Holyfield again or, say, Lennox Lewis for another world
championship, he likely would be an underdog. Just as likely, he
would lose.
</P>
<P>
   So we're left to judge him on the past, a past that includes an
impressive run against mediocre opposition over three-plus years
and a nondescript career beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   Would Tyson at his best be able to compete with the greatest
heavyweights in history? Possibly. Is he among the greatest when
his entire career is examined? No way.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson was a very good fighter but never a great one.
</P>
<P>
   __ Vargas' day: Interesting timing.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Vargas of Oxnard, whose demolition of Raul Marquez drew
nationwide raves, was named Fighter of the Year at the World Boxing
Hall of Fame induction ceremonies on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it could be the last time he's invited.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas faces jail time if he's convicted of pending assault
charges, although his lawyers believe charges will be dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if he doesn't stay out of trouble, he'll never realize
his immense potential and return to the Hall for what really
counts: induction.
</P>
<P>
   __ Inductees: Boxers inducted into the Hall were former WBA
bantamweight champion Khaosai Galaxy, one of the most dominating
little men of the 1980s; former lightweight champ Ismael Laguna,
whose list of opponents reads like a Hall of Fame; Jose Luis
Ramirez, who had a record of 102-9, with 82 knockouts; and Los
Angeles resident Joey Barnum, a lightweight contender in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Among those inducted in the expanded category were Bruce Tramp,
one of the most significant matchmakers of his generation, and
referee Larry Rozadilla.
</P>
<P>
   __ Correction: The network on which the Nov. 6 Joe Calzaghe-Omar
Sheika fight will be televised was incorrect in last week's column.
The fight will be broadcast on Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   Calzaghe, from England, is the WBO super middleweight champion. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
