<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACEBIZ-OPPORTUNITIES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 THE BUSINESS POSSIBILITIES OF SPACE  &HT;     By TERRY NAGEL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Lots of business opportunities await the
conquerors of space. Peter Diamandis of the X Prize Foundation
predicted, ``The first trillionaires will be made in space.
Everything that we hold valuable on the planet _ mineral resources,
land, energy _ is available in infinite quantities in space.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, a nickel-iron asteroid measuring half a
kilometer in diameter would be worth $25 trillion in platinum-group
metals at today's prices.
</P>
<P>
   As the price of space flights drops, due to reusable vehicles
flying more often, other benefits might include:
</P>
<P>
   --Rocket mail. Packages could be delivered on the same day
anywhere in the world. Diamandis said Federal Express already has
pledged to make this service available when it's feasible.
Companies even could offer ``yesterday delivery'' of packages on
spaceships that cross the international date line and deliver them
in an earlier time zone.
</P>
<P>
   --Speedier travel. Passengers could circle the world in 11/2
hours and fly between any two points in 45 minutes, according to
Jay Penn of the Aerospace Corp. in El Segundo, Calif. ``But it
would still take four days to get your luggage,'' he joked. Penn
said suborbital flights eventually will be comparable in price to
flights on commercial aircraft for long-range trips.
</P>
<P>
   --Cheaper telecommunications. Satellites carrying gear that
enables beepers, television signals and ATM transfers to go through
would get cheaper. Instead of costing about $10,000 per pound of
payload, they could would drop to one-tenth or, in time, down to
one-hundredth of that cost.
</P>
<P>
   --Medical and scientific breakthroughs. ``In a nongravity
environment,'' said Penn, ``there would be the capability to
manufacture specialized materials, designer molecules and designer
drugs.'' He explained that materials can be electrically separated
more easily in space because the gravitational forces are much
lower. And there's a bonus for silicon users: ``You can grow very
large crystals that are stronger than those on Earth,'' Penn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
