<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DESPITE SLUMPS AND BRUISES, METS FIND WAY TO WIN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With all of New York holding on to their MetroCards
in anticipation of a Subway Series, the New York Mets fought for
their lives in a persistent drizzle Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   They held off disaster time and again, but then again, this has
been their style over this exciting but turbulent season.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they prevailed. In a classic game _ for length, for
significance, for frustration and ultimately for joy _ the Mets
beat the Atlanta Braves, 4-3, in 15 innings, to prolong a season
that may only just be getting interesting.
</P>
<P>
   The top half of everybody's scorecard was much more cluttered
than the bottom. All the hieroglyphics on the top half indicated
the desperate hours of the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the heroes who had carried them through the summer were
having their problems. Their catcher, Mike Piazza, was reeling from
injuries. Their third baseman, Robin Ventura _ who would drive in
the winning run, with a bases-loaded hit that went over the wall
but became a one-run single when he and others were mobbed on the
basepaths _ was also battered, mired in a dreadful slump.
</P>
<P>
   Their left fielder, Rickey Henderson, was recovering from what
was described a few days ago as ``flu-like symptoms,'' and he was
also suffering a Rickey-like funk about being called out of left
field on Saturday night on a double switch in the lineup that had
not been relayed to him.
</P>
<P>
   Did Rickey threaten to quit the team? Were his teammates
disgusted with him? This is merely part of their charm.
</P>
<P>
   This is how they have endured the intrigues and psychodramas of
the Bobby Valentine regime. The players and the fans witnessed the
Mets' management virtually taunt Valentine 55 games into the season
by dismissing three of his coaches, as if to see what he might do
about it. Just to be ornery, Valentine stuck it out.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets also stuck it out through a seven-game slump in the
final two weeks of the season. Valentine added to his own troubles
by volunteering the observation that if the Mets did not get into
the playoffs that he ``probably should not be back.'' He parsed it
and deconstructed it, giving himself room to come back, but there
remains an air of impermanence to him.
</P>
<P>
   It is amazing that the Mets came back at all, but on a
sun-dappled afternoon, only two weeks ago, they clawed their way
into a playoff, which they won, and then they won their first
series with Arizona. It has been ``Perils of Pauline'' all along.
But as the rain fell, the Mets were still extant.
</P>
<P>
   The game was a microcosm of their entire season. They started
with their sturdy Japanese import, Masato Yoshii, who said: ``This
is way too late in the season now to change myself. So I just have
to go up there and do the best that I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii lasted into the fourth inning and was replaced by Orel
Hershiser, who 11 years before had terrorized the Mets in the 1988
league series. His manager at the time, Tommy Lasorda, loved to
introduce Hershiser to the press as the Bulldog, because of
Hershiser's scrunched 1950s hall-monitor smile that belied the
existence of an inner bulldog.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser remains a bulldog, willing himself to keep playing at
the age of 41, because what else could be as much fun as playing
ball? He probably accepted the fourth as a challenge, one of those
Braves innings with so many marks to indicate myriad runners
clogging up the bases. He entered with two men on base and got
three straight outs.
</P>
<P>
   But Hershiser's true bulldog moment came in the sixth, another
of those crowded-scorecard innings. An error and two walks loaded
the bases with one out. Greg Maddux struck out bunting, and burly
Ryan Klesko was caught down the line. Mike Piazza ran Klesko back
toward third and made a relatively high, premature toss to Ventura.
Klesko bolted home.
</P>
<P>
   Guarding home plate was the Bulldog himself, a willowy senior
citizen _ but also a man who had once played defense and left wing
for a Philadelphia Flyers Junior A hockey team. He has known a bit
of contact in his sport life.
</P>
<P>
   If Klesko could dislodge the ball, the Braves would be ahead by
a run, and the potential would be there for the season to go down
and out quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko steamed home. Hershiser caught the toss from Ventura.
Klesko came in standing up, threw an elbow sideways, nothing dirty.
Hershiser planted the ball in his glove, stuck his right hand in
the glove, and braced himself and made the tag. The Bulldog held
on.
</P>
<P>
   The longer the game went, the worse it got for Piazza. He
stumbled over first base in the sixth inning, crumpling into a heap
near the feet of a solicitous Mookie Wilson, the first-base coach.
In the 12th inning he took a foul tip to the body and the umpire
kindly stalled a few extra seconds.
</P>
<P>
   In the 13th, Piazza strained his left arm in yet another
collision at home. He could no longer soldier on. But Ventura would
give him and the Mets at least another game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
