<HEADLINE>
OFF THE WALL: OH, TO BE YOUNG AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; This should be a no-brainer. We can't think of one reason why
slingin' Steve Young should come back this week.
</P>
<P>
   Or this season.
</P>
<P>
   Or this millennium.
</P>
<P>
   So don't. Keep your head in the game if you must, but don't
strap a helmet onto it and stand behind that offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Find a spot for him right now at the '99 retirement home, where
he and John Elway can sit around in the big leather chairs, laugh
at their former teams' pratfalls and remember the good ol' days _
while they are still able to remember. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ You know there's gonna be some nitwit who decides to ``just
do it,'' and then point with his mangled finger a lawsuit at Nike's
``You Are So Beautiful To Me'' commercial, which includes Ronnie
Lott showing his severed pinky. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ And let's dispel this predominant theory that L.A. continues
to get the best national NFL games each week on TV because we don't
have a team _ what's your definition of ``best''?
</P>
<P>
   To the networks, L.A. has been typecast as a Rams-Raiders-49ers
area of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday provided another example.
</P>
<P>
   CBS had seven games from which to choose, and the one we got was
Oakland at Buffalo, along with 14 percent of the country.
Meanwhile, 46 percent saw Miami at New England _ which this week's
Sports Illustrated touts as ``Don't Miss'' in its TV promo _ and
had CBS' A-team announcers of Greg Gumbel and Phil Simms.
</P>
<P>
   Fox had a doubleheader for us. Of the three games available at
10 a.m., we saw St. Louis at Atlanta, as did 20 percent of the
country. The Minnesota-Detroit game went to 47 percent. Fox offered
two games in the 1 p.m. slot. We saw Carolina at San Francisco
along with 18 percent of the country. The rest (77 percent) saw
John Madden and Pat Summerall doing the Green Bay-Denver contest. .
. .
</P>
<P>
   __ ``Think Like A Champion: Building Success One Victory at a
Time'' is the hot-sellin' motivational book out right now. Well,
maybe not !ital!right now. The author is Broncos coach Mike
Shanahan. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ ``When Pride Still Mattered: A Life of Vince Lombardi'' by
Pulitzer Prize winner David Maraniss is a much more motivating
read. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Someone remind Lenny ``The Buffer'' Dykstra that his car-wash
coupons won't work with bail bondsmen. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Some catch-phrase critics have been referring to ``Mystery,
Alaska'' as the `` `Rocky' of hockey'' or the `` `Hoosiers' of
hockey.'' Others call it a ``glorified `Mighty Ducks' for
grown-ups.''
</P>
<P>
   We're just thinking it's the most impressive hockey movie we've
ever been lucky enough to see on a big screen. Don't wait for
video. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Without Wilt, who's going to rap Shaq for not playing
defense? Phil Jackson has already assumed that role. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ My lasting impression of Wilt is from maybe 20 years ago,
when he played in a Manhattan Beach volleyball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   After his match ended, this massive dark man walked through the
white hot sand toward the ocean to cool off from the sweltering
late afternoon sun. After going out to where the waves finally
broke above his knees, he reached his arms over his head and dived
into the current like some great serpent.
</P>
<P>
   The sight was awesome.
</P>
<P>
   But thinking about it again, more incredible was that once he
reached a certain distance out, for the longest time it looked as
if he was walking on top of the water.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was low tide, or there was a sand barge. It was just
mystical.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
