<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACEEXP-ONBOARD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AN EXPERIENCE THAT'S OUT OF THIS WORLD  &HT;     By TERRY NAGEL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ What will it be like to travel in space?
</P>
<P>
   ``Weightlessness? It's awesome _ pure and total freedom! I wish
everyone could experience it. They'd become addicted,'' said former
astronaut Byron Lichtenberg, who flew Space Shuttle missions 9 and
45.
</P>
<P>
   During the filming of ``Apollo 13,'' when the cast and crew
experienced zero gravity, Director Ron Howard said, ``Saying
something is better than sex rarely lives up to that claim.
Weightlessness came awfully close.''
</P>
<P>
   With billing like that, it's no wonder that people are lining up
for space flights offered by two tour companies: Space Adventures
of Alexandria, Va., and Zegrahm Expeditions of Seattle. Both are
selling seven-day packages that include a suborbital flight lasting
about 21/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Space Adventures is working with several rocket firms, so its
itinerary isn't firm. Zegrahm's passengers will board a two-stage
Space Cruiser that takes off from a conventional runway. After it
reaches an altitude of 50,000 feet, the stages will separate and
the first stage will return home.
</P>
<P>
   The second stage's rocket engines will throttle up and boost the
ship up more than 62 miles above Earth, beyond the edge of space.
By comparison, passenger jets cruise at an average altitude of
30,000 feet (5.7 miles) and the best military jets have trouble
climbing above 100,000 feet (about 19 miles).
</P>
<P>
   During the ascent, travelers will be able to see views in all
directions via cameras connected to a wrist control. The
weightlessness period, which will last only 21/2 minutes, will be
one of the highlights of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The other aspect of space travel that astronauts recount with
awe is seeing Earth from space. Many have called it a
transformational experience. On this trip, participants won't see
the entire planet but will get to see Earth's curvature.
</P>
<P>
   Retro rockets will fire to slow the Space Cruiser for re-entry.
It will return to the airfield under jet power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-99 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991017.0207 </DOCNO>
