<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-17 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9999 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-USC-LADN     10-17 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHICH TEAM IS HACKETT COACHING?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC coach Paul Hackett was asked Sunday if he got
any sleep after returning home from South Bend, Ind., on Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. And my headache won't go away either,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   It could take a while before Hackett's head stops hurting after
the Trojans blew a 21-point lead against Notre Dame and lost 25-24
before a national television audience.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours later, Hackett was pondering some of the
things that happened in Notre Dame Stadium. And while there are
many questions, there are almost no answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what's happened. I don't know why,'' Hackett said. ``We
were two different teams. Why? I don't have a clue.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's just one of the plays that had Hackett perplexed: Notre
Dame quarterback Jarious Jackson's fumble that rolled into the end
zone was recovered by the Irish for the winning touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had seven guys on the ball. They had two guys. They got the
ball,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Consider two other plays with which Notre Dame beat USC that
Hackett didn't mention: The 49-yard reception to running back
Julius Jones in the first half, and the 7-yard touchdown pass to
tight end Dan O'Leary in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Both Irish receivers were wide open, even though those plays had
been repeatedly stressed in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew some of the plays that were coming and still let it
happen,'' cornerback Antuan Simmons said. ``That (touchdown), it's
their bread-and-butter play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet might sizzle this week with fiery comments about
the coaching, but the problem seems bigger than that.
</P>
<P>
   The first sign of a healthy program is winning on the road, and
the Trojans' road record is a sickly 3-7 since the start of last
season. The Trojans have demonstrated repeatedly they are not
mentally capable of being one of the conference's elite teams.
</P>
<P>
   Another sign of health is confidence, and USC loses it faster
than anyone in the second half. The Trojans are inept at protecting
leads this season. USC has blown two fourth-quarter leads (Oregon,
Notre Dame) and a third-quarter lead (Arizona).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to perform in the clutch,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Added linebacker Markus Steele: ``The second half we just
couldn't put things together. That comes from heart. You have to go
out and do it. We're not playing a full 60 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the space of a few weeks, the Trojans have gone from thinking
they could play in the Rose Bowl to maybe not going to a bowl at
all. USC (3-3, 1-2) has to win four of its final six games to be
eligible for a bowl. You look at the schedule and circle the
victories.
</P>
<P>
   All along, October has stood out as the critical portion of the
schedule. So far, USC is 1-2, and here comes conference-leader
Stanford (4-0, 4-2) to the Coliseum on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are going to say the season's over,'' wide
receiver R. Jay Soward said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the team doesn't appear ready to throw in the towel, but
it's also confused about its direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``USC's one of the top schools in the nation and we're not even
ranked,'' linebacker Zeke Moreno said. ``I feel bad. We've got to
do something.''
</P>
<P>
   The only answer of course, is to win.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: Center Eric Denmon (ankle) appeared OK on Sunday and
is listed as possible for the Stanford game, along with offensive
tackle Matt Welch (shoulder). Left guard Donta Kendrick re-sprained
his ankle and is considered doubtful. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
USC STATUS REPORT &QL; 
__ GAME: 6 &QL; 
__ RESULT: Notre Dame 25, USC 24 &QL; 
__ RECORD: 3-3, 1-2 &QL; 
__ THIS WEEK'S GPA: 2.73 &QL; 
__ CUMULATIVE GPA: 2.67 &QL; 
QUARTERBACKS &QL; 
Mike Van Raaphorst was solid, as usual, but two turnovers and a
missed TD pass to a wide-open R. Jay Soward were costly. &QL; 
C+ &QL; 
RUNNING BACKS &QL; 
Chad Morton ran as hard as he had all season and had 58 yards in
the first half. But Notre Dame held him to 27 in the second half. &QL; 
B &QL; 
RECEIVERS &QL; 
Windrell Hayes, R. Jay Soward and Kareem Kelly had big catches.
Hayes' best catch was incorrectly ruled out of bounds by the
official. &QL; 
A &QL; 
OFFENSIVE LINE &QL; 
In a complete turnaround from Arizona, the line gave Van Raaphorst
excellent pass protection and opened some wide lanes for Chad
Morton. &QL; 
B+ &QL; 
DEFENSIVE LINE &QL; 
Ennis Davis had three sacks and recovered a fumble, but Jarious
Jackson's speed was something that could never be completely shut
down. &QL; 
B- &QL; 
LINEBACKERS &QL; 
Once again, Markus Steele was everywhere with 12 tackles. But who
was supposed to cover RB Julius Jones on the 49-yard pass play? &QL; 
B- &QL; 
DEFENSIVE BACKS &QL; 
The biggest turning point was probably Ife Ohalete's personal foul
that revived a Notre Dame touchdown drive. &QL; 
C- &QL; 
SPECIAL TEAMS &QL; 
The first blocked kick of the season, by Antuan Simmons, was nice,
but all anyone will remember is the 11-yard punt in the fourth
quarter. &QL; 
C &QL; 
COACHING &QL; 
The play-calling in the first half was the most creative it has
been since Paul Hackett became head coach. Too bad it was
overshadowed by Notre Dame's 22-point comeback. &QL; 
B- &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
