 `VACATION GODDESS' WINS FUNDING  &HT;     By STAN BUNGER and JAN BOYD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know, attracting attention in the highly competitive dot-com
world isn't easy, and startup executives often must go to great
lengths to get noticed. But sometimes you just have to wonder, what
were they thinking?
</P>
<P>
   We offer, without further comment, a portion of a bio shipped to
us last week from Pamela Bergeson, CEO of Bid4Vacations.com, along
with a photo in which she is wearing a tiara and a beauty-queen
sash labeled ``Ms. Vacation Goddess.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN ITALICS)
</P>
<P>
   In May of 1998, Ms. Bergeson got the idea for the company when
she bid for a computer at an online auction site. After winning,
she found herself jumping up and down. She thought others would get
excited about winning vacations by way of an online auction. The
company was officially launched in the heart of Colorado's
e-commerce corridor on April 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Stats: Nick Name: Dubbed the ``Vacation Goddess'` by the firm's
venture capitalists (photo attached).
</P>
<P>
   Career goal, Age five: To be a Stewardess and have ``Marsha
Brady'` hair.
</P>
<P>
   First job: At Disneyland, I was hostess of the ``Tiki Room.''
</P>
<P>
   Three words that best describe me: Risk taker, determined and
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   I'd give anything to meet: Cindy Crawford, poster child of
``Beauty &AMP; Brains.'`
</P>
<P>
   (END ITALICS)
</P>
<P>
   And this woman's company attracted venture funding. Budding
entrepreneurs, take heart.
</P>
</TEXT>
