<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: ATLANTA'S EXPLOSIVE OFFENSE COMES TO A STANDSTILL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Atlanta Braves are trying to get to their fifth
World Series in the 1990s, but they sure are taking a strange
route.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, needing only one more victory to attain their
coveted goal, put 25 runners on base against the New York Mets in a
game at Shea Stadium Sunday that moved from afternoon to evening.
Only three of the runners scored, and the Braves lost Game 5 of the
National League Championship Series, 4-3, in a 15-inning,
5-hour-46-minute marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Weiss led off the 15th inning with a single, becoming the
23rd Braves base runner, and he scored the run that gave the Braves
a 3-2 lead. But the Braves left two other runners on in the inning,
giving them 19 for the game. The Mets had left nine on in the first
14 innings, then added three more in the 15th, when Robin Ventura
and two other runners did not round the bases and score after
Ventura hit what appeared to be a grand slam. He was credited with
a single and the Mets just one run, the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves were so feeble with runners on base that in one
five-inning span, the fourth through the eighth, they stranded 11
runners.
</P>
<P>
   Five of those runners failed to score in the sixth and seventh
innings, which epitomized the battle of strategic wits the
managers, Bobby Valentine of the Mets and Bobby Cox of the Braves,
had waged through the entire series.
</P>
<P>
   With the scored tied, 2-2, Ryan Klesko led off the sixth by
hitting a hard grounder directly at John Olerud at first base. But
Olerud couldn't contain the ball, and it rolled behind him. Edgardo
Alfonzo, who had darted over to back up, retrieved the ball quickly
and threw to Orel Hershiser, who had scooted over from the mound in
case he had a play at first. But the throw was high, and by the
time Hershiser reached high to catch the ball, he was past the
base.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones then sacrificed Klesko to second, and Hershiser
walked Eddie Perez intentionally. Perez, at that point, had seven
hits in 15 times at bat in the series. But Hershiser then threw
four balls unintentionally to Walt Weiss, loading the bases. Greg
Maddux was the next batter. He was pitching too well and it was too
early for Bobby Cox to consider a pinch hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux, a good batter, hit some sharp fouls and had a 1-2 count
when he suddenly squared to bunt. Klesko broke from third and came
racing down the baseline. Cox had called for a most unconventional
suicide squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser's pitch was low and away and Maddux missed it. Klesko
instantly stopped heading home. Mike Piazza fired to third, his
throw slightly high, but Ventura reached up and caught it. Klesko
reversed direction again, and Ventura pursued him before throwing
home, where Hershiser made a quick tag.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, the Mets had gone from a one-out bases-loaded jam to
being out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' half of the seventh inning began harmlessly with
Gerald Williams lofting a fly to right field for the first out. But
then Hershiser hit Bret Boone with a pitch. Cox sent the fleet Otis
Nixon in to run for Boone, and Valentine called for Turk Wendell to
replace Hershiser, triggering what would be a series of pitching
changes in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones, having an awful series after he destroyed the
Mets single-handedly in Atlanta last month, was the first batter
Wendell faced, and he struck out. But as he struck out, Nixon stole
second. Brian Jordan was the next batter for Wendell, and the first
two pitches to him were balls. That prompted Valentine to replace
Wendell with Dennis Cook. The Mets' manager chose that precise
moment to make the change because he was planning two moves ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko, a left-handed hitter, would bat after Jordan, and if
Valentine brought in the left-handed Cook, Cox would have the
right-hand-hitting Brian Hunter bat for Klesko. Had Valentine
waited for Klesko to come to bat before he brought in Cook, the
left-handed reliever would have had to pitch to Hunter. But because
he came in to pitch to Jordan, Valentine would be able to counter
Cox's move with Hunter with a right-handed pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine wasn't taking a chance by having Cook pitch to the
right-handed Jordan because he was going to walk him intentionally,
throwing balls three and four purposely wide. Cook did that, Hunter
was announced as batting for Klesko and Valentine summoned Pat
Mahomes. Even though the walk was charged statistically to Wendell
because he threw the first two balls, Cook was credited with facing
one batter because Jordan completed his at-bat against Cook.
</P>
<P>
   Once a pitcher enters a game, he has to remain in the game until
he dispatches one batter.
</P>
<P>
   So now Valentine had the matchup he wanted, right-handed pitcher
against right-handed batter. So what did Mahomes do? He walked
Hunter on four pitches. That wasn't quite what Valentine had in
mind because the walk loaded the bases. But Andruw Jones, the next
Braves batter, also hits right-handed, and Cox wasn't about to use
a pinch-hitter for him because he is Atlanta's best defensive
outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, with only three hits in 15 at-bats in the series, worked
the count to 2-2 before hitting a fly ball to left field that
Rickey Henderson caught, ending the inning and the whirlwind of
changes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
