u s BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     10-17 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HENDERSON LOST FACE, BUT STILL PERFORMED
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The most important game in the New York Mets' season
stretched almost six hours into the rain-soaked night at Shea
Stadium Sunday night, finally ending in a scene of triumph for the
home team. But it began, in daylight, on a bizarre note of discord,
perhaps offering evidence of the sniping and backbiting that became
as a much a part of their armament this year as their gritty
``never say die'' play.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets arrived at Shea Stadium with a controversy hovering
overhead like the clouds that dropped bursts of rain on the
extra-inning marathon Sunday .
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the game, reporters stood in pockets on the field
surrounding players talking among themselves. The topic of
conversation was not Atlanta: Andruw Jones or Chipper Jones or the
despised reliever, John Rocker. The topic was Rickey: Rickey
Henderson, the Mets' veteran left fielder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' dramatic victory of Saturday evening had quickly been
replaced by heated controversy revolving around Henderson's angry
reaction to being removed in the ninth inning of that game. The
Mets had taken the lead in the bottom of the eighth inning when
Melvin Mora and Roger Cedeno had executed a double steal and then
scored. With adrenaline flowing and spirits high, Henderson trotted
out to his post in left field.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months Valentine, pointing to a rash of injuries that
plagued his 40-year-old left fielder, had replaced Henderson for
defensive purposes with Mora. But this time there was no Mora.
Henderson, perhaps indulging an aging star's ego, assumed that
Valentine had finally come to his senses and was going to leave him
in at crunch time. Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine had simply forgotten to make the switch. Now he had
the choice of leaving Henderson in to avoid embarrassing him or
take him out in full view of sold-out Shea Stadium, risk
humiliating Henderson and deal with fallout later. Valentine chose
the latter. He dispatched Mora to left field to pull Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   Mora was mortified. ``I just told Rickey, `Rickey, he sent me
here.' Rickey said: `What? You've got to be kidding.' I said, `No,
he sent me here.' I don't make the decision, man. He says go to
left, I go to left field. I have to go to left field.''
</P>
<P>
   A seething Henderson slowly made his way off the field.
Valentine stood on the top step of the dugout and apologized, but
Henderson kept going. He went into the clubhouse and packed some
clothes. Afterward, he stayed out of media range.
</P>
<P>
   What could he say? Throughout the season there had been an
undercurrent of resentment, frustration and exasperation over what
essentially boils down to Henderson's style. Despite having an
exceptional season, there have been times when Henderson has not
run as hard as some thought he should. After Saturday's game, Turk
Wendell, the Mets reliever, disparaged Henderson with a thinly
veiled barb, saying there was only one quitter in the Mets'
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Quitter? Henderson? At 40, he is acknowledged as one of the
greatest leadoff hitters of all time. Who is Turk Wendell? Before
the game Wendell tried to apologize to Henderson. Henderson was not
interested.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson conceded that he was angry at the way he was taken out
of the game. ``How it was done, the reason it was done,'' Henderson
said. ``But he's the manager, I'm the player. We don't always
agree, but we have to stick together as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, in his first time at bat, Henderson beat out an infield
hit. He distracted Greg Maddux and forced him to throw more to
first than usual. Maddux finally grooved a home-run pitch to John
Olerud.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson also misjudged a fly ball in the fourth that allowed a
double to Bret Boone. Boone scored on a double by Chipper Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson left the game after striking out in the ninth inning.
The game went on and on, with startling turns and many big plays
until it finally concluded with a Robin Ventura smash in the bottom
of the 15th inning. By that time, the Henderson controversy was
over.
</P>
<P>
   For the Mets, this was a high-water mark. No playoff in 11
years, now finally a crucial victory over Atlanta, the National
League team of the decades, in extra innings. Their season was
still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy or no controversy, the Mets took a major step
forward Sunday night, and the game that revolved around Rickey
Henderson at the beginning was about something very much more at
the end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
