<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS-BRAVES GAME WAS LONG BUT HARDLY BORING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By the time the Mets' 15-inning, 4-3 victory over
Atlanta ended on Sunday night, the Yankees-Red Sox playoff game had
reached the seventh inning and ESPN's Washington-Arizona National
Football League game was in the second half. Oh, it was long, but
those many scoreless innings were rarely boring.
</P>
<P>
   Not when Braves Manager Bobby Cox and Mets Manager Bobby
Valentine had to empty their benches and contemplated activating
themselves. Not when, as NBC's Bob Costas noted, a post-season game
can come down to a journeyman like the Mets' Todd Pratt, 32, who
walked to tie the score at 3-3, against Kevin McGlinchy, the
Braves' 22-year-old rookie reliever.
</P>
<P>
   Costas' perfectly terse home run call _ ``a drive to right . . .
back to Georgia . . . gone . . . a grand slam'' _ was followed
smartly by describing the game as a ``a 5-hour-47-minute trip to
bedlam'' and the ruling that Robin Ventura's game-winning grand
slam had been reduced to a game-winning single because he never
reached second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at the umpires, but they'd left the scene, but as we
were going off the air, we got it from Red Foley,'' Costas said
afterward, referring to the game's official scorer. ``For a long
time, the scoreboard said 3-3, then 7-3, and as I was leaving, it
said 4-3.''
</P>
<P>
   Costas and the NBC analyst Joe Morgan were quick to raise doubts
that Ventura's grand slam should count. But Ventura evidently
didn't care, knowing the single was what mattered. Prodded by Craig
Sager, an NBC reporter, to return to the field to complete the
four-base circuit previously blocked by his cheering, exuberant
teammates, Ventura said, ``I've had enough.''
</P>
<P>
   On Fox's telecast of the Yankees-Red Sox playoff game, the
producer Mike Weisman alertly replayed Chris Chambliss' American
League Championship Series-winning home run for the Yankees against
the Kansas City Royals in 1976 when an on-field mob scene prevented
him from touching all four bases.
</P>
<P>
   Chambliss, now the Yankees' hitting coach, was wired for sound
by Fox on Sunday night and provided commentary about the events at
Shea Stadium. ``Is that lousy, or what?'' he said, regarding the
ruling on Ventura's home run. Told by the team trainer Gene
Monahan, ``You've got to go around the bases, just like you had to
go around,'' Chambliss replied, ``I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura's dramatic grand slam-cum-single immediately evoked a
comparison with Kirk Gibson's pinch-hit two-run home run for the
Dodgers to win Game 1 of the 1988 World Series against Oakland.
Costas, who was part of NBC's coverage that day, said Ventura's hit
was not Gibson's peer. ``It was a World Series game,'' he said.
``And in truth, the Mets didn't need a home run to win the game. As
soon as the ball got into the outfield, they won. In the Gibson
game, they were down one run, with two outs, and there was his
physical condition.'' Gibson limped painfully to the plate that
day.
</P>
<P>
   But still, Costas said, ``This game ranks way up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Had a dreary victory by the Mets sent the series to Game 6,
Costas added: ``Somewhere in the back of your mind, you're saying,
`Ugh, another flight.' But now we can fly back to Atlanta on
adrenaline.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-99 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
